fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-075",
  description: "Implement proposal 033 M1+M2+M3 — LogicalQuery disjunction via binary push_choice primitive. See docs/proposals/033-resolver-primitives-and-disjunction.md. M1: extend Candidate enum in kb/resolve.rs with Continuation(Vec<TermId>, Substitution) — body-only candidate (no head unification), reuses all FrameState::ChoicePoint alts/dedup/solution-accounting machinery. M2: create stdlib/anthill/kernel/kernel.anthill with 'operation push_choice(?a: Term, ?b: Term) -> Bool' (binary — both branches share the frame tail captured once at the choice point, like a WAM continuation pointer) and 'rule or(?a, ?b) :- push_choice(?a, ?b)'. Wire anthill.kernel into the prelude-load chain. Add BuiltinTag::PushChoice in kb/mod.rs:27, register as 'anthill.kernel.push_choice' in register_standard_builtins (mod.rs:1656). Handle PushChoice in step_init (not execute_builtin — same special-case pattern as Not/HoApply): walk both args through σ to get goal_a, goal_b; let tail = goals[1..]; produce ChoicePoint with [Continuation([goal_a, ...tail], σ), Continuation([goal_b, ...tail], σ)]. M3: replace kb/execute.rs:382 NotYetImplemented with rewrite to or(L_goal, R_goal); extract wrap_as_single_goal helper from the negation path. Tests: push_choice standalone, or(a,b) with both/one branch succeeding, shared variables, basic disjunction yielding both branches, disjunction inside conjunction (no DNF push-down — falls out of frame structure), nested disjunctions, shared variables across branches. Long-stream variant deferred to WI-077. Foundational scope: push_choice is the substrate for the future Branch effect (proposal 026 §Effects) and downstream cut/soft-cut/if-then-else/once/findall — see proposal 033 §Future work.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-047"],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-05-03T09:29:31Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-076",
  description: "Implement proposal 033 M4 — multi-goal negation in LogicalQuery. See docs/proposals/033-resolver-primitives-and-disjunction.md. Lift current single-goal limitation in kb/execute.rs:356 (NotYetImplemented for multi-goal negation) using the wrap_as_single_goal helper extracted in WI-075/M3: synthesize an intermediate conjunction-rule head and emit not(synth_head). Low impact — single-goal covers most cases — but completes negation(query) constructor for arbitrary subqueries. Tests: negation(conjunction(p, q)) semantics matches not(synth_head) where synth_head :- p, q.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-075"],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-05-03T09:29:31Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Verification report: docs/status/wi-047.md. Core execute(LogicalQuery) API + acceptance test pass. Reopened with deps on WI-074 (reflect-ops parity test - sorts/operations/rules already exist in anthill-stl/src/reflect/bridge.rs, only equivalence check needed), WI-075 (disjunction), WI-076 (multi-goal negation). Quantifiers/aggregations stay deferred under WI-048.", at: "2026-04-22T19:36:36Z", workitem: "WI-047", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-077",
  description: "Long-stream stress test for execute_logical_query / SearchStream: build a KB with N (>=1000) matching facts (or a recursive rule yielding N solutions), wrap the resulting SearchStream as StreamSource::Resolver, drive splitFirst to exhaustion, and assert (a) all N solutions surface, (b) stream arena slot is reclaimed (stream_arena_live_count returns to 0), (c) memory/perf does not blow up. Current coverage tops out at 3 solutions on Resolver streams (eval_m4_test.rs); infinite-stream tests only exercise StreamSource::Native, not the resolver path. Should also gate disjunction work (WI-075) so the same harness can verify MPlus over long branches.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-078",
  description: "Land proposal 027 (Effect handlers and standard effects): see docs/proposals/027-effect-handlers-and-standard-effects.md. Substrate confirmation (verified 2026-04-23): the defunctionalized eval (activation stack with explicit Frame/AwaitState in eval/frame.rs and eval/eval.rs, per 026/M1) already exists — no evaluator refactor needed. Sequencing per proposal §Migration plan, in two phases. PHASE A (substrate, do first): (a) add Clone to Frame and ActivationStack in eval/frame.rs after auditing AwaitState fields for cloneability; (b) define HandlerAction carrier (Pure | Throw | Fail | Choice) in eval/effects.rs and migrate existing handlers to return it; (c) add RuntimeAPI snapshot_eval_state / resume_with / push_choice / fail_branch operations and wire Choice interpretation; (d) WI-075 push_choice resolver-side prerequisite (parallel). PHASE B (handlers + ergonomics): (e) default Branch handler returning Choice(a, alt_b) for branch / Fail for fail (this is WI-054's scope, recast on the carrier model); (f) default Error handler returning Throw(payload) — propagates to EvalError (this is WI-070's scope on the carrier model); (g) Reader sort + handler in stdlib + Rust default; (h) push/pop handler stack: HashMap<Symbol, Vec<Handler>>, push_handler/pop_handler/with_handler in RuntimeAPI, optional 'with handler H for E do body end' grammar; (i) bracket(setup, body, cleanup) stdlib op via with_handler. Kernel-side stdlib changes: add 'operation branch(a: T, b: T) -> T effects Branch' to Branch sort + sub-effect derivation 'rule Effect[T = Suspension] :- Effect[T = Branch]' to effects.anthill. Tests: per-handler unit tests; integration test for branch inside let yielding LogicalStream; nested with-handler tests; bracket success+error path tests. Relates: WI-050 (M5 framework, landed); WI-053 (Suspension, sibling — overlaps phase A's snapshot/resume API); WI-054 (Branch, replaced by phase B step e); WI-070 (Modify follow-up, parallel — already planned); WI-077 (long-stream stress test, harness reusable for MPlus over Branch).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-075"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-080",
  description: "Wire anthill.reflect.not(query: Term) -> Bool as eval-time negation-as-failure. Implementation: builtin in anthill-stl/src/reflect/builtins.rs wraps the goal in a resolver `not(...)` Fn term (functor = anthill.reflect.not) and runs a one-shot kb.resolve_lazy. Behavior: ground q with solutions → Bool(false); ground q with no solutions → Bool(true); ungrounded q → EvalError::Internal('floundering') since NAF is unsound on unground goals and eval-time has no outer frame to DELAY on. Reuses the existing resolver BuiltinTag::Not step_naf handling (resolve.rs:519) — one `not`, one meaning (NAF) across rule-body and eval-time invocation. Acceptance: 3 tests in anthill-stl (satisfiable → false, unsatisfiable → true, ungrounded → floundering error). All pass. Completes the eval-time surface of reflect.anthill. Delivered 2026-04-23.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-047"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-23T00:00:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-079",
  description: "Typing-pass parity test: verify the operations-form spec in docs/proposals/typing_pass_spec.anthill produces the same TypeOf facts as the Rust implementation in rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs for a corpus of test programs. Approach: (a) build a small corpus of well-typed and ill-typed test programs covering: literals, variables, lambdas (with and without annotations), let, match (exhaustive and non-exhaustive), constructor patterns, operation calls, effect-row inference, type-parameter binding, structural unification of parameterized/arrow/named_tuple types, subtyping relationships. (b) run each program through the Rust typer; collect resulting TypeOf facts (per occurrence) and any LoadError diagnostics. (c) (when typing_pass_spec.anthill operations are wired as runnable anthill code) run the same programs through the spec; collect TypeOf facts; compare. Initial milestone before the spec is runnable: lock down a snapshot of expected TypeOf facts from the Rust typer as the reference, so the spec implementation has a concrete target to match. Reason WI-011 was closed in favor of this WI: the operations-form spec already exists; what's missing is the equivalence guarantee. Closes the practical concern WI-011 was capturing without the Horn-rules infrastructure ambition.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-081",
  description: "Math library: Vec3, quaternion, 3D rotations and rigid-body transforms in anthill.prelude.math (or similar). Followup from lf1 example which currently uses a project-local Vec3. Should support rotation by yaw/quaternion, vector arithmetic, dot/cross products, magnitude/normalize. Backed by tl::expected on the C++ side for any operation that can fail (e.g. normalize(0)).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-082",
  description: "Kernel extension: allow Quoted to reference an external source file. Either as a new field form (e.g. Quoted with file path argument) or via a separate construct. Driven by lf1 example, where the Mavic2Pro inner stabilization loop is roughly 100 lines of vendor C++ that should ride along verbatim alongside the anthill spec; inlining as an escaped string literal is impractical. Proposal needed: kernel-spec section 4.2 Quoted Terms, syntax plus scoping rules plus how the referenced path resolves relative to the spec file.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-04-27T09:36:51Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-083",
  description: "Byte / byte-array support in anthill. Currently no first-class bytes sort — String is used as a stand-in for binary payloads (e.g. lf1's webots.Emitter.send / Receiver.get_data, which on the C++ side take/return const void* with explicit size). String stand-ins break for payloads containing null bytes and require reinterpret_cast to round-trip serialized structs. Needed: a Bytes sort (or List[T = Byte] equivalent) with primitive operations (length, concat, slice, from_string, to_string), Implementation facts mapping to std::string (size-tracked) or std::vector<std::byte> in C++, and parser/typing support for byte-literal syntax. Driven by lf1 webots bindings; will also be needed by blefusku (proto wire format).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-084",
  description: "Term-level named constants in anthill. Currently the language has primitive literals and entities but no way to declare a named constant of a primitive type. Workarounds (entity-as-constant + side fact, unit-sort with coercion) are clunky. Proposed shape: 'const NAME: Type = literal_expr' at namespace or sort scope, identifier-resolvable everywhere a term is expected. Drives: webots binding sentinels (CHANNEL_BROADCAST = -1, infinity-as-velocity-mode), magic numbers in the safety proof's KinematicAssumptions / DistanceBounds. Should compose with the proposal-026 expression evaluator so constant expressions can be folded at load time.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-085",
  description: "anthill-todo CLI: 'add' generates duplicate IDs (WI-001 instead of next sequential) when the workitems.anthill file has a parse error. Root cause was upstream of the CLI: the tree-sitter grammar's string_literal regex /\"[^\"]*\"/ rejected backslash-escaped sequences, so any string containing \\\" (which the printer emits to encode embedded quotes) failed to parse. The whole file's parsed view collapsed, leaving zero WorkItems in the KB and the CLI's next-id logic falling back to WI-001. Same root cause produced 'WorkItem sort not found in KB' for files that combined embedded quotes with em-dashes. Fixed: (1) tree-sitter grammar string_literal regex now accepts /\"([^\"\\\\]|\\\\.)*\"/ and grammar regenerated, (2) parse/convert.rs decodes escape sequences (\\\", \\\\, \\n, \\r, \\t) into the resulting Literal::String, (3) added persistence_test::round_trip_escapes_preserve_content and round_trip_entity_with_string_fields_preserves_escapes regression tests covering term-source-term round-trip with quotes / backslashes / em-dashes / control chars in both positional-arg facts and named-arg entity-shaped facts. Verified end-to-end: lf1 webots dir loads, anthill-todo add now allocates next sequential id even with quotes and em-dashes in the description.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-04-25T19:19:29Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-086",
  description: "anthill.realization.directMemory: a system-modeling sublibrary capturing host-language memory/ownership concerns. Parameterized sorts: Borrowed[T] (non-owning const ref), BorrowedMut[T] (non-owning mut ref), Owned[T] (explicit owned), Shared[T] (refcounted), Pinned[T] (non-movable). C++ codegen lowers each via a CarrierBinding on the wrapper sort itself. Lets specs express 'this handle borrows from its owner' instead of relying on convention + raw pointer carriers. Driver: lf1 webots bindings (Robot::getGPS returns webots::GPS *, semantically Borrowed[T = GPS]); future use cases include smart-pointer-heavy APIs, hardware MMIO, async self-references. Until this lands, lf1 elides borrow semantics and relies on raw-pointer carriers + codegen convention. Open design questions: auto-deref vs explicit unwrap; how Borrowed interacts with effects (Modify self); whether Borrowed[T] auto-satisfies sorts that T satisfies; aliasing/exclusivity rules.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-087",
  description: "Operation attributes / metadata in anthill — the kernel mechanism. Operations need a way to carry structured metadata that downstream tools read. Three distinct uses, ALL riding on this one mechanism: (1) named marker facts for recurring lowering patterns (e.g. Vec3FromConstDoublePtr3 — codegen has one handler per marker, marker is reusable across many operations); (2) one-off escape hatch with literal host-language body (CppBody(\"...\") — for ad-hoc glue that doesn't fit a known pattern); (3) profile/dispatch hints (Profile(\"cpp20-stl\")). Note: @ is taken for effects (grammar.js:608 arrow-type annotation; WI-004 may extend it to operation declarations) so attributes need a different vehicle. Two candidate shapes: (A) keyword-introduced clause matching effects/requires shape: 'operation foo(...) -> R effects (E) meta Vec3FromConstDoublePtr3, Profile(\"cpp20-stl\")'; (B) nested fact block reusing existing keyword: 'operation foo(...) -> R effects (E) fact Vec3FromConstDoublePtr3 fact Profile(\"cpp20-stl\")' where the operation symbol is the implicit subject. (B) is semantically purer — attributes already ARE facts about the operation symbol, the realization model is already fact-based, and no new keyword needed. Open design: pick (A) vs (B); attribute argument forms; name resolution scope; how attributes interact with effects and contracts.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-088",
  description: "Marshalling-pattern markers for lf1 webots bindings (and reusable later). Named marker facts that the C++ codegen recognizes and synthesizes a body for, abstracting recurring lowering patterns so each operation just declares which pattern it follows rather than spelling out the body. First marker needed: Vec3FromConstDoublePtr3, applying to operations whose anthill return is Vec3 and whose C++ side returns a const double pointer at 3 contiguous doubles. Codegen handler synthesizes a single line that reads the pointer and constructs the Vec3, where METHOD is the snake_case operation name converted to camelCase. Operations needing it in lf1: GPS.get_values, GPS.get_speed_vector, Gyro.get_values, Receiver.get_emitter_direction. Variants likely needed: EulerAnglesFromConstDoublePtr3 for InertialUnit.get_roll_pitch_yaw, Vec4FromConstDoublePtr4 for InertialUnit.get_quaternion when modeled. Lives in webots/marshalling.anthill project-local until a second consumer needs the same patterns; then lift. Depends on WI-087 (operation attributes mechanism). NOT to be confused with the generic CppBody escape hatch: markers are abstract, CppBody is verbatim.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-087"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-089",
  description: "anthill.realization.cpp_std: C++ language mapping file, sibling to rust_std.anthill. One LanguageMapping fact per profile (cpp17-stl, cpp20-stl) with effect_map (Modify to lvalue ref, Error to tl::expected wrap), type_map (Int to int64_t, Float to double, Bool to bool, String to std::string, List to std::vector, Option to std::optional, Bytes to std::vector of std::byte when WI-083 lands), trait_return TraitsClass per docs/cpp-forward-mapping.md. Plus a NamingConvention fact: language: cpp, method_case: camelCase, source_case: snake_case. Codegen uses this as the default when translating operation names. Per-operation overrides ride on WI-087 attributes (a CppName fact in the operation block) to handle irregulars such as acronyms (get_gps, get_imu). Driver: lf1 example needs cpp_std and lf1's webots realization references it.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-087"],
  status: Open)

