fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-092",
  description: "Parser error span recovery: tighten the failure window so a single-construct error inside a sort body does not subsume the rest of the body in the error span. Symptom observed during WI-085 diagnosis: a malformed effects clause (\"effects (Modify self)\" instead of \"effects Modify[self]\") at byte 316 produced a parse error spanning 316..1947 — almost the entire sort body. Bisection by truncating the file made later innocent constructs (multi-line imports, trailing effects before end) look like they were the trigger, since each truncation either ended on the bad clause (failed) or after it (passed). Fixing the real bug was easy once isolated, but the diagnostic was actively misleading. Improvement: per-clause recovery in the operation/sort body so the error span ends at the next recognizable clause boundary (\"effects\", \"requires\", \"operation\", \"end\"). Should not require grammar changes — tree-sitter has explicit ERROR recovery hooks. Likely a few-hour change to grammar.js plus regenerate.  Driver: improves debuggability for everyone authoring anthill specs; webots-modelling/lf1 was the first project with enough hand-authored binding files to surface this.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-10T16:46:47Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-093",
  description: "Time stdlib (anthill.prelude.time): minimal time vocabulary needed for simulation, scheduling, and impurity reasoning. Three pieces. (1) Tick effect — sort Tick with fact Effect[T = Tick]. Operations marked 'effects Tick' depend on or advance simulation/wall-clock time; two calls separated by a Tick are not interchangeable. (2) Clock resource — sort Clock with entity clock, plus operations: now(c: Clock) -> Timestamp effects Tick; advance(c: Clock, by: Duration) -> Unit effects {Modify[c], Tick}. (3) Arithmetic on existing Duration / Timestamp data shapes from primitives.anthill — addition, subtraction, comparison, Numeric and Ordered satisfaction facts as appropriate. Driver: lf1 webots example wants Design B effect modeling — sensor reads stay pure (referentially transparent within a tick, matching webots's contract that sensor values update only via Robot::step), and Robot::step is the only Tick-emitting op. Without a Tick effect we can't express this, so all impurity is currently flattened into Modify. Connected to safety.anthill's inductive_invariant which already reasons in discrete steps; Tick on step makes the proof transition explicit. Out of scope: real-time / wall-clock semantics, time zones, scheduling primitives — those are separate stdlib chunks once concrete consumers appear.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-094",
  description: "World naming predicate for webots (and other simulator) bindings. Tightens the string-typed coupling between controller code and world-file device names by modeling them as anthill facts. Three fact shapes: (1) RobotKind(name, devices: List[NamedDevice]) — devices baked into a robot proto, e.g. Mavic2Pro's gps/gyro/inertial-unit/4-propellers. (2) WorldRobot(world, name, kind, extra_devices: List[NamedDevice]) — robot instance in a specific world, with per-instance additions like a radio Emitter or Receiver. (3) NamedDevice(name, sort) — a (name, anthill-sort) pair. Plus a derived predicate has_device(world, robot, device, sort) :- WorldRobot(...), RobotKind(...), in_devices(...) that binds (world × robot × device-name) to its sort. Codegen check: every Robot.get_X(r, lit_name) call where lit_name is a String literal triggers a query has_device(?world, r.name, lit_name, X); a mismatch produces a typed warning at codegen time. Same name resolving to different sorts on different robots (radio = Emitter on leader, Receiver on followers) is naturally captured per-robot. Driver: lf1 example. First implementation: webots/robot_kinds.anthill listing Mavic2Pro's standard devices; per-world file under examples/webots-modelling/lf1/ listing the lf1 world's robot instances and extras. Codegen-side check is a follow-up under the eventual anthill-cpp-gen WI; the model itself is useful even without the check (tooling, documentation, supervisor-dispatch). Generalizes beyond webots: a Gazebo or hardware target would have its own robot kinds and world-file analogues.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-095",
  description: "Finish proposal 002 (arrow sorts) implementation. Source grammar/loader/IR for arrow types is already in. Remaining: (a) author Functor/Applicative/Monad typeclass sorts in stdlib using existing arrow syntax; (b) operation-name-as-value (eta-expansion) so 'flatMap(m, pure)' parses with 'pure' as a value; (c) term-headed application '?f(?x)' for arrow-sorted variables, with Miller-pattern unification in the resolver; (d) effect subtyping for arrow types — '(A) -> B <: (A) -> B @ E'; (e) C++ codegen lowering for 'arrow' / 'arrow_effect' functor terms to 'std::function<R(Args...)>'; (f) higher-kinded codegen — when a sort parameter's body declares its own type params, emit 'template<template<typename...> class F>' instead of 'typename F' so Functor/Monad-style sorts compile to C++. The nested-body source form 'sort F { sort T = ? }' already encodes the kind information; codegen just needs to read it. See docs/proposals/002-arrow-sorts.md.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-096",
  description: "Proposal 025.1 Phase 1 — Proof cache (XDG, sha256, JSON). Independent of new tactic types; immediate ~6x speedup on discharge.sh. Deliverables: anthill-smt-gen/src/cache/ module (key.rs sha256 over emitted_smt_lib + canonical-serialised tactic term + ordered hint QNs + transitive rule_dep_hash + transitive fact_dep_hash + stdlib version + z3 --version + cache_format_version; store.rs JSON-per-entry with two-level hex fanout under per-solver subtree <root>/projects/<repo-hash>/proofs/z3/v1/; location.rs XDG resolver with override chain --cache-dir / ANTHILL_CACHE_DIR / anthill.toml / XDG default); anthill-cli new flags --no-cache --refresh-cache --show-cache --gc-cache --stats; wrap emit_satisfiability_check + emit_obligation call sites in anthill prove with cache lookup. Two-layer transitive dep guarantee: emitted_smt_lib bytes catch changes that surface in emission output; rule_dep_hash + fact_dep_hash catch transitive changes that don't (e.g. dep elided as dead code, or a future tactic dispatch path that consults more deps than emission). Property: for proof A whose deps are {B, C, D} where D itself depends on {D_A, D_B}, changing D_B's body or any D_B-referenced fact MUST invalidate A's cache key, at any depth — no silent stale hits possible. Risks: dep-hash correctness — DO NOT reuse requires_chain (typing.rs:1443; that walks sort-requires typeclass relations, wrong primitive). Build a fresh transitive walker over rule bodies; reuse emit_satisfiability_check_with_deps::visited_rules as the dep collection (already populated transitively during emission); for each visited rule content-hash its canonical body terms and the referenced facts' canonical fields; combine in canonical (sorted-by-QN) order. Acceptance: discharge.sh second run reports all hits and finishes <600ms wall-clock; regression test: editing a transitively-referenced fact invalidates a dependent proof's cache key. Path encoding for repo-hash with symlinks: use canonicalised paths. See docs/proposals/025.1-z3-tactic-dsl.md §Cache key + §Implementation plan Phase 1.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T16:37:17Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-097",
  description: "Proposal 025.1 Phase 2 — Grammar + tactic-term IR. Gates every later phase. Deliverables: tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js extends field_value admissible-value grammar to accept tactic terms (named applications, combinator calls, raw(...) escape, mapping ... -> rule X) with corpus tests; anthill-core/src/parse/convert.rs produces typed Tactic IR enum (Smt, Then(Vec<Tactic>), OrElse(Vec<Tactic>), Repeat{tactic, times}, Par(Vec<Tactic>), Raw(String), Induction{...}, Ranking{...}, Mapping(Vec<MappingEntry>)); backwards compat preserved (existing 'by z3(logic: \"LRA\")' continues to parse and dispatches as Tactic::Smt{logic}). Acceptance: existing safety_*.anthill proofs in lf1 parse unchanged; new corpus tests cover each tactic term shape; cargo test all green. Risks: tree-sitter conflicts on deeply nested rules (mitigation: explicit conflict entries; iterate corpus tests one tactic at a time); backwards compat (mitigation: corpus tests covering each existing lf1 proof BEFORE any grammar edit). See docs/proposals/025.1-z3-tactic-dsl.md §Implementation plan Phase 2.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-096"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T17:01:56Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-098",
  description: "Proposal 025.1 Phase 3 — Pass-through tactics + raw escape hatch. Validates the IR end-to-end before tackling meta-tactics. Deliverables: anthill-smt-gen emit_tactic(Tactic) -> String serialiser maps IR to Z3 input syntax — Smt(args) to (check-sat-using (using-params smt :timeout :random_seed)); Simplify/qe/propagate-values to (using-params <name> ...); Then to (then a b); OrElse to (or-else a b); Repeat{tactic, times} to (repeat <t> <n>); Par to (par-or a b); Raw(s) verbatim splice. Update lf1 existing proofs to dispatch through the new emitter (no behavioural change; validates the IR). Acceptance: discharge.sh reports 5/5 unsat unchanged; new tests cover each pass-through tactic shape. Risks: Z3 tactic naming drift across versions (mitigation: z3 --version captured in cache key, version bump → entries miss → re-run). See §Implementation plan Phase 3.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-097"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T19:32:01Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-099",
  description: "Proposal 025.1 Phase 4 — Outcome layer (models, cores, interpolants). Needed before meta-tactics so they can emit their RankingProof / ProofCore facts. Deliverables: emit (set-option :produce-models true) / :produce-unsat-cores true / :produce-interpolants true per outcome flags; parse Z3 output (model strings, unsat-core lists, interpolant expressions); anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs registers fact schemas for ProofCounterexample(proof, model, variable_assignments) and ProofCore(proof, required_rules), inserted as facts on outcome; cache value layout (Phase 1) extended to carry these fields. Acceptance: a deliberately-broken proof (negate the safety claim) returns disproved with a parsed model in ProofCounterexample; an unsat lf1 proof with cores: true populates ProofCore.required_rules with the contributing rule QNs. Risks: Z3's (model ...) text parsing is non-trivial (mitigation: store raw text always; structured variable_assignments is best-effort). See §Implementation plan Phase 4.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-098"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T20:28:24Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-100",
  description: "Proposal 025.1 Phase 5 — ranking meta-tactic (HEADLINE). Lifts the lf1 manual ranking-function discharge from lf1_real_spec_test.rs::lf1_transponder_excursion_ranking_function_manual into the language. Replaces hand-plugged PostArmedExcursionBound(max_ticks: 6) fact with an in-language proof. Deliverables: Tactic::Ranking{measure, decrease_when, state_sort, well_founded_on, sub_logic} produces 2 SMT-LIB queries — boundedness (forall state. measure(state) >= 0) and decrease (forall s, s'. decrease_when(s, s') => measure(s') < measure(s)); each sub-query uses Smt emit path so cache+outcome compose; combine verdicts (both unsat → proved; either sat → disproved; either unknown → unknown); on proved, emit RankingProof(name, measure, bad_step, bound_witness) fact (bound_witness from solving (maximise measure(state)) over precondition or fallback to user-supplied pessimistic_bound: N); anthill-core registers RankingProof fact schema; safety_transponder.anthill migration: replace PostArmedExcursionBound fact with proof post_armed_excursion_bound by z3(tactic: ranking(...)) end. Acceptance: discharge.sh reports 5/5 unsat unchanged; lf1_transponder_excursion_ranking_function_manual marked #[ignore] (then deleted in Phase 8). Risks: bound_witness via (maximise ...) brittle (mitigation: binary-search query OR pessimistic_bound: N user arg); user's bad_step rule may reference operations that don't translate to SMT (mitigation: surface error pointing at mapping ... -> rule X). See §Implementation plan Phase 5.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test+discharge")],
  depends_on: ["WI-099"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-04-27T21:03:59Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-101",
  description: "Proposal 025.1 Phase 6 — induction meta-tactic. Reprioritised: lf1 reachability lift (∀k. d_min ≤ d_k ≤ d_max) DOES need this — see WI-104..WI-108 for the prerequisite chain (predicate vars, nested impl, kernel principle generation, Int.induction, SLD support). Deliverables: Tactic::Induction{over, base, step} reads the auto-generated induction principle (WI-106 / WI-107) for the named sort and emits one subgoal per constructor; each subgoal dispatches to base or step (defaulting to Smt) via the existing emit path; combine verdicts (all subgoals proved → proved; any disproved → disproved). Acceptance: a stdlib proof using induction (e.g. List length is non-negative) discharges unsat; lf1 reachability proof discharges via Int.induction; clear error if the sort's induction principle isn't in the KB. See §Implementation plan Phase 6.",
