fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-163",
  description: "scaland resync — structural-op vs typeclass-op disambiguation. Prelude.registerStructuralOps in scaland/core/src/main/scala/anthill/load/Prelude.scala registers bare functor names (eq, neq, neg, and, or, not, lt, lte, gt, gte, div, mod, pow, arrow) as Operations under anthill.prelude — these are the names the Pratt parser produces from infix operators (`?a + ?b` → Fn(\"add\", ...)). When typeclass files load (eq.anthill defines anthill.prelude.Eq.eq, ordered.anthill defines Ordered.lt, etc.), every reference to `eq` in a rule body resolves ambiguously to BOTH anthill.prelude.eq AND anthill.prelude.Eq.eq, producing AmbiguousSymbol cascades during load. Same for neg (Float.neg vs prelude.neg). Fix must be a real disambiguation — downgrading Ambiguous to a warning is NOT acceptable. Design options: (a) drop registerStructuralOps entirely — let the parser emit functor names that resolve via the typeclass under the value's sort; (b) register structural ops as a distinct SymbolKind (e.g. SymbolKind.StructuralPlaceholder) that's filtered out during sort-method lookup and only consulted as a last-resort fallback; (d) wire structural ops to dispatch through fact-witness lookup at resolve time — eq(?a, ?b) where ?a: T resolves through Eq[T] fact to T's eq operation. Investigate how rustland handles this in rustland/anthill-core/src/intern.rs and resolve.rs — it does not produce AmbiguousSymbol on the same inputs. Mirror its mechanism. Acceptance: sbt test green; ParserIntegrationTest can load EmbeddedStdlib expanded with eq.anthill + ordered.anthill + numeric.anthill without AmbiguousSymbol(eq, ...) cascade.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-05-02T10:31:41Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-164",
  description: "realization profile `rust+anthill` — hybrid bundle of Rust shim + embedded anthill spec. Sibling to `rust_std` (full codegen) and `cpp_std`. Captures the anthill→(Rust shim + embedded spec) realization where the program is interpreted at runtime by a thin Rust host that bakes the .anthill files via include_str! and dispatches `main(args)` through the WI-051 interpreter. Composable with `rust_std` at sort granularity: some sorts realize to native Rust, others stay interpreted in the same binary. Schema delta: the realization layer today says \"spec X is replaced by host code Y\" (rust_std/cpp_std are substitution profiles); rust+anthill needs an *embedding* profile shape — a new `runtime_form` discriminator on LanguageMapping (or equivalent) distinguishing substitution from embedding, plus an AnthillBundle entity (files: List[String], entry: Symbol, effect_handlers: List[T = HandlerBinding]) naming what to bake in and how to wire effects. Includes: stdlib/anthill/realization/rust_anthill.anthill — LanguageMapping fact + supporting entities; codegen knob in anthill-rust-gen (proposal 029) to honour the embed shape — emit a thin shim crate that builds KB from include_str!d files at startup, registers stdlib + project handlers, calls interp.call(entry_qname, args). Driver / acceptance: anthill-todo (WI-009) is the first consumer — its WorkItem entities + workflow rules realize via rust+anthill, the resulting `cargo install` ships one static binary with no .anthill files on disk; integration test asserts `target/release/anthill-todo list` works in a fresh tempdir without runtime stdlib lookup. Migration story: rust+anthill is the bridge from WI-009a (interpret everything, ship now) to WI-009b (rust_std for hot sorts, no interpreter): per-sort profile flip, no rewrite, identical user-facing binary. Out of scope for v1: full anthill-rust-gen (proposal 029); per-effect codegen knobs beyond Console/Modify/Error; no_std bundle variant.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-02T10:13:31Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-165",
  description: "Publish anthill workspace crates to crates.io. Anthill is now meaningfully usable end-to-end (parser, KB, SLD, interpreter via WI-051, stdlib argparse via WI-159, rust+anthill bundling via WI-164) — time to make it discoverable. Sweep all workspace crates: anthill-core (foundation), anthill-cli (the `anthill` binary), anthill-stl (codegen runtime), anthill-todo (work-item CLI), anthill-cpp-gen / anthill-rust-gen / anthill-smt-gen (codegen). Per crate add: license = \"MIT OR Apache-2.0\" (or Apache-2.0 alone if preferred), repository (github), readme, expanded description (one-line), keywords, categories. Add a `version = \"...\"` clause alongside every `path = \"..\"` inter-crate dep so consumers from the registry resolve correctly while local dev still uses path. Verify name availability on crates.io for all seven names — if any is taken, propose an alternative now (e.g. `anthill-lang-core`). Decide initial version: probably 0.1.0 to signal pre-stable; add CHANGELOG.md per crate or a single workspace-level one. Acceptance: cargo publish --dry-run --allow-dirty succeeds for every crate in dependency order (anthill-core first, leaf crates last); a RELEASE.md runbook lives in the repo root documenting the publish order, version-bump checklist, and yank policy; CI gate that runs `cargo publish --dry-run` for changed crates on PR. Out of scope for v1: cargo-release / release-please automation; signed releases; private mirror. Driver: WI-009 (the anthill-todo port) ships as `cargo install anthill-todo` once this lands. Sibling track: a follow-up Path-B git-rev mode for `anthill codegen bundle` lands first as a stopgap so iterations on WI-009 can keep moving without polluting the registry; that work is captured separately.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-166",
  description: "scaland — make match expression `end` keyword optional. Today scaland's matchExpr requires an explicit `end` keyword to terminate the arm list (`match scrut case ... case ... end`). Stdlib cli/help.anthill and cli/parse.anthill use the indentation-delimited form without trailing `end`. Both files fail to parse mid-format_help / parse_argv operation because matchBranch.rep(1) stops at the next non-case token, then matchExpr requires `end` and fails when it sees `operation` instead. Fix: make `keyword(\"end\")` an optional suffix (`.?`) — matchBranch.rep(1) naturally terminates at the first non-case token. Mirror reference: rustland's tree-sitter grammar accepts both forms. Files: scaland/core/src/main/scala/anthill/parse/AnthillParser.scala (one-line change to matchExpr). Acceptance: sbt test green; cli/help.anthill and cli/parse.anthill parse cleanly; new ParseTest case for indentation-delimited match.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-05-03T08:18:51Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-167",
  description: "scaland matchExpr — drop `end` keyword to mirror rustland's grammar. Originally framed as needing indentation-aware parsing for nested matches in cli/parse.anthill. Closer look at rustland's tree-sitter grammar showed: `match_expr: match scrut repeat1(match_branch)` with NO `end` keyword. cli/parse.anthill works in rust because it's written so the greedy-inner parse matches human intent — every nested match is followed by `operation` or end-of-block, never by another outer `case`. WI-166 had introduced `keyword(\"end\").?` as an OPTIONAL terminator; that was the actual bug — matchExpr greedily consumed the `end` belonging to the enclosing sort. Fix: drop `end` from matchExpr entirely; matchBranch.rep(1) self-terminates at the first non-`case` token, identical to rust. No indentation tracking, no columnOf, no divergence. cli/parse.anthill parses cleanly. Files: scaland/core/src/main/scala/anthill/parse/AnthillParser.scala (matchExpr — one-line revert of WI-166's end.? addition). Acceptance: sbt test green; cli/parse.anthill parses cleanly.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-05-03T09:12:38Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-168",
  description: "Revise proposal 007 (persistence layer) for Value/TermView integration. 007 was written pre-Value (proposal 026/026.1) and reads as TermId-only — its §5 'Backward Chaining Integration' speaks neutrally of 'facts' returning from queryable stores without committing to representation. The unreconciled gap with 026.1: 007's queryable-store path (SQL retrieval, backward-chaining hooks) and 026.1 Q4's external-stream path (Value::Entity rows via bind_value, no TermStore allocation) describe overlapping concerns in unreconciled vocabularies. The 026.1 Q4 motivation (avoid hash-consing 1M rows from a 1M-row scan) is *exactly* a SQL-store scaling concern — i.e. canonical 007 use case — but Q4 is filed as 'deferred/optional' and 007 doesn't reference it. Concrete tasks: (1) Add §'Value integration' to 007 specifying that retrieved facts from queryable stores currently enter the KB via assert_fact (TermId path), hash-consing every row into the main TermStore. (2) Cross-reference 026.1 Q4 as the path for queryable-store row scaling — describe how bind_value + TermView would let SQL rows surface as Value::Entity bindings without TermStore allocation. (3) Decide and document: is 026.1 Q4 a 'future optimization' or a 'required path' for queryable stores beyond N rows? The threshold matters for downstream (proposal 033 §Open questions §5 references this gap). Alternative form: write a new proposal that synthesizes 007 + 026.1 Q4 into a unified 'external data sources' architecture, supersedes the relevant sections of both, and gives one canonical answer to 'how does external data flow through σ'. Independent of WI-075/076/033 implementation; recorded as parallel proposal-base hygiene work. Acceptance: docs/proposals/007 (or successor proposal) addresses Value integration explicitly; proposal 033 §Open questions §5 either resolved or replaced with a concrete cross-reference.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-05-03T10:34:16Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-052b",
  description: "026.1 Q4 Stage B (delivered) — routing-side wiring for external-source backends. Adds the resolver path that turns a goal whose head functor has a registered route handler into ExternalRow candidates pulled from a Box<dyn ExternalStream>. Concrete pieces: (1) RouteHandler trait + RouteRegistry on KB (kb/route.rs); (2) Candidate::ExternalRow variant in kb/resolve.rs; (3) step_init eager-drain of the registered handler's stream after the discrim-tree query, with match_view + bind_value preserving Value::Entity / Value::Str lineage; (4) is_duplicate_projection skipped when σ has any non-Term Value binding (reify can't see those, so dedup would collapse genuinely distinct external rows); (5) public KB API: register_route_handler / route_handler_for. Acceptance: tests/route_dispatch_test.rs::stage_b_routed_goal_yields_external_rows — register a 3-row WorkItemBackend, query WorkItem(id: ?, description: ?), assert 3 distinct solutions surface as Value::Str bindings, and KB.term_store_len() unchanged from baseline. All workspace tests pass. Follow-ups (separate WIs): (a) lazy per-iteration stream pumping (current path is eager-drain — correct, but materializes a Candidate per matching row); (b) anthill-level retrieve(store, pattern) builtin matching the stdlib operation signature in stdlib/anthill/persistence/store.anthill (currently List[Term]; needs to evolve to Stream[Term] to align with Q4 — design decision pending); (c) consult anthill-level route(GoalSort(?))=Store rules at resolution time instead of the direct functor→handler registry (concrete-backend-driven).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-052"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-03T13:55:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-169",
  description: "Synth-rule lifetime management. Proposal 033 §M4 / WI-076 introduced `synthesize_conjunction_rule` (kb/execute.rs) which asserts a fresh `_synth_N(?vars) :- body` rule into the KB on every multi-goal disjunction or negation branch lowering. The synth rule persists for the lifetime of the KB — long-running processes that issue many reflect queries with multi-goal branches accumulate symbol-table entries, RuleEntry allocations, and discrim-tree leaves indefinitely. Each synth functor is unique by construction, so structural dedup never collapses identical synths. The cost per call is bounded (~one rule + one symbol + one discrim leaf) but unbounded in aggregate. Concrete fix options: (a) Have `execute_logical_query` return a SearchStream wrapper that retracts collected synth RuleIds on drop. `KnowledgeBase::retract` (kb/mod.rs:710) already handles index/refcount cleanup correctly. (b) Track synth rules in a per-query arena and bulk-retract after stream exhaustion. (c) Cache by structural body hash so repeated identical queries reuse one synth rule. The interned synth symbol can't be reclaimed without symbol-table GC, but bounding RuleEntry growth is the larger leak. Acceptance: long-running test that issues N multi-goal disjunction queries asserts KB rule count stays bounded (or grows by less than N). Background: kb/eval/builtins.rs:543 (kb_execute) is the long-running entry point; tests/eval_q3_test.rs::q3_disjunction_multi_goal_branch_lifts_via_synthesized_rule etc. exercise the synth path.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-076"],
  status: Open)

