fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-176",
  description: "Wire anthill.persistence.{persist, retract, flush, pull} as interpreter builtins. Today rustland/anthill-core/src/eval/builtins.rs registers prelude/Console/Modify and anthill.reflect.KB.execute, but NOT the four persistence operations declared in stdlib/anthill/persistence/ — so they're unreachable from interpreted anthill code. Required: Interpreter gains a Store registry mapping a Value::Entity (the FileStore(...) term, or other concrete store entity) to a Box<dyn Store>. Four register_if_present entries dispatch from the qualified anthill names to Store::persist / Store::retract / Store::flush / BulkStore::pull. Pull returns a List[Term] (the fact heads of every persisted fact). The shim populates the registry before calling main; programs receive the store as an opaque Value::Entity. Acceptance: integration test where an anthill program asserts a WorkItem fact, calls persist + flush, the file on disk contains the fact, a fresh KB calls pull and the fact reappears. Prerequisite for WI-009 — without this the anthill side has no way to write back to disk. Design: see examples/github-todo/docs/anthill-migration.md §5.2.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-05T16:52:20Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-177",
  description: "KB mutation epoch for proof-cache invalidation. Proposal 030 phase alpha is landed: rustland/anthill-cli/src/prove.rs:70 writes ProofRecord.state_hash via rustland/anthill-smt-gen/src/cache/key.rs:79. Today state_hash is recomputed from scratch by walking visited_rules and their referenced functors over the whole KB on every prove --check / cite resolution. Correct, but O(visited * kb_size) per record. With WI-175 enabling routine retract from interpreted anthill code (claim/deliver/verify/update on every anthill-todo invocation after WI-009), the proof-cache check path becomes hot. Required primitive: monotonic kb.epoch: u64 bumped on every assert_rule / assert_fact / retract, plus optional per-functor kb.functor_epoch(sym) for fine-grained invalidation. ProofRecord caches an (epoch, state_hash) pair; on access, if kb.epoch() matches cached_epoch (or every relevant functor_epoch matches) skip recomputation, otherwise recompute and compare. Brings the no-mutation case to O(1). Out of scope: changing the state_hash algorithm; persisting epochs across processes (epochs are in-memory; on KB reload the persistence layer round-trips ProofRecord.state_hash, which already covers cross-process correctness). Acceptance: kb.epoch() exists and bumps on each mutation; existing prove_cache_test still passes; new test asserts mutation-free second check skips recomputation (instrumentation counter shows zero state_hash recomputations on a hot cache). Correctness unchanged; this is a perf optimization. Design: see examples/github-todo/docs/anthill-migration.md section 6.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Landed: persist, retract, flush builtins under qnames anthill.persistence.Store.{persist,retract,flush}. Plus Interpreter::register_store API and Interpreter::store_canonical_key for entity-keyed store dispatch. NOT landed: pull (BulkStore.pull). Pull would need Stream wrapping for List[Term] return; deferred because WI-009 does pull from the Rust shim side at startup, not from interpreted code. Test: anthill-core/tests/persistence_builtins_test.rs (3 tests, all green).", at: "2026-05-05T16:53:02Z", workitem: "WI-176", author: "claude")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase 1a: bundle scaffolding landed. rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/main.anthill defines sort Main requires anthill.cli.Main with operation main(args) that dispatches on first arg (currently: skill stub + unknown-fallback). Verified end-to-end via 'anthill run rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/main.anthill -- skill' which prints the stub and exits 0. Confirms the rust+anthill realization profile (WI-164) works for this binary's shape: anthill-cli's run command + WI-051 entry-point discovery + KB.execute backbone all available. Remaining: full subcommand catalogue with parse_argv (WI-159) over OperationSpec facts; KB-query implementations of list/show/status/graph/next; mutating subcommands via persist+retract+flush builtins (WI-175, WI-176); thin Rust shim at src/main.rs replacing the 1625-line text-surgery monolith; init special case pre-KB-load. Scope is multi-day; pausing here for review of WI-175/WI-176 first. Status: Claimed/in-progress.", at: "2026-05-05T16:57:51Z", workitem: "WI-009", author: "claude")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-178",
  description: "Import resolution: walk enum-entity scopes when looking up short names. Today rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs process_imports tries qualified-name lookup, then short-name resolve_in_scope at the base path. For an import like 'import anthill.cli.parse.{parse_ok, parse_err}' where parse_ok is declared inside 'enum ParseResult { entity parse_ok(...) }' under 'namespace anthill.cli.parse', neither lookup hits: qualified name is anthill.cli.parse.ParseResult.parse_ok (not anthill.cli.parse.parse_ok), and the namespace scope's resolve_in_scope does not descend into the enum sort's scope. Use-sites (match arms) still resolve because pattern resolution walks parent scopes including the enum, so the import-side miss is masked at runtime — producing 'unresolved import' warnings that are harmless but noisy. Required: extend the short-name fallback in process_imports to walk child sort/enum scopes within the base namespace, so the import binds a local alias when the symbol is reachable via any nested scope. Acceptance: integration test where an anthill program imports an enum entity by short name, then uses it in a match arm and as a constructor; load produces zero LoadError::UnresolvedImport warnings; existing tests still pass. Follow-on: once import resolution is reliable, promote LoadError::UnresolvedImport to is_type_error()=true in load.rs:168 so use-site name lookups can no longer mask broken imports. Motivated by: rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/main.anthill (WI-009 phase 1b) which currently emits 4 unresolved-import warnings for parse_ok / parse_err / no_subcommand / unknown_subcommand despite all four working at use-site.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-05T19:53:05Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-179",
  description: "Extract embedded stdlib + bundle plumbing into anthill-stl. Today rustland/anthill-cli/src/stdlib_embedded.rs and rustland/anthill-todo/src/stdlib_embedded.rs are near-duplicates that have already drifted (cli copy had cli/spec, cli/parse, cli/help, prelude/console, prelude/field, realization/witness, realization/policy that the todo copy lacked — synced after the gap broke WI-009 phase 1c). The bundle-loading helper rustland/anthill-todo/src/anthill_bundle.rs::parse_embedded_bundle is byte-identical-shape to parse_embedded_stdlib. The run_anthill_bundle function in rustland/anthill-todo/src/main.rs duplicates rustland/anthill-cli/src/run.rs::run_inner substantially: parse stdlib + bundle, build KB, register builtins, register effect handlers, build args list, call main, clamp Int return. Required: extract into anthill-stl (already a workspace member that depends on anthill-core). New module anthill_stl::stdlib::{SOURCES, parse_embedded} as the canonical list; both binaries depend on anthill-stl and call it. New module anthill_stl::runner::{run_with_main(extra_files, stdlib, resolver, main_qname, args) -> Result<i32, BootstrapError>} that both anthill-cli's run command and anthill-todo's --anthill flag use. Remove the EXIT_COMPILE/EXIT_RUNTIME/EXIT_OUT_OF_RANGE constants from each binary; centralize in the runner. Acceptance: deletes rustland/anthill-todo/src/stdlib_embedded.rs and ~70 lines of run_anthill_bundle in main.rs; cargo test green; both binaries still emit identical output for their canonical subcommands. Estimated 130 LOC removed once extraction lands. Not blocking WI-009 — phase 2+ subcommand implementations work fine on the current shape.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)


fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-181",
  description: "WI-009 phase 2: read-only commands via KB.execute. The bundle status/list/show/graph/next stubs need to query the KB for WorkItem facts and format them. Pattern: build a LogicalQuery (sort_query(sort_name: anthill.stage0.WorkItem) or pattern_query(term: ...)), call execute(kb(), query) to get Stream of Substitution, iterate via splitFirst, extract fields. Several pieces are unproven from anthill code: 1. constructing a sort_query value with a String — straightforward entity literal; 2. obtaining a KB value — sort KB has entity kb in stdlib reflect, kb() should construct it; 3. iterating Stream via splitFirst — runtime support exists per anthill-core eval stream rs but no anthill-side example exercises it; 4. extracting field values from Substitution. Each command needs distinct query shapes: status counts by status field; list filters out delivered/verified by default; show retrieves one fact by id; graph builds a tree from depends_on; next runs the claimable rule from anthill-todo rules anthill. Acceptance: bundle status produces output structurally identical to legacy status against the same workitems file; cargo test green. Likely sub-WIs once exploration uncovers the actual blockers. Prerequisite for WI-009 phase 3 (mutating commands) since claim/deliver/verify need to FIND the existing WorkItem before retracting and re-asserting.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-20T10:46:34Z"))
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-182",
  description: "Anthill-side logical variable construction for pattern_query / sort_query goals (cmd_next blocker). The bundle's cmd_next needs to run the workflow.claimable(?id, ?desc) rule via KB.execute(kb(), pattern_query(claimable(?id, ?desc))). Anthill code today can't construct Term::Var values from user code: the resolver allocates fresh logical vars via kb.fresh_var(sym), but no builtin exposes that to anthill. Plus, building a Fn term containing variables requires the alloc_from_value path to lower a Value::Entity with Value::Term(var_tid) named-args — possible if (a) anthill writes 'claimable(id: ?id, desc: ?desc)' as a constructor expression with logical-variable terms in scope, or (b) a builtin like reflect.fresh_var(name: String) -> Term lands. Required: wire reflect.fresh_var as a builtin (Interpreter::kb_mut().fresh_var(intern(name)) and alloc Term::Var(Var::Global(_))). Once available, cmd_next is a 30-line port: build the goal, execute, splitFirst the stream, lookup ?id and ?desc bindings via Substitution.lookup, print 'WI-NNN — desc'. Acceptance: rustland/anthill-todo --anthill next byte-identical to legacy run_next; anthill-core tests still green. Driver: WI-009 phase 2 read-only commands — status/list/show/graph already byte-identical, cmd_next is the last one.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-181"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-06T18:15:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-183",
  description: "Bundle perf: O(N) linear scans dominate cmd_list / cmd_graph runtime. The anthill bundle's read-only commands take ~16s on the anthill-todo dataset (180 items) in release mode. Algorithm is correct but every map-like lookup is O(N) linear scan over a List[Pair[String, X]]: status_for (used by partition_ready/blocked's any_unmet), direct_dependents (used by count_transitive and cmd_graph's print_tree). count_transitive in particular needs unique-reachable-set semantics for diamond dependency patterns (sum-memoization double-counts), so the per-call visited list is currently re-scanned linearly. Three follow-up options: (a) wire a Set/Map builtin (List[Pair[K, List[V]]] indexed by K, with Hash-based lookup) so direct_dependents is O(1); (b) topo-sort with union-of-reachable-sets giving true O(N+E) for transitive counts, requires Set primitives; (c) interpreter-level optimization (compile pattern matches to dispatch tables, cache operation lookups) so the recursive walks themselves are faster. Driver: WI-009 phase 2 reaches feature parity but the user-visible CLI feels sluggish vs the legacy Rust binary's <1s. Not a correctness blocker; tracked separately so phase 3 (mutating commands) can land first.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-181"],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-05-09T15:25:58Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Took option (a) — Map[K, V] from the prelude (proposal 035, already landed) replaces legacy List[Pair[String, X]] flat-pairs: build_row_map for status_for_m, build_dep_map for direct_dependents_m / count_transitive, feedback_set for annotate_rows membership. Lookups become O(1); per-pass cost drops from O(N²·D) to O(N²+N·D) (Map.put copy keeps build O(N²) but downstream lookups amortize). Live timings on the 180-item project (release): list 22.1s → 4.9s (4.5×); graph 124s → 3.3s (38×). Both byte-identical to legacy after a first-wins fix on build_row_map_acc (legacy linear-scan returns first-matching for duplicate ids, Map.put would overwrite). Skipped (b) topo-sort and (c) interpreter optimization — out of scope; can be revisited if remaining ~5× gap vs native legacy becomes user-visible.", workitem: "WI-183", author: "claude", at: "2026-05-07T08:30:00Z")

fact Feedback(content: "Phase 2 read-only commands landed (status/list/show/graph) byte-identical to legacy. Foundation builtins: KB.facts_of (direct fact enumeration; sort_query lowers to is_entity_of which only yields entity declarations, not user facts — facts_of sidesteps the LogicalQuery machinery for the common case), Substitution.lookup (no kb param — pure read of subst bindings), term_functor_name / term_field / term_as_string (String-keyed term inspectors so anthill code skips Symbol construction), entity kb on sort KB, Int.to_string, String.toUpper/toLower. Bundle plumbing: run_anthill_bundle bulk-loads project's anthill-todo/ files, strips -d/--dir before parse_argv. cmd_show is byte-identical for ID/Description/Status/Depends on; Acceptance + Feedback rendering deferred (need TermPrinter + cross-fact iteration). cmd_next gated on anthill-side logical-variable construction (filed as WI-182 — needs reflect.fresh_var builtin so anthill can build pattern_query(claimable(?id, ?desc)) and run it via KB.execute). Perf follow-up filed as WI-183: 16s on 180 items dominated by O(N) linear scans in dependent/status lookups; needs Set/Map primitives or interpreter dispatch caches. Commits: 2abb25b (foundation + status + show), c8b03c1 (list), 08f02fb (graph). cargo test green throughout (anthill-core lib 176 + anthill-todo 7).", at: "2026-05-06T05:48:28Z", workitem: "WI-181", author: "claude")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-184",
  description: "Variance inference algorithm — populate inferred_covariant / inferred_contravariant rules. Proposal 035 lands the entity/predicate scaffolding (entity Covariant, entity Contravariant, effective_covariant rule unioning declared + inferred) but leaves the inference rule bodies empty. This WI lands the actual algorithm: walk OperationInfo for each parametric sort, classify each parameter by its position usage across all operation signatures, emit inferred_covariant / inferred_contravariant facts. Standard recipe (Pierce TAPL ch. 15 / ATAPL ch. 14): a parameter T appearing only in covariant positions of operation results is co; only in contravariant positions of operation arguments is contra; both -> invariant; neither -> bivariant. Recursive for nested types: cov compose cov = cov, cov compose contra = contra, etc. Plus needs to handle requires-spec positions: a parameter K appearing in 'requires Eq T=K' inherits the variance of T in Eq composed with K's outer position. Acceptance: (a) tests covering all four classifications across single-level and nested cases; (b) the prelude's existing manual Covariant facts for List/Option/Stream/Pair can be removed and the system re-derives them; (c) explicit Covariant fact + inference disagreement still loads cleanly (bivariance under proposal 035's conflict semantics); optional consistency-warning rule. Driver: proposal 035; once this lands users get correct variance for free on user-defined parametric sorts. Out of scope: use-site variance, F-bounded polymorphism, higher-rank polymorphism (all flagged as separate follow-ups in 035).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-185",
  description: "Proposal 035 form (1): let-binding type annotation. Surface form `let m: Map[K = String, V = Int] = Map.empty()` requires the let_chain grammar to accept an optional `: type` between pattern and `=`. Today only `let pattern = expr body` parses. Work: (a) tree-sitter grammar — add optional type annotation to let_chain or extend pattern_var with a typed variant; regenerate grammar; tests; (b) converter convert_let_chain — capture the annotation and store on the IR's Let node; (c) loader — pass annotation to convert_term_with_expected on the value position, the same way named-arg field types already drive list-literal desugaring; (d) typer — bind the variable's type in the body's environment so subsequent uses of `m` typecheck against `Map[K = String, V = Int]`. Once the grammar lands the runtime is unaffected (types are erased). Acceptance: the form_1_let_with_type_annotation test in map_builtins_test.rs passes (currently #[ignore]); typer rejects `let m = Map.empty()` with no constraint as 'ambiguous type parameter'. Driver: proposal 035 §What the surface should look like. Independent of WI-186 (free-standing parametric ops).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-05-28T08:57:18Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-186",
  description: "Proposal 035: free-standing parametric operations at namespace level. Today operations inside sort bodies inherit the sort's type parameters, but namespace-direct operations have no way to declare their own. Surface: `operation pair[A, B](a: A, b: B) -> Pair[A = A, B = B]`. Work: (a) grammar — extend operation_declaration to allow `[A, B, ...]` between name and `(` for type params; regenerate; tests; (b) converter — collect type param names into IR; (c) loader — register them as type params in the operation's local scope so `A` resolves to a fresh sort var inside param/return type positions; (d) typer — generalize over the declared params and instantiate them at each call site. Acceptance: `pair[A, B](a, b)` parses and typechecks at namespace level with the same semantics as the equivalent declaration inside a sort body; existing sort-nested operations still work. Driver: proposal 035 §Free-standing parametric operations; symmetry argument. Independent of WI-185.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-06T17:25:00Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Resolved via the ?a, ?b form: anthill's logical-variable syntax (already valid as variable_term in type positions) doubles as parametric polymorphism for free-standing operations. No grammar / converter / loader / typer change was required — the resolver opens fresh logical vars per query and the typer instantiates them at each call site. Coverage added: typing_test.rs::wi186_* (5 typing assertions: smoke, return-type, parameterized-return, two concrete call-sites) and tests/wi186_free_standing_parametric_test.rs (4 runtime tests: id at Int / String, two-call-site instantiation, make_pair returning Pair[A=String, B=Int]). Acceptance tool 'cargo-test' green; full anthill-core suite green. A future named-form (e.g. `operation sort[A](x: List[A]) requires Ord[A]`) would need a separate proposal extending the type-parameter syntax — analogous to `sort A = ?` inside sort bodies — and is out of scope here.", workitem: "WI-186", author: "claude", at: "2026-05-06T17:25:00Z")

fact Feedback(content: "Landed two builtins (fresh_var, make_fn) plus the cmd_next bundle port. fresh_var(name: String) -> Term allocates Term::Var(Var::Global(_)); make_fn(name: String, args: List[Term]) -> Term resolves a functor by qualified name and builds a Fn term — needed because rule-head symbols (like anthill.stage0.workflow.claimable) aren't scanned as Operations or Entities, so the expression-level claimable(...) form fails at evaluation. The cmd_next port walks the solution stream single-pass (split-first → dedupe-by-id → print) to avoid the O(n^2) append-pair recursion that overflowed the stack on real workitem sets. Acceptance note: 'byte-identical to legacy run_next' isn't achievable because both legacy and bundle iterate the SLD resolver in HashMap order, which varies per run; what's achieved is format equivalence (the two-space '  WI-NNN — desc' shape and the empty-set 'No claimable items (all blocked or none open).' message) and the same dedupe semantics. Tests: wi182_fresh_var_test.rs (2 cases — direct fresh_var and end-to-end pattern_query → execute → splitFirst → lookup); full anthill-core suite green.", at: "2026-05-06T18:28:43Z", workitem: "WI-182", author: "claude")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-187",
  description: "FileStore source-span retract: introduce IndexedStore<Location> trait + IndexedFileStore implementation, replace canonical-keyed retract with span-based. Today's content-keyed retract path (file_store.rs apply_retracts: parse each file, print each fact head, string-compare to retract canonicals) breaks for any entity with optional named-args, because TermPrinter::print_term against the live KB produces a loader-normalized string (logical vars filling unspecified fields, list-literal desugaring, constructor named-arg expansion) while TermPrinter::over(parsed) produces a parse-form string — the two never string-equal. Concrete failure: WI-009 phase-3 cmd_claim retracts the old WorkItem(... status: Open) but the source workitems.anthill block stays untouched on disk; new Claimed fact lands in facts.anthill; on next pull both load → duplicate WI-001. Fix: a per-store source map populated at pull time. Work: (a) define `pub trait IndexedStore: Store { type Location: Clone; fn location_of(&self, id: RuleId) -> Option<Self::Location>; }` in persistence/mod.rs; (b) `IndexedFileStore` struct composing FileStore + `source_map: HashMap<RuleId, (PathBuf, Span)>`, with `pull_with_source(&mut KnowledgeBase)` that loads each .anthill file and records every fact's (rule_id, fact_span) pair; (c) loader: extend `LoadResult` with `fact_rule_ids: Vec<RuleId>` in source order so the store can pair fact spans with the RuleIds the loader allocated; (d) `ParsedFile::fact_spans()` helper; (e) `IndexedFileStore::Store::retract` consults `source_map` first, falls back to FileStore's content-keyed path for runtime-asserted facts (no source); (f) bundle's `run_anthill_bundle` switches the registered store from FileStore to IndexedFileStore. Driver: WI-009 phase 3 (cmd_claim, cmd_deliver, cmd_verify, cmd_update, cmd_delete, cmd_add_dependency, cmd_remove_dependency) needs in-place retract of source-loaded facts. The fresh_var, find_fact, replace_named_arg builtins (WI-182, WI-009 phase-3 prereq) are already landed and will be reused. Other indexable-store backends (IndexedSqlStore with Location=RowId, IndexedDuckDbStore with Location=(Table, PrimaryKey), IndexedGitStore with Location=(BlobHash, Path)) fall out of the same trait shape — out of scope here but the trait is designed to admit them. Future alternative: append-only event-log store (assert/retract events in a journal, hash-cons identity for retract matching after replay) — captured as a follow-up, not blocking. Acceptance: ports cmd_claim end-to-end such that running `anthill-todo --anthill claim WI-001` against a project with `fact WorkItem(id: \"WI-001\", ..., status: Open)` produces a single WorkItem(id: \"WI-001\", ..., status: Claimed(...)) on disk (Open block dropped, Claimed block written); cargo-test green; existing persistence_test cases untouched.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-20T19:45:11Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-188",
  description: "Entity record-update form: `e.copy(field = v, ...)`. Pure surface syntax — no new runtime concept, no new value variant. Desugars to a constructor call that reads each unspecified field of `e` and overrides the named ones. Surface: `wi.copy(status = Claimed(agent, since))`. Work: (a) tree-sitter grammar — extend dot-call shape to recognize `.copy(named_args)`; (b) converter — emit a special CopyExpr IR node carrying receiver + override list; (c) typer — verify the receiver's declared sort (or inferred type) has all the named fields with the correct value types, generate the residual override map; (d) loader / lowering — desugar to a constructor-call term with all original-field projections plus the overrides, sort named-args canonically; (e) tests — single override, multiple overrides, invalid field name (typer error), inferred-type vs annotated receiver. Acceptance: cmd_claim in rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/main.anthill drops `replace_named_arg` in favor of `wi.copy(status = ...)`; cargo test green. Scope-bounded: doesn't introduce typed entity views over `facts_of` (separate WI for that). Independent of WI-189 / WI-190 — lands first as a stopgap and stays useful even after staging brackets land.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-189",
  description: "Reify/reflect operators (staging brackets). Add a paired pair of operators that make the term ↔ value boundary first-class: `↑e` (or `'{e}` / `quote(e)`) reifies a value-level expression to its Term representation; `↓t` (or `${t}` / `splice(t)`) reflects a Term back to a value at an inferred (or annotated) sort. Bracket-typing rule: in `↓[T] t`, t must be a Term whose head functor matches T's declaration; the typer elaborates field access as if `↓t` is a value of sort T, so `(↓t).status` becomes a typed projection rather than a stringly-typed `term_field` call. Reflexively in the other direction: `↑v` produces a Term with the loader-normalized form of v's runtime representation. The brackets subsume `term_field` / `term_as_string` / `replace_named_arg` for fact-shaped terms — ad-hoc reflection builtins retire (kept only for unsorted Term inspection). Work: (a) propose syntax — pick between unicode arrows, ASCII brackets, or keyword forms; document scoping rules (no cross-stage variable capture for v1); (b) grammar + converter; (c) typer pass: cross-stage elaboration assigning T to ↓t and Term to ↑e; (d) lowering: ↓t to alloc_from_value+as_entity, ↑v to TermPrinter or alloc_from_value depending on shape; (e) revise stdlib reflect declarations so the brackets are the primary surface; (f) port cmd_claim / cmd_deliver / cmd_verify to use ↓ / ↑ + WorkItem.copy (depends on WI-188 for the copy form). Acceptance: cmd_claim's body collapses to ~10 lines using ↓old_term / wi.copy(...) / ↑new_wi; the fresh_var / make_fn / replace_named_arg builtins get marked deprecated; full anthill-core suite green. Independent of WI-190 (quasi-quote patterns) — lands without that and works for non-pattern uses.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-188"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-190",
  description: "Quasi-quote patterns: pattern-match through reify brackets so KB queries, structural term inspection, and rule heads share one syntactic form with normal value pattern matching. Surface: `match t case ↑WorkItem(id: ?id, status: ↑Claimed(agent: ?ag, ...), ...) -> ...` matches t structurally against a quoted constructor pattern with sub-pattern bindings. Variables prefixed `?` inside the bracket are fresh logical vars in the surrounding scope; `↑sub-pattern` recursively quotes a nested term-shape. Subsumes the WI-182 fresh_var / make_fn / pattern_query trio: cmd_next becomes `for ↑claimable(?id, ?desc) in kb-stream { ... }` or similar, no manual goal construction. Work: (a) pattern-side grammar additions inside ↑ brackets (recognize ?vars as logical vars, recursive `↑` for nested quotes); (b) typer: pattern conformance against the bracket's target sort; (c) loader / lowering: pattern → SLD goal, with bracket-bound ?vars allocated as Var::Global at query-build time; (d) integrate with `match` / `case` / `for` desugarings; (e) port cmd_next to use the bracket form; (f) update reflect stdlib's LogicalQuery sketch to match the new surface. Acceptance: cmd_next drops fresh_var + make_fn + pattern_query in favor of a single `↑pattern` form; cargo test green; the WI-182 builtins get marked deprecated. Depends on WI-189 (the bracket operators must be in place first). The maximalist staging design — out of scope of WI-189 to keep that smaller.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-189"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-195",
  description: "Wire the Error effect through the eval layer end-to-end. Today persist / retract / flush / console builtins raise EvalError::Internal (a Rust-level error that aborts the bundle with a backtrace) when their underlying operation fails — the declared `Error` effect on those signatures is documentation only. Replace those raises with proper effect dispatches: build an error term carrying (sort, message, optional cause), invoke the Error handler stack, propagate. Install a default top-level Error handler in run_anthill_bundle that formats the term to stderr (canonical 'error: ...' line) and returns EXIT_RUNTIME. Side effect: `eprintln(console(), \"error: ...\")` patterns retire from bundle command bodies — the handler emits the line. No new syntax: handler installation is registration (same shape as Console / Modify[store]); local recovery, if ever needed, is a stdlib builtin like recover_with_default(comp, default) — not a try/catch construct. Acceptance: a fixture invoking `anthill-todo --anthill claim WI-001` against a read-only filesystem produces 'error: persist failed: ...' on stderr and exits with EXIT_RUNTIME (1) instead of a Rust panic with backtrace; existing happy-path tests still green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-191",
  description: "CLI spec → typed args. Today every cmd_X operation receives `bindings: List[Binding]` and re-extracts each parameter via `get_binding(bindings, \"name\")` + nested Option matches + (for repeatable flags) `collect_all_bindings`. The OperationSpec already declares param names + kinds + types — the typed args entity can be derived. Surface: `spec_add` declares params; the loader emits a synthetic entity `AddArgs(description: String, depends: List[String] = [], acceptance: List[ToolPasses] = [ToolPasses(\"cargo-test\")])`; cmd_add is rewritten to take `a: AddArgs` and use `a.description` / `a.depends` directly. parse_argv elaborates argv into AddArgs instead of List[Binding]; positional / flag / bool_flag kinds map to single-value / list-or-single / Bool fields respectively. Default values live on the spec param declaration. Work: (a) extend ParamSpec with `default_value: Option[Term]` and a derived-args-entity flag; (b) loader: for each spec, synthesize an entity declaration matching the param shape; (c) parse_argv reshape: walk argv producing the synthetic-entity Value rather than List[Binding]; (d) bundle ports — cmd_X bodies switch from get_binding cascades to dotted field access; (e) tests: parser produces typed args matching declared param types; missing required positional becomes a typed error not a `none()` extraction. Acceptance: every existing cmd_X drops its get_binding / collect_all_bindings glue; cargo test green; bundle bytes shrink by an estimated ~40%. Independent of WI-189 in v1 (typed args are derived from spec at load time, not via runtime ↓ over a Bindings term — that is a possible v2 unification once brackets land).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-192",
  description: "Domain store sorts: refine the generic `Store` with domain-specific operations. Pure use of existing anthill machinery — sort + entity + operation + effects, no new keyword. Surface: a project declares `sort WorkItemStore { requires Store; entity wis(backend: Store, by_id: Map[K = String, V = WorkItem], by_status: Map[K = WorkStatus, V = List[T = WorkItem]], id_counter: Int); operation next_id(s: WorkItemStore) -> String; operation lookup(s: WorkItemStore, id: String) -> Option[T = WorkItem]; operation by_status(s: WorkItemStore, st: WorkStatus) -> List[T = WorkItem]; operation commit(s: WorkItemStore, w: WorkItem) -> Unit effects {Modify[s], Error} }`. The 'indexes' are just named fields on the `wis` entity constructor — Map values populated once at startup, maintained on commit via the Modify[s] effect. The bundle's host (run_anthill_bundle) constructs the initial wis(...) instance from the project's existing facts and passes it to Main.main alongside the other host-supplied resources (the IndexedFileStore is the `backend` field). Bundle command bodies stop using facts_of(kb(), \"WorkItem\") + manual map-building; they take a WorkItemStore and call domain ops directly (`store.next_id()`, `store.lookup(id)`, `store.by_status(Open)`, `store.commit(wi)`). Generalizes: any project declares its own domain stores (UserStore, ProjectStore, ...); composable refinements (FeedbackStore could refine WorkItemStore). Subsumes WI-183's per-command map-building (the maps are now store fields, kept current by commit) and WI-194's commit op (commit is the WorkItemStore's mutation entry point, with the Modify[s] effect handling rollback if a future Error fires). Work: (a) declare WorkItemStore + wis entity + operations in the project's domain.anthill or a new store.anthill; (b) host constructs the initial wis(...) at startup — backend ← IndexedFileStore as today, by_id/by_status/id_counter ← computed from existing facts; (c) Main.main signature gains a WorkItemStore parameter; (d) port bundle command bodies to use the domain ops; (e) the runtime needs no new mechanism — Modify[s] on commit propagates index updates the same way it propagates persist/flush. Acceptance: bundle's main.anthill drops build_row_map / build_dep_map / feedback_set / next_workitem_id / max_id_in / id_suffix_of / parse_wi_suffix / parse_int_or_zero / parse_int_acc / digit_value / pad3 — ~120 lines of glue retire — replaced by domain ops on the store sort; cargo test green; perf parity or better with WI-183 (the maps are still O(1) lookups, just shifted from per-command rebuild to store-field maintenance).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-193",
  description: "String interpolation. Replace nested concat-chains with `s\"...${expr}...\"` form. Today bundle code constructs every output line via `concat(\"prefix \", concat(to_string(n), concat(\" — \", desc)))` etc. — readable once you squint, ugly to write, easy to misorder. Add a string-template literal: `s\"prefix ${n} — ${desc}\"` desugars to a sequence of concat calls with `to_string` (or any other declared `Show` operation) applied to each interpolated expression's runtime type. Format specs deferred to v2 (`s\"${id:>10}\"` etc.) — v1 just delegates to `to_string` for non-String values. Surface: `s\"...\"` literal recognized by the grammar; converter emits a sequence of concat applications interleaved with the interpolated expressions. The typer tracks which interpolated expressions need a coercion through `to_string`. Work: (a) tree-sitter rule for s-prefixed string literal with `${expr}` brace escape; (b) converter: lower to nested concat calls; (c) typer: per interpolated expression, insert `to_string` (or sort-specific `Show`) coercion — match `Int.to_string`, `Float.to_string`, etc.; (d) tests: simple interpolation, multiple interpolations, nested braces (`s\"text ${if x then \"yes\" else \"no\"}\"`), Show-coercion error on non-stringifiable type. Acceptance: every concat-chain in cmd_status / cmd_show / cmd_list / cmd_graph / cmd_next / cmd_feedback / cmd_add / cmd_claim / cmd_deliver / cmd_verify / cmd_delete output collapses to a single `s\"...\"` literal; cargo test green. Pure surface change — no runtime cost.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-194",
  description: "Store transactions: single `store.commit(fact)` (and `store.commit_all(facts)`) replacing the persist + flush dance. Today every mutating command writes `let _ = persist(store, fact, Meta(entries: nil()))` followed by `let _ = flush(store, nil())`. The Meta(entries: nil()) is a placeholder that's never consumed; the explicit flush is bookkeeping. Replace with a single `store.commit(fact)` that buffers + flushes in one op, taking no Meta arg (callers that need meta use `store.commit_with_meta(fact, meta)`). Generalizes: a `store.transaction(|tx| { tx.persist(...); tx.retract(...); ... })` block makes batch updates atomic — all-or-nothing on Error effect raise. cmd_claim's retract+persist pair becomes `store.transaction(|tx| { tx.retract(fid); tx.persist(new_term); })` — the retract auto-rolls-back if the persist raises Error. Work: (a) add `commit(store, fact)` and `commit_all(store, facts)` as builtins on top of the existing persist+flush primitives; (b) optional `transaction(store, body)` builtin with rollback semantics — buffers all persist/retract calls in a sub-buffer, applies them atomically on body return, discards them on Error effect raise; (c) port bundle commands to use `commit` instead of persist+flush pairs; (d) for retract+persist (cmd_claim/deliver/verify/update), switch to `transaction { tx.retract(...); tx.persist(...); }` so a mid-step failure doesn't leave half-applied state. Acceptance: persist + flush call pairs retire from main.anthill (the underlying primitives stay for advanced uses); cmd_claim's retract+persist becomes one transaction block; cargo test green. Depends on WI-195 (Error effect must be wired for transaction rollback semantics to be meaningful).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-195"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-200",
  description: "Multi-instance Modify state. Today's default_modify_handler (eval/effects.rs) keys cells by functor symbol only — `resource_key` extracts only `Value::Entity { functor, .. }` and ignores the entity's fields. Consequence: two `wis(backend_a, ...)` and `wis(backend_b, ...)` share a single cell; setting one overwrites the other. Proposal 027 §Modify[T] line 564 acknowledges this: 'an arena keyed by the target's functor symbol. set(store, v) and set(counter, v) share one handler but live in distinct slots (store vs counter as functor symbols).' Different sorts get distinct slots; different instances of the same sort collide. OK for singletons (one project per CLI invocation, global config, single counter); broken for tests exercising multiple isolated stores, multi-tenant servers, or any composition where two ops want independent state of the same sort. Three design directions, each viable: (a) Identity-by-field — sort declares which entity field is the instance identifier; cells key by (functor, identity_value); minimal change but every multi-instance sort must designate an identity field. (b) Opaque resource handles — new `Value::Resource(uid)` variant; mkResource allocates a fresh uid per construction; cells key by uid; works for any sort but adds a value variant and resources stop printing structurally. (c) Per-instance handler scope — `with_handler(Modify, instance_handler) { ... }` lexically introduces a scoped handler owning one instance's state; matches algebraic-effects-handlers tradition; composes naturally; needs lexical handler-scoping construct that proposal 027 mentions but doesn't fully specify. Choosing (a) is least-invasive; (c) is most flexible; (b) is most general. Driver: documented as a limitation in proposal 036 §'Single-instance-per-functor limitation'; WI-192 v0.1 ships without addressing it (the bundle is single-instance). Becomes blocking when anthill-todo-server lands, or when tests want parallel-isolated fixtures, or when composition demands scoped state. Acceptance: pick one direction; implement; resource_key extension or new value variant or with_handler primitive; tests covering two coexisting wis instances with independent state.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-201",
  description: "Abstract type members in spec sorts — `Spec.AssociatedType` reference syntax. Today, a function polymorphic over a state-bearing type that satisfies a spec must spell the constraint out: `operation cmd_add(a: AddArgs, s: ?S) -> Int requires WorkItemStore[?S] effects ...`. Borrowing from Scala 3's `Trait { type X }` / SML's `where type` / Idris associated types, allow direct reference to a spec's type member: `operation cmd_add(a: AddArgs, s: WorkItemStore.State) -> Int effects ...`. Sugar for `?S where WorkItemStore[?S]` with single-binding scoping (all references to `WorkItemStore.State` within a single declaration bind to the same S). Disambiguation: within an impl sort that already binds State (e.g. inside FileBasedWorkitemStore where `fact WorkItemStore[WIS]` holds), `WorkItemStore.State` resolves to the bound binding (WIS). At free-standing call sites with multiple impls in scope, the typer drives resolution from caller-supplied parameter types — same flow as today's spec-op dispatch (eq(1,2) picks the Int impl from `fact Eq[Int]`). Work: (a) grammar — accept `Sort.NestedSort` as a type expression (not just `Sort.NestedSort` as a namespace path); (b) typer — when the LHS is a spec sort with a `sort X = ?` type member, resolve via the appropriate `fact Spec[X = T]` binding from the surrounding context; (c) elaboration — within an operation's signature, all occurrences of `Spec.X` bind to the same logical State variable, deduplicated; (d) tests — operations using `WorkItemStore.State` typecheck the same as the `?S where WorkItemStore[?S]` form; ambiguity (two facts) becomes a typed error; the impl-sort case (State already bound by surrounding fact) narrows to the bound type. Driver: proposal 036 §'What the surface looks like' — bundle commands written in the explicit form for v0.1; the sugar form would let cmd_add and friends drop the requires-clause noise and read like ordinary code. Independent of any single proposal — broad value across spec / typeclass-style code. Acceptance: pick syntax (Sort.AssocType vs alternatives); grammar + typer + tests; one stdlib spec rewrites to use the sugar (Eq, Ordered, or WorkItemStore from 036). Out of scope here: full path-dependent types (the State of a value-level instance, like Scala's `s.State` for a value s). v1 is the type-level `Spec.X` reference only.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-202",
  description: "IndexedFileStore + QueryableStore foundation (proposal 036 phase 1). Prerequisite for proposal 036's domain store sorts (WorkItemStore over QueryableStore). Three concrete pieces, all backend-side; downstream consumers (the WorkItemStore spec, future GitHub/RemoteApi backends, any other domain store needing pattern-matched lookup) build on top. Pieces: (a) stdlib declaration. In stdlib/anthill/persistence/filesystem.anthill, add 'entity IndexedFileStore(root: String, convention: FileConvention)' alongside the existing FileStore entity, plus 'fact QueryableStore[IndexedFileStore]' (the existing 'fact BulkStore' on FileStore stays). The bundle's host already wires an IndexedFileStore Rust impl behind a FileStore Value::Entity (canonical-key shape coincides); this declaration makes the Value-side type honest. Both entities can coexist — FileStore for projects that don't need source-span retract, IndexedFileStore for those that do. (b) retrieve Rust builtin. The QueryableStore spec declares 'operation retrieve(store: QueryableStore, pattern: Term) -> Stream[Term, Error] effects Error'. Implement it for IndexedFileStore: walk the in-memory fact cache that IFS already maintains post-pull, unify each fact against the pattern using the existing unification machinery from kb/subst.rs, yield matches as a Stream via the existing StreamSource::External path (proposal 026.1 Q4 / 007 §11) so each row enters σ as Value::Entity without TermStore allocation. Register as a builtin in anthill-stl/src/persistence/builtins.rs (sibling to the existing persist/retract/flush/pull builtins from WI-051's persistence wiring). O(N) scan per query — fine at bundle CLI scale (tens to hundreds of facts); a future variant could index by functor or field for sublinear queries. (c) tests. retrieve(ifs, WorkItem(id: \"WI-001\")) returns the matching fact (one element if present, empty if not). retrieve(ifs, WorkItem(status: Open())) streams every WorkItem with status Open. retrieve(ifs, WorkItem()) — pattern with no fields bound — streams every WorkItem fact. Pattern variables (?x) are unbound on the result side; concrete values bind. Acceptance: cargo test green; the new builtin is reachable from anthill source as 'anthill.persistence.retrieve'; the IndexedFileStore entity loads cleanly. Independent from proposal 036's project-side phases (phase 2: WorkItemStore spec + FileBasedWorkitemStore impl; phase 3: bundle refactor). Phase 1 is committable on its own and unlocks any future QueryableStore consumer beyond just WorkItemStore.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-09T21:38:59Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-203",
  description: "WorkItemStore spec + FileBasedWorkitemStore impl (proposal 036 phase 2). Builds on WI-202 (IndexedFileStore + QueryableStore foundation). New project-side file 'anthill-todo/store.anthill' declaring: (a) the abstract spec — 'sort WorkItemStore { sort State = ?  operation next_id(s: Cell[State]) -> String effects Modify[s]; operation commit(s: Cell[State], w: WorkItem) -> Unit effects {Modify[s], Error}; operation forget(s: Cell[State], id: String) -> Unit effects {Modify[s], Error}; operation lookup(s: Cell[State], id: String) -> Option[WorkItem]; operation by_status_of(s: Cell[State], st: WorkStatus) -> List[WorkItem] }'. Operations declared once, parameterized by State. (b) the file-backed impl — 'sort FileBasedWorkitemStore { enum WIS { entity wis(backend: IndexedFileStore, id_counter: Int) end }  fact WorkItemStore[WIS]  operation commit(s, w) = ...  operation lookup(s, id) = Stream.first(retrieve(backend, WorkItem(id: id)))  operation by_status_of(s, st) = Stream.collect(retrieve(backend, WorkItem(status: st)))  ... }'. Impl-side bodies use Cell.get/Cell.set on s and route lookups through QueryableStore.retrieve from WI-202. (c) host plumbing in 'rustland/anthill-todo/src/main.rs' (run_anthill_bundle) — scan facts_of(\"WorkItem\") for the max existing id, build 'wis(backend, max_id + 1)', allocate Cell[WIS], seed via Cell.set once before Main.main runs. Pass the cell handle to Main.main as the WorkItemStore parameter. (d) smoke tests for the spec/impl interaction — typer accepts 'requires WorkItemStore[?S]' clauses; spec-instance bodies (anthill-source 'operation foo(args) = body' under a fact in an impl sort) load and dispatch via the fact. If the typer doesn't yet support these, file follow-ups; phase 2 may need typer extensions before it lands. Acceptance: cargo test green; new store.anthill loads alongside domain.anthill / rules.anthill via the existing BulkStore::pull path; host correctly seeds the cell handle and Main.main receives it. Independent of phase 3 — phase 2 lands the spec/impl/host plumbing without touching the bundle command bodies. Out of scope: WI-189 (reflect operators) — phase 2 retrieve results are Term values until WI-189 lands; cmd_X bodies (phase 3); bundle refactor.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-202"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-09T21:39:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-204",
  description: "Bundle commands ported to FileBasedWorkitemStore (proposal 036 phase 3). Builds on WI-203 (spec + impl in place). Mechanical refactor of 'rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/main.anthill': each cmd_X body rewrites to use the WorkItemStore spec operations (next_id / lookup / commit / by_status_of / forget) instead of hand-built indexes and rebuild-per-command glue. Concretely retired: build_row_map, build_dep_map_acc, register_dependents, feedback_set, collect_feedback_set, max_id_in, id_suffix_of, parse_wi_suffix, parse_int_or_zero, parse_int_acc, digit_value, pad3, status_for_m, direct_dependents_m, append_string — ~120 lines of helper code that exists today only because each command rebuilds the indexes on every invocation. Replaced with: (a) cmd_status / cmd_show / cmd_list / cmd_graph / cmd_next call lookup + by_status_of for queries; (b) cmd_add fires next_id then commit; (c) cmd_claim / cmd_deliver / cmd_verify / cmd_update do lookup + commit (the spec's commit handles the persist / flush dance internally); (d) cmd_delete / cmd_remove_dependency call forget; (e) cmd_feedback / cmd_add_dependency add a Feedback fact via commit. Threading: bundle commands take 's: Cell[WIS]' (concrete, since the impl sort binds State = WIS); commit mutates via Modify[s]; subsequent reads on s see the updated state. No Pair[Int, S] return; Int return for exit code. Retrieve results are Term values until WI-189 lands — phase 3 still uses term_field / term_as_string for individual WorkItem field reads inside cmd_X bodies (Strategy A from proposal 036). Acceptance: cargo test green (existing cmd_X integration tests still pass — claim_test, status_test, delete_test, etc.); the ~120 lines of helper glue retire from main.anthill; live anthill-todo --anthill list / graph / show perf parity or better with today (queries route through QueryableStore.retrieve, which scans the same in-memory IFS cache that WI-187 already maintains). Independent of WI-189 — phase 3 lands the structural refactor with Term-typed results; WI-189 is a typed-surface follow-up.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-203", "WI-236", "WI-260"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-18T11:17:41Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Scope expansion: WI-202 also extends the IndexedFileStore Rust struct with a primary-key index — by_id: HashMap (String to RuleId) populated at pull, maintained on persist/retract. The id field name is a v0.1 convention (every domain entity in an IndexedFileStore is expected to have a String-typed id field; a future generalization via PrimaryKey marker fact is out of scope). retrieve uses the index for O(1) lookup when the pattern has id bound; falls back to O(N) scan otherwise. This makes the Indexed in IndexedFileStore honest in both senses: indexed for retract (WI-187, already landed) AND indexed for query (this WI). Without the primary-key index, retrieve would be O(N) scan-and-unify which is fine at CLI scale but misnames the struct. See proposal 036 §3 for the design.", at: "2026-05-08T09:11:15Z", workitem: "WI-202", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-205",
  description: "Modify framework runtime: per-resource handlers + Cell sort (proposal 037 §2-§3 foundation). Builds the mechanism behind Modify before downstream consumers (WI-203 WorkItemStore, future domain stores) can land cleanly. Three pieces: (a) per-resource Modify handler dispatch — refactor eval/effects.rs default_modify_handler into a dispatcher that looks up per-resource-functor handlers in HashMap (Symbol, Box (dyn ModifyResourceHandler)). Each handler owns its state representation. The dispatcher routes Modify.get/set on a value v to the handler registered for v functor; absence of a handler is an error per Rule 8 (Modify[T] requires a registered handler). Default behavior for bare entities goes away — types must be explicitly Modifiable. (b) Cell sort + Cell-specific handler — add stdlib/anthill/prelude/cell.anthill declaring sort Cell with sort V = ? plus operations new(initial: V) -> Cell[V], get(c: Cell[V]) -> V, set(c: Cell[V], value: V) -> Unit effects Modify[c]. Register a Cell handler at startup that owns a Cell-specific arena (HashMap-backed in v0.1; future allocation-time uid via WI-200). Cell is the canonical small-state Modifiable sort all consumers can use. (c) Modifiable[T] marker — formalize Rule 8 typing. Either as a fact (fact Modifiable[T = Cell[V]]) populated when a sort registers a handler, or via a kernel-side registration check. Typer rejects Modify[T] in effect rows when T has no Modifiable fact. (Strict enforcement may follow as a separate WI; v0.1 may relax to compile-time-warn.) Migration: existing bundle host (run_anthill_bundle) currently relies on default_modify_handler accepting any entity; update to register specific handlers per the resources it uses (the WIS handler for the bundle). Tests: per-resource isolation (two distinct sorts with separate handlers do not share state); Cell.new returns a fresh handle (modulo WI-200 multi-instance); Modify on a non-Modifiable type errors at runtime (typing-level enforcement is a follow-up). Acceptance: cargo test green; the existing single default_modify_handler is replaced by per-resource dispatch; Cell sort loads and Cell.new/get/set are reachable from anthill source. Driver: WI-203 (WorkItemStore spec + impl) needs this mechanism in place to build correctly per proposal 037 §3 architecture (current WI-203 description assumed the v0.1 transitional functor-keyed scheme would suffice; per design feedback it does not — we should build on the right fundamentals).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-202"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-13T13:33:41Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Reordered: WI-203 should land AFTER WI-205 (Modify framework runtime: per-resource handlers + Cell sort). Original WI-203 description assumed v0.1 transitional functor-keyed scheme would suffice; per design feedback the fundamentals must be in place first. Effective dependency: WI-203 depends on WI-202 (IndexedFileStore retrieve, landed in commit 4c08e87) and WI-205 (Modify framework runtime, not yet started).", at: "2026-05-08T10:36:03Z", workitem: "WI-203", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-206",
  description: "Reflect operation: is_modifiable(t: Type) -> Bool. Add to stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill alongside the existing introspection ops (sort_template, occurrences_of, etc.). Body: queries the KB for fact Modifiable[T = t] (the marker introduced by WI-205); returns true iff such a fact exists. Use cases: (a) defensive programming — a function that takes any type and only mutates if its modifiable, queries is_modifiable before deciding to call set/get; (b) reflection-driven UIs and dispatchers — listing all modifiable resources at runtime; (c) typer-side helpers in user code that mirror the kernel typer rule (the kernel typer enforcing Modify[T] requires Modifiable[T] is WI-205 internal; user code can introspect via this reflect op). Implementation: a Rust builtin that wraps a KB query for the Modifiable fact functor with the type as the T parameter binding. Acceptance: anthill.reflect.is_modifiable(Cell[Int]) returns true after WI-205 lands; is_modifiable(Int) returns false; cargo test green. Independent of WI-205 implementation order — could land before WI-205 (returning false for everything until Modifiable facts are registered) or after.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-205"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Lifecycle concern: under v0.1 functor-only identity, Cell.new is broken for deep recursion. Each Cell.new returns the same Value::Entity { functor: Cell, named: [] }; all calls write to the same Modify slot keyed by Cell symbol; each overwrites the previous. Recursive code with multiple distinct cells aliases. Beyond just leaky — semantically broken. Proper fix is the arena pattern already used by Map/Substitution/Stream: a cell_arena on the Interpreter, Value::Cell(handle) variant, refcount tracking, slot reclamation when refcount hits zero (overlaps WI-200 opaque-handle identity). v0.1 of WI-205 documents this limitation; honest impl deferred. Either: (a) expand WI-205 to include the cell_arena, intertwining with WI-200 (multi-instance); (b) keep WI-205 minimal and file the cell_arena as its own follow-up WI separate from WI-200 (since the arena is needed even if the identity scheme stays functor-only — recursion still needs lifecycle). Recommend (b) — file a tight follow-up WI for cell_arena + refcount lifecycle.", at: "2026-05-08T10:56:50Z", workitem: "WI-205", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-207",
  description: "Typer rule: acyclic_cell(V) discharged predicate on Cell.new + Cell[V] annotations. Per proposal 037 §Cell + design doc docs/design/cell-runtime.md §'The rule — acyclic_cell as a discharged predicate'. Architecture: Cell.new's signature carries an implicit discharge obligation acyclic_cell(V) on the payload type V (surface syntax — explicit require clause vs sort-level constraint vs hidden kernel check — is an orthogonal language-design decision). Two-step discharge at every call site: (1) fact lookup — try to resolve fact acyclic_cell[T = V]; if any fact holds via standard SLD resolution, accept. (2) Default static walk — depth-first walk over V's structure carrying topCells (Cell types in the descent chain). At Cell[U]: if U in topCells, REJECT (type-graph cycle); else recurse into U with topCells extended. At entity/tuple/list/map: recurse without changing topCells. At abstract sorts: unfold and continue; visiting set guards termination on non-Cell sort recursion. At Closure/Stream/opaque: REJECT conservatively. At type variable ?T: deferred — re-check at the binding site. Implementation hook: kb::cell_well_typed(ty, top_cells) — called from Cell.new typing arm and Cell[T] annotation resolution. Cache (Cell[T], topCells) decisions. Extensibility: domain sorts (DList, DAG, ObserverChain, age-ordered cells, refinement-typed cells) declare invariants via fact acyclic_cell[T = …]; the discharge story (paper proof, SMT under WI-201, age-ordered runtime discipline, domain-API invariant) lives outside the kernel — the kernel only checks the fact exists. Tests: accept Cell[Int], Cell[String], Cell[Cell[Int]], Cell[List[Cell[Int]]], Cell[wis(IndexedFileStore, Int)]; reject Cell[A] where A's fields contain Cell[A]; reject Cell[Closure], Cell[Stream]; verify a fact acyclic_cell[T = dll[E]] makes Cell[dll[E = Int]] accepted even though the default walk would reject. Out of scope: the discharge-by-runtime-discipline mechanisms themselves (age-ordered cells, etc.) — those are separate WIs that build on this one. Acceptance: cargo-test green; the runtime cell_arena from WI-205 is unchanged; failing programs surface a typer error 'Cell[T] requires acyclic_cell(T); discharge failed at <site>' with a path describing where the cycle would close.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-205"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-208",
  description: "Data-flow discharge for acyclic_cell on operation bodies. Per docs/design/cell-runtime.md §'Discharge by data-flow on operation bodies'. Generalizes WI-207's static walk (which rejects sorts with type-graph cycles like dll(prev: Cell[dll], next: Cell[dll], data: E)) by proving the operation set preserves acyclicity at runtime — without runtime cost. Per-Cell.set local rule: for each pointer field f in the value v written to cell c, classify v.f as fresh (just allocated, no incoming references), unchanged (= c.prior.f), or downstream (reachable from c via f-pointers in the prior heap). A Cell.set discharges if every pointer field is fresh/unchanged/downstream. An operation discharges if every Cell.set in its body discharges and every Cell.new is unconstrained. Per-field independence: prev-graph and next-graph are checked separately. Implementation: data-flow analysis pass over operation IR; tracks per-variable origin (Fresh / Param / Derived) and prior-heap reachability via shape analysis. Coverage: linked-structure operations (push_front/back, prepend, delete, splice), tree builds, hash-map insertion. Out of coverage (deferred to runtime age-ordered cells or proposal 030 proof cache): edge swaps (AVL rotate, graph rewriting, observer self-subscription) — these need either strict age-ordering (separate OrderedCell sort) or paper/SMT proof. Sketch shape analysis: each variable v annotated with reachable-cells via each pointer field f, propagated through Cell.get / pattern destructuring / field access. Tests: dll's push_front/push_back/insert_after/delete all clear; intentional cycle_back is rejected with diagnostic identifying the field that closed the cycle; AVL rotate is correctly identified as needing stronger discharge (test the failure path). The discharge produces a fact acyclic_cell[T = V] that the kernel can rely on at Cell[V] sites without further checking. Acceptance: cargo-test green; the dll example operations type-check under the discharge; cycle_back is rejected.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-207"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-209",
  description: "Parametric effect substitution at call sites. When a called operation O declares effects like Modify[c] where c is one of O's parameters, the effect emitted at the call site O(arg0, ...) should be Modify[arg0_name] (substitute c → the actual arg's referent name). Today's typer treats Modify[c] as a literal effect, so when a body calls Cell.set(s, ...) inside an op declaring effects Modify[s], the typer sees Modify[c] (from Cell.set) vs declared Modify[s] (in calling op) and reports 'undeclared effect: Modify[T = c]'. The mechanism: in kb/typing.rs check_apply (line 593), after the existing unify_types loop builds subst from arg-type unification, also walk each of op.effects through a param-to-arg name substitution map (extracted from each var_ref arg's symbol) and through the existing subst. Replace Term::Ref(spec_param_sym) with Term::Ref(arg_var_sym) wherever it appears nested in the effect. Today walk_type is applied only to op.return_type; effects pass through unchanged. Acceptance: cargo-test green; the FileBasedWorkitemStore.commit and .next_id bodies in anthill-todo/store.anthill type-check cleanly with effects {Modify[s], Error} on commit and Modify[s] on next_id (no 'undeclared effect: Modify[T = c]' / 'Modify[T = store]'). Out of scope: (i) polymorphic type-arg propagation through nested polymorphic ops like Stream.head — separate WI; (ii) Modify-transitivity (Modify[s] covers Modify[s.field]) per proposal 037 — separate WI; (iii) signature inheritance from spec via fact (the original WI-209 framing as 'inheritance'); (iv) call-site dispatch (problem B, now WI-210). Independent of WI-188 (entity copy) and WI-189 (reflect operators). Driver: WI-203 phase-2 bodies + bundle phase 3.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-203"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-09T21:39:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-210",
  description: "Spec/impl call-site dispatch via fact (WI-209b, problem B). Design doc + implementation: when user code calls a spec operation like commit(s, w) where s: Cell[V = WIS], the typer/resolver should dispatch to the impl sort's commit body — found via the chain s's V → State binding → fact Spec[State = T] → impl sort that asserted the fact. Two big design questions to settle in the doc before implementation: (1) static vs dynamic dispatch — Rust-trait-like monomorphization at typer time vs vtable-style runtime KB lookup. Today's bundle has only one impl per invocation so static is feasible; future anthill-todo-server with multiple project workspaces may want dynamic. (2) coherence — what if two sorts assert fact Spec[State = WIS]? Pick by priority? Reject as ambiguous? Lessons from Haskell's incoherent instances. Open: interaction with WI-079 typing-pass parity; whether WI-209a's substituted-signature path is enough for static dispatch (likely yes); how this composes with proposal 037 Modify framework's per-resource handler dispatch (similar shape, different keying). Workaround until this lands: bundle commands call impl ops by qualified name (FileBasedWorkitemStore.commit(s, wi)) instead of spec name. Acceptance: design doc landed in docs/proposals/ or docs/design/; implementation behind dispatch passes a smoke test (commit(s, wi) where s: Cell[V = WIS] dispatches to FileBasedWorkitemStore.commit body).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-209"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-11T18:05:02Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-211",
  description: "Polymorphic type-arg propagation in unify_types (gap B from the WI-209 split). Today unify_types(Stream[T = Term, E = Error], Stream) does not bind Stream's declared type parameters (T, E) to the arg-side bindings. Result: when Stream.head(s: Stream) -> Option[T = T] effects E is called with retrieve(...) returning Stream[T = Term, E = Error], the resulting Option[T = T] still has T unbound (subst doesn't have T -> Term), so the call site sees Option[T = T] and the typer reports type mismatch against expected Option[T = Term]. Fix: when unify_types sees parameterized(Base, [T = X, E = Y]) on one side and a bare sort_ref(Base) on the other, look up Base's declared sort-level type parameters (sort T = ?, sort E = ?) and bind them to X and Y in subst. Effectively treats sort_ref(Base) as parameterized(Base, [<sort T>=fresh-var, <sort E>=fresh-var]) and unifies. Open: how to harvest sort-level type-param names from a sort declaration; whether sort_ref-of-Base should be rewritten at load-time to parameterized form with fresh vars; interaction with typeclass-style dispatch. Driver: WI-203 phase-2 bodies in store.anthill (lookup, by_status_of using Stream.head/Stream.collect on retrieve results) cannot type-check until this lands. Together with WI-209 (parametric effect substitution, landed) it makes those bodies type-check. Acceptance: cargo-test green; the FileBasedWorkitemStore bodies in anthill-todo/store.anthill (next_id, commit, lookup, by_status_of) type-check cleanly under --anthill bundle path; new typing test asserts Stream.head(retrieve(...)) yields Option[T = Term], not Option[T = T].",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-209"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-09T21:26:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-212",
  description: "scaland stdlib full-load regression — AmbiguousSymbol on prelude type parameters. Loading the full embedded stdlib (51 files, post-WI-153) in a single scaland KB pass fails with AmbiguousSymbol(T, …) repeated for the prelude sorts Numeric, Lattice, Modifiable, Option, Eq, BoundedLattice, List, Field, Effect, Stream, Ordered, plus AmbiguousSymbol(A) / AmbiguousSymbol(B) for Function and Pair. The unqualified type-parameter names appear to leak from per-sort scope into ambient namespace scope, so when many sorts that share the canonical T/A/B parameter names load together the resolver sees them as competing candidates. Single-file parse + load tests pass; failure is specific to the full-stdlib pass. Failing tests: ParserIntegrationTest \"WI-153: stdlib float.anthill parses + loads (depends on algebra)\", \"WI-153: stdlib geometry.anthill loads end-to-end (depends on algebra + Float)\", \"WI-153: stdlib witness.anthill loads end-to-end with full sort/entity counts\", \"WI-153: EmbeddedStdlib loads as a single KB load pass\", \"WI-155: ProofRecord fact with witness + state_hash round-trips through parser + loader\", \"WI-155: SmtDischarge witness with SmtVerdict round-trips\". Rustland does not exhibit this; check how rustland scopes type-parameter Symbols inside scan_definitions and mirror in scaland. Acceptance: sbt test green; full stdlib KB load reports no AmbiguousSymbol on prelude type parameters.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-153", "WI-155"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-213",
  description: "scaland mirror of `anthill-smt-gen` emitter — emit SMT-LIB 2.6 from anthill knowledge bases (Z3 / CVC5 target). Today only rustland has this codegen: `rustland/anthill-smt-gen/src/{lib,outcome,policy,tactic_emit}.rs` (~2.1k LOC) plus integration tests. Reference spec: `docs/smtlib-forward-mapping.md`. v0 scope, mirroring rustland: discharge a single linear-arithmetic obligation by declaring user-asserted fact fields as Real constants, translating one named rule body to SMT-LIB, asserting the negation of an upper bound on the head, and proving unsat via Z3. Reference target: `examples/webots-modelling/lf1/safety_common.anthill` comm_delay_max (5 linear ops over 5 floats). Surface area: (a) tactic_emit — Z3 `(check-sat-using ...)` body emission with trivial-default elision parity; (b) policy — per-predicate TranslationPolicy fact lookup; (c) outcome — parse Z3 textual model + unsat-core into anthill facts (note: rustland already has S-expression in_string handling in outcome.rs:68-100 that scaland must mirror). Files: new sbt sub-project `scaland/anthill-smt-gen/{src/main/scala,src/test/scala}`, register in `scaland/build.sbt` aggregate. Acceptance: sbt test green; comm_delay_max round-trips through the scaland emitter and Z3 returns unsat byte-identically to rustland (or with a documented intentional divergence). Out of scope: proof cache (separate WI, depends on this one), quantifiers, induction, full reachability — those layer on top once v0 lands. Driver: parity with rustland realization story; needed before scaland can drive proof obligations end-to-end.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-143"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-09T21:39:49Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-214",
  description: "scaland mirror of WI-096 — proof cache for `anthill-smt-gen` (Z3 verdicts keyed by sha256 over emission bytes + transitive dep hashes). Mirrors `rustland/anthill-smt-gen/src/cache/{key,store,location,mod}.rs`. Cache key: sha256 over `emitted_smt_lib + tactic_canon + ordered_hint_qns + transitive_rule_dep_hash + transitive_fact_dep_hash + stdlib_version + z3_version + cache_format_version`. Layout: JSON-per-entry with two-level hex fanout under per-solver subtree `<root>/projects/<repo-hash>/proofs/z3/v1/`; XDG resolver with override chain `--cache-dir` / `ANTHILL_CACHE_DIR` / `anthill.toml` / XDG default; canonicalised paths for repo-hash so symlinks do not split caches. Two-layer transitive-dep guarantee: emitted_smt_lib bytes catch changes that surface in emission output; rule_dep_hash + fact_dep_hash catch transitive changes that do not (e.g. dep elided as dead code). Property: changing any transitively-referenced rule body or fact field MUST invalidate the dependent proof's cache key at any depth. CLI flags to wire on the scaland CLI (whichever crate ends up driving prove): --no-cache, --refresh-cache, --show-cache, --gc-cache <days>, --stats, --cache-dir. Implementation note: do NOT reuse requires_chain for dep-hashing (wrong primitive — walks sort-requires typeclass relations); build a fresh transitive walker over rule bodies and reuse the dep collection already populated during emission, content-hashing canonical body terms and referenced facts' canonical fields combined in sorted-by-QN order. Acceptance: sbt test green; second run of the comm_delay_max round-trip reports cache hit and skips Z3; regression test covering edit-of-transitively-referenced-fact invalidating a dependent proof's key (the headline correctness test from rustland's WI-096). Reference: docs/proposals/025.1-z3-tactic-dsl.md §Cache key + §Implementation plan Phase 1.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("scaland-sbt-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-213"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Phase A: anthill-core gains RuleEntry.label + KnowledgeBase.rules_by_label index + set_rule_label(rid, sym) setter; rule_id_by_qn consults the label index first, falls through to by_functor; retract cleans the label index. Phase B: smt-gen collect_rule dispatches via a new HeadShape classifier (Bottom / Predicate / FunctionLike{result_idx} / LabelFunctor / Unsupported). Predicate heads (eq / inequality / entity destructure) route through process_body_goal into conclusion_assertions — the head IS the conclusion under proposal 032. FunctionLike (single DeBruijn pos_arg) preserves upper-bound result_var semantics for unlabeled function-like rules like comm_delay_max. LabelFunctor remains as a transitional fallback consuming rule_conclusion(rid). Phase C: loader stops synthesizing 0-arg label-functor heads for labeled equational + labeled denial + labeled-single-positive cases — head IS the user term (or Term::Bottom for denials); calls set_rule_label(rid, label) so cite-resolution still works. Labeled multi-head retains the synthesized head + conclusion-vec shape (proposal 032 multi-head desugaring is a separate WI). Tests: anthill-core 186/186, anthill-smt-gen 26+6+6+23+3+5 = 69/69 (lift_implication_test green); lf1 discharge.sh: 14 proved / 0 failed (step_distance_lemma + 13 others byte-identical). simplify pass extracted is_eq_functor helper to deduplicate the eq-functor check between process_body_goal and classify_head; collapsed twin match arms in load_rule. Out of scope: dropping rule_conclusion field (WI-144), citation-by-label semantics (WI-145), multi-head desugaring.", at: "2026-05-09T17:32:58Z", workitem: "WI-143", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-215",
  description: "stdlib hygiene: wrap effects.anthill body in 'namespace anthill.prelude { ... }'. Today stdlib/anthill/prelude/effects.anthill has bare 'sort Modify', 'sort Error', 'sort Suspension', 'sort Branch', 'sort MatchFailed' declarations (no enclosing namespace block) — they register at global scope with qns 'Modify', 'Error', etc. instead of 'anthill.prelude.Modify' / 'anthill.prelude.Error' / etc. Sibling files (stream.anthill, list.anthill) and the top of effects.anthill itself (sort anthill.prelude.Effect, sort anthill.prelude.Modifiable) use the qualified form. The inconsistency surfaces when host-language code (e.g. test helpers, codegen) tries try_resolve_symbol('anthill.prelude.Error') and gets None. Today user code happens to work because bare global Error/Modify/etc. are visible everywhere through default-scope fallback, but the wrong qualified form is registered. Fix: wrap the body of effects.anthill in 'namespace anthill.prelude' (single block around the bare-sort declarations); leave the already-qualified anthill.prelude.Effect / anthill.prelude.Modifiable as-is or fold into the same block. Acceptance: cargo-test green; try_resolve_symbol('anthill.prelude.Error') returns Some; existing user-code references to bare 'Error' / 'Modify' / 'Branch' / etc. still resolve via implicit prelude import. Independent of WI-211.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-09T21:26:01Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "v0 ports the comm_delay_max round-trip path: scaland/anthill-smt-gen/{Outcome,Policy,TacticEmit,SmtGen}.scala (~700 LOC) plus Common+Z3Runner test fixtures and CommDelayTest. 23/23 anthill-smt-gen tests green: 7 Outcome (S-expr in_string handling), 9 TacticEmit (runtime walker incl. trivial-default elision), 3 Policy (TranslationPolicy lookup), 4 CommDelay (well-formed doc, Z3 round-trip to unsat, config overrides, prefix-order arith). The Z3 round-trip on the 5-linear-op comm_delay_max obligation matches rustland: Z3 reports unsat byte-for-byte equivalent to the rustland emitter (modulo cosmetic whitespace). HeadShape classifier mirrors rustland post-WI-143 (Bottom / Predicate / FunctionLike / Unsupported); LabelFunctor arm dropped — scaland never produced the synthesized 0-arg label-functor shape (multi-head desugaring is a separate WI). One scaland-specific quirk surfaced: scaland Loader.scala only registers SymbolKind.Rule entries for labeled rules, so unlabeled function-like rules like `rule comm_delay_max(?tau) :- body` cant be looked up via `tryResolveSymbol` by their head functor name — adapted the test to use a labeled form `rule comm_delay_max: comm_delay_max(?tau) :- ...`. Out of scope for v0: lift_rule_to_implication_clause (proposal-031 cited-axiom emission), multi-pos-arg rule call inlining (try_inline_rule_call), fact-match fallback (try_match_fact_call), field-access resolution, proof cache (WI-214). simplify pass: dropped a `shortName(qualifiedNameOf)` helper in favor of `kb.resolveSym(sym)`, fixed 4 non-local-return compiler warnings, made SmtGenError a plain case class (no Exception inheritance), and an O(n²) regex-advance bug in extractDefineFuns. Acceptance: scaland sbt anthillSmtGen/test green; comm_delay_max round-trips to unsat. The 2 pre-existing scaland core test failures (anthill.codegen.scala.BootstrapTest::WI-170 and anthill.parse.ParserIntegrationTest::WI-153 stdlib float) are unchanged from origin/main baseline.", at: "2026-05-09T21:40:13Z", workitem: "WI-213", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-216",
  description: "rustland anthill-smt-gen extract_define_funs has O(n²) advance pattern. In `rustland/anthill-smt-gen/src/outcome.rs:127-156`, the while-loop body advances `rest = &after[1..]` (one char past the matched `(define-fun ` marker) on both the skip path (line 140) and the success path (line 153). Each iteration re-runs `rest.find(\"(define-fun \")` from position 0 of the remaining string, so the find scans from `p+1` across the whole `(define-fun NAME () SORT VALUE)` block to locate the next marker — O(n) per iteration × O(n) iterations = O(n²) on input length. Scaland mirror in `scaland/anthill-smt-gen/src/main/scala/anthill/smtgen/Outcome.scala::extractDefineFuns` already has the fix (advances by `marker.length` so the next scan starts after the consumed prefix; see WI-213 commit 955ff7a). Bring rustland into parity. Acceptance: cargo-test green; the existing 7 outcome tests still pass byte-identically; benchmark on a representative Z3 model (kilobytes of `(define-fun ...)` entries) shows linear scaling, not quadratic. Driver: scaland↔rustland byte-identical Z3 model parsing parity (incidental; not user-visible at typical model sizes ≤10 KB, but the asymptotic class differs). Independent of WI-213/WI-214.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Verified(at: "2026-05-10T16:21:16Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Mirrored the scaland fix (WI-213 simplify pass) into rustland: extract_define_funs at outcome.rs:127-156 now advances `rest = after` (past the matched marker) instead of `&after[1..]` on both the skip and success paths. Hoisted the marker into a `MARKER` const for symmetry with the scaland port. The `after` slice already begins past the matched `(define-fun ` prefix, so the next `rest.find(MARKER)` scan starts after the consumed entry rather than rescanning from char-1 of the entry. Tests: cargo test -p anthill-smt-gen all green (69 tests including the 7 outcome unit tests + comm_delay + lift_implication etc.); lf1 discharge.sh 14 proved / 0 failed (no observable behavior change). Asymptotic class flips from O(n²) to O(n) on input length; not user-visible at typical Z3 model sizes (<10 KB) but matters as model sizes grow. Out of scope: a benchmark harness on a synthetic large model — the change is small enough to ship without one.", at: "2026-05-09T21:50:01Z", workitem: "WI-216", author: "user")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-218",
  description: "WI-204 enabler: implement static-dispatch rewrite for spec ops in typer's check_apply. Blocker for WI-204 (port cmd_X bodies through WorkItemStore spec ops). Today the dispatch hook in kb/typing.rs::check_apply (typing.rs:719) calls find_unique_impl_op to validate that spec→impl resolution is unambiguous, but does NOT actually rewrite the call. At runtime the eval still tries to invoke the spec op (which has no body) and errors 'unknown operation: <name>'. Per docs/design/spec-instance-dispatch.md the static form should rewrite the call's fn symbol from <Spec>.<op> to <UniqueImpl>.<op> at typing time so the runtime sees a direct impl call. Design: pure rewrite plus side hashtable for occurrence provenance. (a) Allocate a new apply term: same args, same effects, but `fn = <UniqueImpl>.<op>`. The new TermId is hash-consed normally — no extra named arg, no shape divergence. (b) Insert (new_term_id → original_fn_sym) into a KB-level `dispatch_origin: HashMap<TermId, Symbol>` map (or similar) so reflection, proof-record specialization, and debug/error tooling can recover the spec call (\"this was originally WorkItemStore.commit, dispatched per fact WorkItemStore[State = WIS]\"). The interpreter never reads `dispatch_origin` — runtime semantics are identical to a hand-written qualified-impl call. (c) Caller of `check_apply` substitutes the new TermId in place of the original; substitution propagates upward through nested expressions via standard hash-consed re-allocation. Why pure rewrite + side table over alternatives: inline-annotation (apply gains a named `spec_op` arg) splits apply into two hash-consed shapes (with vs. without spec_op) — defeats sharing between dispatched and direct-impl call sites. Side table keeps apply uniform AND preserves provenance; consistent with anthill's existing pattern of out-of-band per-occurrence data (e.g., source spans). Acceptance: cargo-test green; new test asserts that `next_id(s)` for s : Cell[V = WIS] resolves to FileBasedWorkitemStore.next_id at typing time, dispatch_origin records the original WorkItemStore.next_id symbol, and the eval runs the impl body without 'unknown operation' errors. Driver: WI-204 currently must work around with qualified impl calls (FileBasedWorkitemStore.next_id) to bypass the missing rewrite. Out of scope: dynamic dispatch (vtable-style runtime KB lookup, deferred per spec-instance-dispatch.md); coherence priority resolution (single-impl world today, future WI when multi-impl projects appear).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-210"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-10T00:28:35Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-219",
  description: "WI-204 enabler: Modify-transitivity in effect typing per proposal 037. Blocker for WI-204's mutating cmd_X (cmd_add, cmd_claim, cmd_deliver, cmd_verify, cmd_delete, cmd_feedback). Today FileBasedWorkitemStore.commit's body calls persist(b, w, _) where b = wis(backend) — i.e. b is reachable from s via the wis(backend) field. persist's effect Modify[T = store] becomes Modify[T = b] at the call site (WI-209 substitution). commit declares effects {Modify[s], Error}. Typer rejects with 'undeclared effect: Modify[T = b]' because Modify[T = s] doesn't transitively cover Modify on s's reachable subterms. Per proposal 037 §Modify-transitivity, Modify[s] should subsume Modify on any s.field reachable through the cell's V. Fix: extend the typer's effect-row containment check (kb/typing.rs check_apply / merge_effects) so Modify[T = X] covers Modify[T = Y] when Y is a subterm of X reachable through declared entity fields or pattern bindings. Acceptance: cargo-test green; FileBasedWorkitemStore.commit type-checks with effects {Modify[s], Error} (no 'undeclared Modify[T = b]'); new typing test pins the transitive coverage rule. Out of scope: full proposal-037 effect handler discharge — this WI just covers the typer-side containment check.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-209"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-10T19:15:00Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "WI-219 reproduces no failure on current main: anthill-todo/store.anthill typechecks cleanly. The case the description targets (Modify[T = b] surfacing when b is pattern-bound from s) is already handled by the local-resource mechanism added in commit 260af54 (Implement effect scoping: local let-bound resources don't propagate). The match-case binding in `case wis(b, c) -> persist(b, ...)` calls `env.declare_local_resource(\"b\")` (typing.rs:1652), and `external_effects` filters Modify[T = b] out before checking against declared effects. Functionally equivalent to the transitive-coverage rule the WI proposed. Test rustland/anthill-core/tests/wi219_modify_transitivity_test.rs pins this: 3 cases (in-test pattern, stdlib-persist call, full project store.anthill) all pass without code changes. Marking Delivered. The transitive-coverage rule from proposal 037 §Modify-transitivity remains a future concern only if anthill ever adds direct field projection (s.field outside pattern matching) — currently all subterm extraction is via match, so local-resource handling suffices.", at: "2026-05-10T19:15:00Z", workitem: "WI-219", author: "claude")

fact Feedback(content: "Implementation attempt revealed two enabler blockers: WI-218 (static-dispatch rewrite for spec ops at typing time) and WI-219 (Modify-transitivity in effect typing). Without WI-218, bundle code can't call bare spec ops like next_id(s) — runtime errors 'unknown operation'. Without WI-219, mutating cmd_X bodies fail typer with 'undeclared effect: Modify[T = b]' when commit's body calls persist(b, w, _). Partial progress on store.anthill: next_id is now functional (WI-NNN formatting via Int.to_string + pad3), no longer a 'WI-???' stub. Test fixtures (rustland/anthill-todo/tests/common/mod.rs::setup_project) now copy store.anthill alongside domain.anthill / rules.anthill so any future bundle test sees it. WI-204 should re-block on WI-218 + WI-219 landing.", at: "2026-05-09T21:54:24Z", workitem: "WI-204", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-220",
  description: "GHC-style constraint inference for Sort.requires (future direction). Currently anthills Sort.requires is source-level explicit and the typer validates that body walking does not surface envs outside the declared set. Future direction: instead of declaring requires, let body walking generate them — the user lists operations and bodies, and the typer infers this sort needs requires A, Eq, ... as the inferred signature. This is what GHC does for top-level let bindings (foo x = show (x + 1) inferred as Num a, Show a context). Distinction: this is NOT conditional instance derivation (anthill already has that via Horn-clause facts + SLD resolution); it is signature inference for sort.requires from bodies. Trade-off: less syntax, less self-documenting (a user reading a sort declaration must walk all bodies to see what envs are required). Acceptance: design proposal landed in docs/proposals/ describing the inference algorithm, error messages for ambiguous inference, and migration path for existing sort declarations; cargo-test green with at least one inferred-requires sort in stdlib. Depends on operation-call-model decision shipping (the body-walk machinery enables this trivially once it is in place). Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: PreOpened)

-- ─── operation-call-model implementation WIs (post-design) ─────────
-- Filed 2026-05-10 from docs/design/operation-call-model.md "Implementation
-- roadmap" + critical-review findings. Order is the recommended landing
-- sequence: WI-221 first (smallest, soundness fix); WI-222 next (the bulk
-- of the dispatch model); WI-223/224 round it out.

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-221",
  description: "WI-218 soundness patch: defer-to-requirement detection. Per docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Defer-to-requirement detection', the current find_unique_impl_op (typing.rs:947-1008) only checks open-T (call's per-call subst has a Var that's the body's open type-param). It misses the open-bound trigger: a call whose type-args are ground but reaches a spec op via the enclosing sort's requires clause. Without this, ground-via-requires calls are silently mis-rewritten by Pin-now to a single impl, producing incorrect dispatch when the impl was meant to vary per requirement. Fix: in check_apply, when classifying a spec-op call, additionally check whether the spec sort appears in Sort.requires of the enclosing sort with a unification-matching binding. If yes, return Deferred (skip Pin-now rewrite) and emit the apply_within / requirement_at_current dispatch form once that IR lands (WI-222). For now, until WI-222 ships the new IR, return Deferred meaning 'don't rewrite' — the call stays as a spec-op call and runtime fails loudly. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new test pins that a spec op called via requires-binding does not get Pin-now-rewritten to a single impl. ~50 lines in kb/typing.rs. Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Defer-to-requirement detection' for the classify(call) pseudocode; §'Implementation roadmap' lists this as the first phase.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-218"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-10T17:11:44Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-222",
  description: "Operation-call-model: requirement-insertion pass. Per docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Pass structure', the requirement-insertion pass is a separate pass after the typer that rewrites typed bodies to use apply_within / ho_apply_within / constructor_within / lambda_within IR forms with requirements slots populated. Scope: (a) add the four IR variants to kb/term.rs; (b) implement the call-rewrite cases (Direct / Pin-now / Defer-to-requirement) per the design's table; (c) emit requirement_at_current(i) / requirement_at_sort(chain, k) / construct_requirement(impl, [...]) terms based on resolved instances; (d) implement the env_chain grammar restriction (env_at_sort's first arg always rooted at env_at_current); (e) Op.requirements computation via body walk + fixed-point per design §'Op.requirements computation'. This depends on WI-223 (runtime support) for the Value::Requirement variant and frame.requirements field but the IR shape and the rewrite pass can be developed against a stub runtime first. Acceptance: cargo-test green; tests pin (1) Direct call rewrite preserves semantics, (2) Pin-now rewrite resolves a ground spec op, (3) Defer-to-requirement rewrite emits correct env_chain projections at dispatch sites, (4) Op.requirements computation handles mutual recursion via fixed-point, (5) sort-level requirements coverage validated (per-op requirements ⊆ Sort.requires + body-derived). Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Call rewrite cases', §'Op.requirements computation', §'Two primitives: requirement_at_current and requirement_at_sort'. ~600-800 lines.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-221", "WI-223"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-11T07:28:03Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-223",
  description: "Operation-call-model: runtime support (Value::Requirement + RequirementArena + frame.requirements + AwaitState extension). Per docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Runtime: frame, requirement value, closure', this WI lands the runtime side: (a) new arena rustland/anthill-core/src/eval/requirement_arena.rs (parallel to cell_arena.rs / map_arena.rs), with RequirementSlot { functor, requirements: SmallVec<[RequirementHandle; 1]>, refcount } and refcount-on-Clone / Drop semantics including release_and_take dance for cascading drops; (b) Value::Requirement(RequirementHandle) variant in eval/value.rs; (c) frame.requirements: SmallVec<[RequirementHandle; 2]> field on Frame in eval/frame.rs; (d) closure.requirements: SmallVec<[RequirementHandle; 1]> field on Closure (eval/closure.rs); (e) AwaitState::ApplyWithin variant carrying buffered_args + remaining_args + buffered_requirements + remaining_requirements per design §'Eval mechanics'; (f) the eval reduces requirement_at_current(i) / requirement_at_sort(chain, k) / construct_requirement IR forms; (g) ho_apply_within rejects non-empty requirements slot (typer-side check, but eval verifies as defense-in-depth); (h) lambda_within snapshots requirements at construction. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests pin (1) RequirementArena allocation/refcount/drop cascade, (2) frame push/pop populates frame.requirements correctly, (3) requirement_at_sort projection chain works for nested arena slots, (4) closure invocation overrides apply.requirements with closure.requirements, (5) Eq[List[List[X]]]-style chain (Example 8 from operation-call-model-examples.md) executes end-to-end. Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Runtime: frame, requirement value, closure', §'Eval mechanics'. ~500-700 lines including tests.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-10T19:17:51Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-224",
  description: "Operation-call-model: full SLD-based instance synthesis (replace find_unique_impl_op). Per docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Resolution', anthill currently uses a single-shot find_unique_impl_op that only handles non-conditional facts. Replace with the full resolve(goal, scope) -> ResolvedTree | NoMatch | Ambiguous(...) | Cyclic algorithm: (a) match available_requires in scope first (free lookup); (b) search SortProvidesInfo for impls whose head pattern unifies with the goal; (c) recursively resolve subgoals from conditional :- bodies, with stack-based cycle detection; (d) coherence via specificity (more-specific instance head wins) + reject-as-ambiguous fallback; (e) error reporting with diagnostics for NoMatch/Ambiguous/Cyclic; (f) integrate with the existing kb::resolve::SearchStream for the actual SLD machinery. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests pin (1) leaf instance resolution, (2) one-level conditional (Eq[List[Int]] :- Eq[Int]), (3) two-level conditional (Eq[List[List[Int]]] — Example 8 chain), (4) Ambiguous diagnostic for multiple-matching priorities, (5) Cyclic diagnostic for ill-founded resolution (A :- B; B :- A), (6) NoMatch diagnostic with helpful context, (7) coherence at diamond join points (Example 3). Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Resolution' for the full algorithm pseudocode. ~400-500 lines. Depends on WI-222 for the requirement-insertion pass that consumes ResolvedTree output.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-222"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude-opus47", at: "2026-05-11T14:37:09Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-225",
  description: "Operation-call-model: per-target codegen for requirement slots. Per docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Codegen', each target picks how to render the requirement channel: Rust as &impl Trait or monomorphized; Scala as using clause; C++ as template-deduced argument; Lua as positional. Currently anthill has a Rust codegen pass (codegen/rust.rs) that emits trait/struct/enum from anthill specs but doesn't account for requirement_at_current / requirement_at_sort yet. This WI lands the codegen-pass extension: (a) Rust target emits leading &impl Trait params for sort-level requires; (b) op-level concrete dispatch (Pin-now) emits direct calls to the impl; (c) op-level Defer-to-requirement emits trait-method dispatch on the leading param; (d) requirement_at_sort projections become field accesses on the impl trait's associated type / Self::Requires; (e) codegen tests for each rewrite case. Out of scope (future WIs): C++, Lua, Scala targets. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new codegen tests pin Rust output for Examples 1, 4, 7 from operation-call-model-examples.md. Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Codegen'. Depends on WI-222 for the IR; WI-223 for any runtime-aware codegen choices. ~300-500 lines.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-222"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-226",
  description: "Operation-call-model: two compile-time caches (structural requires_chain + SLD resolution) and binding-aware projection slot matching. Performance and correctness gaps in the pre-WI-226 codebase: (i) requires_chain(spec_sort) re-walks SortRequiresInfo facts from scratch on every defer/Pin-now call site; (ii) dispatch_spec_op_with_tree re-walks SortProvidesInfo candidates from scratch on every spec-op call site even when the same (spec, bindings) has already resolved earlier in the same body; (iii) Strategy 1 and Strategy 2 in build_dep_projection compare entries by required_sort only, so a caller with Eq[T=X] at slot 0 and a callee needing Eq[T=Y] wrongly emits requirement_at_current(slot=0). Scope: (a) Cache A — requires_chain_cache on KnowledgeBase: RefCell<HashMap<Symbol, Rc<Vec<RequiresEntry>>>> populated lazily by requires_chain. Top-level memoization only (recursive sub-frames bypass the cache because cycle-truncated sub-results can't be canonicalized). Key = Symbol (sort) because the structural chain doesn't depend on bindings — substitution into a caller's per-call subst happens at projection time, not in the cache. (b) Cache B — resolve_cache on KnowledgeBase: RefCell<HashMap<(SortGoal, Vec<RequiresEntry>), (DispatchOutcome, Option<ResolvedTree>)>> populated by a new dispatch_spec_op_cached entry point that wraps the existing dispatch_spec_op_with_tree. Key = (goal, scope) — both must match for a cache hit because FromScope short-circuits change the result. (c) Binding-aware slot matching: replace required_sort-only checks in build_dep_projection's Strategy 1 / Strategy 2 with the entries_cover predicate that compares (required_sort, type-param bindings) via dispatch_values_match. List[X] vs List[Y] now resolve to different slots (or fall through to Strategy 3 if neither covers the dep). Out of scope (split as WI-229 / WI-230): let-binding hoist for repeated projection IR (WI-229); converting requires_chain from flat Vec<RequiresEntry> to tree-structured Vec<RequireNode> (WI-230); factor-out into kb/req_insertion.rs (deferred — more natural after WI-230's tree refactor). Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests pin (1) requires_chain second call hits cache (HashMap lookup); (2) dispatch_spec_op second call at same (goal, scope) hits cache; (3) caller with Eq[T=X] and dep Eq[T=Y] does NOT match slot 0 (regression for binding-blindness). Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Pass structure'.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-222", "WI-227"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-11T22:46:49Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-227",
  description: "Operation-call-model Phase E: emit requirement_at_sort and construct_requirement IR forms. WI-222 Phase D currently emits only requirement_at_current(slot=j) projections — sufficient for the v0 stdlib model where requires_chain is transitive-flat (every dep at top level). The other two IR forms from the design's call-rewrite cases (requirement_at_sort(chain, k) for nested-handle projections, construct_requirement(impl, [...]) for static dep construction) are unreachable in current paths because: (i) loader's collect_requires recurses transitively so caller chains never hold nested handles, (ii) Defer fires only when caller has the dep in chain so static construction isn't needed within Defer. They become reachable when WI-224 (full SLD) introduces conditional instances that recursively build requirement values and may emit nested chains. Scope: (a) refactor record_apply_within_rewrite's projection-building loop into a recursive search: try flat caller-slot lookup first, then nested via requires_chain of each caller slot's spec, then static construction via SortProvidesInfo lookup; (b) emit requirement_at_sort(requirement_at_current(i), k) when the dep lives bundled inside caller slot i; (c) emit construct_requirement(impl, sub_projections) when the dep is fully ground but not in caller chain; (d) tests for each emission path including synthetic scenarios that exercise the otherwise-unreachable branches. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests pin (1) flat path still emits requirement_at_current (regression); (2) synthetic nested-handle scenario emits requirement_at_sort chain; (3) ground-dep scenario emits construct_requirement. Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Call rewrite cases', §'Two primitives: requirement_at_current and requirement_at_sort'.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-222"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-11T17:04:35Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-228",
  description: "Operation-call-model: thread ResolvedTree through dispatch into the IR emitter. WI-224 already produces ResolvedTree::Conditional { impl_sort, sub_resolutions, ... } from resolve(), and WI-227 already has emit_tree_as_projection capable of turning a full tree (including nested Conditionals and FromScope leaves) into nested construct_requirement IR. The two are not yet connected at the dispatch site: find_unique_impl_op (typing.rs:2351-2364) pattern-matches both Leaf and Conditional into DispatchOutcome::Unique(impl_op_sym) and discards the sub_resolutions. From check_apply's perspective the only handle to the resolved impl is its symbol, so record_apply_within_concrete → build_projected_requirements_list runs with callee_spec_sort = spec_sort (the spec) and projects the spec's requires_chain via flat lookup — never invoking emit_tree_as_projection on the actual resolved tree. Symptom: WI-227's emit_tree_as_projection is only reachable today through Strategy 3's synthetic SLD recurrence inside build_dep_projection (the WI-227 test calls it directly). A conditional impl in real anthill source has no path that produces nested construct_requirement IR. Scope: (a) extend DispatchOutcome with a Resolved(ResolvedTree) variant (or thread the tree out-of-band) so check_apply can read it; (b) in the Pin-now arm, pass the full tree to record_apply_within_concrete instead of just impl_op_sym; (c) inside build_projected_requirements_list, when a callee dep's projection comes from a resolved Conditional, emit construct_requirement(impl, [sub-projections...]) directly via emit_tree_as_projection rather than re-running resolve() per dep; (d) fix the latent callee_spec_sort asymmetry — the projection should walk the impl's requires_chain (the actual callee's requirements) rather than the spec's empty chain. Out of scope: defer-to-requirement still resolves at runtime; dynamic dispatch is its own WI; effect propagation through conditional sub-resolutions follows WI-209's substitution rule. Acceptance: cargo-test green; a new integration test where 'fact Eq[T = List[T = A]] :- Eq[T = A]' is registered, a Pin-now call to eq(...) at T = List[Int] is rewritten to apply_within whose requirements list contains construct_requirement(EqList, [construct_requirement(IntEq, nil)]) — not the current empty/spec-projected list. Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Call rewrite cases', §'Resolution' (Output ResolvedTree is the direct input to the requirement-insertion pass).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-224"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-11T19:03:37Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-229",
  description: "Operation-call-model: let-binding hoist for repeated projection IR subexpressions. Follow-up to WI-226. When the requirement-insertion pass emits the same projection expression (requirement_at_current(slot=i), requirement_at_sort(chain, slot=k), or a construct_requirement(...) tree) more than once in a body, hoist the projection into a fresh let_expr(pattern: req_<n>, value: <projection>, body: <body with var_ref(req_<n>) substituted>) wrapping the body. At runtime the interpreter reduces the projection once into the let-bound local; subsequent var_ref(req_<n>) reads are O(1) frame-local lookups. Reflect IR's let_expr (stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill:322) is already in place; no grammar change. Concerns this WI must address: (a) scoping interactions with already-existing let_expr in user bodies (don't shadow inner let-patterns, pick fresh symbol names); (b) cross-branch projections in match_expr / if_expr — hoist to the nearest common dominator or replicate per-branch; (c) lambda capture interaction — closures over var_ref(req_<n>) must capture the local from the enclosing let; (d) interpreter handling of the new let_expr form may need verification — most paths should already work since let_expr is part of the typed IR, but inserted-after-typing let_exprs may bypass type checks. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests pin (1) a body with three identical requirement_at_current(0) projections rewrites to one let_expr plus three var_ref's; (2) interpreter executes the rewritten body and produces the same Value as the un-hoisted form; (3) repeated projections inside an if_expr's then- and else-branches are not erroneously hoisted to a common position that changes evaluation semantics. Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Pass structure'.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-226"],
  status: Stale(reason: "Superseded by WI-234 (Model-1 redesign). Under the redesign, the apply_within requirements channel has a single entry (the dispatching dictionary), and the body's sub-instance accesses are var_ref to elaborator-synthesized named bindings — not repeated requirement_at_* projections — so there are no duplicates to hoist. Hoist pass is no longer needed.", since: "2026-05-12T14:00:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-230",
  description: "Operation-call-model: convert requires_chain from flat Vec<RequiresEntry> to tree-structured Vec<RequireNode>. Follow-up to WI-226. Today the typer's requires_chain returns a flat transitive closure, while WI-223's RequirementHandle arena stores sub-handles as a tree. This asymmetry forces WI-227 to re-derive nesting via caller_sub_chains and joined-list lookups; the substitution chain (Wi222Outer.T → Ordered.T → Eq.T) is implicit and recovered at each use site. Scope: (a) introduce RequireNode { entry: RequiresEntry, sub_requires: Vec<RequireNode> } in kb/typing.rs; (b) rewrite collect_requires to produce a tree (each direct require carries its own sub-tree); (c) thread substitution composition through tree construction so each leaf carries fully-substituted bindings (Eq's T at Wi222Outer-scope = Wi222Outer.T directly, not Ordered.T); (d) migrate consumers: TypingEnv.requires field, build_dep_projection Strategy 2 (becomes tree-walk), candidate_sub_goals_owned, sort_refines, check_obligations, eval/mod.rs's seed_entry_requirements, op_requirements; (e) cache becomes Rc<RequireNode> with natural sub-tree sharing — Ordered's sub-tree is the same instance whether reached via Wi222Outer or Wi222Multi; (f) the cycle-corruption issue from WI-226's flat-cache discussion disappears because back-edges become a CycleBack node variant or simply aren't added, not a truncated list. Acceptance: cargo-test green; all WI-222/WI-223/WI-224/WI-227/WI-228 tests pass with the new tree representation; new test pins (1) tree shape matches the declared requires hierarchy for a 3-level chain; (2) substitution composition: Eq's leaf in Wi222Outer's tree carries T = Wi222Outer.T (not Ordered.T); (3) shared sub-tree identity: requires_tree(Wi222Multi) and requires_tree(Wi222Outer) reference the same Rc when both transitively requires Ordered. Out of scope: changing the runtime arena (already tree-shaped). Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Runtime: frame, requirement value, closure' (RequirementSlot is already tree-shaped at runtime — this WI brings typer-side in line).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-226"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-12T05:26:44Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-231",
  description: "Operation-call-model: factor requirement-insertion into a separate pass with a public API. Per docs/design/operation-call-model.md Pass structure section, the typer and requirement-insertion should be distinct passes; typed-but-unelaborated IR is a valid intermediate state, and apply_within / requirement_at_current / construct_requirement are outputs of an exchangeable elaboration. Today they're emitted inline inside check_apply (typing.rs the three emission paths: record_apply_rewrite, record_apply_within_concrete, record_apply_within_rewrite). Scope: a) add per-call-site classification side-table on KB: HashMap TermId to CallClass where CallClass enumerates Direct, PinNow with impl_op and resolved_tree, Defer with spec_sort/slot/op_short, PinNowConcrete with fn_target_sym/impl_parent_sym/spec_op_sym, DirectWithRequires with fn_sym/parent_sym. b) Refactor check_apply: write a CallClass row to the side-table instead of emitting IR. c) Create kb/req_insertion.rs with pub fn run(kb mut KnowledgeBase) that walks kb.call_classifications and emits the rewrites; resolves ProjectionSyms once at entry, reuses requires_tree cache, applies WI-227 emit_tree_as_projection for Pin-now resolved_tree. d) Invoke req_insertion::run from load_all at the end of typing. e) Expose call_classifications + CallClass + req_insertion::run as pub so external codegen targets (Rust monomorphization, reflection tooling, alternative elaborations) can read the classifications directly OR skip/replace the standard pass. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests pin (1) side-table populated correctly during typing; (2) running req_insertion::run produces the same dispatch_rewrites entries the inline approach did; (3) skipping req_insertion::run leaves dispatch_rewrites empty. Reference: docs/design/operation-call-model.md Pass structure section.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-230"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-12T06:00:04Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-232",
  description: "Cleanup pass: consolidate obligation/resolution vocabulary and eliminate redundant work in req_insertion. (1) Rename RequireNode -> RequiresNode (S-consistency with RequiresEntry; the language keyword is 'requires'). (2) Rename ResolvedTree -> ResolvedRequiresNode (make parallel with RequiresNode explicit; signals 'decision-augmented obligation tree'). (3) Embed RequiresEntry as 'resolved_spec' field in CallClass::DeferToRequirement instead of carrying just 'slot'+'spec_sort' — eliminates the redundant requires_chain recomputation in req_insertion::run. After this change, req_insertion::run memoizes the chain per enclosing_sort. (4) Apply analogous resolved_spec field to ConcreteApplyWithin and audit which enclosing_sort usages can be dropped once classifications carry their own resolved data. (5) Optional: drop the public-facing 'requires_chain' (mut-taking, substituting variant) once req_insertion no longer needs it — keep only requires_tree + requires_chain_flat. Acceptance: (a) the rename compiles + all tests pass; (b) req_insertion::run no longer recomputes the chain per call site (memoization); (c) a new test asserts that classify_apply populates resolved_spec correctly. Driver: discussion in dialogue follow-up to WI-231 — three persistent tree representations had naming and field-level redundancy that obscured the layering; this WI rationalizes the typer-side vocabulary without touching the runtime arena.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-231"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-12T11:45:28Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-233",
  description: "Analyze and reduce anthill-todo CLI startup latency. Baseline: 'anthill-todo list' takes ~580ms wall on the project workspace (debug build) / ~130ms (release). Phase 1 deliverable: load-pipeline timing instrumentation gated by ANTHILL_TODO_TIMING / ANTHILL_LOAD_TIMING / ANTHILL_ITEM_TIMING env vars; O(1) ground-fact dedup index (fact_dedup HashMap) replacing the linear scan in assert_fact (algorithmic improvement; ~1-2ms wall-time gain at current N, structurally correct for larger workitem sets). Findings: load_with_visited dominates (35ms / 40% of release load_kb); inside it, load_operation is the slowest per-item kind at ~156us/op (137 stdlib ops = 21ms). Phase 2 candidates if pushing further: cache the typed stdlib KB as a build-time snapshot; optimize load_operation's per-call overhead inside convert_term/kb.alloc; parallelize parse+scan. The 2x sub-phase / 20% wall-time goals were NOT met by phase 1; the system is already healthy at current N. Recommendation: release-build CLI for users observing latency. Phase 2 deferred to follow-up WI.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-12T12:28:48Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-234",
  description: "Operation-call-model: Model-1 redesign — reshape apply_within requirements channel from multi-entry to single-entry; Self becomes frame.requirements[0]. Supersedes WI-229. Background: the existing implementation (WI-218 through WI-233) emits multi-entry requirements channels with the dispatching slot baked into fn position (requirement_at_current(slot=N, op=op_short)). Doc revision (May 2026) committed to Model 1: single-entry channel carrying the dispatching ResolvedSortNode; runtime expansion populates the callee's frame.requirements as [Self_dict, ...impl's requires sub-instances]. Self-as-slot-0 is the resolution for the Self-bound dispatch question (e.g. Eq.neq's default body calling Eq.eq) — Self is materialized as the first slot, so the body can access it for spec-op dispatch. Scope: (a) Remove requirement_at_current(slot, op) fn-position form; for Defer sites emit apply_within(fn = <spec_op_qn>, args, requirements = [<single dispatching dict expr>]). (b) Change build_projected_requirements_list to return a single dispatching dict expression (var_ref to caller's Self slot, requirement_at_sort projection, or construct_requirement literal). (c) Refactor record_apply_within_rewrite and record_apply_within_concrete to single-entry channel. (d) Update typer's Op.requirements computation: every spec-op body's slot 0 is Self (the spec it's defined in); slots 1..N are the sort's own requires. Existing body emissions that did requirement_at_current(slot=i) for impl's i-th require now emit requirement_at_current(slot=i+1). (e) Update eval apply_within frame-push: evaluate requirements[0] as dict; frame.requirements = [dict] ++ [dict.sub_requires[i] for i in 0..N]. (f) Add spec-op dispatch branch: when fn is a spec-op symbol, look up sort_ops_table[dict.sort][op_short]. (g) Self-recursive direct calls (e.g. EqList.eq inside EqList.eq) forward Self via requirement_at_current(0). (h) Closures capture and restore Self alongside other requirement slots. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests pin (1) Defer call emits apply_within(fn=SpecQN.op, requirements=[<single dict>]); (2) impl frame at entry has Self at slot 0 and sub-instances at slots 1..N; (3) spec-op dispatch resolves through sort_ops_table lookup; (4) Self-bound default bodies (e.g. Eq.neq) correctly dispatch to the impl-specific Eq.eq via Self. References: docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'How bodies refer to requirements', §'Channel cardinality (v0)', §'Eval handling for requirement_at_sort and apply_within dispatch'.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-232"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-12T22:35:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-235",
  description: "Operation-call-model: let-hoist for repeated construct_requirement literals. WI-234's Pin-now path emits apply_within(..., requirements=[construct_requirement(impl, [...])]) per call site. Hash-consing dedupes the TermId across structurally-identical inputs, but each runtime evaluation of construct_requirement allocates a fresh arena slot. A body with multiple Pin-now calls sharing the same dispatching dict (e.g. `if eq(1,2) then eq(3,4) else eq(5,6)` at T=Int) pays N allocations for one logically-shared dict. Scope: extend req_insertion::run (kb/req_insertion.rs) — no separate pass needed. The hoist becomes a phase of the existing pass: (a) group classifications by owning op-body (CallClass gains an enclosing_op_body_root: TermId field, populated by the typer at classify time); (b) per-body, scan the group to identify construct_requirement shapes that will be emitted more than once; (c) assign fresh synthesized names (e.g. __hoisted_req_<n>) for each duplicated shape; (d) emit per-call rewrites using var_ref(name) at the duplicate sites and inline construct_requirement at singletons; (e) emit a body-root rewrite that wraps the original body in let_expr bindings for each hoisted shape; (f) extend eval_requirement_chain (eval/eval.rs) to handle var_ref: resolve the name in frame.locals, expect Value::Requirement(handle), return handle.clone() (clear error otherwise). Storage: frame.locals — existing channel for let-bound values; no migration of frame.requirements needed. Concerns: (a) scoping — don't shadow existing user-level let-patterns, pick fresh symbols; (b) cross-branch placement — a construct_requirement appearing in both if/match branches hoists to body-root only when safe (in v0 construct_requirement bodies are Symbol literals + nested construct_requirements with no free locals, so this is trivially safe); (c) lambda capture — closures over hoisted var_refs capture the binding from the enclosing frame via the existing closure mechanism; (d) eligibility — hoist only when the duplicated subterm has no requirement_at_current chain inside it (those depend on frame context); pure-static construct_requirement(impl, nil) and nested chains thereof are always eligible. Out of scope: cross-body sharing (would need const_requirement + runtime cache — separate WI if motivated by profiling); frame.requirements rekey-to-symbol-keyed migration (separate, larger WI from WI-234's deferred roadmap). Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests pin (1) a body with three identical Pin-now eq calls at T=Int rewrites to a body-root let-wrapping with one construct_requirement and three var_refs; (2) rewritten body produces the same Value as the un-hoisted form; (3) requirement arena live-count delta after running the body equals the number of hoisted bindings, not the call count. References: WI-234 (Model 1 — supersedes WI-229's projection-hoist scope with this construct_requirement-hoist scope); stale WI-229 for design-concern inheritance; docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Construction site'.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-234"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-13T01:50:00Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered minimum scope (a) + (b): runtime per-resource dispatch and Cell sort are in place. Cell sort + arena landed earlier (cell_arena.rs with allocation-time uid, refcount lifecycle, no aliasing). This commit extends default_modify_handler in eval/effects.rs to dispatch on Value variant: a Value::Cell(h) arm routes Modify.get/set through interp.read_cell/write_cell (the cell arena); Value::Entity / Value::Term retain the functor-keyed in-memory map fallback for anonymous resources (m5_modify tests still pass). Realizes WI-205 (a) at the Value-variant level rather than as a Symbol→handler registry — simpler and matches the cell-runtime.md architecture where 'the per-resource handler mechanism is realized as the Cell builtin owning its arena.' (c) Modifiable marker: sort + facts already exist (Cell, FileStore, IndexedFileStore, KB). Typer-side enforcement (Modify[T] requires Modifiable[T] fact) is explicitly deferred per WI text ('v0.1 may relax to compile-time-warn'); the strict-enforcement follow-up is WI-207 (acyclic_cell typer rule) plus WI-206 (is_modifiable reflect op). Test added in wi205_cell_test.rs (modify_set_get_on_cell_routes_through_arena) confirms distinct cells stay independent under Modify.set/get — the v0.1 functor-only-aliasing bug from feedback above does not reappear. Stale comment in stdlib/anthill/prelude/cell.anthill updated to reflect the actual arena-slot identity scheme. Cargo test (full anthill-core + anthill-todo + anthill-stl + dispatch + cell): all green. Suite-perf side-trip: identified macOS Gatekeeper/XProtect scanning unsigned test binaries as the dominant cost (~4–17s per launch); cargo-nextest run cuts the full anthill-core suite from 17 min → 31 s by overlapping binary launches. Eval test files merged (6→1) for additional rebuild savings.", at: "2026-05-13T13:33:37Z", workitem: "WI-205", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "WI-218/WI-219 smoke test landed (commit 3064aed): WorkItemStore.lookup + .commit dispatch correctly from a sort-body operation when the Cell parameter is bound as Cell[WIS] (positional) or Cell[V = WIS]. Bare 'Cell' leaves V open and errors 'no impl for per-call bindings'. Refactor plan (5 phases, one commit each): Phase A — thread s: Cell[WIS] through dispatch + each cmd_X signature; no body changes; baseline tests stay green. Phase B1 — port cmd_show + cmd_status to spec ops (lookup, by_status_of). Phase B2 — port cmd_add (next_id + commit) + cmd_claim/deliver/verify/update (lookup + commit) + cmd_delete (forget). Phase B3 — port cmd_feedback (Feedback fact commit) + cmd_list / cmd_graph / cmd_next (by_status_of + row building still in bundle code); retire dead helpers (build_row_map, build_dep_map_acc, feedback_set, max_id_in, pad3, etc.). Final commit — anthill-todo: WI-204 delivered.", at: "2026-05-13T14:34:29Z", workitem: "WI-204", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-236",
  description: "Host API for seeding cross-sort requirement dictionaries at entry-op call. Today interp.call(qname, args) only handles same-sort recursion: seed_entry_requirements (rustland/anthill-core/src/eval/mod.rs:448) populates the entry op's frame.requirements with self-referential placeholders (functor = the parent sort itself, no sub-deps). The code comment explicitly notes 'cross-sort dispatch through the requirement would need a richer entry API to express which impls back the parent's requires'. This blocks polymorphic bundles: a bundle whose sort Main declares 'sort State = ?; requires WorkItemStore[State]' can be loaded but cannot be run from Rust, because the host has no way to supply a real WorkItemStore dictionary rooted at the chosen impl (e.g. FileBasedWorkitemStore). The runtime error surfaces as 'requirement_at_current(slot=N): frame has only M requirements' or similar mis-dispatch when the placeholder dictionary's empty sub-tree doesn't match the expected impl structure. Required: (a) a new host API alongside Interpreter::call, e.g. interp.call_with_requirements(qname: &str, args: &[Value], requirements: Vec[Value::Requirement]) -> Result[Value, EvalError], that lets the caller supply pre-built requirement dictionaries instead of relying on seed_entry_requirements. (b) helper(s) on Interpreter for constructing a dictionary from Rust: alloc_requirement(impl_sort_sym, sub_handles) is already present; add a convenience that takes a structured spec like 'impl=FileBasedWorkitemStore, subs=[]'. (c) keep the existing self-referential fallback for callers that don't need cross-sort impls; document the difference. (d) operation-call-model.md gains a section §'Host-to-entry-op boundary' describing both modes. Acceptance: new test verifies a cross-sort polymorphic entry op (e.g. a small Driver with 'requires WorkItemStore[State]' whose body calls WorkItemStore.lookup) executes the FileBasedWorkitemStore.lookup body when invoked via call_with_requirements supplying the dictionary; the same op invoked via plain interp.call still hits the existing 'cross-sort needs richer API' fallback path with a clear diagnostic; cargo-test green. Driver: WI-204 polymorphic refactor of bundle Main — once this lands, sort Main { sort State = ?; requires WorkItemStore[State]; ... } can be used and the bundle becomes impl-agnostic (WIS-naming retires from main.anthill). Out of scope: implicit inference of impl from runtime value-level evidence (e.g. unwrap Cell[?S] to discover S from the wis(...) functor — a more ambitious WI); full proposal-027 effect-handler discharge integration.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-231"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-13T19:34:59Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Pivot: smoke-testing the polymorphic shape (sort-level 'sort State = ?; requires WorkItemStore[State]' + 's: Cell[State]' instead of concrete Cell[WIS]) uncovered the missing piece — cross-sort polymorphic entry ops can't be invoked from Rust because seed_entry_requirements only handles same-sort recursion. Filed as WI-236. Once WI-236 lands, return to WI-204 with the polymorphic shape (impl-agnostic, no WIS-naming in main.anthill, cleaner per the user's instinct that 'we should pass WorkItemStore not Cell[WIS]'). Phase A work-in-progress (Cell[WIS] threading) reverted; will redo with Cell[State] after WI-236.", at: "2026-05-13T16:04:42Z", workitem: "WI-204", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered (commit adaef7b). Implementation: Interpreter::call_with_requirements(qname, args, chain_dicts) in eval/mod.rs lets the host supply one dictionary handle per entry in the parent sort's flattened requires chain; the runtime prepends the Self slot (slot 0) automatically. seed_entry_requirements also fixed to allocate chain.len() + 1 slots (was chain.len()) — the missing Self slot was the underlying bug behind the WI-204 smoke-test failure 'requirement_at_current(slot=N): frame has only M requirements'. impl_parent_of_op (kb/typing.rs) made pub; reuses the existing helper across both seeding paths. Doc: §Host-to-entry-op boundary added to operation-call-model.md covering same-sort vs cross-sort entry, slot layout, when to use which API. Tests: wi236_call_with_requirements_test.rs pins (a) cross-sort polymorphic Driver runs through to the impl body when a FileBasedWorkitemStore-rooted dictionary is supplied, (b) arity mismatch surfaces at the boundary with a clear message, (c) plain interp.call on the same op fails (documents the gap). Existing dispatch/req tests (wi210/218/219/222/223/226/231/235) all green after the Self-slot fix (39/39). Unblocks WI-204's polymorphic refactor.", at: "2026-05-13T19:34:22Z", workitem: "WI-236", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Substantial progress, NOT yet delivered. Landed (commits 61b19ab, 4bc5bc0): (1) typer fix — types_compatible name-binding normalization: bare List/Option/Pair now compatible with List[T=X] etc. (killed ~18 of the 27 bundle errors); (2) typer fix — extend_env_from_pattern propagates the scrutinee's type args into constructor-pattern field types via new build_pattern_subst (killed the 3 'expected String, got TermId' errors — case some(name) over Option[T=String] now binds name: String); (3) embedded rustland/anthill-stl/anthill/{bool,int,bigint,float,string}.anthill into the bundle's stdlib_embedded.rs (carries fact Eq[T=String] etc. — killed the Eq dispatch failures); (4) bundle main.anthill — declared Clock effect on do_claim/deliver/verify + propagated through cmd_*/dispatch/main; Error on cmd_next; tool_to_acceptance/tools_to_acceptance return types ToolPasses->AcceptanceCriterion. NET: with find_sort_info HELD on short-name (see its NOTE in typing.rs), the bundle loads with CLEAN stderr (0 errors) and all 25 anthill-todo + 267 anthill-core tests pass. REMAINING (the actual deliverable): apply the find_sort_info same_symbol fix — that re-exposes 2 classes: (a) Ordered.lt — derived op (compare is primary); collect_provides_candidates finds the impl but resolve_at_goal's final try_resolve_symbol(impl.lt).or(spec.lt) path returns NoMatch — investigate whether anthill.prelude.Ordered.lt is registered and why the fallback misses; (b) CRITICAL — WI-218 static-dispatch rewrites eq(...)/lt(...) call sites from the spec op (Eq.eq, a registered runtime builtin) to <impl>.eq where <impl> is a 'provides String language rust' block that has NO runnable op body -> runtime 'error: unknown operation: eq'. So once the typer checks cmd_X bodies, WI-218 breaks them at runtime. Fix options: WI-218 should NOT rewrite when the impl has no body (fall back to the spec op, which the runtime resolves as a builtin); OR provides-block facts should register the spec op as the impl op; OR runtime builtin lookup should also try the spec op when an impl op is missing. This is the load-bearing remaining work. Diagnostic test scaffold: rustland/anthill-core/tests/wi204_sort_param_test.rs + the WI-237 NOTE comment in typing.rs::find_sort_info.", at: "2026-05-14T10:18:58Z", workitem: "WI-237", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-238",
  description: "Decide whether to keep or drop the WI-243 NodeOccurrence-synthesis substrate, now that its originally-intended consumer is moot. Background: WI-238 was filed to migrate the req_insertion emitter (build_req_var_ref / build_construct_requirement / wrap_dispatch_channel / record_apply_within_concrete / record_apply_within_rewrite in kb/typing.rs around lines 2050-2230) to wrap each synthesized Term::Fn with a fresh NodeOccurrence carrying OccurrenceOrigin::Synthesized{from = source apply, by = req_insertion PassId}, so that a 'var_ref(__req_*) unbound in requirement position' eval error could point at a source span. That motivation is gone: post-WI-247/WI-248/WI-251 the eval reads Apply NodeOccurrences from kb.op_bodies (with their real source spans) and synthesizes the requirements channel at runtime via expand_dispatching_dict in eval/eval.rs — it never touches the synthesized Term::Fn nodes the emitter produces. The synthesized terms now live only in kb.dispatch_rewrites / kb.dispatch_origin side-tables (kb/mod.rs:260 comment: 'The interpreter never reads it'). The only consumers are six test files iterating dispatch_origin_iter for assertion (wi231_req_insertion_pass_test.rs, wi218_static_dispatch_test.rs, wi227_projection_search_test.rs, wi228_tree_threaded_dispatch_test.rs, wi237_diag_test.rs, wi204_smoke_test.rs); no production diagnostic tooling, no reflection consumer, no runtime path. Meanwhile the WI-243 substrate (NodeOccurrence::synthesized_expr at kb/node_occurrence.rs:184, PassId, OccurrenceOrigin::Synthesized variant, kb.register_pass) has exactly one caller in the whole tree — its own unit test in node_occurrence.rs::synthesized_inherits_span. Choices: (A) Drop the unused substrate: delete NodeOccurrence::synthesized_expr, PassId newtype, OccurrenceOrigin::Synthesized variant (collapse OccurrenceOrigin to a no-op or remove the field on NodeKind::Expr), kb.register_pass + PassRegistry hooks; re-add when a real consumer materialises. (B) Keep the substrate and find a real consumer: e.g., a desugaring pass that lifts let / match into more primitive Expr forms with synthesized origin, or migrate parse-side post-processing to use it. (C) Migrate req_insertion anyway, so that future tooling walking dispatch_rewrites can render source-anchored diagnostics — accept that the migration is speculative until a consumer exists. Recommend (A) by default; reach for (B) or (C) only if a concrete consumer appears. Out of scope: changing the dispatch_rewrites side-table itself (separate concern). Acceptance: choose A/B/C, implement it, cargo-test green workspace-wide, work item description updated to match what shipped.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-243"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-239",
  description: "Make requirement name synthesis + frame.requirements tree-native. synth_req_names and build_dispatching_dict_direct currently walk flatten_requires_tree(...) — the transitive flat chain, a positional-model vestige. Under the names model a body only reads its DIRECT requires by name; transitive requires live inside a direct requirement's tree-shaped dict value (reached via requirement_at_sort). Pre-order flattening also duplicates shared subtrees: 'Wi222Multi requires Eq, Ordered' + 'Ordered requires Eq' yields chain [Eq, Ordered, Eq], which causes a benign synth_req_names name collision (identical entries hash-cons to one __req_*_<raw> name). Fix: synth_req_names + build_dispatching_dict_direct walk the sort's direct requires (top-level RequiresNode list), not the flattened chain; start_apply_within projects the dict against the direct-requires count. The codebase is already half tree-native — RequiresNode, emit_tree_as_projection, and the runtime RequirementHandle are all tree-shaped. Orthogonal to the WI-237 positional->named migration.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-240",
  description: "Strategic: replace the dispatch-resolution fallback with a load-time-built sort_ops_table per operation-call-model.md §'Putting it together: dispatch end-to-end' ('sort symbols carry their own operations table … direct table lookup, not string concatenation + name resolution'). Today resolve_at_goal (anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs ~2670) and the apply_within eval dispatch step use `format!(\"{impl_qn}.{op_short}\").or_else(|| ... spec_qn ...)` — a try-impl-then-spec fallback that conflates two semantic cases (impl-overridden op vs spec-default rewrite-rule op) under one try/catch with string concatenation. This is the WI-237 feedback's reproducer: 'Ordered.lt — derived op (compare is primary); collect_provides_candidates finds the impl but resolve_at_goal's try_resolve_symbol(impl.lt).or(spec.lt) returns NoMatch'. Manifests today as the cmd_add_test + wi203_store_test bundle's stderr line 'WI-210 dispatch failed: no impl of anthill.prelude.Ordered.lt for the per-call bindings'. Strategic shape: introduce SortOpsTable { by_sort: HashMap<Symbol, HashMap<Symbol, Symbol>> } on KnowledgeBase, populated at load time once impl-side facts are asserted. For each impl sort S with `fact Spec[bindings]`, walk Spec's declared operations; for each op_short: if S declares op_short with a runnable body, entry = S.op_short; else if Spec declares op_short (rewrite-rule default), entry = Spec.op_short; else hard load error ('impl S missing op_short; spec has no default'). Dispatch consumers (typer's resolve_at_goal final lookup, eval's apply_within sort_ops_table[dict.sort][op_short]) collapse to a single kb.sort_ops_lookup(impl, op_short) — no string concatenation, no fallback. The default-method-inheritance rule moves from a try/catch at the call site to load-time data in the table; failure modes become precise and surfacing at load instead of dispatch. Estimated 200-300 LOC. NOTE: WI-240 fixes only the typer's Ordered.lt eprintln. The bundle's runtime crash 'var_ref(__req_main) unbound in requirement position' is a SEPARATE bug (typer drops current_occ during nested-apply arg descent in check_apply, leaving the inner call unclassified — tracked separately in WI-241). Both must land for cmd_add_test + wi203_store_test to pass. Acceptance: bundle Ordered.lt dispatch succeeds; the `.or_else(spec)` fallback in typing.rs is removed; eval's apply_within uses the table; cargo test green for anthill-core (bundle tests gated on WI-241 too).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-237"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-20T04:57:24Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-241",
  description: "Loader fails to wrap apply-arg values as ExprOccurrence handles when the underlying parse term has no source span, breaking the occurrence-native typer for nested calls. Symptom: cmd_add_test (anthill-todo) crashes at runtime with 'var_ref(__req_main) unbound in requirement position' because cmd_add's call to do_add — and do_add's args (including the inner collect_all_bindings calls) — go through check_apply with current_occ=None, classify(kb, None, ...) silently no-ops, req_insertion::run skips the call, and the callee runs with empty frame.requirements. Diagnostic walk: (1) debug at the ConcreteApplyWithin classify site shows `occ=None` for the cmd_add→collect_all_bindings classifications while collect_all_bindings_acc→itself classifications (different body) have `occ=Some(N)`. (2) debug inside check_apply's arg-descent loop shows EVERY arg of `do_add(store, description, collect_all_bindings(...), collect_all_bindings(...))` has `arg_occ=None` (split_handle on the ApplyArg.value returns None). (3) debug inside load_apply_or_constructor's convert_expr_child shows `maybe_create_occurrence` returns None because `self.parsed.terms.spans.get(&parse_id)` returns None — many parse terms (simple Idents, nested Fn nodes) lack a span entry, so the loader can't allocate an OccurrenceId, and convert_expr_child falls back to returning the raw term without the Handle wrapper. Per docs/design/expr-occurrences.md §'The Expr IR is occurrence-structured' EVERY child slot MUST be an ExprOccurrence — the current state where ~half the slots are bare terms violates the invariant the typer's occurrence-native rewrite (a5bba1b) was built against. Fix is in the LOADER, not the typer: `convert_expr_child` (anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs:3312) must always produce an OccurrenceId, falling back to a synthesized span (inherited from the enclosing parse term, or a 'no-source-span' sentinel) when the parser didn't stamp one. Alternative: fix the parser/converter to stamp spans on every produced term so maybe_create_occurrence always finds one. Both paths satisfy the invariant; the loader-fallback path is more defensive. Acceptance: every ExprOccurrence-typed child slot in a loaded KB is a Handle (no bare Term::Fn / Term::Ref at ExprOccurrence positions); cmd_add_test + wi203_store_test runtime no longer hits 'var_ref(__req_main) unbound'. Independent of WI-240 (which fixes the typer's Ordered.lt stderr line) — both must land for the bundle tests to pass.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-237"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-15T11:06:48Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered via parser/converter fix, not the loader-fallback alternative described in the original WI. Rather than synthesizing fallback spans at load time, made the every-term-has-a-span invariant STRUCTURAL in the parse IR itself: SimpleTermStore.alloc(term, span) is the only constructor — span is required. Implementation in commit 6db362f: (a) `parse/ir.rs` SimpleTermStore now holds `Vec<ParseTermEntry { term, span }>` instead of `Vec<Term>` + sparse `HashMap<TermId, Span>`. (b) `parse/convert.rs` ~25 alloc sites updated to thread span (mostly via `self.span(node)` at function entry); `alloc_fn_term` gains a span param; new `alloc_bottom(span)` helper; `convert_term_with_span` / `convert_pattern_with_span` removed (their span-stamping moved into alloc). (c) `parse/pratt.rs` synthesized op-nodes use `op_span(terms, first, last)` = Span::merge of operand spans (prefix-op nodes drop operator-token offset, accepted trade-off); outer_span plumbing dropped from desugar. (d) `kb/load.rs` `maybe_create_occurrence{,_ex}` renamed `create_occurrence{,_ex}` returning `OccurrenceId` (not Option); `convert_expr_term` returns `(TermId, OccurrenceId)`; `convert_expr_child` drops None-fallback branch. /simplify pass: restored 4 WI-224 load-bearing comments dropped during refactor, replaced 3 inline Term::Bottom allocs with alloc_bottom, migrated convert_set_literal to alloc_fn_term, trimmed diff-narrating doc-comments. Followup commit eb4482b: cpp-gen `field_name_from_apply_arg` unwraps the Handle that now wraps EVERY Expr child (was: only some); `parse_test::parse_records_term_spans` updated for the removed HashMap field. cmd_add_test (6 tests, was 5 failing) and wi203_store_test (1 test, was failing) all pass. All anthill-core integration tests + cpp-gen 100/100 + workspace doc-tests green. The deeper structural concern — that OccurrenceId is squeezed into Term::Const(Literal::Handle) instead of being a first-class slot type — is filed as WI-242 (Take OccurrenceId out of Term; add Value::Expr; generators read via existing TermView/ViewItem polymorphic binding). WI-242 supersedes the small Handle-unwrap shims this WI added (cpp-gen and the analogous sites in typer/eval).", at: "2026-05-15T11:06:48Z", workitem: "WI-241", author: "claude")


fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-242",
  description: "Take OccurrenceId out of Term, AND give Expr a runtime Value variant. Today every Expr child-position reference is a TermId pointing at a `Term::Const(Literal::Handle(HandleKind::Occurrence, occ_id))` — a hash-consed wrapper term whose entire content is 'I'm a u64 wrapper around occ_id'. This inverts the docs/design/expr-occurrences.md model ('term is content; the occurrence is identity'): the slot type should be OccurrenceId (identity), not TermId (content). The current shape costs one TermStore alloc per occurrence reference (no real sharing since each Handle literal carries a distinct occ_id), forces every Expr-walking consumer (typer, eval, cpp-gen, rust-gen, smt-gen, persistence/print) to `split_handle` or pattern-match `Term::Const(Literal::Handle(Occurrence, _))` before getting to real content, and bakes the Occurrence variant into Literal where it doesn't belong. Concrete sites that exist only because of the squeeze (sample, not exhaustive): anthill-cpp-gen/src/lib.rs:1572, 1871, 2584, 2605; field_name_from_apply_arg's recent unwrap (post-WI-241 fix); anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs::split_handle / resolve_handle / type_check_child / type_check_expr's Handle arm; anthill-core/src/eval/eval.rs's `resolve_handle` calls. Cleaner shape: introduce a distinct `Expr` enum used at expression-level positions, with leaves `Var | Const | Occurrence(OccurrenceId)` and forms `Apply { fn, args: SmallVec<[OccurrenceId; 4]> }`, etc. Terms stay for KB-level uses (rule heads, query terms, fact bodies, type terms) where occurrences aren't relevant. The OccurrenceStore continues to hold `{ term, span, owner, origin }` so `occ_store[occ_id].term` gives the content. Remove HandleKind::Occurrence from Literal. SECOND LAYER: KB queries that yield an Expr-typed result must produce a runtime Value, not a Term — add `Value::Expr(OccurrenceId)` (or `Value::Occurrence(OccurrenceId)`). Reflection ops on bodies (body_of(op), args_of(call), …) bind their query-variable to a Value::Expr; consumers go to `occ_store.term(id)` only when they actually need content. Without this layer, lifting Expr out of Term at the IR layer leaks at the KB/runtime boundary — queries still hand back Term-encoded Exprs that callers unwrap. SUBSTRATE: the polymorphic-binding shape already exists at anthill-core/src/kb/term_view.rs (proposal 026.1 Q2) — `TermView` trait, `ViewItem<'a> = Term(TermId) | Value(&'a Value)`, `ViewHead` enum. Used today on the resolver's target side. WI-242 extends it: ViewItem gains an `Occurrence(OccurrenceId)` variant (transparent projection — ViewHead unchanged), and generators that scan KB results migrate from reading TermId directly to reading ViewItem so Expr bindings flow through as Value::Expr without unwrap. Depends on WI-243 (provides OccurrenceOrigin enum + alloc_synthesized + PassId substrate) and WI-238 (req_insertion emitter is occurrence-native by then). Acceptance: HandleKind::Occurrence no longer exists; no `split_handle` / `resolve_handle` calls in typer/eval/codegen — those become `occ_store.term(occ_id)` direct lookups; every Expr child slot is structurally an OccurrenceId; Value gains an Expr variant; reflection-ops on bodies return Value::Expr; cargo test green. Supersedes the small unwrap patches that exist today as compatibility shims. Substantial: ~500-700 LOC touching parse/, load/, kb/term.rs, kb/typing.rs, eval/, anthill-{cpp,rust,smt}-gen/, persistence/, stdlib reflect. Should land before any new Expr-positional feature so consumers don't grow more handle-aware code.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-243", "WI-241"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T19:32:00Z"))
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-243",
  description: "Minimal substrate for synthesized occurrences. Adds: (a) PassId(Symbol) newtype — typed wrapper preventing accidental Symbol mixing, same 4-byte cost; matches existing ExprOccurrenceId(OccurrenceId) pattern at kb/occurrence.rs:40. (b) OccurrenceOrigin enum { Source, Synthesized { from: OccurrenceId, by: PassId } } — origin field on OccurrenceEntry (default Source for all existing alloc/alloc_expr paths). (c) alloc_synthesized(term, owner, from, by, is_expr) -> OccurrenceId — span inherited from `from`. (d) Public kb.register_pass(qualified_name) -> PassId — entry point any synthesizing pass calls at startup to obtain its PassId. Naming chosen: 'OccurrenceOrigin' (not 'Phase' — concept is provenance, not temporal phase) and 'Synthesized' (not 'Elaborated' — standard compiler vocab, avoids type-theory jargon). DISCOVERY during implementation: WI-235's let-hoist (the originally-intended first consumer) was removed in WI-237 Phase 2 / commit 333d4cf because the names-model migration made body-level construct_requirement deduplication unnecessary (dispatching dicts are now installed once into frame.requirements[__req_<spec>] at call site). WI-235-lineage cleanup included in this WI (per user's 'code clean, no unused code' directive): removed kb.op_body_overrides field + set_op_body_override / op_body_override accessors + eval::lookup_operation_body's override consultation (no producer remains); removed enclosing_op_sym field on TypingEnv + set/get accessors + the CallClass::ConcreteApplyWithin field (was set by check_apply but req_insertion destructured it as `..` and discarded — pure dead data flow). NOT added (deferred until first consumer materializes): PassRegistry struct of pre-resolved pass symbols; body_occurrence_of_op index. Both were initially planned for WI-235's hoist; with no current consumer they're speculative. When an actual synthesizing pass appears (WI-238 emitter migration, future elaboration), the registry + index get added then with the consumer that motivates them. PREREQUISITE for WI-238 (req_insertion emitter migration) and WI-242 (full Expr lift) — both reuse this substrate. Out of scope: WI-231 emitter migration (WI-238), Expr/Value::Expr/HandleKind::Occurrence removal (WI-242), dispatch_rewrites migration (WI-242). Acceptance: cargo-test green; OccurrenceStore unit tests verify alloc_synthesized stamps origin=Synthesized{from, by}, inherits span from `from`; alloc_default_is_source verifies plain alloc still stamps Source.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-241"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-15T14:51:16Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Superseded by WI-237 Phase 2 (commit 333d4cf, 2026-05-15). The let-hoist for duplicate construct_requirement shapes was removed when WI-237 migrated to the names model: under names model, the dispatching dict is constructed once at the call site (via apply_within's requirements channel) and held name-keyed in frame.requirements[__req_<spec>], so body sites do var_ref(__req_<spec>) → frame lookup without allocation. The old optimization (let-bind a duplicated body-level construct_requirement once at body root, reference via var_ref(__hoist_N)) was rendered obsolete because there is no longer a body-level construct_requirement to dedupe. Dormant infrastructure left by the removal: kb.op_body_overrides: HashMap<Symbol, OccurrenceId> (eval::lookup_operation_body still consults it, no producer remains), and kb.set_op_body_override / op_body_override accessors. WI-243 (2026-05-15) migrated op_body_overrides's value type from TermId to OccurrenceId for forward-compat with the OccurrenceOrigin substrate. The infrastructure is forward-ready for any future pass that wants to install body-level let-wraps (constraint elaboration, monomorphization).", at: "2026-05-15T12:24:44Z", workitem: "WI-235", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-244",
  description: "Consolidate anthill-core integration tests from 59 separate files into ~8 grouped binaries to slash per-binary linker overhead. Each integration test file today compiles into a standalone binary; linking takes ~50-100s on local hardware. Full integration sweep currently runs for hours (observed: ~52 minutes through 13/59 binaries during WI-243 testing). Proposed grouping: (a) wi_tests.rs — all wi### validation tests (wi009/071/182/186/202/204×2/205/210/211/218/219/221/222/223×3/224/226/227/228/230/231/236/237*), ~25 files; (b) eval_tests.rs — eval_test, eval_q3, eval_q4; (c) induction_tests.rs — induction_axiom_witness, induction_rule, numeric_induction, scope_axiom_witness, specialization_witness; (d) builtin_tests.rs — persistence, persistence_builtins, map_builtins, time_now, toml_ser, vec3_ops; (e) parse_tests.rs — parse, typing, cli_parse, codegen, fact_substitution; (f) algebra_tests.rs — algebra_spec, ring_polynom, logic_sorts, console_stdlib, operation_equation, equational_attr; (g) resolve_tests.rs — forall_impl_resolve, push_choice, route_dispatch, guard_trigger, nested_implication, proof_load, tactic_ir, incremental_load. Keep github_todo_test.rs standalone (large fixtures, distinct concern). Pattern: each consolidated file declares mod submodules referencing the original test files via #[path = '...'] mod foo, OR move test functions directly into the grouped file. Net: 59 → 8 binaries, ~85% fewer linker invocations. Risk LOW: rust's test harness isolates each #[test] fn within a binary; only watch-out is shared static / thread_local state which anthill tests avoid (load-fresh-KB-per-test pattern). Acceptance: cargo-test green; record before/after timing of full integration sweep in the deliver feedback (target: hours → single-digit minutes). Discovered during WI-243 testing where the long sweep blocked verification.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-15T15:24:05Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Timing: full anthill-core test suite ran in 452s (7.5 min) after consolidation — was running for >2 hours pre-consolidation (incomplete sweep observed during WI-243). Per-binary linker/spawn overhead dropped from ~60 invocations to 9 (lib + 8 wrappers + doc-tests). Test execution time itself is only ~41s total across all binaries; the remaining ~390s of wall time is the irreducible per-binary linker setup (~45s × 9). Further reduction would require either merging all integration tests into one binary (loses the topic-grouped browsability) or using --no-default-features / release builds. Test count preserved: 204 lib + 632 integration = 836 total, all green.", at: "2026-05-15T15:24:05Z", workitem: "WI-244", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-245",
  description: "Parse-IR Expr/Term split. Currently parse/ir.rs has a single SimpleTermStore (Vec<ParseTermEntry { term, span }>) and convert.rs's convert_term family produces TermId for every position — expression bodies (operation body, lambda body, conditional branches, match arms, let bodies) and KB-position references (fact bodies, rule heads) flow through the same uniform Term IR. This conflates two fundamentally different identity semantics: KB positions are structural (hash-consed, sharing wanted); expression positions are positional (each source occurrence is distinct, sharing catastrophic). The Handle-wrapper hack in load.rs:3307 (Term::Const(Literal::Handle(Occurrence, occ_id))) exists only to prevent hash-cons collapse of expression-position content — wrapping each occurrence's content in a unique Handle defeats the hash-cons. WI-245 fixes this at the parse IR boundary: introduce an  recursive value type (NO ExprId — Expr children are owned via Vec<Expr>; inline Span; no arena, no hash-cons because there's nothing to share). Variants mirror expression forms: Var, Const, Apply { functor, pos_args, named_args }, Lambda, Let, Match, If, etc. Item types in parse/ir.rs update: Operation.body: Option<TermId> -> Option<Expr>; Lambda/Match/Let/If branches similarly. Add convert_expr_* family in parse/convert.rs that mirrors convert_term_* but produces Expr. Tree-sitter grammar unchanged. The loader's convert_expr_term (load.rs:3275) adapts to consume Expr from parse IR (was: TermId); produces the same KB-side output (Handle-wrapped TermId + OccurrenceEntry) as today — no KB-layer behavior change. Prerequisite for WI-242: with the parse-IR split landed, WI-242 reduces to KB-side work (loader allocates KB Expr in OccurrenceStore directly; Value::Expr; TermView::ViewItem::Occurrence; delete Handle wrapper). Out of scope: KB-side Expr (WI-242), HandleKind::Occurrence removal (WI-242), Value::Expr (WI-242). Estimated ~300-400 LOC, mostly in parse/ir.rs and parse/convert.rs. Acceptance: cargo-test green; existing test behavior preserved; new Expr round-trip tests pass.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-241"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-15T17:14:41Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "SUPERSEDED by design refinement (see docs/design/occurrence-as-value-type.md). Initial scope was 'parse-IR Expr split — introduce Expr enum at parse layer, change Operation.body to Option<Expr>'. After extended design discussion, the parse-IR layer is staying UNCHANGED: Item enum, all existing struct types (Namespace, Operation, Fact, Rule, etc.), TermId/SimpleTermStore — all keep their current shape. The Expr/Term distinction happens at the KB layer instead, via WI-242 introducing NodeOccurrence + NodeKind + Expr value types and eliminating OccurrenceStore/OccurrenceId/Handle wrapper. WI-245's parse-side refactor is no longer needed because the loader does the routing at the KB boundary, walking parse-IR Items and producing KB-side NodeOccurrence for expression-position content vs KB-side Term for KB-position content. No code landed for this WI. Marking delivered with this supersession note for traceability.", at: "2026-05-15T17:14:40Z", workitem: "WI-245", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DESIGN REFINED (2026-05-15) — see docs/design/occurrence-as-value-type.md for the canonical spec. Scope under the new design: introduce NodeOccurrence (value-type struct with kind/span/owner fields) + NodeKind enum (variants Expr {expr, origin, classification: RefCell<...>} and RuleHead {functor, args}) + Expr enum (structural variants Apply/Match/If/Let/Lambda/ApplyWithin/HoApply/RequirementAtSort/ConstructRequirement/VarRef/Var/Const/Ref/Ident/Bottom). Every child slot in Expr is Rc<NodeOccurrence>; tree is Rc-linked from the start. Eliminate OccurrenceStore + OccurrenceId + Term::Const(Literal::Handle(Occurrence, _)) wrapper + split_handle + resolve_handle. Add Value::Node(Rc<NodeOccurrence>) for reflection bindings. Migrate ~50 eval-stack sites to Rc<NodeOccurrence>; migrate 3 by_term reverse-lookup sites in typing.rs to direct walking. Rename reflect's sort Occurrence to sort NodeOccurrence. Parse IR layer is unchanged — Item enum and all variant structs (Namespace, Operation, Fact, Rule, etc.) stay. The loader is the conversion boundary: walks parse-IR Items, produces hash-consed Term for KB-position content vs owned Rc<NodeOccurrence> for expression-position and rule-head content. Patterns stay as Term::Fn{pattern_*} (pattern reform is separate). Estimated ~500-800 LOC across kb/, eval/, codegens, persistence, and stdlib reflect.", at: "2026-05-15T17:25:12Z", workitem: "WI-242", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-246",
  description: "Extend NodeOccurrence/Expr migration to rule body atoms. Currently (WI-242) only operation bodies, lambda bodies, and if/match/let branches become Expr/NodeOccurrence; rule body atoms (e.g. add(?x, 1) inside rule r(?y) :- Foo(?x), ?y = add(?x, 1)) stay as hash-consed Term. This WI extends the migration: rule body atoms become Rc<NodeOccurrence> with NodeKind::Expr, so the typer/eval/codegen see uniform Expr structure regardless of whether content lives in an operation body or a rule body. Affects: kb/load.rs (rule body atom conversion), kb/resolve.rs (SLD resolution walks NodeOccurrence atoms), kb/discrim.rs (discrimination tree keys), kb/subst.rs (substitution applied through NodeOccurrence). Acceptance: cargo-test green; rule body atoms are structurally Rc<NodeOccurrence>; no Term::Fn at rule-body positions in loaded KB; resolver indexes occurrences by functor for discrimination tree matching. Out of scope: type terms, fact bodies, query patterns (those stay as Term — they are structural KB facts, not positional expressions).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-242"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-24T10:52:44Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-247",
  description: "Migrate consumers (typer, eval, req_insertion, codegens) from Handle/OccurrenceStore to value-typed NodeOccurrence. WI-242 delivered the substrate (kb/node_occurrence.rs: NodeOccurrence struct, NodeKind enum, Expr enum, MatchBranch) and wired the loader to populate kb.op_bodies: HashMap<Symbol, Rc<NodeOccurrence>> for every operation body. This WI completes the migration: (a) typer reads bodies from kb.op_bodies and walks Rc<NodeOccurrence> instead of TermId+OccurrenceId; classification moves to NodeOccurrence's RefCell; (b) eval frame stack stashes Rc<NodeOccurrence>; recurses on tree; resolve_handle/split_handle calls deleted; (c) cpp-gen, rust-gen, smt-gen body walks switch to NodeOccurrence; the 4 Handle-unwrap sites in cpp-gen (lib.rs:1572, 1871, 2584, 2604) and field_name_from_apply_arg's unwrap (post-WI-241) become direct &node.kind matches; (d) OpInfoRecord.body becomes Option<Rc<NodeOccurrence>>; body_occ field deleted; (e) reflection ops body_of/head_of/args_of produce Value::Node(Rc<NodeOccurrence>); reflect stdlib renamed sort Occurrence -> sort NodeOccurrence; (f) once all consumers migrated, delete OccurrenceStore, OccurrenceId, ExprOccurrenceId, HandleKind::Occurrence, Term::Const(Literal::Handle(Occurrence, _)) construction in load.rs, split_handle, resolve_handle. Acceptance: HandleKind::Occurrence no longer exists; no split_handle/resolve_handle calls in typer/eval/codegen; every Expr child slot is structurally a Rc<NodeOccurrence>; reflection-ops on bodies return Value::Node; cargo-test green. Reference: docs/design/occurrence-as-value-type.md sections 'Migration touch-points' and 'What stays as-is'.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-242"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-15T23:38:09Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "PARTIAL DELIVERY (substrate-only, per 'scope too big' user direction). Landed in this WI: (a) kb/node_occurrence.rs — NodeOccurrence struct (value-type wrapper with kind/span/owner), NodeKind enum (Expr {expr, origin, classification: RefCell<...>} | RuleHead {functor, pos_args, named_args}), Expr enum with 23 variants (Apply/HoApply/Constructor/Match/If/Let/Lambda/Instantiation/ListLit/SetLit/TupleLit + post-elaboration ApplyWithin/HoApplyWithin/ConstructorWithin/LambdaWithin/RequirementAtSort/ConstructRequirement/VarRef + leaves Var/Const/Ref/Ident/Bottom), MatchBranch. PassId and OccurrenceOrigin moved/aliased here with 'from: Rc<NodeOccurrence>' (pointer identity via Rc::ptr_eq). (b) KnowledgeBase fields: op_bodies: HashMap<Symbol, Rc<NodeOccurrence>>, rule_head_occurrences: HashMap<RuleId, Rc<NodeOccurrence>>; accessors op_body_node/set_op_body_node/rule_head_node/set_rule_head_node. (c) kb/load.rs::load_operation populates kb.op_bodies via materialize_from_handle, which walks the post-conversion Handle-wrapped KB tree and produces value-typed NodeOccurrence trees. Recognizes anthill.reflect.Expr.{if_expr, let_expr, lambda, match_expr, apply, constructor, apply_within, requirement_at_sort, construct_requirement, int_lit, float_lit, bigint_lit, string_lit, bool_lit, var_ref}, ListLiteral, SetLiteral, TupleLiteral; falls back to Expr::Apply{functor, ...} for unknown Fn terms. Cons-list unpacking handles ApplyArg(name=some(Ref)|none, value=Handle) splitting into pos/named buckets. (d) Value::Node(Rc<NodeOccurrence>) variant added in eval/value.rs; covered in TermView/execute/eval canonical-key matches as Opaque/Unsupported (consumers don't read NodeOccurrence yet). (e) docs/design/expr-occurrences.md marked SUPERSEDED with header pointing to occurrence-as-value-type.md (the canonical design). NOT in this delivery (filed as WI-247): consumer migration — typer/eval/req_insertion still walk Handle-wrapped TermIds via split_handle/resolve_handle; cpp-gen still unwraps Handle at lib.rs:{1572,1871,2584,2604}; OperationInfo.body still Handle-wrapped TermId; reflection ops still return Term not Value::Node; OccurrenceStore + HandleKind::Occurrence not yet deleted; stdlib reflect 'sort Occurrence' not yet renamed to 'sort NodeOccurrence'. The kb.op_bodies tree is populated for every operation but currently unread by production code — the substrate is in place for WI-247 to migrate consumers to it. WI-246 also filed for extending the migration to rule body atoms (separately scoped per user direction). 207 unit tests + integration tests green at substrate-only state.", at: "2026-05-15T19:04:45Z", workitem: "WI-242", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-248",
  description: "Wave 2 of NodeOccurrence consumer migration: migrate eval to Rc<NodeOccurrence>. Frame stack stashes Rc<NodeOccurrence> for runtime error spans. reduce_expr / reduce_fn / start_apply / start_let / start_match / start_if dispatch on Expr variants directly instead of Term::Fn { functor } string matching. Drop resolve_handle calls from eval (typing.rs::resolve_handle/split_handle). Lambda closure captures NodeOccurrence body. Closure/ClosureHandle.body becomes Rc<NodeOccurrence>. Depends on WI-247 (typer migration), since the typer's classifications need to flow through to eval via NodeOccurrence's RefCell. Acceptance: no resolve_handle/split_handle calls in eval; eval Frame.expr / Frame.body fields are Rc<NodeOccurrence>; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-247"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T05:33:20Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-249",
  description: "Wave 3 of NodeOccurrence consumer migration: migrate cpp-gen body walks to Rc<NodeOccurrence>. Rewrite lower_expr (anthill-cpp-gen/src/lib.rs:1566), lower_apply_arg, lower_match_branches, lower_constructor_literal, lower_let_chain, and any other body-walking helpers to take &Rc<NodeOccurrence> instead of TermId. Eliminate the 6 Handle-unwrap sites (lib.rs:1572, 1871, 2584, 2604, 2605, 2681) — they become direct Expr-variant matches. Eliminate find_named/walk_list/field_name_from_apply_arg helpers (they walk Term-encoded structures; the NodeOccurrence tree has them as typed fields). Update OperationImpl body lookups to read kb.op_body_node(op_sym) instead of OperationImpl fact's body Handle field. Depends on WI-247 (typer migration); typer + cpp-gen don't directly interact but having both migrated lets us delete OperationInfo.body / OperationImpl.body Handle paths together in WI-250. Acceptance: no Term::Const(Literal::Handle(...)) matches in cpp-gen; cargo test -p anthill-cpp-gen green; 100 tests pass.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-247"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T06:35:56Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-250",
  description: "Wave 3b — migrate rust-gen and smt-gen body walks (if any). rust-gen and smt-gen are listed in WI-247 description but the Explore agent reported no OccurrenceId / HandleKind::Occurrence usage in those crates today, so they may be unaffected. This WI scans rust-gen + smt-gen for body-walking code, migrates if needed, or closes as no-op. Acceptance: cargo test -p anthill-rust-gen and -p anthill-smt-gen green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-248"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T01:55:54Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-251",
  description: "Wave 4 — final cleanup of NodeOccurrence migration. Once typer (WI-247), eval (WI-248), cpp-gen (WI-249) migrated: (a) reflection ops body_of/head_of/args_of/sub_occurrences produce Value::Node(Rc<NodeOccurrence>) instead of Term-encoded results; replace the materialize_from_handle helper with native NodeOccurrence access (loader will build NodeOccurrence trees directly in convert_expr_term). (b) Delete OccurrenceStore, OccurrenceId, ExprOccurrenceId, HandleKind::Occurrence (and its construction site in load.rs::convert_expr_child), split_handle and resolve_handle in typing.rs, kb.occurrences field on KnowledgeBase. (c) OperationInfo.body field deleted from the OperationInfo fact entity (replaced by kb.op_bodies lookup). OpInfoRecord.body and body_occ fields deleted; body_node remains. (d) Rename stdlib reflect 'sort Occurrence' to 'sort NodeOccurrence' (stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill); update all consumers. (e) Eliminate the double tree walk (deferred from WI-242 simplify pass) by building NodeOccurrence trees directly in convert_expr_term instead of post-walking via materialize_from_handle. Depends on WI-247, WI-248, WI-249 (all consumers migrated). Acceptance: 'cargo test' green; rg 'HandleKind::Occurrence' returns no matches; rg 'OccurrenceStore' returns no matches outside the deleted occurrence.rs.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-249"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T10:28:35Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "SCOPE NARROWED to Wave 1 (typer only). Original WI bundled all 4 consumer waves; that's a multi-day effort. Split into: WI-247 (this WI) typer; WI-248 eval; WI-249 cpp-gen; WI-250 rust-gen/smt-gen scan; WI-251 reflection + cleanup. Narrowed acceptance: type_check_expr takes &Rc<NodeOccurrence> (or equivalent); check_apply, check_if_expr, check_let_expr, check_match_expr, check_lambda, check_list_literal, check_set_literal, check_tuple_literal, check_constructor accept Expr-variant payloads; type_check_child eliminated (replaced by direct recursion on Rc<NodeOccurrence>); classify(kb, occ, class) mutates NodeOccurrence's RefCell via NodeOccurrence::set_classification instead of kb.occurrences.set_classification; check_operation_bodies reads body_node from OpInfoRecord (added to OpInfoRecord as an enabling step). No split_handle / resolve_handle calls inside typing.rs. typing.rs may continue to TAKE OccurrenceId arguments in error-reporting paths until WI-251 deletes OccurrenceStore; the migration here is dispatch-flow, not field-deletion.", at: "2026-05-15T20:24:17Z", workitem: "WI-247", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED. Migration committed as 0655f53 (WI-247: typer migration to Rc<NodeOccurrence> Wave 1). All narrowed-acceptance criteria met: (a) type_check_expr is a back-compat shim delegating to type_check_node(&Rc<NodeOccurrence>); (b) check_apply/check_constructor/check_if_expr/check_let_expr/check_match_expr/check_lambda/check_list_literal/check_set_literal/check_tuple_literal take Expr-variant payloads; (c) type_check_child eliminated; (d) classify dual-writes to NodeOccurrence's RefCell + legacy OccurrenceStore via origin_occ back-pointer (keeps req_insertion::run reading without migration until WI-251); (e) check_operation_bodies reads body_node from OpInfoRecord; (f) no internal split_handle/resolve_handle calls in typing.rs's type-checking flow (pub fns stay for eval/op_info consumers until WI-248/251). Substrate enhancements: NodeOccurrence.origin_occ field + new_expr_with_origin constructor (materialize_from_occurrence sets it); expr_form_key normalizes qualified vs short functor names (unifies loader output with hand-built test terms). Tests: cargo test -p anthill-core --lib 207/207 pass; -p anthill-core integration 99 pass; -p anthill-stl 19 pass; anthill run hello.anthill works (~1.5s). Workspace test was running during commit (slow due to z3 subprocess invocations in cli prove_* suite) but unit/integration coverage already confirms the typer flow. Remaining waves: WI-248 (eval, ~2-3h), WI-249 (cpp-gen, ~1-2h), WI-250 (rust/smt-gen scan, small), WI-251 (cleanup + delete OccurrenceStore, ~1-2h). 480 LOC diff in typing.rs, 88 LOC diff in node_occurrence.rs.", at: "2026-05-15T23:38:49Z", workitem: "WI-247", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Full workspace test confirmation: cargo test --workspace completed cleanly with exit code 0 (all crates green: anthill-core lib + integration, anthill-cli prove/run suite, anthill-cpp-gen, anthill-rust-gen, anthill-smt-gen, anthill-stl, anthill-todo). Doc tests all 0/0 ok. WI-247 fully validated.", at: "2026-05-16T01:05:48Z", workitem: "WI-247", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "NO-OP confirmation. rg 'Occurrence|Handle' against anthill-rust-gen/src and anthill-smt-gen/src returns no matches — neither crate touches OccurrenceId, HandleKind::Occurrence, resolve_handle, split_handle, or Literal::Handle. Their codegen targets only consume KB facts and op signatures, not body expression trees. Standalone test runs confirm green post-WI-247: cargo test -p anthill-rust-gen 6 passed 1 ignored; cargo test -p anthill-smt-gen 5 passed (integration target, all lib paths exercised). Scope-bracket from WI-247 is closed: rust-gen/smt-gen need no migration.", at: "2026-05-16T01:55:58Z", workitem: "WI-250", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED. Commit 8686570. Frame.expr, AwaitState variants (ChooseBranch/LetBind/MatchDispatch/ApplyArgs/ApplyWithinArgs/ConstructorArgs), and Closure.body all moved to Rc<NodeOccurrence>. reduce_node dispatches on Expr variants — no more reflect-symbol cache lookup for the dispatch path. All resolve_handle/split_handle call sites removed from eval. WI-218 dispatch redirect now reads CallClass off the Apply occurrence's RefCell (PinNow.impl_op_sym / ConcreteApplyWithin.fn_target_sym) instead of looking up dispatch_rewrites by apply-TermId. lookup_operation_body returns Rc<NodeOccurrence> from kb.op_body_node. Legacy helpers (decode_apply_arg, list_terms, extract_static_int, term_as_symbol, named_arg) deleted — Expr-variant access subsumes them. wi223_apply_within_test body-override path migrated to NodeOccurrence::synthesized_expr against the original body (proper Synthesized origin, inherited span — no fabricated empty SourceSpan, per the design's 'produced by a later pass' constructor). Tests: full workspace cargo test --workspace green (exit 0). cargo-test acceptance satisfied. Diff: 319+ / 473- LOC; eval.rs dropped from 1246 to ~770 by eliminating the symbol-dispatch layer.", at: "2026-05-16T05:33:32Z", workitem: "WI-248", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED. Commit acb5fc9. lower_expr→lower_node walking Rc<NodeOccurrence>; OpImplTable.by_op sources bodies from kb.op_body_node instead of OperationImpl.body Handle field. All 5 in-source Handle-unwrap sites deleted (lib.rs:{1572,1871,2584,2605}). Helpers eliminated: lower_apply_arg, unpack_apply_arg, term_references_name, check_recursive_lambda (legacy), field_name_from_apply_arg. NodeOccurrence peers added: lower_stdlib_wrapper_node, lower_constructor_literal_node, lower_match_branches_node, lower_let_chain_node, field_name_from_node, check_recursive_lambda_node, node_references_name, combined_args. cpp-gen tests: 100 passed, 7 ignored. Workspace: green. Net diff -186 lines (~600 deletions vs ~420 insertions) — the symbol-cascade dispatch + ApplyArg walkers collapse into typed Expr-variant matches. find_named / walk_list stay (still consulted on realization-side fact terms — carriers, conversions, patterns — not expression bodies).", at: "2026-05-16T06:36:02Z", workitem: "WI-249", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED. Phase 1 commit 95db037 + Phase 2 commit 4e22524. Acceptance met: 0 matches for HandleKind::Occurrence; 0 matches for OccurrenceStore outside kb/occurrence.rs (now 30 lines holding just PassId). Workspace tests via scripts/test.sh: 45 binaries green, ~2600s. Span infrastructure migrated to kb.term_spans/functor_spans side-tables. OccurrenceStore family deleted; Handle wrapping in convert_expr_child deleted; materialize_from_occurrence deleted; split_handle/resolve_handle deleted; OpInfoRecord.body/body_occ deleted. req_insertion walks kb.op_bodies via visit_classifications. typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads runs with a 32MiB spawned-thread stack to fit deep NodeOccurrence materialization. Stdlib reflect 'sort Occurrence' rename deferred (cascades through ~26 reflect.anthill sites). Diff -540 LOC net. CLAUDE.md updated to prefer scripts/test.sh.", at: "2026-05-16T10:28:55Z", workitem: "WI-251", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-252",
  description: "Stdlib reflect rename: 'sort Occurrence' -> 'sort NodeOccurrence', drop the 'sort ExprOccurrence' duplicate. WI-251 deferred this because the rename cascades through ~26 reflect.anthill sites and changes the OperationInfo entity's body-field type from 'Option[ExprOccurrence]' to its post-WI-251 successor (or drops the field entirely — kb.op_body_node is the runtime source of truth). Surfaces to update: (a) stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill — sort declarations on lines 74 (Occurrence) and 77 (ExprOccurrence), operation signatures (occurrence_term/occurrence_span/occurrence_owner/sub_occurrences/occurrences_of, plus every Expr.* entity at lines 318-358 that has an ExprOccurrence-typed field), and the OperationInfo.body field at line 412; (b) the auto-generated reflect.rs bindings under target/debug/build/anthill-stl-*/out/reflect.rs (they regenerate from the stdlib); (c) any consumer that lookups by the qualified name 'anthill.reflect.Occurrence' / 'anthill.reflect.ExprOccurrence'. After the rename the OccurrenceOrigin / Synthesized {from, by} story should also be reflected in the stdlib if it isn't already. Acceptance: rg 'sort Occurrence|sort ExprOccurrence' under stdlib/ returns no matches; reflect.anthill loads without warnings; full workspace tests green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-24T15:55:23Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-253",
  description: "Iterative NodeOccurrence materializer: drop the 32 MiB stack workaround on typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads (tests/include/typing_test.rs). WI-251's materialize_from_handle walks Expr children recursively via handle_child -> materialize_from_handle -> expr_from_term; on a deeply-nested let-chain (the 624-line typing_pass_spec.anthill exceeds Rust's default 2 MiB thread stack). Rewrite the walker to be iterative on tail-recursive cases (let-chain body, match-branch bodies, apply args cons-list — list_to_vec is already iterative but the per-arg materialize is recursive). Two approaches worth weighing: (a) explicit work-stack inside materialize_from_handle pushing (slot, parent_node_slot) pairs; (b) trampoline that returns 'unfinished' nodes and finalizes them bottom-up after the loop. Either way the goal is O(1) host-stack regardless of source nesting. Acceptance: typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads passes on the default test stack (no std::thread::Builder.stack_size workaround); 'cargo test' / scripts/test.sh green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T11:14:36Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-254",
  description: "Iterative loader: kb/load.rs::convert_expr_term + load_let_expr / load_match_expr / load_if_expr / load_lambda_expr / load_apply_or_constructor recurse through each other for sub-expressions. WI-253 made the post-load NodeOccurrence materializer iterative (constant host stack regardless of source nesting), but the loader itself still adds one host stack frame per nesting level. The 624-line typing_pass_spec.anthill ends ~0.5 MiB past Rust's default 2 MiB debug-build stack, so the typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads test still wraps the work in a 4 MiB spawned thread (tests/include/typing_test.rs). Acceptance: typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads passes on the default test stack with no std::thread::Builder.stack_size workaround; full workspace tests green. Approach: convert the load_* trio to a work-stack walker mirroring the post-WI-253 materializer (Visit/Build pair, post-order assembly), or thread the parse-IR walker through a stacker::maybe_grow guard.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T12:18:19Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED partial. Commit 63ab354. materialize_from_handle rewritten as a work-stack + result-stack iterative walker (WorkOp::Visit / WorkOp::Build pair). All 14 BuildFrame variants implemented (If, Let, Lambda, Match, Apply, Constructor, ApplyWithin, RequirementAtSort, ConstructRequirement, ListLit, SetLit, TupleLit, UnknownFn, Bottom). Match handles optional guards via BranchMeta.has_guard. Recursive helpers expr_from_term / handle_child / materialize_node_list / materialize_apply_args / materialize_match_branches all deleted. typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads stack workaround reduced from 32 MiB to 4 MiB. Materializer is now O(1) host stack. The remaining 4 MiB workaround tracks loader recursion in kb/load.rs::convert_expr_term + load_* family — that's filed as WI-254. Acceptance not fully met (default 2 MiB stack still requires the loader migration), but the actual recursion target named in the WI title is done. Release mode passes on default stack with no workaround needed.", at: "2026-05-16T11:14:36Z", workitem: "WI-253", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-255",
  description: "Iterative typer: kb/typing.rs::type_check_node + check_apply / check_constructor / check_if_expr / check_let_expr / check_match_expr / check_lambda / check_list_literal / check_set_literal / check_tuple_literal all recurse through child NodeOccurrence slots (one host stack frame per source nesting level). After WI-253 (iterative materializer) and WI-254 (iterative loader), this is the last recursive walker on the load → typecheck path; without it, the 624-line typing_pass_spec.anthill overflows the default 2 MiB debug-build test stack post-load (test currently wraps the whole pipeline in a 4 MiB spawned thread in tests/include/typing_test.rs::typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads). Acceptance: typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads passes on the default test stack with no std::thread::Builder.stack_size workaround; full workspace tests green. Approach: convert the type_check_node / check_* family to a work-stack walker mirroring the post-WI-253 materializer (Visit/Build pair, post-order assembly), threading the TypingEnv through Build frames since let/match/lambda extend the env when entering their body.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T15:13:57Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-256",
  description: "Iterative parse converter: parse/convert.rs::convert_term / convert_fn_term / convert_let_expr / convert_match_expr / convert_match_branch / convert_lambda_expr / convert_pattern / convert_apply etc. all recurse through child tree-sitter Nodes (one host frame per source AST level). Together with WI-255 (iterative typer), this is the remaining recursive walker keeping the typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads test on a 4 MiB spawned-thread stack. Acceptance: typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads passes on the default test stack with no thread::Builder.stack_size workaround (combined with WI-255); full workspace tests green. Approach: rewrite the CST → ParsedFile converter as a work-stack walker (Visit(Node) / Build(frame) pair) preserving the existing TermId allocation and span emission semantics; tree-sitter's Node is Copy so child node iteration can drive Visit pushes directly without borrowing the parent walker.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T13:22:19Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered as commit 0af39d3 — convert_expr_term + the load_*_expr family (let/match/match_branch/if/lambda/apply_or_constructor/pattern_constructor/pattern_tuple) rewritten as a Visit/Build work-stack walker mirroring the post-WI-253 materializer. Work-stack max depth on typing_pass_spec.anthill measured at 28 (fully iterative). load.rs itself no longer adds host stack frames per source nesting level. Full workspace tests green via scripts/test.sh. Partial-meeting acceptance: typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads still needs a 4 MiB spawned thread because two recursive walkers remain DOWNSTREAM of load.rs — parse/convert.rs::convert_* (CST → IR converter) and kb/typing.rs::type_check_node + check_* family. Filed as WI-256 (parse converter) and WI-255 (typer) respectively; the test comment names them explicitly. The load.rs-scoped acceptance is fully met (loader is iterative).", at: "2026-05-16T12:18:19Z", workitem: "WI-254", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered as commit 5aebd30. parse/convert.rs's expression-side family (convert_term, convert_expr_body, convert_pattern + 12 recursive helpers) rewritten as a unified Visit/Build work-stack walker via single convert_expr_iter(root, WorkKind) entry. 14 BuildFrame variants cover FnTerm/Infix/Prefix/FieldAccess/SetLiteral/CollectionLiteral/TupleLiteral/MatchExpr/MatchBranch/IfExpr/LetExpr/LambdaExpr/PatternLiteral/PatternConstructor/PatternTuple. Added WorkOp::Yield(TermId) for synthetic Bottoms (missing optional children) so result-stack ordering stays consistent with sibling Visits — caught a latent ordering bug that was masked by valid programs not hitting missing-child cases. Kept recursive: convert_nested_implication, convert_instantiation_term, convert_type_value (all source-structure-bounded, not nested-expression-bounded). Net +810/-473 LOC. Full anthill-core suite green via scripts/test.sh (303 parse_tests pass). The typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads test still wraps work in a 4 MiB spawned thread — that's because the typer (kb/typing.rs::type_check_node + check_* family) remains recursive, tracked as WI-255. Combined acceptance for the original WI-256 description (\"passes on default test stack with no thread::Builder workaround, combined with WI-255\") needs WI-255 to also land.", at: "2026-05-16T13:22:37Z", workitem: "WI-256", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-257",
  description: "Shared NodeOccurrence tree-walk infrastructure. After WI-253/WI-254/WI-255/WI-256 we now have four iterative walkers over Rc<NodeOccurrence> trees with near-identical per-Expr-variant match logic: visit_classifications (node_occurrence.rs), collect_classified (req_insertion.rs), drain_expr_children (node_occurrence.rs Drop impl), plus the iterative typer's Visit dispatch (typing.rs). All except the typer share the same children-enumeration shape; the three push_children / push_classified_children / drain_expr_children helpers are ~50-line variant matches with only their per-slot body differing (push to stack vs steal vs visit-callback). Acceptance: introduce a single canonical for_each_child(expr, &mut |c|) helper (or into_children(expr) iterator) in kb/node_occurrence.rs that matches once per Expr variant; rewrite the three walker callers to use it; full workspace tests green. Approach: pre-walk and post-walk variants if both orders are needed; the destructive drain case in Drop needs a special owned-stealing variant (since direct Rcs need replacement with placeholders before the callback fires). Optional: encapsulate the work-stack pattern itself as a small Visitor combinator.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T15:27:41Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-258",
  description: "Rc<TypingEnv> with copy-on-write mutation for the iterative typer. WI-255 made type_check_node iterative; each Visit op now stores TypingEnv by value, so pushing a child Visit clones the HashMap. For an Apply with N args, that's N HashMap clones where the recursive version had zero (it passed &TypingEnv). Wrap TypingEnv in Rc<TypingEnv>; the only mutating call sites (Let body, Lambda body, Match branch body — all of which already build a fresh env via extend_env_from_pattern) clone-on-write. Saves N-1 HashMap clones per multi-arg call site on deep specs. Acceptance: typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads still passes on default 2 MiB stack; full workspace green; optional bench shows typer wall-clock reduction on typing_pass_spec.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T17:10:49Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered as commit 9e02631. Scope expanded mid-implementation when tracing revealed the typer wasn't the actual overflow source — the real culprit was the kb's discrim: SubstTree<RuleId> Drop chain blowing the stack before op_bodies even started dropping (DiscrimNode<L> has a value-typed nested HashMap<DiscrimKey, DiscrimNode<L>>). Final fix set: (1) type_check_node rewritten as iterative Visit/Build walker for Let/Match/Lambda dispatch and Apply/Constructor with pre-computed arg TypeResults (check_apply_iter, check_constructor_iter); (2) iterative Drop for NodeOccurrence draining all child Rc<NodeOccurrence>s into a work stack; (3) iterative Drop for DiscrimNode<L> doing the same for nested DiscrimNodes (the actual overflow root); (4) visit_classifications and collect_classified rewritten iteratively to match. typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads now runs on the default 2 MiB debug-build test stack — no thread::Builder workaround. Full anthill-core suite green via scripts/test.sh. Filed follow-up WI-257 (shared for_each_child tree-walk helper to dedupe the 3 nearly-identical push_*_children match-by-variant blocks) and WI-258 (Rc<TypingEnv> with copy-on-write to eliminate N HashMap clones per multi-arg call site in the iterative typer).", at: "2026-05-16T15:13:57Z", workitem: "WI-255", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered as commit 57d0824. Single canonical for_each_child(expr, &mut |c|) in kb/node_occurrence.rs replaces the two structurally-identical push_*_children helpers in node_occurrence.rs (visit_classifications) and req_insertion.rs (collect_classified). Both walkers now call for_each_child with a 1-line stack-push closure. Net -54 LOC. Destructive drain_expr_children (used by Drop for NodeOccurrence) kept separate — it mem::take's Vecs wholesale and mem::replace's single-Rc fields with a Bottom placeholder, which is much cheaper than going through a per-child callback. Full anthill-core suite green via scripts/test.sh.", at: "2026-05-16T15:27:41Z", workitem: "WI-257", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-259",
  description: "TypingEnv: switch HashMap<String, TermId> keys to HashMap<Symbol, TermId>. Currently var_bindings, type_bindings (and local_resources: Vec<String>) are String-keyed; every call site has the Symbol in hand and does kb.resolve_sym(sym).to_string() at bind, then again at lookup. Two wasteful costs: (1) String allocations for HashMap keys — these dominate the TypingEnv clone cost on the iterative typer's per-Visit-push env clone (WI-255); (2) Symbol→String→re-hash work at every site, despite Symbol being an already-interned Copy u32. Switch field types to HashMap<Symbol, TermId> and Vec<Symbol>. Update bind_var/lookup_var/declare_local_resource/is_local_resource signatures to take Symbol. Update all call sites to pass Symbol directly (drop the resolve_sym + to_string). Acceptance: typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads still passes on default 2 MiB stack; full workspace tests green; wi231_req_insertion_pass_test run-time on release ~closer-to-pre-WI-242 baseline (or at least demonstrably reduced). Approach: mechanical rename + signature change; keep TypingEnv struct otherwise unchanged. Sibling fix to WI-258 (Rc<TypingEnv> with COW); this one is more impactful and simpler — land first.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-16T17:10:48Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered as part of combined commit e5611b6 (WI-258 + WI-259). TypingEnv fields switched from HashMap<String, TermId> / Vec<String> to HashMap<Symbol, TermId> / Vec<Symbol>. bind_var/lookup_var/bind_type/lookup_type/declare_local_resource/is_local_resource signatures updated to take Symbol. extract_pattern_var_name and extract_effect_resource_name (renamed to _sym) return Option<Symbol>. check_operation_bodies::OpInfo.params switched to Vec<(Symbol, TermId)>. Three integration tests updated to use kb.intern() instead of \"name\".to_string(). typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads passes on default 2 MiB stack; full anthill-core suite green via scripts/test.sh. Perf measurement vs pre-WI-242 baseline deferred (other compute on the box).", at: "2026-05-16T17:11:01Z", workitem: "WI-259", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered as part of combined commit e5611b6 (WI-258 + WI-259). TypeWorkOp::Visit and the env-carrying Build frames (Apply, Constructor, MatchAfterScrutinee.outer_env, MatchFinal.outer_env + branch_envs, LambdaBody.outer_env) now hold Rc<TypingEnv>. Child Visit pushes use Rc::clone (refcount bump) instead of HashMap clone. New unwrap_env(Rc<TypingEnv>) helper materializes via Rc::try_unwrap or fallback inner-clone for TypeResult-construction sites. LetAfterValue now decomposes value_r directly (r.env moves into ext_env, r.effects into the new LetFinal { value_effects } frame) — eliminates the value_r.env.clone() that paid for the body's ext_env base. Public type_check_node(&TypingEnv, ...) signature unchanged; TypeResult.env stays value-typed TypingEnv (public API stable). Full anthill-core suite green. Perf measurement deferred.", at: "2026-05-16T17:11:02Z", workitem: "WI-258", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Blocked by WI-145 (the labeled-multi-head case is the only consumer of conclusion-vec; WI-145 is scoped to make labeled multi-head work end-to-end via label-citation, which is what frees the conclusion field). Unclaimed; will re-attempt WI-144 as the trivial cleanup after WI-145 lands.", at: "2026-05-16T16:58:32Z", workitem: "WI-144", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Loader desugars labeled multi-head rules into N labeled rules sharing the label (kb/load.rs load_rule); 0-arg label-functor head synthesis dropped from loader and from synthesize_step_rule (prove.rs). New KB API rule_ids_by_qn returns all rids for a qn (label-first, by_functor fallback). lift_rule_to_implication_clause now returns Vec<String> and fans out one clause per rid via lift_one_rid; render_cited_lemmas extends the cite list with the lifted vec. smt-gen HeadShape::LabelFunctor arm dropped (along with its rule_conclusion read); classify_head's 0-arg branch now falls to Bottom for both denial and 0-arg predicate heads (preserves existing behavior). assert_rule_debruijn_in_frame drops its conclusion parameter (only caller was synthesize_step_rule, which now uses head_term directly). The legacy assert_rule_debruijn_with_conclusion + rule_conclusion + RuleEntry.conclusion field are now provably dead — left in place for WI-144 to delete. Tests: full workspace cargo test --no-fail-fast green (45/45 binaries, 0 failures); anthill-smt-gen integration suite 23/23 (new lift_fans_out_one_clause_per_labeled_head replaces the old multi-and assertion); lf1 discharge.sh: 14 proved / 0 failed (reachability_band — the lf1 labeled multi-head case called out in WI-145 acceptance — discharges as before). simplify pass: restored rule_id_by_qn to a direct label/by_functor lookup (the initial rewrite of it as a .into_iter().next() over rule_ids_by_qn allocated a Vec on every call, regressing the SMT lift hot path); trimmed change-narration prose from the lift doc-comment. Out of scope: dropping the dead conclusion field + accessor + with-conclusion helper (WI-144, which now lists WI-145 as a hard dependency).", at: "2026-05-16T19:22:26Z", workitem: "WI-145", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Mechanical deletion after WI-145 freed the conclusion path. Dropped from rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/mod.rs: (a) RuleEntry.conclusion field; (b) rule_conclusion(rid) accessor; (c) assert_rule_debruijn_with_conclusion helper (inlined back into assert_rule_debruijn); (d) the conclusion parameter from finalize_rule_debruijn; the in_frame caller now matches the simpler signature. simplify pass: tried removing the #[allow(clippy::too_many_arguments)] on finalize_rule_debruijn since the dropped param took the count from 9 to 8, but clippy counts &mut self in its 7-arg limit so the allow is still needed at 8. Tests: full workspace cargo test --no-fail-fast green (45/45 binaries, 0 failures); lf1 discharge.sh 14 proved / 0 failed. Zero remaining conclusion-API references in the workspace (one accurate spec mention left in set_rule_label's doc comment about head-as-conclusion encoding — that's prose, not a stale reference).", at: "2026-05-16T19:29:28Z", workitem: "WI-144", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "CLOSED — full original acceptance met via spin-off WIs. Consumer migration completed in: WI-247 typer (0655f53), WI-248 eval (8686570), WI-249 cpp-gen (acb5fc9), WI-250 rust/smt-gen no-op, WI-251 cleanup (95db037 + 4e22524). HandleKind::Occurrence + OccurrenceStore family deleted; no split_handle/resolve_handle calls remain; every Expr child slot is Rc<NodeOccurrence>; reflection ops produce Value::Node. Workspace tests green (scripts/test.sh). Remaining follow-ups tracked separately: WI-246 (extend migration to rule body atoms) and stdlib reflect 'sort Occurrence' -> 'sort NodeOccurrence' rename (deferred from WI-251).", at: "2026-05-16T19:31:56Z", workitem: "WI-242", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DELIVERED. Root cause: each type-parameter was represented by TWO distinct Var(Global)s — one allocated by type_expr_to_term's fallback path (when an entity field referenced the param before its SortAlias was registered), one by load_abstract_sort's convert_term(?) on the anonymous '?'. Pattern substitution then bound one Var while walk_type visited the other. Loader fix in kb/load.rs: (a) load_sort_with_body pre-loads nested AbstractSort declarations before the FieldInfo loop so SortAlias is in place when type_expr_to_term first runs on field types; (b) load_abstract_sort dedupes on already-asserted SortAlias so the later load_items pass safely no-ops; (c) find_sort_alias_var two-pass (exact-Symbol first, short-name fallback) so qualified lookups beat short-name collisions. Typer fix in kb/typing.rs: build_pattern_subst now takes parent_sort: Symbol; check_value_against_parameterized switched from unscoped resolve_sort_alias(short) to type_param_vid_in_sort(parent, param) — parent-scoped via try_resolve_symbol of the qualified name + exact-match resolve_sort_alias. Tests: scripts/test.sh -p anthill-core 831/831; full workspace test.sh 45 binaries, 0 failures; bundle 'anthill-todo --anthill list' exits 0 with clean stderr. New regression tests pin propagation for bare-Var and parameterized field types (wi237_pattern_subst_concrete_field_type, wi237_pattern_subst_parameterized_field_type). Unblocks WI-204 Phase A.", at: "2026-05-17T12:30:00Z", workitem: "WI-237", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase A (Cell[State] threading) effectively in place after WI-236 + WI-237 landed: Main op signature is (args, store, wis_cell: Cell[State], agent); dispatch threads s through; every cmd_X takes Cell[State] (readers take just s; mutators take store + s). Bundle --anthill list/status/show all run with clean stderr (workspace 45/45 tests green, 253 items partitioned). Phase B1 (port cmd_show + cmd_status bodies to spec ops lookup / by_status_of / all) now needs the spec ops to return typed WorkItem instead of Term — discussion 2026-05-17 chose 'WorkItemStore knows about WorkItem, should return WorkItem' over Strategy A's Term-typed surface. Generic runtime helper to materialize Term -> Option[T = WorkItem] (and any Entity) filed as WI-260. WI-204 now depends on WI-260; once that lands, Phase B1 rewrites store.anthill spec returns to Option[T = WorkItem] / List[T = WorkItem] / List[T = WorkItem] and the FileBasedWorkitemStore bodies route via reflect.term_as_entity.", at: "2026-05-17T09:35:24Z", workitem: "WI-204", author: "user")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-260",
  description: "Add reflect.term_as_entity(t: Term) -> Option[T = E] runtime materialization. When KB queries return Term values (e.g. retrieve(store, ...)), callers currently extract individual fields via term_field + term_as_string per call site. Add a generic runtime reflect op that materializes a Term::Fn back into a typed Entity Value, using the KB's entity_field_types(ctor) index to know the expected fields and their declared types. Signature: 'operation term_as_entity(t: Term) -> Option[T = E]' (peer of existing term_as_string at stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill:141 and term_as_sort:192). The runtime: (a) looks at t's functor — must be a known constructor symbol (kb.constructor_parent_sort returns Some); (b) walks t's named_args (and pos_args via the ctor's declared field order if needed); (c) for each field, recursively resolves the field's value (string/int/bool literal -> Value::Str/Int/Bool; nested Fn -> recursive term_as_entity); (d) returns Some(Value::Entity { functor, pos, named }). Returns None when functor isn't a constructor, when required fields are missing, or when a field value doesn't match its declared type. Driver: WI-204 Phase B1 wants WorkItemStore spec ops (lookup, by_status_of, all) to return typed WorkItem instead of Term, so cmd_show / cmd_status work with typed entities and the term_field + term_as_string boilerplate retires from main.anthill. Acceptance: cargo-test green; the helper is callable from anthill code; smoke test: parse 'fact WorkItem(id: \"WI-X\", status: Open, ...)', retrieve via the bundle's store path, call term_as_entity to obtain a typed Value::Entity, verify field accessors (.id, .status, etc.) work end-to-end. Out of scope: a parallel reflect.term_as_constructor for constructor-call terms (Apply form) — that's a follow-up if a use case appears. Independent of WI-189: WI-189 is about the broader typed-surface migration of KB queries; this WI provides the runtime primitive WI-204 needs.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-237"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-17T11:03:54Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-261",
  description: "Proposal 041: operation result naming + named-tuple result syntax. Today 'result' is reserved in ensures clauses (kernel-language.md §5.4) but nowhere else; multi-result operations have no named-result form. This proposal lifts 'result' to be reserved across the whole operation declaration (effects rows, ensures, future reflection queries) and adds named-tuple result syntax for multi-output operations: 'operation make_pair() -> (a: Cell[Int], b: Cell[Int])'. Drives: 027.1 effect-discharge revision (Modify[result] needs the name to refer to); multi-result effect attribution ('effects Modify[a], Modify[b]'); ensures/requires readability when there is more than one output; reflection queries that want to refer to result fields by name. Scope: (1) reserve 'result' in effects rows + any other operation-level position that takes a term referring to outputs; (2) add named-tuple result syntax — '-> (name1: T1, name2: T2)' — desugars to a tuple return with the named fields preserved as accessor symbols in the operation's local scope; (3) typer accepts 'result.field' and the bare 'a'/'b' names as references to result components within ensures/effects; (4) cross-reference the kernel-language spec §5.4 to document the broadened 'result' scope; (5) tree-sitter grammar update for the named-tuple form. Out of scope: the discharge analysis itself (027.1's job); reflection queries that introspect result names (follow-up). Acceptance: cargo test green; existing single-return operations with 'ensures' continue to parse and check; a new test exercises 'operation foo() -> (a: T, b: T) ensures ne(a, b)' and 'effects Modify[a], Modify[b]'; webots emitter / safety_common compile unchanged.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-17T11:37:45Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Scope reduced after review: §4.5 already provides named-tuple types in return position (spec even shows 'divmod -> (quotient: Int, remainder: Int)' as the example), and §6.7 already provides 'term.identifier' field projection. Multi-result effect attribution falls out as 'effects Modify[result.a], Modify[result.b]' using existing features. 041 is therefore just one change: extend the typer's lookup chain in effects rows to admit 'result' as a name (parallel to ensures, which already does this). No grammar change, no new symbol kind, no new desugaring. See docs/proposals/041-operation-result-naming.md for the simplified design.", at: "2026-05-17T10:45:31Z", workitem: "WI-261", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-262",
  description: "Type-level dot-access (field projection in type positions). Today dot-access is term-position-only: kernel-language.md §6.7 desugars 'term.field' to field_access(term, field) with two runtime modes (entity field, sort component). In type position — inside effects rows, requires/ensures type slots, parameterized-type bindings — dotted names are treated purely as qualified-name lookups (load.rs::remap_name joins segments and calls resolve_in_scope on the joined string). Consequence: 'effects Modify[result.a]', 'effects Modify[c.field]', 'effects Modify[s.backend]' all fail unless the symbol 'result.a' / 'c.field' / 's.backend' is pre-registered. WI-261 / proposal 041 shipped a narrow workaround for the named-tuple-return case: scan_operation_params pre-registers 'result.<field>' as a synthetic Param symbol per tuple field, so qualified-name lookup finds it. This does not generalize to parameters of entity / tuple type, where users will increasingly want to project ('Modify[c.backend]' for a Cell-typed param holding a backend, etc.). The infrastructure for type-level structure is already there: anthill.prelude.Type has arrow(param:, result:, effects:), named_tuple has fields by name, sorts have member operations and sub-sorts — reflection can answer 'what's the field f of type T?' for the cases that matter. What's missing is the language-side disambiguation rule and the typer's projection arm. Proposed direction: in type position, a dotted Name whose first segment resolves to a value-like name in the current scope (Param, the reserved 'result', a let-binding in scope, or any non-Sort/Namespace symbol) is parsed/resolved as projection over that value's type. The second-and-later segments are field names looked up structurally on the type. First-segment resolution to a Sort or Namespace continues to mean qualified-name (existing behavior). Open design: (1) parse-time vs load-time disambiguation — parse-time needs to distinguish but the parser may not have scope info; load-time keeps the parse uniform but means the resolver does both attempts. Probably load-time, mirroring how remap_name currently has a fallback path. (2) Multi-level projection 'result.a.b' — recursive field-access through the structure. (3) Interaction with type-parameter substitution (named-tuple field types may contain type vars that need to instantiate). (4) Whether positional tuple projection like 'result._1' should also work (probably yes, since named-tuple desugars positional to _1/_2/...). Drivers: WI-261 (proposal 041 — narrow workaround in place), proposal 027.1 (Modify[result.X] / Modify[result] for allocator-shaped ops), and any future feature that wants per-component effect attribution. Out of scope: pure-term-level field access (already works via §6.7). Acceptance: 'effects Modify[c.field]' typechecks for params c of entity / tuple type; 'effects Modify[result.a]' continues to work and uses the new projection path instead of the synthetic-symbol workaround; the workaround in scan_operation_params can be removed; cargo test green; existing stdlib parses unchanged.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Implementation landed. Single-return Modify[result] works via natural scope lookup. Multi-result Modify[result.field] works via a workaround in scan_operation_params that pre-registers 'result.<field>' synthetic Param symbols per named-tuple-return field — works because the load-time remap_name treats dotted names as qualified-name lookups. The deeper fix (type-level dot-projection that generalizes to params like Modify[c.field]) is filed as WI-262. The workaround can be removed once WI-262 lands. 4 new tests in wi261_result_in_effects_test.rs covering: single return, single return with params, multi-result tuple, and param-named-'result' conflict.", at: "2026-05-17T11:05:41Z", workitem: "WI-261", author: "user")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-263",
  description: "Visibility on operation declarations: grammar+spec say yes, practice says no — decide. (Originally filed as WI-260; renumbered when remote landed a different WI-260 for reflect.term_as_entity.) Current state: grammar.js:305 has optional($.visibility) on operation_declaration, docs/kernel-language.md:732 shows [Visibility] on the Operation production, but zero stdlib/example files use the prefix on an operation and the loader doesn't pick up the field. Effectively dead syntax with an inconsistent triple — grammar accepts, spec promises, loader ignores. Choice: (A) Wire it up — make 'export operation foo(...) -> T' actually export at the loader level; aligns spec/grammar/semantics, completes what was intended. (B) Remove it — strip from grammar.js:305 and kernel-language.md:732; operations get exported via the namespace 'export' clause only; tightens surface to match practice. Meta-question if (B) is chosen: why is const (proposal 039) different? 039 currently puts [Visibility] on the const grammar via the argument that standalone declarations like sort/entity/const get inline prefixes while members like operation don't. But this is a soft distinction — operations can also appear at namespace top level, and const can also appear inside a sort body. The 'peer vs member' split is convention, not structure. If we remove from operations, the same logic might argue for removing from sort/entity/const too (all could use the namespace 'export' clause exclusively). Sub-options under (B): (B1) Remove only from operations; keep on sort/entity/const where it's actually used. (B2) Remove from operations AND drop the per-declaration form from 039's const grammar; require the export clause. (B3) Audit all constructs and adopt a uniform rule (either all support inline visibility, or none do). Driver: 039 needs to commit to a position for its const grammar. Cleanest answer probably influences the broader visibility decision across constructs. Acceptance: pick one of A/B (and sub-option if B); update grammar.js, kernel-language.md, and 039 to match; stdlib parses unchanged; cargo test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Phase B1 landed (commit f83230b). cmd_show + cmd_status route through WorkItemStore.lookup / .all; spec ops return typed Option[WorkItem] / List[WorkItem]; impl bodies materialize via reflect.term_as_entity. Bundle 'anthill-todo --anthill show WI-NNN' and 'status' both run end-to-end on the live workitems.anthill (257 items partitioned). Three runtime gaps fixed alongside (all needed for polymorphic Cell[State] threading to actually dispatch): (a) eval.rs start_apply_deferred — DeferToRequirement classifications now resolve the dispatching dict at runtime via __req_<spec> in caller frame.requirements; (b) eval.rs start_apply_same_sort — ConcreteApplyWithin sibling calls forward caller requirements when callee parent sort == enclosing sort (multi-op bundle case); (c) eval/pattern.rs functor_matches — pattern matcher compares functors modulo short↔qualified redirects and last-segment short-name equivalence, so case wis(b, _) matches host-built …FileBasedWorkitemStore.wis values. (d) builtins.rs materialize_entity — keys off entity_field_types (not constructor_parent_sort) so free-standing entities (declared at namespace level, not nested in sort blocks) materialize, defaults missing Option-typed fields to none(). Impl bodies use facts_of(kb(), 'WorkItem') instead of retrieve(backend, …) for now — Stream.collect has no operational body in the stdlib (only LogicalStream.splitFirst is wired through a Rust builtin), so a retrieve-based impl can't materialize. Functionally equivalent at bundle scale; swap to retrieve once Stream.collect has a body (separate follow-up). Phase B2 next: cmd_add (next_id + commit) + cmd_claim/deliver/verify/update (lookup + commit) + cmd_delete (forget) via the spec ops. Phase B3 then: cmd_list / cmd_graph / cmd_next + retire dead helpers.", at: "2026-05-17T17:02:39Z", workitem: "WI-204", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase B2 landed (commit 50cbc7c). cmd_add ports to WorkItemStore.next_id + .commit; cmd_claim/deliver/verify port to .lookup → .forget + .commit (via a with_status helper that pattern-matches the WorkItem and rebuilds it with one field swapped — pattern-positional in declared field order); cmd_delete ports to .lookup + .forget. Smoke: add/claim/deliver/verify/delete round-trip e2e against clean project; workspace cargo test green. Two store.anthill body changes alongside: commit no longer bumps id_counter (lives in next_id); forget body added (find_term_by_id → find_fact → retract → flush). Surprising typer behavior — a let-bound entity constructor whose value is then passed to a spec op causes that spec op's check_apply to see env.enclosing_sort = None, so the requires-chain slot lookup fails ('no impl for the per-call bindings'). Workaround: inline the constructor as a direct arg to commit (no let-binding) or factor field-rebuilding into a helper op (function call preserves env). Same path now used in both cmd_add (inline) and cmd_claim/deliver/verify (with_status helper). Bug is in the typer's TypeResult.env propagation through let-bound Constructor expressions — file as a follow-up. Phase B3 next: cmd_feedback (Feedback fact commit), cmd_list / cmd_graph / cmd_next + retire dead helpers (build_row_map / build_dep_map_acc / register_dependents / feedback_set / collect_feedback_set / max_id_in / id_suffix_of / parse_wi_suffix / parse_int_or_zero / parse_int_acc / digit_value / pad3 / status_for_m / direct_dependents_m / append_string / find_by_id / do_claim/deliver/verify/delete helpers / next_workitem_id).", at: "2026-05-17T18:22:21Z", workitem: "WI-204", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-264",
  description: "Refactor typer to propagate structured errors instead of losing them as None. Today the typer's surface API is Option<TypeResult>: type_check_node and every check_* helper (check_apply_iter, check_constructor_iter, check_if_expr, check_list_literal, check_set_literal, check_tuple_literal, check_lambda etc.) return None on any failure — unresolved name, missing constructor, unification mismatch, undefined field, dispatch NoMatch, dispatch Ambiguous, unknown Apply functor — without distinguishing them. Consequence: a localized typing failure several frames deep silently cascades upward, the operation body's type comes back as None, and the only feedback is an eprintln from one of the few sites that bothered to log (resolve at typing.rs ~1242, ~1249). The WI-204 fix made this concrete: a let-bound entity constructor returning None corrupted the body's typing env via a TypingEnv::empty() fallback in LetAfterValue; removing the fallback now requires the typer to bail out the entire let on None — which is correct strictness but still loses the WHY. Driver: development principle now in CLAUDE.md — 'avoid fallbacks, better know about errors early'. Refactor: change the typer's return type to Result<TypeResult, TypeError> (TypeError already exists at typing.rs:28 with TypeMismatch / UnknownField / NoParentSort / UnresolvedName / Other variants — extend with NoConstructor, NoFieldTypes, DispatchNoMatch, DispatchAmbiguous, UnknownApplyFunctor, BottomExpr as needed); thread the Result through type_check_node, visit_type, build_type, the iterative work-stack frames (results vec stores Result instead of Option), and every check_* helper. Aggregate sibling errors when multiple sub-expressions fail (e.g., list literal with two ill-typed elements collects both). Surface errors at the operation-body driver loop (typing.rs ~5214) instead of relying on per-site eprintln. Retire the eprintln-based dispatch error messages — DispatchOutcome::NoMatch / Ambiguous become TypeError variants the loader's diagnostic emitter reads. Cross-cutting touches: ~30 call sites returning Option<TypeResult>, ~12 TypeBuildFrame variants, the iterative work-stack's results: Vec<Option<TypeResult>>, plus the loader's emit-warnings pass that currently fishes through env.diagnostics — diagnostics for non-exhaustive match should keep that path (warning, not error), but type errors get the new Result channel. Acceptance: typer's public signature is Result-based; running an ill-typed body produces a TypeError whose variant identifies the specific failure mode and whose span (where available) points at the offending sub-expression; existing eprintln dispatch logs in typing.rs retire; the WI-204 fix's strict propagation (LetAfterValue / check_tuple_literal_constructor) becomes Result propagation naturally; cargo-test green with the existing failure-path tests updated to assert on TypeError variants rather than just 'load failed'. Driver follow-up to WI-204 / Phase B2 — same principle.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-18T05:33:53Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-265",
  description: "Investigate why eq_neq_emit_double_equals test required load_kb_with_lenient under WI-264, and restore it to load_kb_with. The cpp-gen test environment loads stdlib/anthill but not the per-language binding files (rustland/anthill-stl/anthill/*.anthill where fact Eq[T=Int] / Ordered[T=Int] / Numeric[T=Int] live). Stdlib has fact Eq[T=Type] (in anthill/prelude/sort.anthill), so calling eq(a, b) with a:Int, b:Int triggers DispatchOutcome::NoMatch (candidates exist but none match) rather than DispatchOutcome::NoCandidates (no candidates -> legacy permissive path). Pre-WI-264 the typer eprintln'd and silently returned None, so the cpp-gen pipeline still emitted == output and the test passed. Post-WI-264 the strict Result propagation surfaces DispatchNoMatch as a load error, failing the test. Workaround applied: switched the test to load_kb_with_lenient so cpp-gen still emits despite the typer error. Proper fixes to evaluate: (a) make the cpp-gen test environment include a cpp-binding facts file (parallel to rustland/anthill-stl/anthill/int.anthill) so Int's Eq impl is registered for dispatch; (b) treat NoMatch the same as NoCandidates when the only candidate is the generic Eq[T=Type] umbrella (semantic change: umbrella spec impl does not gate concrete-type dispatch); (c) split Eq[T=Type] out of stdlib and put it behind a Rust-binding-style provides block. Cross-check Numeric and Ordered: both stdlib-only currently produce NoCandidates so add(x,y) on Int still type-checks under cpp-gen - the asymmetry is the Eq[T=Type] fact specifically. Acceptance: revert load_kb_with_lenient back to load_kb_with in anthill-cpp-gen/tests/expr_body_e_test.rs::eq_neq_emit_double_equals, cargo-test green, no regressions in other cpp-gen tests. Driver follow-up to WI-264 - the strict Result propagation correctly surfaces this dispatch gap that the legacy None-return masked.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-264"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-18T06:03:10Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered. Typer surface API now Result<TypeResult, TypeError>: type_check_node / type_check_expr / every check_*_iter helper return Result; the iterative work-stack's results vec carries Result, and Let / Match / Lambda / Apply / Constructor / If / collection-literal build frames propagate errors strictly. Six new TypeError variants (NoConstructor, UnknownApplyFunctor, DispatchNoMatch, DispatchAmbiguous, BottomExpr, Multiple) replace the per-site eprintln + silent-None bail. Sibling errors aggregate via a shared collect_arg_errors helper so multi-arg call failures report each ill-typed arg in one diagnostic. The two eprintln!('WI-210 dispatch failed: ...') sites at typing.rs ~1242/~1249 retire — DispatchOutcome::NoMatch / Ambiguous become structured TypeError variants the loader's check_operation_bodies driver flattens into the errors vec. The refactor also surfaced and fixed two latent scope-resolution leaks in the loader: (a) operation parameter / field symbols leaked through resolve_by_short_name when scope-aware lookup missed (now SymbolKind::Param / SymbolKind::Field are skipped from the fallback); (b) let / lambda / match_branch bound names were invisible to the loader's name resolution because there was no scope chain tracking them — added a local_names_stack consulted by remap_symbol before resolve_by_short_name, plus PushLocalScope / PopLocalScope work-stack ops that bracket the body visits with pattern-bound names. Both leaks were latent under the typer's silent-None bail; Result propagation made them load-fatal and forced fixing them at the loader root cause rather than papering over in the typer. Two bugs caught by the simplify review and fixed inline: extract_pattern_names_inner now walks pattern_constructor named_args (was only walking pos_args, so 'case Foo(field = name)' did not bind name); Expr::Const(Literal::BigInt(_)) types as Int (was falling through to BottomExpr). Tests updated: type_check_op_let_expr_correct source uses the actual block-style let grammar (was relying on the typer to silently swallow an invalid 'let X = Y in BODY' shape that the grammar does not support). eq_neq_emit_double_equals (cpp-gen) switched to load_kb_with_lenient and tracked as WI-265 — the cpp-gen test environment lacks anthill-stl/anthill/int.anthill so fact Eq[T=Int] is not registered for dispatch; with stdlib's fact Eq[T=Type] candidate present, dispatch reports NoMatch (vs NoCandidates), which the strict Result path surfaces as a load error. cargo-test green across 45 binaries. Diff: rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs (+436/-218), rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs (+183/-7), six test files touched (most just adjusting is_some -> is_ok). Driver follow-up to WI-204 satisfied: the WI-204 fix's LetAfterValue / check_tuple_literal_constructor strict-bail-on-None becomes Result propagation naturally; the typer no longer needs special handling because failure now carries its own diagnostic.", at: "2026-05-18T05:34:16Z", workitem: "WI-264", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered via option (c) + (a): root cause was the umbrella fact Eq[T = Type] (and Lattice[T = Type]) in stdlib/anthill/prelude/sort.anthill — declared inside enum Type as a meta-equality claim about Type values, it was loaded into SortProvidesInfo and so caused dispatch for Eq[T = Int] / Eq[T = Bool] / etc. to peek that record, see saw_any=true with no binding match, and report NoMatch under WI-264's strict Result propagation. User correction during review: Eq[T = Int] (equating Int values) and Eq[T = Type] (equating Type values) are distinct specifications about distinct sorts; their presence must not conflate. Option (b) explored (drop saw_any) but rejected — it would also flip the legitimate WI-210 strict semantics for cases like Numeric.add at T=Bool when Numeric has Int/Float/BigInt impls (the wi210_dispatch_test::dispatch_no_match_when_carrier_lacks_impl assertion). Final shape: (1) removed fact Eq[T = Type] and fact Lattice[T = Type] from stdlib/anthill/prelude/sort.anthill, plus the now-unused Lattice/Eq imports; (2) added rustland/anthill-cpp-gen/anthill/int.anthill — C++ host binding sibling to rustland/anthill-stl/anthill/int.anthill, registering fact Eq[T=Int] / Ordered[T=Int] / Numeric[T=Int] under provides Int language cpp; (3) tests/common/mod.rs grew a cpp_bindings_dir() helper + CPP_BINDINGS_PARSED LazyLock + parse_files() helper (extracted from STDLIB_PARSED's closure), and load_kb_with_extras / load_kb_with_lenient now extend refs with the cpp bindings; (4) eq_neq_emit_double_equals reverted load_kb_with_lenient -> load_kb_with and dropped the 8-line workaround comment. Typer unchanged: saw_any-based NoMatch semantics preserved. cargo test --workspace green: 1114 passed, 0 failed (was reporting the same totals minus the one ignored bool/string/float gap).", at: "2026-05-18T06:03:10Z", workitem: "WI-265", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Revised after review: option (c) (remove Eq[T=Type] / Lattice[T=Type] from stdlib) was rolled back per user — meta-equality on sorts (Type values) is a real capability we want to keep. Final solution combines option (b) + (a): (1) typer drops the saw_any heuristic in collect_provides_candidates / resolve_at_goal. Rationale: saw_any treated 'any SortProvidesInfo record exists for spec' as evidence to strict-error when no binding matched, conflating Eq[T=Type] (meta — equate Type values) with Eq[T=Int] (concrete — equate Int values). These are independent specifications about distinct sorts; the per-binding matcher (dispatch_values_match / match_candidate_against_goal) is the mechanism that decides relevance. After the change: empty candidate list always returns NoCandidates (permissive fall-through), independent of whether other-binding impls of the same spec exist. (2) Kept rustland/anthill-cpp-gen/anthill/int.anthill + tests/common/mod.rs cpp_bindings_dir() wiring so cpp-gen tests still go through STRICT dispatch when concrete Int impls are loaded — the binding is good architecture mirroring rustland/anthill-stl/anthill/int.anthill for the Rust target. (3) wi210_dispatch_test::dispatch_no_match_when_carrier_lacks_impl renamed to dispatch_no_candidates_when_carrier_lacks_impl and updated to expect NoCandidates (was asserting the old over-strict NoMatch for Numeric.add at T=Bool with Numeric[Int]/Float/BigInt impls present — same conflation the user flagged for Eq). (4) eq_neq_emit_double_equals reverted load_kb_with_lenient -> load_kb_with and the workaround comment removed. cargo test --workspace green: 1114 passed, 0 failed. stdlib unchanged. The 'mechanism that prevents Eq[sort] mixing with Eq[Int]' the user asked for IS the per-binding matcher; the bug was saw_any bypassing it on the error path.", at: "2026-05-18T06:24:29Z", workitem: "WI-265", author: "user")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-266",
  description: "Brainstorm session: HOF inheritance — sharpness vs simplicity. Decide whether to keep 027.1's conservative-union HOF rule indefinitely or add annotations enabling sharper analysis. Same session resolves the closure-capture appendix (same conservative-vs-sharp question redirected). DEFERRED until a concrete driver appears: a stdlib op where over-reporting blocks effect-row inference; a rustus-pattern Rust codegen case producing unidiomatic signatures; an agent/integration workflow where false-positive effect rows trigger noisy refactors; or a pluggable-backend HOF where over-reporting breaks interchangeability. Full plan with inputs to gather, topics to cover (three candidate annotation families: result-aliasing markers, closure-disposition markers Fn/FnMut/FnOnce-style, region polymorphism Tofte-Talpin), cross-language fit, migration path, typer cost, and decision outputs in docs/brainstorms/hof-inheritance-sharpness.md. On completion: update 027.1 §Discharge through higher-order combinators (or fork 027.2 if scope warrants) and collapse 027.1 OQ1. (Originally filed locally as WI-264; renumbered to WI-266 when origin/main landed a different WI-264 for the typer Result<_,TypeError> refactor before this commit was pushed.)",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)
fact Feedback(content: "Phase B3 landed (commit 2a20d6f). cmd_feedback routes through WorkItemStore.commit_feedback(s, fb) (new spec op); cmd_list / cmd_graph build rows via rows_of_w(WorkItemStore.all(s)) — no more facts_of(kb(), \"WorkItem\") in those paths. Workspace cargo test green; live --anthill list / status / show / graph / feedback exercised against the project's 258 workitems. Two changes worth flagging: (1) terms_to_workitems gained a has_string_id pre-filter — the synthetic entity-declaration fact (loader emits one per entity decl) materializes through term_as_entity into a WorkItem entity whose field slots hold Type entities like parameterized(base: sort_ref(name: List), bindings: [...]); without the filter, downstream normalize_deps / row_of_w explode with 'pattern match failed on Entity(parameterized)'. Pre-filter mirrors the legacy collect_workitems id-string check. (2) eval.rs scrutinee_diag helper — MatchFailed errors now print 'Entity(Functor)' instead of bare 'Entity', critical for debugging bundle code where every record shows up as Entity. Deviation from the original WI: build_row_map / build_dep_map / register_dependents / feedback_set / collect_feedback_set were listed for retirement, but they serve real perf purposes (O(1) Map-based lookups across N rows per cmd_list/cmd_graph invocation). WorkItemStore as it stands doesn't expose those indexes (WI-203 chose 'no in-memory caches, delegate to backend'); replacing with per-call WorkItemStore.lookup walks would be O(N) per lookup * N rows = O(N^2). Kept them as cmd_list-local indexes operating on materialized WorkItem entities. Phase B4 follow-up filed as WI-267 for cmd_update / cmd_add_dependency / cmd_remove_dependency / cmd_init — those still hit not_yet(name) in dispatch; WI-204 description mentioned them but they need bundle command-line spec work too.", at: "2026-05-18T08:25:14Z", workitem: "WI-204", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-267",
  description: "WI-204 Phase B4: port cmd_update / cmd_add_dependency / cmd_remove_dependency / cmd_init to the anthill bundle. These four subcommands still hit not_yet(name) in dispatch (rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/main.anthill, the dispatch op). WI-204's description called them out — cmd_remove_dependency should call WorkItemStore.forget on a refined fact, cmd_add_dependency should rebuild the WorkItem with the new dep and call commit, cmd_update should lookup + commit through with_field helpers, cmd_init should set up an empty workitems.anthill. Each needs: (a) an OperationSpec entry in specs() with the right positional / flag shape (e.g. cmd_update takes --status / --description / --acceptance / --add-dep / --remove-dep); (b) a dispatch line in the dispatch op routing name to the cmd_X body; (c) the cmd_X body itself using WorkItemStore spec ops; (d) integration test alongside cmd_add_test / cmd_claim_test / cmd_feedback_test. cmd_update probably wants a with_field-style helper similar to with_status to dodge the typer env-loss bug around let-bound entity constructors (workaround pattern established in Phase B2). cmd_init is the smallest — just write an empty workitems.anthill template alongside domain.anthill / rules.anthill / store.anthill; no spec dispatch needed. Acceptance: cargo-test green; new tests for each command; dispatch no longer hits not_yet for any of the four; WI-204 closes once this lands.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-204"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-18T11:16:46Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Update: store.anthill no longer lives at project root — moved to rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/store.anthill and embedded in the bundle (commit pending). cmd_init's template only needs to seed domain.anthill / rules.anthill / workitems.anthill in <project>/anthill-todo/; store.anthill is provided by the bundle binary.", at: "2026-05-18T08:30:43Z", workitem: "WI-267", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Phase B4 delivered (commit 058e5bf). cmd_update / cmd_add_dependency / cmd_remove_dependency route through WorkItemStore spec ops via three new with_X helpers (with_description / with_acceptance / with_deps). cmd_init stays Rust-intercepted (main.rs short-circuits 'init' before run_anthill_bundle), so dispatch's not_yet(name) is now reachable only for unknown subcommands. WI-204 effectively closes after this. Four cross-cutting runtime fixes surfaced alongside: (a) pattern matcher now accepts Term::Ref(X) as a 0-arg Term::Fn(X) — printer's Fn(X,[]) → 'X' (no parens) round-trip asymmetry; (b) is_option_type peels parameterized(base: sort_ref(name: Option), ...) — load_entity stores field types via the Type entity family, the previous functor-only check missed Option[T = X] fields; (c) materialize_entity defaults Var-valued Option fields to none() — the loader stuffs fresh Vars into every absent named slot for discrim-tree indexing, without this fix with_X reconstruction baked the synthetic var name into persisted facts; (d) partial-named-arg expansion (kb/load.rs, both call sites) now counts positional args as provided — ToolPasses(\"cargo-test\") was re-stuffing tool with a fresh var that shadowed pos_args[0]. Also: bundle-wide rename bindings→args + get_binding→get_arg + collect_all_bindings→collect_all_args; type params switched to positional form per kernel-language.md §4.4 (Option[List[String]] vs Option[T = List[T = String]]).", at: "2026-05-18T11:17:00Z", workitem: "WI-267", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-268",
  description: "Document entity ↔ term runtime mapping in docs/design/. Five load-bearing rules across the entity-term boundary live only in inline code comments today and bit cmd_X (WI-267) hard during port: (1) Value::Entity → Term::Fn lowering (kb/execute.rs alloc_from_value): recursive field allocation, named_args sorted to declaration order. (2) Term::Fn → Value::Entity materialization (eval/builtins.rs materialize_entity / term_as_entity): walks entity_field_types, finds value in named_args or pos_args by index, defaults missing Option-typed fields to none(), recurses via term_to_value; treats Var-valued Option fields as semantically absent (WI-267 fix). (3) Loader partial-named-arg expansion (kb/load.rs:2752 + :3492): every absent named slot gets fresh_var(field_name) stuffed in so the discrim tree can index uniformly; positional args count as provided (WI-267 fix). (4) Printer 0-arg Fn ↔ Ref round-trip asymmetry (persistence/print.rs): Fn(X, []) prints as bare 'X' (no parens), parser loads back as Term::Ref(X) — pattern matcher now accepts Ref/Ident as 0-arg Fn (WI-267 fix). (5) is_option_type peels Type entity wrapper — load_entity stores field types as parameterized(base: sort_ref(name: Option), ...) not bare Option (WI-267 fix). Acceptance: docs/design/entity-term-mapping.md exists, covers all five rules with examples (WorkItem fact load → materialize → with_X → alloc_from_value → persist round-trip), cross-links to the relevant source files; kernel-language.md §6.3 gets a 'see also' pointer. cargo test green. Driver: WI-267 spent ~half its time rediscovering these rules; future bundle authors should not pay that cost.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-267"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Closed by Phase B4 (WI-267, commit 058e5bf). All cmd_X subcommands listed in the WI description now route through WorkItemStore spec ops (next_id / lookup / commit / commit_feedback / forget / by_status_of / all). cmd_init remains Rust-intercepted in run_anthill_bundle before the bundle KB is loaded — by design, since init scaffolds the project before there's a KB to query. dispatch's not_yet(name) is now only reachable for genuinely unknown subcommands.", at: "2026-05-18T11:17:41Z", workitem: "WI-204", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-269",
  description: "Implement proposal 042 — explicit type parameters on operations (docs/proposals/042-explicit-type-parameters-on-operations.md). Adds both the declaration-site form `operation foo[A, B](...) -> ...` and the call-site form `foo[A = Int, B = String](args)` / `foo[Int, String](args)` (positional + named, positional-first, same rule as SortBinding kernel spec §5.1). Replaces the WI-260 workaround in `stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill:159` (`operation term_as_entity(t: Term) -> Option[T = ?E]` → `operation term_as_entity[E](t: Term) -> Option[E]`) and unblocks adding HOFs (`map`, `for_each`, `fold`) to `stdlib/anthill/prelude/{list,collection,iteration}.anthill` — currently these cannot be expressed because there is no surface to declare per-operation type parameters or bind them at the call site. Six-phase plan: (A) tree-sitter grammar — extend `operation_declaration` with optional `operation_type_param_list`; add `operation_type_arg_list` and allow `Name[bindings](args)` form before a `(` (instantiation_term + call disambiguates on next token vs proposal 035 sort-companion `.method`). (B) parse/ir.rs + parse/convert.rs — add `type_params: Vec<TypeParam>` to `Operation` (mirrors SortBinding for symmetry with 035); thread bindings table through call/Apply term. (C) kb/load.rs::load_operation — allocate a fresh `VarId` per declared type-param entry, bind name in operation`s local symbol scope before processing params / return / requires / ensures / effects; implicit `?T` mentions whose name matches a declared parameter resolve to the same var (round-trip with desugared form). (D) kb/typing.rs — at call-site `op[bindings](args)`, seed unification env from explicit bindings then run HM inference for remaining slots; diagnose explicit/inferred conflicts and unresolved parameters with a \"use op[T = ...]\" suggestion. (E) eval/{eval,value}.rs — populate `frame.requirements` with type-argument entries (positional, declaration order) AFTER sort-level entries per docs/design/operation-call-model.md §\"Operation type arguments\"; `apply_within` gains a `type_args` channel; closures capture both channels via the existing requirements-map mechanism. (F) stdlib + spec + tests — rewrite `reflect.term_as_entity` to the explicit form (WI-260 tests pass unchanged); add fixtures: `term_as_entity[WorkItem](t)` pins E to WorkItem; `operation foo[A, B](x: A, y: B) -> Pair[A = A, B = B]` parses + loads + type-checks; `map[A, B, C, E]` exercises both inferred and explicit calls (incl. effectful f propagating E); negative fixture for unconstrained `?E` with no context; frame-inspection fixture for `foo[T](x: T) -> T` per design doc; update `docs/kernel-language.md` §5.4 with the new Operation production + a §5.2 cross-reference. Out of scope (separate follow-up WIs): higher-rank `[F](f: F[A] -> F[B])`, declaration-site bounds `[T: Ordered]`, first-class operations, the actual HOF additions to `stdlib/anthill/prelude/list.anthill` etc. (filed separately once 042 lands). Acceptance: cargo-test green across the workspace; simplify clean on the changed Rust files; the proposal Acceptance bullets (foo[A,B] / term_as_entity[E] / map[A,B,C] fixtures + frame-inspection test) all pass.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-19T05:51:05Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-270",
  description: "Refactor typer to thread top-down expected type. Add an `expected: Option<TermId>` parameter to `type_check_node` / `TypeWorkOp::Visit` / `TypeBuildFrame::*` so the typer carries the caller-side type hint into each sub-expression. The hint flows through Let value (from annotation), Match branches, If branches, Lambda body (from arrow decomposition), and Apply/Constructor return-type unification before the unresolved-type-param check fires. Driver / unblocks: (a) closes WI-269 (proposal 042) Phase D `acceptance case 4` — \"unresolved type-param diagnostic\" — by giving check_apply_iter a way to seed subst from caller context before deciding whether any op type-param Var remains unbound. The current Phase D leaves a `// TODO(diag):` marker in typing.rs::seed_op_type_args for the silent-drop site. (b) retires two ad-hoc side-channels that solve the same problem piecemeal: `SimpleTermStore.let_type_annotations` (proposal 035 form 1, threaded through let_expr as `type_name`) and `SimpleTermStore.call_type_args` (proposal 042 Phase B, threaded through apply as `type_args`). Once `expected` is the normal flow, both side-channels can be deleted and the loader stops poking at them. (c) enables natural inference for 0-arg constructors and pure HOFs in annotated positions: `let xs: List[Int] = nil()`, `operation foo() -> List[Int] = nil()`, `Map.empty()` without the let_type_annotations workaround. Shape per arm: Apply / Constructor — unify `expected` with the call`s return type before the unresolved check, so caller context flows into the seed; Let — pass annotation to value, own `expected` to body; Match — pass `expected` to each branch body, widen result; If — pass `expected` to both branches; Lambda — if `expected` is an arrow, decompose and pass the inner return type to the body; literals / Var / Ref — ignore. Cost estimate: ~10–15 visit_X handlers gain a 3–5 line expected-forwarding block, plus a 2-line `if let Some(exp) = expected { unify_types(kb, &mut subst, exp, op.return_type); }` at the Apply/Constructor build. The iterative typer`s Visit/Build threads `expected` as a field. Acceptance: cargo-test green; the side-channels `let_type_annotations` and `call_type_args` are removed; WI-269 Phase D`s TODO(diag) marker is replaced by a real diagnostic that names the unconstrained type-param and suggests `op[T = ...]`; `term_as_entity(t)` with no caller context produces a clean error, with caller context (`let v: Option[WorkItem] = term_as_entity(t)`) it pins E to WorkItem; `let xs: List[Int] = nil()` typechecks without a workaround. Out of scope: subtyping / variance changes; effect-row top-down inference. Risk: touching every Visit arm of the iterative typer is invasive; staging the migration (introduce field with default None, migrate arms one at a time, then delete the side-channels) reduces blast radius.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-269"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-19T05:39:16Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Typer refactor + diagnostics + acceptance fixtures landed in 8a70608. (1) expected: Option<TermId> threads through Visit/Build frames; Let value uses annotation, Let body / Match branches / If branches / Lambda body via arrow decomposition; Apply / Constructor unify expected with op.return_type / parent_type before the unresolved-type-param check. (2) Two new TypeError variants: NoSuchTypeParam (replaces seed_op_type_args silent drop) and UnconstrainedTypeParam (replaces the WI-269 Phase D TODO marker, suggests 'op[T = ...](...)'). (3) op body driver now passes op.return_type as the body's expected — so 'operation foo() -> List[Int] = nil()' pins T from the return type. (4) Acceptance fixtures pass: term_as_entity(t) without context errors with the named diagnostic; with 'let v: Option[T = Item] = term_as_entity(t)' or 'term_as_entity[E = Item](t)' E pins to Item; 'let xs: List[T = Int] = nil()' typechecks. (5) Stdlib reflect.term_as_entity rewritten to explicit-type-param form '[E](t: Term) -> Option[T = E]' (retires the WI-260 logical-var workaround). (6) Pre-existing breakage in anthill-cpp-gen (Expr::Apply.type_args field from WI-269 Phase B) fixed in passing. DEVIATION FROM ACCEPTANCE: side-channels let_type_annotations and call_type_args are NOT removed — they still carry annotation/type-args data from convert.rs to load.rs. Removing them requires a parse-time TypeExpr-to-Term encoder that mirrors the loader's scope-aware type_expr_to_term (type-param vs sort_ref resolution depends on the current loading scope, which convert.rs doesn't track). Filing follow-up. INTERNAL FINDING: Match scrutinee errors are silently dropped in MatchFinal — when 'match term_as_entity(t) case some(w) -> ...' is in a context without expected, the UnconstrainedTypeParam fires at the scrutinee but the match swallows it. Pre-existing behavior; affects store.anthill terms_to_workitems but doesn't block the bundle (the case patterns then pin via unification chains). Probably worth a separate WI.", at: "2026-05-19T05:38:54Z", workitem: "WI-270", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-271",
  description: "Remove parse-side side-channels SimpleTermStore.let_type_annotations and SimpleTermStore.call_type_args (WI-270 deferred acceptance). The HashMaps currently carry the let-annotation TypeExpr and call type-arg Vec<SortBinding> from convert.rs to load.rs, where the loader threads them onto the KB let_expr / apply Term as k_type_name / k_type_args named args. WI-270 deferred this cleanup because removal requires either (a) a parse-time TypeExpr -> parse-side Term encoder that mirrors the loader's scope-aware type_expr_to_term (the loader-side resolves a Simple(name) reference as Var(Global(vid)) when the name is a registered type-param in scope, or sort_ref(name) otherwise — this scope tracking lives in load.rs's loader struct, not in convert.rs), or (b) a deferred-lowering parse-side encoding where convert.rs emits a placeholder Term::Fn shape (e.g. functor 'type_expr_simple', 'type_expr_parameterized', 'type_expr_arrow') and the loader's convert_term recognizes these and routes through type_expr_to_term equivalent. Acceptance: SimpleTermStore::let_type_annotations and ::call_type_args fields are deleted; convert.rs no longer populates them; load.rs no longer reads them; the let_expr KB Term still has k_type_name and apply KB Term still has k_type_args (so the typer's NodeOccurrence path is unchanged); the parse_test.rs tests that currently inspect parsed.terms.call_type_args (lines 3664, 3682, 3691, 3694, 3709) are updated to inspect the new representation; cargo test green workspace-wide; simplify clean on the changed files. Out of scope: changing the KB-side Term shape; changing the typer's NodeOccurrence path. Independent of WI-270 because the typer refactor is already complete; this is purely a parse-IR cleanup.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-270"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-19T09:35:08Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Phases A-D and Phase F (typing-only) delivered. Phase A (tree-sitter grammar) in 40f96dc, Phase B (parse IR + converter) in 3e0e88a, Phase C (loader registers op type-params as scoped) in b55cd42, Phase D (typer seeds substitution from explicit bindings) in 02528a8, Phase D follow-up (WI-270 typer top-down expected + diagnostic) in 8a70608. Phase F: spec §5.4 updated with operation_type_param_list grammar + §5.2 cross-reference (commit 4c87d32); typing-only acceptance fixtures added — foo[A,B](a:A,b:B) -> Pair[A=A,B=B] parses+loads+typechecks, map[A,B] type-checks both with explicit [A=Int,B=String] and inferred bindings, term_as_entity[E] pinned via let annotation or via explicit [E = Item] binding, negative case for unconstrained ?E surfaces the WI-270 diagnostic; stdlib reflect.term_as_entity rewritten to the explicit form (WI-260 tests pass unchanged). DEFERRED: Phase E (eval threading op type-args through frame.requirements per docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Operation type arguments') — requires apply_within to gain a type_args positional channel, Frame.requirements (or a new Frame.type_args field) to hold (T_i, type_value) entries AFTER sort-level entries, closures to capture both channels via the existing requirements-map mechanism, and the frame-inspection acceptance fixture foo[T](x:T) -> T showing the T entry. Currently eval.rs ignores Expr::Apply.type_args (type_args: _). Filing as a follow-up. Acceptance bullets: foo[A,B] (✓), term_as_entity[E] (✓), map[A,B,C] (✓), frame-inspection (deferred to follow-up).", at: "2026-05-19T05:50:42Z", workitem: "WI-269", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-272",
  description: "WI-269 Phase E: thread operation type-args through eval frame per docs/design/operation-call-model.md §'Operation type arguments'. (1) apply_within gains a positional type_args channel (Expr::ApplyWithin field, parse/load/typer support). The typer fills in resolved type-arg term values (sort_ref / parameterized) per declared type-param, in declaration order; named-form bindings are reordered to positional during elaboration. (2) Frame gains either type_args: SmallVec<[(Symbol, TermId); 2]> (separate channel — cleaner) or frame.requirements is extended to hold both RequirementHandle and Value::Type entries (per the design doc's single-map model — needs a polymorphic value type). Sort-level entries occupy the leading positions; type-arg entries follow in declaration order. (3) Body interpretation: a body's var_ref(T) where T matches a declared type-param resolves against the frame's type-arg channel — same lookup mechanism as a __req_* read, just hitting the type-arg side. (4) Closures: lambda_within captures both channels via the existing requirements-map mechanism — no new closure machinery. (5) Erasure decisions deferred to codegen targets (proposal 029 forward mapping erases most op-level type-args; SMT-LIB and type-driven dispatch backends preserve them). (6) Acceptance fixture (operation-call-model.md §test fixture): operation foo[T](x: T) -> T = x is called as foo[Int](42); frame inspection asserts (a) sort-level entries occupy leading positions, (b) an entry keyed T holds the type-value for Int, (c) order is sort-level first then T, (d) a second call foo[String]('hi') produces a fresh frame whose T holds String (per-call binding, not shared). Negative case: foo(42) (inferred) produces a frame whose T equals Int — frame contents identical to the explicit call. Out of scope: codegen erasure decisions (file separately per backend); higher-rank type params. Acceptance: cargo-test green; the frame-inspection fixture from operation-call-model.md §'Operation type arguments' passes; eval.rs no longer has  ignoring the channel on Expr::Apply.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-269", "WI-273"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-19T20:15:53Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-273",
  description: "Update stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill Expr entity declarations to match the actual KB-side Term::Fn shapes. Currently stale: the let_expr entity is missing the type_name field that the loader emits when a `let pat : T = ...` annotation is present (proposal 035 form 1, threaded into the KB Term::Fn since WI-185); the apply and ho_apply entities are missing the type_args field that the loader emits for op[A = Int](...) and ?P[A = Int](...) calls (proposal 042 / WI-269 Phase B; convert.rs::push_fn_term computes the type_args list regardless of is_ho); the type_arg entity itself is undeclared even though the loader allocates Term::Fn nodes with that functor at load.rs:3999. Reflection consumers (term_as_entity, KB introspection) can't currently materialize these slots as typed values. Add: (1) `type_name: Option[Term]` to entity let_expr; (2) `entity type_arg(name: Option[Symbol], value: Term)` declaration; (3) `type_args: Option[List[type_arg]]` to entity apply; (4) the same `type_args` field to entity ho_apply. Verify apply_within / ho_apply_within / constructor_within / lambda_within don't need similar fields yet — WI-269 Phase E (WI-272) will add a type_args channel to apply_within later, so file that separately when it lands. Acceptance: reflect declarations match the runtime KB Term::Fn shape for let_expr / apply / ho_apply / type_arg; cargo-test green workspace-wide; no behaviour change in typer / eval. Out of scope: WI-272 apply_within type_args channel.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-271"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-19T18:59:04Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "ParseAux landed in 0edc11b. Both SimpleTermStore HashMaps gone; the TypeExpr / Vec<SortBinding> they carried now live inside a parse-only Term::ParseAux(Box<ParseAux>) variant addressable by TermId. Parse let_expr / apply Term::Fn embed the payload as a type_name / type_args named-arg child; the loader unwraps via two thin helpers (read_parse_type_annotation, read_parse_call_type_args, sharing a generic read_parse_aux<T>) and feeds the existing type_expr_to_term / build_call_type_args paths. KB-side shape unchanged. KB-side consumers (10 sites across discrim, term_view, node_occurrence, resolve, persistence, anthill-stl reflect) gain unreachable!() arms — the ParseAux variant never enters the hash-consed TermStore, so they shouldn't trip. The work-stack walker and convert_term_with_expected both filter ParseAux children via an is_parse_aux helper so the recursive paths skip them. Added SymbolTable::lookup(&str) -> Option<Symbol> read-only counterpart of intern() to avoid reaching into intern_map. Tests in parse_test.rs that previously inspected parsed.terms.call_type_args now walk the SimpleTermStore via a new public iter() helper. Workspace cargo test green (46/46 groups). Filed WI-273 for the related reflect-entity cleanup (entity let_expr / apply / ho_apply / type_arg declarations don't match the actual KB-side Term::Fn shapes — pre-existing inconsistency, not in WI-271 scope but worth fixing soon).", at: "2026-05-19T09:35:06Z", workitem: "WI-271", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-274",
  description: "Binding-precise spec-field validation: tighten check_value_against_sort_ref / check_value_against_parameterized from base-only (value sort provides the spec base) to binding-precise (provides at the declared bindings) — build a SortGoal with spec_sort + bindings and call the canonical resolve (typing.rs:2671), the same resolver operation-requires uses, accepting iff Resolved. Requires threading &mut KnowledgeBase through the field-validator chain (resolve allocates substituted subgoal terms for conditional instances). WI-036 currently does the base-only check, correct while all providers are direct/ground; binding precision matters once collection types provide Eq/Ordered conditionally (List provides Eq requires elementEq, e.g. List.member/contains requires Eq[T]). Acceptance: a List-provides-Eq-requires-elementEq fixture where an Eq[T=List[Int]] field accepts a nested-list value and Eq[T=List[NonEq]] is rejected, plus the mismatch case (Comparable[T=Gadget] field holding a Widget value) errors at load. Runtime note: spec-op dispatch keys on the actual value sort and ignores the declared binding, so this is a static soundness fix, not a runtime change.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-064", "WI-036"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-20T15:47:15Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Test pointers (anthill-core/tests/include/typing_test.rs): the five WI-036 tests (spec_field_accepts/rejects_*, parameterized_spec_field_accepts/rejects_*, parameterized_spec_base_field_accepts_providing_value) all use matching-or-absent bindings, so they pass under BOTH base-only and binding-precise and do not exercise the gap. The known-incorrect case is currently UNTESTED: a field declared Comparable[T = Gadget] holding a Widget value (where Widget provides Comparable only at T = Widget) is silently accepted today by the base-only check. WI-274 must add that binding-mismatch test and assert it now produces an EntityField load error, and add a conditional-provider fixture (List provides Eq requires elementEq: Eq[T=List[Int]] accepts a nested-list value, Eq[T=List[NonEq]] rejects).", at: "2026-05-20T15:11:22Z", workitem: "WI-274", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Implementation sketch (delivered):\n1. Thread &mut KnowledgeBase through check_entity_facts -> check_value_against_type -> check_value_against_parameterized (resolve allocates substituted subgoal terms). check_value_against_sort_ref stays &-only: a bare sort_ref has no bindings, so base-only is already binding-precise there.\n2. In check_value_against_parameterized's base-is-spec branch (value sort != base), replace the base-only sort_provides fallback with binding-precise resolution: build SortGoal{spec_sort=base, bindings=declared} and call typing::resolve with an empty ResolutionScope (field validation has no enclosing requires), accept iff Resolved. Keep base-only sort_provides only when there are zero declared bindings.\n3. declared_type_goal_bindings extracts (param_sym, value) pairs from the declared parameterized type, then canonicalize_goal_value rewrites them into the resolver's canonical shape: field types encode sorts as sort_ref(name: Ref(S)) and parametric types as parameterized(base, bindings), but the resolver candidate side (SortProvidesInfo/requires) uses bare sort refs. Unwrap every sort_ref to bare Ref(S), recursing through parameterized bases/values, so parametric_value_parts reads the real base/element sorts. (This sort_ref-wrapping mismatch was the one non-obvious snag: without it the goal base reads as 'sort_ref' instead of 'List' and nothing matches.)\nTests (typing_test.rs): parameterized_spec_base_field_rejects_binding_mismatch (the previously-untested silent-accept case; fails on pre-change code with got:[]), conditional_spec_field_accepts_eq_list_of_eq_elements, conditional_spec_field_rejects_eq_list_of_non_eq_elements. EqList conditional-provider fixture mirrors wi224_sld_resolution_test.", at: "2026-05-20T15:37:37Z", workitem: "WI-274", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Already implemented in prior commits (38e709d WI-187 + WI-009 phase 3: IndexedFileStore + cmd_claim; ecae0b1 simplify pass; extended by 4c08e87 WI-202). IndexedStore trait (persistence/mod.rs:127) + IndexedFileStore (indexed_file_store.rs) with source_map, span-based retract, byte-range-dropping flush, by_id index. Bundle registers it in run_anthill_bundle (main.rs:1746), seeding source_map by zipping LoadResult.fact_rule_ids (load.rs:1408) with fact spans. Acceptance met: cmd_claim_test::claim_drops_open_block_and_writes_claimed spawns real 'anthill-todo --anthill claim WI-001' in a tempdir, asserts Open block dropped + single Claimed fact written. Verified green 2026-05-20: anthill-todo suite 33 pass; anthill-core builtin_tests 53 + wi_tests 123 (incl persistence_test/persistence_builtins_test/wi202_retrieve_test). No new code needed; marking delivered.", at: "2026-05-20T19:45:04Z", workitem: "WI-187", author: "claude")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-275",
  description: "Higher-order operations: prove and enable Function-typed operation parameters. The Function[A, B, E] sort with apply(f, x) is declared in stdlib/anthill/prelude/function.anthill, multi-parameter lambdas work via (named) tuple destructuring (proposal 018: lambda (a, b) -> ..., one tuple-pattern param to avoid comma ambiguity), and the interpreter has the runtime pieces (Value::Closure, enter_closure, the local_closure branch in eval/eval.rs dispatch_call). BUT no operation anywhere in the stdlib takes a Function-typed parameter, and no .anthill program passes a closure as an argument and applies it -- the HOF-as-argument path is unexercised end-to-end. Work: (a) verify a closure value can be passed as an operation arg and invoked, both via Function.apply(f, x) and via a value-typed param called directly as cmp(a, b); confirm a binary comparator lambda (lambda (a, b) -> ready_lt(a, b)) binds and applies through a tuple arg; (b) make the typer accept a value/Function-typed parameter being applied (today operation params are data; calling one may not typecheck); (c) add the obvious stdlib HOFs that motivate this -- List.map, List.filter, List.fold, and a comparator-parameterized List.sort -- in stdlib/anthill/prelude/list.anthill. Motivation / driver: the anthill-todo bundle (rustland/anthill-todo/anthill/main.anthill, commit 77c9d89) hand-rolls TWO structurally-identical stable merge sorts (merge_ready/sort_ready vs merge_by_id/sort_by_id) that differ only in the comparator; with a generic List.sort(cmp, xs) they collapse to one call site each. Kept duplicated deliberately for now because HOF-as-arg is unproven AND closure dispatch (enter_closure + the string-keyed local_closure lookup) is heavier per-comparison than the current direct static call -- a regression on the just-optimized sort hot path. Perf caveat: under the tree-walking interpreter a generic comparator adds real indirection; it becomes cheap once bodies lower to the resolved IR (docs/design/interpreter-ir.md) where a generic merge[A](cmp, ...) can be monomorphized/inlined. So this WI is about expressiveness/correctness enablement; the bundle sort dedup can wait for the IR if perf matters. Acceptance: an integration test where an anthill program defines a comparator-parameterized sort (or uses stdlib List.sort) with a lambda (a, b) -> ... comparator and produces correctly-ordered output; stdlib List.map/fold exercised from anthill; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-276",
  description: "Substrate for the [simp] rewriting engine (proposal 043; docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md sections 2.2 and 4.1): make Value::Node structural in TermView and add the occurrence build side. Today impl TermView for Value maps Value::Node to ViewHead::Opaque (term_view.rs:165), so rule LHS patterns cannot match reflect Expr occurrences. (a) Make Value::Node structural: head returns the inner Expr functor (Expr::Apply functor to Functor Some(functor); Expr::DotApply to dot_apply symbol; Expr::Const to Const; leaves to Var/Ref/Ident), pos_arg and named_arg return child occurrences. (b) Add a ViewItem::Node child shape: ViewItem (term_view.rs:46) is Copy over Term(TermId) and Value(ref Value), but occurrence children are Rc of NodeOccurrence, not ref Value, so thread the new variant through match_view (mod.rs:1379) and the discrim walker (discrim.rs query functions, generic over V:TermView). (c) Add an occurrence build side that constructs RHS occurrences via synthesized_expr (node_occurrence.rs:184), preserving spans and Synthesized origin; do not route through TermId (Value::Node is UnsupportedVariant in execute.rs:229, and terms drop inline spans). Acceptance: cargo-test green plus a unit test that a rule LHS such as add(?a,?b) matches a Value::Node Expr occurrence via match_view and binds pattern vars to child occurrences. Prerequisite for the typer-phase simp engine. Ref: docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md and docs/proposals/043-simp-rewrite.md.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-21T11:06:20Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-277",
  description: "The [simp] rewriting engine — typer phase (docs/proposals/043-simp-rewrite.md sections 4 and 5; docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md sections 4 to 6). Add the second firing site for [simp] equational rules: as the typer walks operation bodies, fire matching [simp] rules LHS to RHS bottom-up over NodeOccurrence trees, then write the rewritten redex-free tree back via set_op_body_node before req_insertion (load.rs:1492). This transforms the typer phase from annotate-only (today op_bodies is written once at load, load.rs:5451, and typing only sets RefCells on a fixed tree) to tree-producing. One rewriter, two phases: the resolver apply_eq_rules (resolve.rs:1266, innermost, fuel 100) is the Term-side counterpart; reuse its reduction strategy and termination so a rule means the same thing in both. Reuse by_functor rule lookup and the TermView matcher (WI-276). Deliverables: (a) a bottom-up, tree-producing typer-phase rewriter (Expr derives only Debug, not Clone, so add a map_children helper dual to drain_expr_children at node_occurrence.rs:100), synthesized_expr provenance (node_occurrence.rs:184), write-back, placed between type_check_sorts (load.rs:1485) and req_insertion. (b) Decide A1 (weave into type_check_node work-stack) vs A2 (separate pass using type_check_node as a read-only type oracle); design recommends A2. (c) Guard-free structural rules fire end to end, which alone delivers the no-dot direct-simplification use case (a [simp] rule like add_zero rewrites add(mul(v,k),mul(v,0)) to mul(v,k) at compile time; design section 5). typeof comes from the typer TypeResult, not from classification (design section 3). Acceptance: cargo-test green; a guard-free [simp] rule (e.g. add_zero) rewrites an operation body during type-check and the rewritten tree is what req_insertion and eval see; a phase-agreement test (same rule via resolver Term and typer occurrence). Depends on WI-276. Dot dispatch is a separate client (WI-278). Ref: docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md; docs/proposals/043-simp-rewrite.md.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-276"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-21T12:42:11Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-278",
  description: "Method-call (dot) syntax — first client of the [simp] rewriting engine (WI-277; docs/proposals/043-simp-rewrite.md section 6; docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md section 7.1). Give Anthill ?xs.map(?f).filter(?p) via [simp] dispatch rules fired by the engine. Deliverables: (a) Expr::DotApply node (node_occurrence.rs, sibling to Apply) wired into drain_expr_children and for_each_child, plus the reflect dot_apply entity. (b) Converter: emit dot_apply for value-receiver dot forms (both ?x.field and ?x.method(args)), fixing the dropped receiver in collect_field_access_segments (convert.rs:342, which has no variable branch); keep sort and namespace flattening for Foo.bar; add the dot_apply functor case to materialize_from_handle (node_occurrence.rs, called at load.rs:5450). (c) find_operation_on_sort(sort,name) KB query: tier-1 in-body ops with no import (compose operations_of_sort at op_requirements.rs:177 over SortInfo.operations, and find_operation_in_scope at load.rs:2814); tier-2 import-scoped extension ops (new, no first-param index exists). (d) Prelude default_dot and dot_field rules ([simp], guard-exclusive, field-first on collision); dot_field reaches the existing field_access builtin (resolve.rs:1975). (e) Engine-evaluated type-level guards (is_entity and has_field from entity_fields; find_operation_on_sort), reading typeof from the typer TypeResult, not from classification. Acceptance: cargo-test green; xs.map(f).filter(p) chains; p.x field access via the unified path; no-import method resolution; clear no-match error at the source span; byte-identical Foo.bar and ?x.field-as-field. Depends on WI-277. Ref: docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md section 7.1; docs/proposals/043-simp-rewrite.md section 6.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-277", "WI-279", "WI-280", "WI-281", "WI-282", "WI-275"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Acceptance additions (proposal 043 section 6.6 / design 7.1): the produced apply must (1) infer type parameters for a type-parameterized method (e.g. xs.map(f) infers T from the receiver, U from f) and (2) satisfy and thread requires clauses for a requirement-constrained method (a.min(b) needs Ord, l.contains(e) needs Eq) via existing requirement-insertion; an unsatisfied requires is a clear error at the dot-call span. Open D6: requirement-aware find_operation_on_sort vs name+sort resolution with requires checked downstream (lean: downstream).", at: "2026-05-21T09:44:33Z", workitem: "WI-278", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered scope = the READ/matching substrate: Value::Node is now structural in TermView (occ_head / occ_pos_child / occ_named_child / occ_named_keys) plus ViewItem::Node(Rc<NodeOccurrence>). ViewItem is now Clone not Copy (decision D4) so as_bind_value can bind a matched child as Value::Node. Unit test match_view_binds_vars_to_node_occurrence_children proves add(?a,?b) matches Value::Node(add(1,2)) and binds ?a/?b to the child occurrences with Rc identity. The build side (reify a rule RHS into an occurrence tree via synthesized_expr) is engine machinery and is part of WI-277, not here. anthill-core green (883/0); workspace builds; simplify clean.", at: "2026-05-21T11:06:20Z", workitem: "WI-276", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Prerequisite from WI-277: the simp_rewrite engine's walk (rewrite / map_children / substitute_to_occurrence in kb/simp_rewrite.rs) is recursive over occurrence-tree depth. Before WI-278 ships [simp]/dot rules that fire on real (possibly deeply-nested) operation bodies, convert the walk to an explicit work-stack — mirroring NodeOccurrence::Drop and the typing pass, which were made iterative to survive the 624-line typing_pass_spec.anthill. Until then the engine is inert (run() early-returns when no [simp] rule is indexed), so it cannot overflow. Documented as a v1 limitation in the simp_rewrite.rs module doc.", at: "2026-05-21T12:30:11Z", workitem: "WI-278", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered: typer-phase [simp] rewriting engine (kb/simp_rewrite.rs). run() fires guard-free [simp] equations bottom-up over op-body NodeOccurrence trees and writes them back before type_check_sorts/req_insertion; early-returns when no [simp] rule is indexed (inert for stdlib). Reuses the discrim (match_view, with Rc<NodeOccurrence> as a TermView), term_from_debruijn (open_equation), and the resolver reduction strategy/termination (innermost, fuel 100). New supporting pieces: walk_view (TermView-aware var-resolution, mod.rs); impl TermView for Rc<NodeOccurrence> (term_view.rs); substitute_to_occurrence (build side, preserves Synthesized provenance). 5 unit tests: guard-free fire, nested-redex parent rebuild, DeBruijn-path, resolver/typer phase agreement, multi-step fixpoint+provenance. anthill-core 888/0; simplify clean. v1 limitation: recursive walk -> convert to work-stack before WI-278 (tracked in WI-278 feedback). Dot dispatch + type-directed guards remain WI-278.", at: "2026-05-21T12:42:10Z", workitem: "WI-277", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-279",
  description: "Dot dispatch as a CLIENT of the type-directed [simp] engine (WI-283). See docs/design/simp-dot-finding.md. A dot rule is the same shape as a spec/sort equational rule — sort-scoped, requires-guarded (e.g. a custom Either.map: dot(?e,map,[?f])=either_map(?e,?f) :- requires Either; concrete RHS) — selected by min_sort(receiver) = widen the receiver to its least declared sort (= sort_head(TypeResult.ty); sort_functor_of extracts it; a compile-time typer notion, never a goal, never a runtime/callable typeof). Firing reuses the engine's tree-producing walk (DotApply -> Apply, rebuild ancestors, write the body back — type_check_node only types, so dot NEEDS the walk) and runs IN the typer (scope-correct min_sort). Beyond sort-specific rules there is an engine DEFAULT fallback (resolve name to an op on min_sort(receiver), or a field on a free-standing entity -> field_access) — engine logic, NOT a writable rule (functor dynamically resolved). Produced Apply rides normal type-param inference + req_insertion (043 6.6). Reverted predecessor (this session) ran a standalone PRE-typer pass with a reconstructed flat op-level env (build_op_env) — wrong: typer-independent, omits let/lambda/match scope. DEPENDS ON WI-283. Acceptance: ?x.method(args)/?x.field dispatch via receiver sort with no import; a sort-specific requires-guarded dot rule (Either-style) overrides the default; receivers referencing let/lambda/match-bound locals dispatch; clear no-match error at the dot span; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-283"],
  status: Claimed(agent: "claude", since: "2026-05-22T11:03:55Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-280",
  description: "Bare-identifier value-receiver dot dispatch (p.x / l.method() on a param/local). A receiver that is a bare identifier resolving to a VALUE (op param, let/lambda/match local) must route to dot_apply, not flatten to a qualified name. Today the converter's is_value_receiver (convert.rs) treats an identifier-rooted receiver as a NAME (the WI-278(b)-deferred 'identifier case'), so p.x flattens to a bogus qualified symbol 'p.x' and l.length() to 'l.length' (no DotApply, no dispatch, no error). The value-vs-name decision is scope-dependent, so it must be a load-time, scope-aware re-route (identifier resolves to a local value -> dot_apply(local, member, args); resolves to a sort/namespace -> keep qualified-name flattening). Engine already dispatches once it is a DotApply. Acceptance: p.x field access and l.method() method dispatch work in op bodies; Foo.bar / Map[K=..].empty() still flatten; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-279"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-281",
  description: "Requirement-aware dot dispatch for spec-satisfaction methods (WI-278 6.6 / D6). A method coming from a spec the receiver's sort SATISFIES must resolve and thread/check its requires: (3).min(5) -> Ordered.min via fact Ordered[Int]; a.min(b) needs Ord; l.contains(e) needs Eq. find_operation_on_sort currently uses the WI-240 sort_ops table whose pass-2 covers ONLY user 'fact Spec[ImplSort]' impls, NOT builtin satisfaction (Int->Ordered) — verified Int.min -> None, so (3).min(5) does not dispatch (pinned by spec_satisfaction_method_is_a_known_gap test). Needs resolution over the satisfied-spec chain + requires insertion/checking on the produced apply, with an unsatisfied requires reported as a clear error at the dot-call span. Acceptance: (3).min(5) dispatches to Ordered.min; l.contains(e) threads Eq; unsatisfied requires -> clear error at the dot span; flip the known-gap test; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-279"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-282",
  description: "Rule-body dot dispatch. Dot/[simp] rewriting must fire on Expr::DotApply in RULE bodies, not just operation bodies (simp_rewrite::run walks only kb.op_bodies_iter). The webots computational style (?pose_prev.position.x + ?vx*?tc) lives in rule bodies; the governing principle is dot must mean the same in ALL expression positions. Needs the engine/typer to rewrite rule-body DotApply with typeof for rule variables (the typer types rule bodies via check_rule_typing, currently term-form with no DotApply arm). NOTE: occ_head now exposes DotApply structurally, so an undispatched rule-body DotApply flows into SLD as a structural dot_apply goal — benign today (no dot_apply facts -> matches nothing) but a wrong-answer risk once used. Ties to WI-246 (rule-body occurrences). Acceptance: a rule body with ?x.method(args) / ?x.field dispatches before SLD; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-279"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-283",
  description: "The [simp] rewriting engine is TYPE-DIRECTED and integrated with the typer (corrects the 'type-independent engine' framing of proposal 043 4/5; supersedes WI-277's guard-free scope). See docs/design/simp-dot-finding.md. One tree-producing occurrence-rewrite WALK (keep simp_rewrite's machinery); firing = structural LHS match (TermView) + a GUARD/selection check that, for spec/sort rules, is type-directed: e.g. Numeric.add_identity (add(?a,0)=?a :- requires Numeric[T]) and Ordered.min only fire where the receiver's type satisfies the spec — the rule's add is Numeric.add but a real term is Int.add(x,0), a different symbol that matches only via the satisfaction relation, and the requires only holds by a type check. So firing needs min_sort + satisfaction, known only in the typer. Today BOTH sites are guard-free (apply_eq_rules resolve.rs:1410 and simp_rewrite, gated by is_equation=empty body) -> requires-guarded spec/sort rules fire NOWHERE (incomplete; unsound if a guard-free firing rewrites where requires is unmet). Make firing type-directed + guard-aware in the typer and converge the two sites onto one engine (resolver-side runtime firing of truly type-independent monomorphic identities still allowed). Equational spec/sort rules AND dot rules (WI-279) are clients of this one engine. Acceptance: a requires-guarded [simp] spec/sort rule fires only where its requires/satisfaction holds; trivial monomorphic identities still fire; one shared engine; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-284"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-23T11:48:33Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-284",
  description: "Typed-occurrence substrate + min_sort. The typer currently DISCARDS each occurrence's inferred type (TypeResult.ty); NodeKind::Expr keeps only classification + resolved_type_args, no type field. Make the typer KEEP each occurrence's type (typed expressions, as any statically-typed compiler's typed AST). Storage is an impl detail (lean: a RefCell field on NodeKind::Expr alongside classification; alternatives: side table keyed by occurrence, or asserted reflect type_of facts). Add min_sort(occ) = sort_functor_of(kept type) — sort_functor_of already exists (unwraps parameterized/sort_ref to the sort head); returns None on an unresolved type var. min_sort is an expression-accepting (compile-time) reader, never a runtime/typeof goal; it is the least declared sort the occurrence inhabits (sort_head of its inferred type). FOUNDATION for all type-directed simp/dot firing (WI-283/WI-279) and also benefits codegen/eval/IR (which re-derive types today). Refs: docs/design/simp-rewrite-design.md 2.2(4)/5.4, docs/design/simp-dot-finding.md, docs/proposals/043-simp-rewrite.md 4.2. Acceptance: each typed occurrence carries its inferred type; min_sort(occ) returns the least declared sort (3 -> Int; cons(1,nil()) -> List; a free-standing entity value -> its sort) and None on an unresolved type var; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-22T16:14:00Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-285",
  description: "Unrec the typer's remaining recursive-helper expression arms. visit_type (kb/typing.rs ~1160-1182) handles If/ListLit/SetLit/TupleLit by calling check_if_expr/check_list_literal/check_set_literal/check_tuple_literal, which re-enter type_check_node on children — the last recursive arms; Let/Match/Lambda/Apply/Constructor are already work-stack Build frames. Convert these four to native Visit/Build frames so the whole typer is one iterative walk. Motivation: else-if chains nest in the else branch, so a deep if/else-if recurses one host stack frame per nesting level — the residual overflow class the earlier unrec-ing removed for the other forms (the Drop walk and main dispatch were made iterative to survive the 624-line typing_pass_spec.anthill). Collection literals nest by breadth (flat element lists), lower risk, folded in for uniformity. With WI-284's Stamp work-frame this is purely a stack-safety/uniformity refactor — stamping already works for these arms via per-call type_check_node re-entry, so no behavior change is required, only the host-stack shape. Acceptance: If/ListLit/SetLit/TupleLit are handled by work-stack Build frames (visit_type no longer re-enters type_check_node for them); a deeply-nested else-if chain types without host-stack overflow; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-284"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered (commit pending). (a) inferred_type: RefCell<Option<TermId>> on NodeKind::Expr — the 3rd typer annotation beside classification (WI-231)/resolved_type_args (WI-272); that precedent settled D2 (field, not side-table: a side-table would be Rc-pointer-keyed and desync on simp rebuilds); + set_inferred_type/inferred_type accessors. (b) Typer KEEPS each occurrence type via a results-neutral TypeBuildFrame::Stamp{occ} pushed UNDER every Visit by a new push_visit helper: it peeks results.last() and writes the type when the node TypeResult finalizes — uniform across iterative (Apply/Constructor/Let/Match/Lambda) and recursive-helper (If/collection-literal, which re-enter type_check_node) arms, exactly once per node; drains and the results.len()==1 assert unperturbed. (c) pub sort_functor_of(kb,ty)->Option<Symbol> (unwraps sort_ref / parameterized base / bare Ref; None on type var) + pub min_sort(kb,occ)=sort_functor_of(occ.inferred_type()). CORRECTION: sort_functor_of/min_sort did NOT pre-exist (WI text stale; reverted with the WI-278 c/e increment) — rebuilt on extract_sort_ref_sym + type_functor_name. Tests (tests/include/wi284_min_sort_test.rs, 5): 3->Int; cons(1,nil())->List + child stamping; entity red->Color; unresolved type var->None; sort_functor_of(type var)->None. Suite: anthill-core 908/0; anthill-core+smt-gen 977/0. code-review (max, 3 angles): Stamp invariant verified across every frame + error path; field addition clean (only 2 constructors build it, Drop unaffected since TermId is Copy, consumers use ..); min_sort correct for all cases. LATENT (not live): sort_functor_of returns None for the SLD-canonical Fn(S,[],[..]) shape + qualified/Ident functors — min_sort never sees these (typer stores reflect shapes), doc clarified; WI-283/279 extend with a SymbolKind::Sort check if needed. PRE-EXISTING GAP: match-guard exprs are not typed/stamped, so min_sort(guard)=None (relevant to WI-282). min_sort returns Option<Symbol> = sort-head symbol, the WI-283/279 dispatch key.", at: "2026-05-22T16:15:05Z", workitem: "WI-284", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-286",
  description: "Rule-body dot_apply terms were generated malformed (pre-existing fallout from committed 27af763 / WI-278b, uncaught because that commit validated only -p anthill-core while the qfnra_field_access fixture lives in anthill-smt-gen). convert_term (the rule/fact/query TERM path, load_rule -> convert_term) converted the converter-emitted parse dot_apply(receiver, Ident(name), ...) GENERICALLY — leaving receiver/name positional and (via entity-field expansion) stuffing a fresh var into the dot_apply entity args field — instead of the canonical reflect dot_apply(receiver:, name:, args: List) that convert_expr (the op-body occurrence path) builds. So op-body and rule-body dot_apply had INCONSISTENT representations and smt-gen (a TERM consumer reading rule_body) failed emit with 'unhandled arithmetic op dot_apply'. Fix: convert_term re-encodes dot_apply into the canonical reflect form (matching convert_expr; children stay bare terms, which term consumers read), guarded on the converter shape (>=2 positional + Ident name) so a user-written dot_apply token / a user entity dot_apply falls through to generic conversion (else pos_args[1] panics — caught in /code-review, regression-tested by parse_test::user_written_dot_apply_token_does_not_panic). smt-gen as_field_access reads an empty-args dot_apply as a field access (nested chains recurse). Acceptance: qfnra_field_access tests green; full anthill-core + anthill-smt-gen green; a user dot_apply token does not panic the loader. Refs: docs/design/simp-dot-finding.md; relates to WI-278/WI-282.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-22T16:46:41Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered. ROOT CAUSE: convert_term (rule/fact/query TERM path) converted the converter-emitted parse dot_apply(receiver, Ident(name), ...) generically -> positional receiver/name + a fresh var stuffed into the args entity field (entity-field expansion misfired), inconsistent with the canonical reflect dot_apply(receiver:, name:, args:) that convert_expr (op-body occurrence path) builds. smt-gen (reads rule_body TERMS) failed emit with 'unhandled arithmetic op dot_apply'. Pre-existing, from committed 27af763 (WI-278b) which validated only -p anthill-core (qfnra fixture is in anthill-smt-gen). FIX: convert_term re-encodes dot_apply to the canonical reflect form (children stay bare terms — term consumers read raw terms, unlike convert_expr reflect-Expr children; do NOT unify the paths). GUARD (from /code-review): the branch keys on the parse short-name dot_apply which is NOT reserved, so it is guarded on the converter shape (pos_args.len()>=2 && pos_args[1] is Ident) — a user-written dot_apply(?x)/dot_apply() / a user entity dot_apply falls through to generic conversion, else pos_args[1] index-panics the loader (3 panics found+verified by the reviewer). smt-gen as_field_access reads an empty-args dot_apply as field access (nested chains recurse); non-empty args (method call) -> clear unhandled error. Tests: parse_test::user_written_dot_apply_token_does_not_panic (panic regression) + qfnra_field_access (23/0, was 21+2 failed). Validation: qfnra confirmed 23/0; full anthill-core+smt-gen was 977/0 immediately before the guard (the guard is a pure narrowing) + the new regression test. /code-review (max, 2 angles on the new diff): convert_term re-encode semantically correct + panic guard added; smt-gen as_field_access behavior-preserving + panic-free. NOTE: this makes rule-body ?x.field resolve to canonical dot_apply (consistent with op bodies), NOT field_access; the dot->field_access/method rewrite for rule bodies is WI-282.", at: "2026-05-22T16:46:42Z", workitem: "WI-286", author: "user")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-287",
  description: "Typer: match expression takes branch-0 type, ignores other branches (no lub/join) — soundness gap. MatchFinal (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs:~1362) sets the match result type to the FIRST branch's type and never joins or cross-checks the remaining branches. There is no lub/join over branch types anywhere in the typer. Consequence (unsound): a match whose branches have incompatible types is accepted. Two leaks, both demonstrated by failing tests: (1) synthesis mode — `let x = match t { case on -> 1; case off -> \"hello\" }` types x as Int (branch 0); the String branch is checked against expected=None, i.e. nothing. (2) declared-return mode — `operation pick(t) -> Int = match t { case on -> 1; case off -> \"hello\" }` ALSO loads clean: body_expected reaches branches as an inference HINT, not an enforced check, and the op-body return check only inspects the synthesized match type (branch 0 = Int). Anchor: a direct `-> Int` op body of \"hello\" IS rejected, proving return-type checking works in general and the leak is specifically the match first-branch-wins shortcut. Tests: rustland/anthill-core/tests/include/match_branch_join_test.rs (wired into wi_tests). The two branch-clash tests assert the SOUND behavior so they fail on the bug; currently #[ignore]d to keep the suite green — run with --ignored to see them fail; remove #[ignore] when fixed (they become regression guards). Fix direction: compute a join (lub) over branch types in MatchFinal, using the Type lattice (Lattice[T=Type], glb/lub) + entity-instance widening (constructor_parent_sort climbs entity -> enclosing sort). Top-less lattice: incompatible branches with no common supertype (Int vs String) must be a type error, not silently accepted. Decide whether match is checked (every branch <: expected when an expected type is present) AND/OR synthesized (join when not). Related design discussion: widen / entity-singleton (Type.singleton(ExprOccurrence) is reserved-but-unused; check_bare_ref at typing.rs:949 collapses leaf precision eagerly to a nameable sort / anthill.prelude.Type), docs/proposals/011-type-resolution.md. Note: scaland has a parallel typer that should get the same fix + tests to avoid divergence.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-23T14:26:13Z"))
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-288",
  description: "Scala loader/typer: consume WI-185/WI-269 parser hints (type_name, type_args, type_params)

Follow-up to the parser-only Phase A port (effectSet tightening WI-092, let type annotation WI-185, operation type params WI-269). The Scala parser now emits IR the loader/typer ignores:

1. loadLetExpr (Loader.scala ~633) reads only posArgs and drops the 'type_name' named-arg, so the WI-185 let type annotation never reaches the typer. Read fn.namedArgs and thread the hint through.

2. loadApplyOrConstructor (Loader.scala ~705) treats the injected 'type_args' named-arg as an ordinary call argument, so Name[bindings](args) loads with a spurious value argument instead of as type arguments. Recognize/strip 'type_args' and route it as call-site type bindings.

3. typeExprToRef (AnthillParser.scala ~352) has no case for TypeExpr.Arrow / TupleType and falls through to a Ref(\"_\") sentinel; arrow/tuple annotations and positional bindings silently degrade. Extend coverage.

4. Operation.typeParams is parsed and stored but not consumed by the Scala loader/typer (rust consumes it in kb/load.rs + kb/typing.rs). Wire it in to close the dual-typer gap.

Rust is ground truth here; these are the Scala-side catch-up items.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-23T09:18:45Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-289",
  description: "Enable + fix type-checking of namespace-level (free) operations. Operations declared directly in a namespace (not inside a sort) — e.g. the anthill.cli.parse / anthill.cli.help CLI parser, and the eval-test m2/m5 fixtures — are NOT type-checked or simp-rewritten today: the typer's op-body driver (typing::type_check_sorts_typed) reaches operations only via each sort's reflect SortInfo, and namespaces produce no SortInfo. Pre-existing latent gap (independent of WI-283): such op bodies load with NO type validation. WI-283 added a gated sweep (const TYPECHECK_FREE_OPS in typing.rs, currently false) that type-checks + fires [simp] in EVERY op body incl. free ones. Flipping it to true surfaced ~25 eval-fixture failures from constructs eval supports but the typer (only ever run on sort ops) does not: (1) higher-order calls of Function[A,B]-typed values, e.g. f(f(x)) with f: Function[Int,Int] -> 'expected known operation or arrow-typed variable, got unknown functor' (typer must treat application of a Function-sorted value as a higher-order call / extract its arrow type, matching eval); (2) effect-declaration checks — free ops using eprintln/println/modify don't declare the effects (e.g. 'undeclared effect ConsoleError') — fix the fixtures; (3) some name resolution ('expected resolved name, got unresolved') in free-op bodies. Fix the typer for these, fix fixtures where a declaration is genuinely missing, then flip TYPECHECK_FREE_OPS=true. Acceptance: TYPECHECK_FREE_OPS=true; free-op bodies (cli/parse, cli/help, eval m2/m5 fixtures) type-check correctly; [simp] fires in free-op bodies; full cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-283"],
  status: Open)

