fact Feedback(content: "Superseded/subsumed by proposal 044 (docs/proposals/044-unified-name-resolution.md) — this grammar removal is step 7 of that proposal, do it last.", at: "2026-05-23T07:00:10Z", workitem: "WI-291", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Code-review parity findings (LOW, benign — both engines green; track for the parity pass):\n1. scaland Prelude exposes reflect Expr/Pattern/TypedExpr variants as bare names (defineSort variant-exposure link + defineEntity addExposed); rustland register_prelude does NOT. Bare match_expr resolves in scaland reflect scope but not rustland. Benign (converter never emits bare match_expr as a rule-head functor). Decide: drop the scaland reflect-variant links, or add them to rustland register_prelude.\n2. scaland Loader adds the variant-exposure parent link unconditionally; rustland gates on is_new (load.rs ~533). A sort contributed across multiple files gets duplicate non-enclosing parent links in scaland — benign (visited-guard + symbol dedup) but diverges. Add an is_new-equivalent guard.\n3. scaland uses joinSegments (full dotted name) for the exposed variant name; rustland uses only the last segment (load.rs ~527). Identical for single-segment entities (all current stdlib); diverges only for dotted entity names. Use the last segment in scaland.", at: "2026-05-23T08:47:33Z", workitem: "WI-290", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered: core of proposal 044 done on main — unified name-resolution description (kernel-language.md 8.6) + uniform behavior on rustland & scaland (visible-by-default, variants-only exposed set + variant-exposure links, R2 inherited-op binding), stdlib export statements stripped. Both engines green.\n\nRemaining follow-ups (all tracked, none blocking):\n- 3 LOW parity gaps (see prior feedback): reflect-variant exposure asymmetry; missing is_new gate on scaland variant link; joinSegments-vs-last-segment.\n- 'internal' hide gate: documented in 8.6 but NOT yet enforced by either engine (no stdlib uses 'internal'). Needs an internals set + filter on both, with a test.\n- Head-functor dispatch unification: rustland registers unlabeled-rule head functors as Goals, scaland does not — explicitly future work per proposal 044.\n- WI-291: remove the now-no-op 'export' keyword from the grammar (do last).", at: "2026-05-23T08:51:19Z", workitem: "WI-290", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-294",
  description: "Scala loader/typer: port operation-body loading + type-hint consumption (WI-288 follow-up). Builds the Scala-side operation loading that WI-288's parser hints feed into; gated behind the scaland Term->Value resolver migration (mirror of rustland WI-246: occurrence-native SLD, Value::Node, Rc<NodeOccurrence>) so it lands on the right substrate. Currently in scaland: convertExprTerm + its load* helpers (loadLetExpr, loadApplyOrConstructor, etc.) are DEAD CODE — no caller; operations are only defined as symbols in scan pass 1 (Loader.scala:125-134), never loaded into the KB as OperationInfo facts; and there is NO native-Scala typer (the 'dual typer' = Rust typer + the self-hosted typer in stdlib/anthill/reflect/typing.anthill run via SLD). Scope: (1) Phase-2 operation handler in Loader.loadItems that builds anthill.reflect.OperationInfo facts (name/params/return_type/effects/requires/ensures/body/type_params), mirroring rustland kb/load.rs:5569-5708; (2) wire convertExprTerm as the operation-body converter; (3) item 1 of WI-288 — loadLetExpr: thread the 'type_name' named-arg into Expr.let_expr.type_name (Some/None); (4) item 2 of WI-288 — loadApplyOrConstructor: strip the 'type_args' named-arg and route as Expr.apply/ho_apply.type_args (cons-list of reflect type_arg(name,value)); constructor has no type_args (drop); (5) item 4 of WI-288 — register operation type-params as scoped Sort symbols in an operation scope (kb.symbols.define + addTypeParam), mirror rustland load.rs:357-362, and allocate per-param Vars published in OperationInfo.type_params; (6) typer-side seeding of call-site type_args onto op type-param Vars (rustland typing.rs reseed_type_params_from_call_args) — only meaningful once the typing.anthill rules run over loaded OperationInfo in scaland. Reference WI-288 (delivered: item 3, typeExprToRef arrow/tuple). Rust is ground truth. Acceptance: sbt test green; new LoaderTest cases asserting OperationInfo fact shape (incl. type_params) and let_expr.type_name / apply.type_args round-trip; parity with rustland load_operation on a small fixture.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-288"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Rescoped to the substrate-neutral fix. Investigation found the WI's premise was partly off: items 1,2,4 target a Scala loader/typer that does not exist yet — convertExprTerm + load* helpers are DEAD CODE (no caller), operations are never loaded into the KB as OperationInfo facts, and there is no native-Scala typer. Those three items only become meaningful/testable once operation-body loading exists, and the loader's term-building is itself in the path of the in-flight Term->Value resolver migration (rustland WI-246). Delivered here: item 3 — typeExprToRef (AnthillParser.scala) now lowers TypeExpr.Arrow -> anthill.prelude.Type.arrow(effects,param,result) and TypeExpr.TupleType/multi-param-arrow -> Type.named_tuple(fields: List[TypeField]), mirroring rustland type_expr_to_term, replacing the silent Ref(\"_\") sentinel. This is purely parser-side (upstream of the resolver), substrate-neutral, and tested (3 new ParseTest cases; full scaland suite 145 green). Items 1,2,4 + operation-body loading + typer seeding moved to WI-294 (depends on WI-288), gated behind the scaland Value migration.", at: "2026-05-23T09:18:40Z", workitem: "WI-288", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-292",
  description: "Resolver-side type-directed [simp] firing via a reflect min_sort builtin. Today the resolver (apply_eq_rules) holds type-erased terms with no min_sort, so it fires only type-independent identities and SKIPS requires-guarded rules (equation_is_requires_guarded, resolve.rs); the typer (simp_fire_guard_holds, typing.rs) does the type-directed firing on typed occurrences. To truly converge the two firing sites onto one engine (proposal 043 4.1/4.2 'one rewriter'), expose min_sort over typed occurrences to resolution: a reflect/expression-accepting builtin that, given a typed occurrence, yields its inferred sort head, so the resolver can evaluate the sort-level requires/satisfaction guard itself and fire requires-guarded rules where the carrier provides the spec (instead of skipping them). Needs: (a) resolution over typed occurrences (Value::Node carrying inferred_type), (b) min_sort wired as the expression-accepting builtin, (c) the implicit enclosing-sort requires materialized/checkable as a resolvable guard. Also fold in the matcher gap noted in WI-283 (positional rule LHS does not match a named-arg redex) if it blocks carrier-by-name firing. Acceptance: a requires-guarded [simp] rule fires correctly via the resolver/prove path where the carrier satisfies the spec; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-283"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered (commit pending). ROOT CAUSE: MatchFinal set the match type to branch 0 (result_ty = Some(body_r.ty), first-branch-wins); IfExpr returned then_r.ty and its frame didn't even carry expected. Leaves (literals/refs) ignore expected, so it was an inference HINT, never enforced; the only enforcement was the op-body return check, which saw the synthesized type = branch 0. Hence Int/String branch clashes loaded clean in both synthesis (let x = match) and declared-return (op body) positions.\n\nFIX (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs): new compute_branch_join_type(kb, branch_tys, expected, construct) — checked mode (expected present): every branch must types_compatible with it (covers entity->sort + requires-refine); synthesis mode: fold branch types with join_types. Threaded body_expected into MatchFinal and expected into IfExpr frames; both call the shared helper. join_types = commutative common-supertype: type_var short-circuit, directional types_compatible (supertype wins), more_general_type for the mutually-compatible (bare-vs-parameterized) case, else entity->enclosing-sort widening climb (bounded 0..64), else None.\n\nSCOPE: ALSO fixed if (identical first-branch-wins gap; user asked) via the same helper — extends past the WI's match-only text.\n\nDESIGN (sound common supertype, NOT strict lub): the synthesized result is an upper bound, not the lattice-theoretic lub. For bare-vs-parameterized (none():Option vs some(1):Option[T=Int], mutually types_compatible) the STRICT lub is Option[T=Int] (none is polymorphic), but the typer neither tracks that a bare type is the polymorphic kind nor unifies at the join, so more_general_type returns the conservative bare Option (user-confirmed choice) — never over-claims a binding a declared -> Option might not have. Checked mode prefers the precise join but never widens past expected and never collapses to a type_var hint (would lose the concrete type for a match/if passed as a generic arg).\n\nTESTS (wi_tests, 7 total, all green): un-ignored the 2 match clash tests + anchor (match_branch_join_test.rs); new if_branch_join_test.rs = synthesis clash, op-body clash, positive control (if c then 1 else 2 loads clean), bare/param join in both branch orders.\n\nCODE-REVIEW (max, 5 angles + sweep): (1) FIXED — join_types was order-dependent for bare-vs-param (types_compatible true both ways); made commutative via more_general_type. (2) FIXED — (clash, Some(exp)) arm could collapse a genuine clash to a wildcard if exp were a type_var; added type_var guard (currently unreachable — args use push_visit_no_hint, op/let/lambda hints are concrete — but self-consistent). LEFT (documented, not bugs): 0..64 climb bound (defensive, single-level entity->sort today, unbounded would be worse); exhaustiveness diagnostic skipped when a branch ALSO has a type error (type error is the more fundamental signal); min_sort now more-defined for a branch with an unresolved arm (suite confirms no [simp] regression).\n\nSCALAND: WI text said 'scaland has a parallel typer that should get the same fix' — INACCURATE. scaland has NO expression typer yet (user-confirmed; zero subtype/lub/types_compatible machinery). Nothing to port; recorded so future 'mirror in scaland' typer notes don't mislead.\n\nVALIDATION: full anthill-core suite 0 failures (incl. all 7 branch tests, 218 lib, wi_tests, eval/github_todo/algebra/builtin/induction/resolve).", at: "2026-05-23T14:26:39Z", workitem: "WI-287", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-293",
  description: "Typer: consume declared variance facts (Covariant/Contravariant) in types_compatible / parameterized_compatible / join_types, instead of hardcoded uniform covariance. PROBLEM: variance is declared AS FACTS (proposal 035; stdlib/anthill/reflect/typing.anthill:117-151 — entity Covariant(sort: Symbol, param: Symbol) / Contravariant(sort, param), with no-fact=invariant / both=bivariant, plus indirection rules effective_covariant / effective_contravariant and a check_variance(?S,?P,?V1,?V2) resolver rule), but NOTHING consumes them: grep finds zero Rust readers of check_variance/Covariant/effective_*, and no stdlib rule queries check_variance either — the facts/rules are inert. Instead the typer hardcodes variance: parameterized_compatible (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/typing.rs) checks every binding value covariantly via types_compatible(actual_val, expected_val) REGARDLESS of declared variance, so a contravariant or invariant parameter is checked covariantly (potential unsoundness — e.g. a function-typed or mutable-cell parameter); arrow_compatible separately hardcodes structural arrow variance (contravariant param, covariant result/effects). TASK: wire effective_covariant/effective_contravariant (or check_variance) into types_compatible/parameterized_compatible so per-parameter variance is honored: invariant default => exact/equal binding value; covariant => actual_val <: expected_val (current behavior); contravariant => expected_val <: actual_val (flipped); bivariant => either. Then extend WI-287's join_types to recurse into bindings using the same variance, so a covariant T gives join(Option[T=Cat], Option[T=Dog]) = Option[T=Animal] instead of the current conservative clash (today join_types can't form parameterized lubs — it only does sort_ref widening — so WI-287 deliberately left the synthesized result a sound common supertype, not the strict lub; this WI is what would make it a real lub for parameterized sorts). SCOPE: distinct from WI-184 (the variance INFERENCE algorithm, Open) — this CONSUMES hand-declared facts and can land before inference exists; it is the prerequisite that makes WI-184's output meaningful. OPTIONAL (proposal 035 line 178): fold the hardcoded arrow_compatible into Function[A,B] with covariant(Function,B)/contravariant(Function,A) facts for uniformity. TESTS: contravariant param rejected where covariant-checking would wrongly accept; invariant param requires exact binding; covariant join Option[Cat]/Option[Dog] => Option[Animal]; bivariant accepts either. Note: scaland has no typer (see WI-287), so rust-only.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-295",
  description: "Lightweight cross-namespace import for rule-defined predicates. PROBLEM: a predicate defined only by rules (e.g. type_compatible in anthill.reflect.typing) cannot be imported from another namespace -- import anthill.reflect.typing.{type_compatible} fails with unresolved-import. process_imports Selective arm (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs ~955) resolves a name only via by_qualified_name + resolve_in_scope; rule heads register no importable symbol there (only sort/entity/operation + registered builtins do). is_entity_of imports ONLY because it is a registered builtin (BuiltinTag::IsEntityOf); type_compatible and refines are pure rule heads, invisible to import. The export keyword is a no-op (proposal 044, load.rs:505, visible-by-default). Yet the predicate IS resolvable everywhere else: rule_id_by_qn (mod.rs:1706) resolves a qualified name label-first then by_functor, and the resolver matches goals by functor symbol -- so the gap is purely that the import path never consults the rule indices. TASK: in process_imports ImportKind::Selective arm, add a fallback -- when a selective-import name resolves to nothing as sort/entity/operation/builtin, try resolving it as a rule-head predicate (try_resolve_symbol(qualified) then by_functor non-empty, or rule_id_by_qn) and add_import aliasing that symbol. A few lines; no new construct, no declarations, no closure. MOTIVATION: lets a self-hosted relation (the typing relation synth/check/wf_type in docs/proposals/typing_pass_spec.anthill) live in its own namespace and import type_compatible, instead of co-locating into anthill.reflect.typing (current workaround). SCOPE: extends proposal 044 (unified name resolution) to rule-predicate heads; mirror in scaland for parity. This is the minimal FQN-access for rule-defined predicates, NOT the full declared/closed-relations feature (deferred vision in docs/brainstorms/declared-relations.md). NOTE: load-only -- does NOT address the separate Expr-as-data resolver panic (open_debruijn_node in node_occurrence.rs) that blocks running typing rules. ACCEPTANCE: importing a rule-defined predicate from another namespace resolves, and a goal through it resolves cross-namespace; new test; cargo-test green; scaland parity.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-05-23T16:30:29Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-296",
  description: "Resolver: open_debruijn_node must handle child-bearing control-flow Expr forms at rule-body atom positions (currently panics). PROBLEM: open_debruijn_node (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/node_occurrence.rs:614) opens Apply/Constructor/Instantiation/HoApply by remapping DeBruijn->Global in their children, but its catch-all arm debug-asserts that any other child-bearing Expr cannot occur at a rule-body atom position (line 651). It CAN: reflection/typing rules legitimately match expression structure as data, e.g. synth(...) :- occurrence_term(?e, lambda(param:.., body:?b)), ... The materializer (visit_fn) elaborates reflect-Expr functors lambda/let_expr/if_expr/match_expr into Expr::Lambda/Let/If/Match, and opening the rule body for resolution (occurrence/typed path, post-WI-283) hits the assert and panics. Reproduced: anthill query of anthill.reflect.typing.synth with --resolve panics (Discriminant 6 = Lambda). TASK: extend open_debruijn_node to open the children of ALL child-bearing Expr variants (Match/If/Let/Lambda/DotApply + the *_within elaboration forms), mirroring the Apply/Constructor arms (open each child position, rebuild only if changed); either explicit per-variant arms or a generic map_children mirroring for_each_child (node_occurrence.rs:531). Drop the catch-all panic for child-bearing forms; keep it only for genuine leaves. ACCEPTANCE: the synth query no longer panics (opens cleanly, even if it then delays on the unimplemented occurrence_term); a test opening a rule whose body matches lambda/match_expr resolves without panic; cargo-test green. SCOPE: precondition for running the self-hosted typing relation (WI-079); Rust-only.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "user", at: "2026-05-23T16:30:28Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-297",
  description: "Implement occurrence reflection builtins occurrence_term / occurrence_span / occurrence_owner / sub_occurrences. PROBLEM: these are stubs returning BuiltinResult::Delay (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/resolve.rs:1518, comment: Occurrence builtins stubs returning Delay until Phase 2). The self-hosted typing relation and any reflection rule depend on occurrence_term to destructure an expression occurrence, e.g. synth(?, ?e, Int, nil) :- occurrence_term(?e, int_lit(value: ?)); with the stub, every reflection rule first goal delays and nothing resolves. TASK: implement at least occurrence_term(occ, term): given a bound occurrence (Value::Node / occurrence handle), bind or unify the second arg with its term structure; building block exists, occurrence_to_term (node_occurrence.rs:762) converts an occurrence to a TermId. Decide the mode (functional: bind term from occ; or relational: match a pattern against the occurrence structure). Implement occurrence_span (-> SourceSpan), occurrence_owner (-> Symbol), sub_occurrences (-> List[Occurrence]) similarly. Delay on unbound occurrence. ACCEPTANCE: synth on a literal occurrence resolves to its sort (int_lit -> sort_ref(Int)) once the opener fix is in; a builtin test that occurrence_term binds the term of a known occurrence; cargo-test green. SCOPE: the Phase 2 the stub references; precondition for WI-079 (runnable typing spec); Rust-only.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-23T21:28:03Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-298",
  description: "Rule-occurrence opener: remap DeBruijn vars inside the REMAINING TermId fields after the param lift (open_debruijn_node / substitute_occurrence), AND make the remaining occurrence walkers symmetric with node_to_debruijn for Pattern-kind occurrences. PROBLEM (WI-296 code-review finding 3): open_debruijn_node and substitute_occurrence walk only Rc<NodeOccurrence> children via for_each_child + reassemble; several TermId-typed fields hold materialized terms with DeBruijn vars that are NOT remapped to fresh Globals — diverging from the term-level term_from_debruijn (which remaps all subterms). LATENT today: SLD matching uses the TERM body (patterns remapped correctly there); the occurrence view's un-remapped fields only bite once the typer/simp READS them (typing rules over rule occurrences, WI-079). SCOPE AFTER WI-319 (Pattern reform): WI-319 lifts Lambda.param / LambdaWithin.param / Let.pattern / MatchBranch.pattern from TermId to Rc<NodeOccurrence>(NodeKind::Pattern). WI-298's residual scope is now: (1) Let.type_annotation: Option<TermId>; (2) Expr::Apply.type_args / Expr::ApplyWithin.type_args: Vec<(Option<Symbol>, TermId)>. Plus, NEW from WI-319 code-review (deferred fixes): (3) extend the Pattern-kind descent to the OTHER walkers that don't yet recurse into Pattern children — collect_occurrence_global_vars_ordered (node_occurrence.rs ~1188), collect_occurrence_global_vars, occurrence_has_unbound_var, collect_occurrence_type_constraints (typing.rs ~7215), collect_unbound_vars_node (resolve.rs ~2721), (try_)occurrence_to_term (node_occurrence.rs ~1297). Latent today because Pattern.Var.type_ann is always None at load_pattern_var (load.rs:4963), but the slot is in the public Pattern enum API and any future pass writing to it (proposal 035 lambda binder annotations; reflection-synthesized patterns) silently undercounts/skips vars. REQUIRES: thread kb (term store) into open_debruijn_node + reassemble + their callers (open_debruijn_node currently has no kb), then remap those TermIds via KnowledgeBase::term_from_debruijn (mod.rs:1938) — mirroring the closing-side node_to_debruijn. ACCEPTANCE: a rule whose body has a let with a type annotation referencing ?p (or an Apply type_arg referencing ?p) shows the bound var in the occurrence view remapped to the same Global as the body's ?p; all listed walkers descend into Pattern children via for_each_pattern_child; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-319"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-28T16:27:21Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-299",
  description: "Centralize Rust-side entity-term construction so named args are always canonicalized to declared field order. PROBLEM: the discrim matcher matches named args POSITIONALLY (discrim.rs:573 descends NamedKey(query_keys[i]) against the tree's i-th pattern key), and the loader canonicalizes loaded patterns/facts to declared field order via entity_field_names (load.rs:3112). But Rust-side term builders sort named args by Symbol::index() (interning order) — build_list (mod.rs:2187/2202), make_sort_ref, and others at mod.rs:2248/2261/2282/2317. index-order only COINCIDENTALLY equals declared-order (verified for source_span/cons during WI-297: works today, but reversing the order makes the structured pattern silently match 0 solutions). A future change to interning order (e.g. a new stdlib entity interning a shared field name earlier) would silently break matching of any Rust-built >=2-named-arg entity term against a loaded pattern, with no error. SCOPE: add a single canonicalizing constructor (e.g. KB::make_entity_term(functor, pos, named) that calls the existing pub(crate) KB::sort_named_canonical added in WI-297) and route the existing s.index()-sorting builders through it; remove the ad-hoc s.index() sorts. Rust-only. Loaded terms need no change (loader already canonicalizes). PRECONDITION CONTEXT: WI-297 added KB::sort_named_canonical (generic over value type) and already fixed its own two builders (make_source_span_term, build_occurrence_cons_list); this generalizes that fix to the pre-existing builders.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-297"],
  status: Open)


fact Feedback(content: "Root-cause + right approach (traced in WI-297). Rule-body atoms should be produced as occurrences NATIVELY in the front-end, NOT derived from terms via materialize_from_handle. Today convert.rs builds Term::Fn for bodies and mod.rs:638 derives body_nodes by RE-INFERRING Expr structure from the functor NAME (visit_fn key dispatch). Term::Fn is structurally poorer than Expr (it does not record apply-vs-constructor-vs-if), so the re-inference assumes 'apply(...) is a call' and is LOSSY for reflection patterns: apply(fn:?f, args:?Args) collapses to an empty Apply<apply>() (verified — subject foo(1,2) survives via the UnknownFn path, but the recognized-key apply pattern is interpreted and emptied). Same class as int_lit(value:?)->Bottom that WI-297 patched for leaf keys (push_unknown_fn). RIGHT FIX: build body occurrences directly from the CST (structure + spans known there), eliminating both the term intermediary AND the re-inference — no materialize_from_handle for bodies, no loss. ASYMMETRY (confirmed): HEAD stays a hash-consed TermId because it is SEARCHED in the discrimination tree (must be canonical/span-free); BODY atoms are GOALS (resolved, never searched -> no hash-consing) so they can be occurrences only, dropping body: Vec<TermId> (the De Bruijn opener, delay pre-check, and dedup all either have occurrence equivalents or reify on demand — none is a correctness need). This subsumes WI-298 (no TermId-pattern / control-flow special-casing) and the compound-form occurrence_term work; the lens-patch framing in WI-300 is the WRONG direction and is superseded.", at: "2026-05-23T21:21:31Z", workitem: "WI-246", author: "user")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-300",
  description: "Requirement goals in rule bodies (conditional-rule requirements). Today a realization requirement cannot be expressed as a rule-body goal: req_insertion::run (req_insertion.rs:41) weaves requirement forms (Expr::ApplyWithin / ConstructRequirement / RequirementAtSort / VarRef) ONLY into kb.op_bodies, never rule body_nodes. A 'requires(Eq[T])' written in a rule body (e.g. 'something(?x,?y) :- eq(?x,?y), requires(Eq[T])') parses — keywords are soft (grammar.js:23) — as an ordinary Expr::Apply{functor: requires, pos_args:[Eq[T]]} goal with NO requirement semantics: convert_rule_body (convert.rs:1647) has no special case, and at resolution it is just an undefined predicate that fails. Requirements today live only as: the standalone 'requires <Type>' decl -> SortRequiresInfo fact (load.rs:6004), and operation requires/ensures clauses -> OperationInfo reflect fact fields (load.rs:5850). SCOPE: design + implement rule-body requirement goals (conditional rules) — decide the surface syntax/semantics (likely a distinguished goal recognized in convert_rule_body or a type-directed weave), extend req_insertion (or an analog) to process rule body_nodes, and represent the woven form as occurrences consistent with the op-body *Within forms. Builds on the per-rule is_requires_resolved/mark_requires_resolved flags (mod.rs:456) which already exist but are not backed by body-level occurrence synthesis. Surfaced during WI-246 Phase 3c review.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-301",
  description: "Effect-set type representation: make `Effect = {}` and `Effect = {Modify[s]}` expressible as a type-argument value, end to end. PROBLEM: an effect set has no representation as a type-binding value. (1) GRAMMAR — sort_binding's value slot is `_type` = {simple_type, parameterized_type, variable_term, tuple_type, arrow_type} (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:1001); the effect-set form `_effect_set` (grammar.js:369) lives only in `effects` clauses and arrow `@`, and its braced variant is commaSep1, so empty `{}` has NO production anywhere. Thus `Effect = {}` / `Effect = {Modify[s]}` are ungrammatical in both named and positional instantiation forms. (2) TYPE MODEL — stdlib/anthill/prelude/sort.anthill's Type enum carries effects only inside arrow(param, result, effects: List[Type]); a TypeBinding(param, value: Type) cannot hold a set of effects. (3) REFLECTION/SPEC — stdlib/anthill/reflect/typing.anthill + docs/proposals/typing_pass_spec.anthill treat effects as List[Type] on arrows only (effects_subset / merge_effects / external_effects), never as a type-argument value; stdlib/anthill/prelude/function.anthill:15 explicitly flags 'exact encoding depends on how empty effect sets are represented'. DESIGN (agreed): add `entity effect_set(effects: List[Type])` to the Type enum, mirroring arrow's effects: List[Type]; `{}` -> effect_set(effects: []), `{Modify[s]}` -> effect_set(effects: [Modify[s]]); this also fixes the pure-Function `E = {}` encoding. TASK: (a) grammar — let an effect-set expression (incl. empty `{}`) be used where a `_type` is expected (the sort_binding value slot), regenerate parser, add corpus tests; (b) converter — build effect_set Type terms from the new node; (c) prelude/sort.anthill — add the effect_set Type constructor; (d) reflect/typing.anthill + typing_pass_spec.anthill — type/classify effect-set type arguments; (e) restore explicit `Effect = {}` on the 3 list.anthill facts (Collection / IndexedSeq / Iteration) that the substrate change temporarily dropped. ACCEPTANCE: `fact Iteration[Iterator = List[T], Element = T, Effect = {}]` parses and stores an effect_set binding (not silently dropped); a reflection query over List's Iteration provides-fact sees Effect = effect_set([]); typer accepts effect-set type arguments; cargo-test green. SCOPE: converter + typer are Rust-only (scaland has no typer); the grammar change is shared. CONTEXT: surfaced while checking whether `fact Iteration[List[T], T, {}]` (positional) equals the named form — positional type args DO work (loader maps index -> declared param via type_params_of_sort), but the `{}` effect arg never parsed; the silent drop only became visible once parse() started surfacing tree-sitter ERROR/MISSING nodes (the WI-303 substrate). RELATED (separate, not in scope): fully-qualified names are rejected as instantiation_term functors (reflect.anthill `fact anthill.prelude.Modifiable[T = KB]` had to be rewritten to the imported short name `fact Modifiable[T = KB]`) — file its own WI if dotted instantiation functors should be supported.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-302",
  description: "Computed type arguments: allow an expression (operation / method call) as a type-binding value, e.g. `Function[A = param_type, B = result_type(br), E = result_effects(br)]` and `List[T = TypingEnv.apply_subst(env3, elem_type)]`. PROBLEM: sort_binding's value slot is `_type` (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:1001) = {simple_type, parameterized_type, variable_term, tuple_type, arrow_type}; a function/method call (fn_term / field_access call) is not a `_type`, so `[T = f(x)]` is ungrammatical. The reference typing spec docs/proposals/typing_pass_spec.anthill NEEDS this to express type construction from computed components (a Function type whose B / E are computed from sub-results) in its reference-algorithm part. These parse errors are masked because parse() swallows tree-sitter ERROR / MISSING nodes (see WI-303). CONSEQUENCE: the test typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads (rustland/anthill-core/tests/include/typing_test.rs) is GREEN only because the errors are swallowed; making it honest is part of WI-303. TASK: decide and implement how computed expressions may appear in type-argument position — likely widen the sort_binding value slot (and convert_instantiation_term's named branch + convert_type_value, which today only preserves parametric type shapes) to accept a term expression, with the typer evaluating / normalizing it to a Type; define the interaction with the existing _type forms. ACCEPTANCE: `List[T = f(x)]` and `Function[B = g(y)]` parse; typing_pass_spec.anthill parses with 0 errors; cargo-test green. SCOPE: grammar + converter are shared; typer is Rust-only (scaland has no typer). RELATED: WI-301 (effect-set type args) — both widen what may appear as a type argument; coordinate the grammar change.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Claimed(agent: "claude", since: "2026-05-26T15:18:37Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-303",
  description: "Fire parse errors early: surface tree-sitter ERROR / MISSING nodes from parse() instead of silently dropping them. PROBLEM: parse() (rustland/anthill-core/src/parse/mod.rs) never inspects tree.root_node().has_error(); it returns Ok with only the converter's own errors. tree-sitter recovers from malformed input by inserting ERROR / MISSING nodes and continuing, and the converter walks past anything it does not recognise — so a broken construct is silently dropped (an `Effect = {}` binding vanishes; the anthill-stl carrier host bindings were dropped; computed type args dropped). Violates CLAUDE.md 'avoid fallbacks, know about errors early'. PROTOTYPE (validated then reverted this session): a collect_syntax_errors(root, source) walk that prunes clean subtrees via has_error, reports is_error / is_missing once per error subtree (source-ordered), and has parse() return Err if any are found. BLAST RADIUS (measured with the prototype): zero behavioural regressions, but it surfaces ~37+ latent malformed TEST FIXTURES across at least 4 binaries (builtin/toml_ser 16, parse 12, wi 2, integration+cpp-gen 7) that only ever parsed via error recovery, in three mechanical classes: (1) brace-less namespace or bare sort missing `end` (toml_ser_test build_test_kb namespace; parse_test bare `sort ns.A`); (2) variable / abstract-sort inline description missing the grammar-required trailing `?` — `?x {< .. >}` must be `?x {< .. >}?` (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:778-786); (3) `?`-logic-vars in EXPRESSION positions — `let ?y = x` must be `let y = x`. PLUS a false-green canary: typing_test.rs typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads panics on parse errors and is green ONLY because they are swallowed; it must be made honest (depends on WI-302 plus the spec gaps). TASK: land collect_syntax_errors in parse(); fix all surfaced fixtures (mechanical, no logic change); make typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads honest; confirm full suite green. RELATED gaps that fire-error exposes: WI-301 (effect-set type args), WI-302 (computed type args), dotted-name instantiation functors (a reflect.anthill workaround was applied), and the carrier host-binding sugar (anthill-stl rewritten to the braced carrier-bindings form; anthill-cpp-gen/anthill/int.anthill was deliberately LEFT in the swallowed carrier-equals-string form because the braced form actually loads the carrier, which makes cpp-gen emit this provides block's artifact — a .rs path — as a C++ #include and breaks the header-compile tests; fix the cpp-gen carrier braced-form AND its bogus .rs artifact together). The carrier braced-form rewrite, list.anthill effect-set removal, reflect.anthill short-name fix, and the check_effects return type were landed separately this session as safe cleanups. ACCEPTANCE: parse() returns Err on a source containing an ERROR / MISSING node (e.g. a fact whose binding is `Effect = {}`); all in-tree .anthill files and test fixtures parse clean; typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads honest; cargo-test green. SCOPE: the parser is shared (Rust impl drives this); the fixture fixes are Rust-test-only.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-304",
  description: "Build the operation-body NodeOccurrence natively in convert_expr_term (parse IR to occurrence), eliminating the materialize_from_handle round-trip at the op-body load site (load.rs:5828-5829). Op-body analog of WI-246 (rule bodies); finishes WI-251 item (e) (eliminate the double tree walk by building NodeOccurrence trees directly in convert_expr_term), which was left undone when WI-251 was delivered. TODAY: loader does convert_expr_term (parse to reflect-form Term handle) then materialize_from_handle (Term to occurrence via visit_fn last-segment name-matching re-inference). The handle is vestigial as a term: nobody reads OperationInfo.body / OperationImpl.body as a term; all consumers (cpp-gen OpImplTable WI-249, typer WI-247, eval WI-248, req_insertion, op_requirements, op_info, simp_rewrite) read the occurrence via kb.op_body_node / op_bodies. PLAN: thread a parallel occ_results Vec<Rc<NodeOccurrence>> through convert_expr_terms work-stack walker (visit_load / build_load). Leaves build their Expr leaf directly (Const/VarRef/Var/Ref/Ident), NOT via materialize_from_handle. Internal frames assemble the Expr variant from child occurrences; the pure assembly helper node_occurrence::build_frame can be reused since it touches no KB terms. let/lambda/match keep pattern/param as a TermId field from the term side (Expr::Let.pattern is a TermId), so the pattern childs occurrence is discarded, not consumed: mind the stack discipline (term results and occ_results diverge on patterns). Guards are always none in convert today (build_load sets guard=build_none). Use the natively-built occurrence at the op-body site instead of materialize_from_handle; set_op_body_node(functor, native_occ). Keep building the term handle for the OperationInfo.body field until WI-252 retires it. SCOPE: op-body load path only. materialize_from_handle STAYS for its other callers (rule-body reflect-form atoms at build_body_atom_occurrence:4662; the apply_subst+materialize reflection/typer-rewriter reify path at node_occurrence.rs:1286); deleting it entirely plus dropping the handle is gated on WI-252 (drop OperationInfo.body field, migrate the OperationInfo(body: some) presence check to op_body_node) and migrating those remaining callers natively. ACCEPTANCE: op-body occurrence built without any materialize_from_handle call; cargo test green (typer + cpp-gen + eval exercise op bodies); native occurrence matches prior materialize output as verified by the suite.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-24T15:44:36Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Delivered commit 26e7dc7. convert_expr_term now returns (TermId, Rc<NodeOccurrence>) and builds the op-body occurrence natively via a parallel expr_occ_results stack: leaves through node_occurrence::build_expr_leaf, internal frames reuse build_frame (pub(crate)), let/lambda/match patterns occ-suppressed (PushOccSuppress/PopOccSuppress), match branches via an expr_match_metas side stack. Op-body site no longer calls materialize_from_handle; term handle still built for OperationInfo.body (WI-252 to retire it). materialize_from_handle retained for rule-body reflect atoms + the apply_subst reify path. Behavior-preserving (more precise spans); full workspace 1237 green incl. 2 new wi304 tests; multi-agent code-review found no active bugs.", at: "2026-05-24T15:44:36Z", workitem: "WI-304", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered commit 5bf42b9 (rename only). Merged reflect Occurrence + ExprOccurrence into one abstract sort NodeOccurrence: reflect.anthill (sort decls + occurrence_* ops + all Expr.* entity fields + MatchBranch + type_of + OperationInfo requires/ensures/body), prelude/sort.anthill + prelude/effects.anthill imports+entities, and the typing_pass_spec.anthill load fixture (incl. dedup of the collapsed import). anthill-stl reflect.rs regenerates to a single NodeOccurrence struct; no hand-written Rust referenced the old generated structs. OperationInfo.body RETYPED Option[ExprOccurrence] -> Option[NodeOccurrence], NOT dropped. Acceptance met: no 'sort Occurrence|sort ExprOccurrence' under stdlib/; reflect.anthill loads clean (the 3 typing_pass_spec load warnings are pre-existing, unrelated to the rename); full workspace 1237 green; focused rename-completeness review found no surviving refs / dups / mangled identifiers. NOT done (deliberately scoped out, see follow-up WI): dropping the OperationInfo.body field + OperationImpl.body + ceasing to build the term handle + migrating the OperationInfo(body: some(_)) presence check.", at: "2026-05-24T15:55:23Z", workitem: "WI-252", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-305",
  description: "Retire the operation-body term handle entirely. After WI-304 (op-body occurrence built natively) and WI-252 (NodeOccurrence rename), the term handle from convert_expr_term is still built and stored only to fill OperationInfo.body and OperationImpl.body, which no consumer reads as a term (all read kb.op_body_node). Drop both fact body fields and stop building the handle: (a) remove the body field from the OperationInfo entity (reflect.anthill) and OperationImpl (realization.anthill); (b) migrate the only logical use of body presence — the typer/spec OperationInfo(body: some(_)) has-body check (docs/proposals/typing_pass_spec.anthill ~410,796) — to derive has-body from kb.op_body_node instead; (c) in load.rs load_operation, stop building/storing the handle (convert_expr_term need only return the NodeOccurrence) once nothing needs the TermId; keep set_op_body_node. Then materialize_from_handle is gated only by its remaining callers (rule-body reflect atoms in build_body_atom_occurrence, the apply_subst reify path). Acceptance: OperationInfo/OperationImpl have no body field; no convert_expr_term handle stored; cargo test green; typing_pass_spec loads with no NEW warnings.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-252"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-24T16:51:09Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-306",
  description: "Reserved keyword 'lambda' cannot be used as a term/pattern functor, blocking the reflect AST. PROBLEM: the grammar reserves 'lambda' for lambda_expr (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:945, 'lambda' <param> -> <body>). But anthill.reflect defines 'entity lambda(param: Pattern, body: NodeOccurrence)' (stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill:319) and 'entity lambda_within(...)' as legitimate Expr-AST constructors. The entity DECLARATION parses (entity-name position accepts the word), but USING it as a functor in a term or pattern — 'lambda(param: ..., body: ...)' — fails: tree-sitter sees the 'lambda' keyword and produces ERROR nodes (confirmed via npx tree-sitter parse; 'foo(body: ?b)' parses, 'lambda(body: ?b)' does not). Masked until WI-303 made parse() surface ERROR/MISSING nodes. CONSUMER: docs/proposals/typing_pass_spec.anthill lines 165 and 200 destructure occurrence_term(?e, lambda(param: var_pattern(...), body: ?body)) — 2 of the parse errors keeping typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads #[ignore]d (the other 3 are WI-302 computed type args). DESIGN OPTIONS: (a) allow reserved keywords (at least 'lambda') as functor names in fn_term/pattern position (tricky in tree-sitter: keyword/identifier collision, ambiguity risk with lambda_expr); (b) rename the reflect AST constructor away from the keyword (e.g. 'lambda_expr'/'lam'/'closure'), updating reflect.anthill + consumers + typing_pass_spec. TASK: pick an approach, implement, add corpus/grammar tests, fix typing_pass_spec.anthill's lambda sites. ACCEPTANCE: the reflect lambda AST node is usable as a term/pattern functor; typing_pass_spec.anthill's lambda lines parse clean; cargo-test green. SCOPE: grammar + converter shared (Rust + scaland). Together with WI-302 this unblocks un-ignoring typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads (WI-303).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-24T20:34:49Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Partially landed: collect_syntax_errors in parse() fails fast on tree-sitter ERROR/MISSING; cpp int.anthill carrier braced + bogus .rs artifact dropped; cpp-gen from_kb guards empty artifact (no more #include <>); swallowed test fixtures fixed across parse/toml_ser/typing/wi210/wi261/wi304/match_binding/header_compile/policy; full suite green. NOT yet closed: typing_pass_spec.anthill still does NOT parse clean (acceptance 'all in-tree files parse clean' unmet). typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads is #[ignore]d (made honest, no longer false-green) pending WI-302 (computed type args, lines 497/505/557) + WI-306 (lambda keyword/functor collision, lines 165/200). Un-ignore + close WI-303 once WI-302 and WI-306 land.", at: "2026-05-24T17:03:41Z", workitem: "WI-303", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Delivered commit f8d0ea4. Added reflect builtin operation_body(op) -> Option[NodeOccurrence] (reads op_body_node, builds some(value: Value::Node)/none() as occurrences via match_view; arg0 non-Symbol fails cleanly). Dropped OperationInfo.body + OperationImpl.body; load_operation no longer stores the handle (still built transiently in convert_expr_term, which the native node-build reads — fully term-free node-build is a WI-304 follow-on). typing.rs operation_has_no_body migrated to op_body_node (OperationInfo-existence gate preserved). typing_pass_spec migrated to operation_body. Tests: new wi305 resolver test + 6 load_operation parse tests + 4 cpp-gen diag dumps migrated to op_body_node. materialize_from_handle now has NO op-body caller (remains for rule-body reflect atoms + the apply_subst reify path). Note: diag_phase_b fails at LOAD on a pre-existing malformed-source bug (x.name resolution in (p).x/?p.y), unrelated to WI-305 — fixture cleanup (WI-258 territory). Full workspace 1238 green; multi-agent code-review clean after the two fixes.", at: "2026-05-24T16:51:09Z", workitem: "WI-305", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-307",
  description: "Implement Proposal 045 — effect sets, effect expressions, and effect checking (docs/proposals/045-effect-sets-and-expressions.md). Introduce effect-sets as a new bindable kind (effects E = ? / effects E = (expr)), an EffectExpression algebra ({}, e, E, +e, -e, merge, and { E1, …, EN } as merge-sugar) that denotes an EffectSet (Set of effect types, normalized modulo ACI), and effect-checking that verifies an operation's actual effects satisfy its declaration. First cut decisions (per the proposal's resolved open questions): finite rows only — defer * (top), +*, -*, and co-finite * - e; 'allow all' = omit the annotation (open by default, closed once annotated, pure = effects {}); merge present/absent conflict is a hard error at normalization; negation on open rows handled by lazy symbolic evaluation (no presence variables in v1); decidability via structural induction on the body + monotone fixpoint over the program's finite effect-label set for recursion. Phased next steps from the proposal: (1) land Set/EffectSet laws + ACI matching substrate; (2) EffectExpression reflect sort + +/-/merge grammar; (3) effects E = ? declaration, arrow.effects/Function.E carry EffectExpression; (4) effect checking (satisfaction, propagation, handler discharge); (5) migrate typing_pass_spec effect handling onto this. Completes proposal 013's deferred effect checking; reframes WI-301 (effect-sets are not type args); type-level analog is WI-302/denoted. Reconcile orphaned stdlib: prelude/set.anthill, prelude/effect-set.anthill, prelude/function.anthill (sort E = ? -> effects E = ?).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Claimed(agent: "claude", since: "2026-05-24T21:41:26Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Scope correction: the [simp] rewrite engine (proposal 043) already exists and fires equations over occurrences during typing. The phase-(1) substrate gap is NOT the rewrite engine but matching modulo ACI: simp has no AC/ACI matching, so commutativity/idempotence as plain [simp] equations loop / are non-confluent (see typing.rs 'commutative law mistagged [simp]', load.rs 'would loop on add_comm-style laws'). Set semantics (insert(a,insert(b,S)) == insert(b,insert(a,S)); insert(a,insert(a,S)) == insert(a,S)) must therefore be matching-modulo-ACI (operator attributes or a canonical set normal form layered on simp), not rules. Phase (1) builds that ACI-matching layer + the Set/EffectSet laws; * (top) stays deferred.", at: "2026-05-24T21:41:06Z", workitem: "WI-307", author: "user")

fact Feedback(content: "WI-306 (lambda keyword/functor collision) now DELIVERED: reflect node renamed lambda -> lambda_expr (matching match_expr/if_expr/let_expr); typing_pass_spec lambda lines parse clean; Rust + scaland suites green. WI-303's remaining blocker for un-ignoring typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads is now ONLY WI-302 (computed type args).", at: "2026-05-24T20:34:50Z", workitem: "WI-303", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "DESIGN PIVOT (2026-05-25): effect checking is now the textbook row-polymorphism algorithm run IN THE TYPER, not ACI matching over a Set value. Rationale: effects are dominated by the polymorphic case (map/fold/Stream.map carry exactly the callback's row) — row polymorphism's home — and absence on open rows (-e) is its lacks-constraint machinery, which dissolves the old hard problem instead of deferring it. Integration point (confirmed by exploration): typing.rs unify_types -> unify_arrow (line ~4929) currently SKIPS the effects field entirely; arrow_compatible (line ~6027) does only a naive positional subset (⊆) check with no row variables. Row unification slots into both. Row tail variable = ordinary Var::Global, bound via the typer's existing Substitution/occurs_in/walk_type — no new variable layer. New phases (supersede the ACI-substrate phases): (v1a) open rows = present labels + row-variable tail; real row unification in unify_arrow + open-row subtyping in arrow_compatible (common polymorphic-propagation case, no -e). (2) EffectExpression surface + grammar elaborating to a row; effects E = ? binds a row variable; arrow.effects/Function.E carry the row. (v1b) lacks constraints for -e absence guarantees, checked abstractly at definition time. (4) handler discharge drops a label. (5) migrate typing_pass_spec onto row unification. The [simp]/ACI/canonical-Set substrate is DECOUPLED from effect checking — optional, only for general sets / runtime catalog. Starting with v1a.", at: "2026-05-25T05:35:31Z", workitem: "WI-307", author: "user")

fact Feedback(content: "DESIGN DECISION (option B — denoted): computed type args (List[T = f(x)], Function[B = result_type(br)]) are represented by wrapping the call expression in Type.denoted(value: NodeOccurrence), NOT stored as a raw term. Rationale grounded in typing.rs: the typer is STRUCTURAL, not resolution-based — canonicalize_type_value (typing.rs:3874) pattern-matches parameterized/sort_ref and passes any other Fn through opaquely; unify_types matches type terms structurally with no SLD/reduction. So a raw f(x) in a binding would become a phantom type literally named 'f(x)' (silently wrong). denoted is the explicit marker the structural typer branches on to invoke evaluation of the carried occurrence at that one spot (a localized reduction hook). The rejected option A (store raw term + make the typer resolution-based, per kernel-language.md §4.4's 'type-checking is KB querying' ideal) is much larger and not what's implemented. RULE for the converter: wrap in denoted IFF the binding value is a redex (operation/method call); leave names, constructor applications, and logical variables as plain Type terms (they are normal forms, handled by unification — that IS 'types are terms'). v1 scope = grammar widens sort_binding value to admit the call form + converter emits denoted + loader builds the occurrence + load doesn't reject; typer ELABORATION of denoted->concrete Type (the actual reduction) can be a follow-on (acceptance is parse+0-errors+load+cargo-green, not full dependent typing). kernel-language.md §4.4 updated to stop overclaiming 'any term in a type position' and to name denoted as the computed-type-arg extension.", at: "2026-05-25T06:06:44Z", workitem: "WI-302", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "SCOPE CORRECTION (supersedes the earlier option-B note): WI-302 is the VALUE-IN-TYPE case, not computed calls. A value standing in a type-argument position (Modify[store], Modify[c] on a param, Modify[result] on a return, Modify[result.a] per projection — proposal 027.1; value-dependent typing per 011) must be represented as Type.denoted(value: occurrence) so it reads as a value INDEXING the type, not as a sort_ref. The parser already admits the surface forms (bare names and field projections in brackets all parse; only call-VALUES like Modify[f(x)] error). So WI-302 is mainly the SEMANTIC representation (load a value-in-type-slot as denoted, scope-aware: name resolves to a value -> denoted, to a sort -> sort_ref), plus admitting any value-expression forms that do not yet parse. SEPARATE, NOT WI-302: the typing_pass_spec sites Function[B = result_type(br)] (497/505) and List[T = TypingEnv.apply_subst(env3, elem_type)] (557) are NOT type annotations — they are expression-position code BUILDING a Type value, and were verified to parse cleanly when rewritten with the explicit Type constructors (parameterized/sort_ref/TypeBinding). That is a spec syntax-mixing fix (no grammar change, no denoted), to be tracked separately. DOC INCONSISTENCY to reconcile: sort.anthill:16-21 comment and 045 line 321 currently frame denoted as the COMPUTED-expression case (Function[B=result_type(br)]) — that example is wrong per this scope; denoted's example should be Modify[x]. kernel-language.md §4.4 corrected accordingly. The grammar experiments (admitting fn_term in sort_binding) were reverted; grammar is back to origin state.", at: "2026-05-25T06:46:39Z", workitem: "WI-302", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-308",
  description: "Fix syntax-mixing in typing_pass_spec.anthill: the reference algorithm (Part II) builds Type VALUES in expression position using the type-annotation instantiation sugar Name[bindings], which conflates two syntaxes. Three sites: line 497 and 505 (Function[A = param_type, B = result_type(br), E = result_effects(br)]) and line 557 (List[T = TypingEnv.apply_subst(env3, elem_type)]). These are not type annotations; they construct a Type value where one binding is computed by an operation call returning Type. Rewrite them to the explicit Type constructors (already imported in the spec): parameterized(base: sort_ref(name: Function), bindings: [TypeBinding(param: A, value: param_type), TypeBinding(param: B, value: result_type(br)), TypeBinding(param: E, value: result_effects(br))]) and parameterized(base: sort_ref(name: List), bindings: [TypeBinding(param: T, value: TypingEnv.apply_subst(env3, elem_type))]). Verified: the explicit form parses with 0 errors on the unmodified grammar (no grammar change, no denoted needed). This is the LAST remaining parse blocker for typing_pass_spec (lambda was fixed in WI-306); after it, un-ignore typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads (WI-303) if it also loads clean. SCOPE: spec doc + the #[ignore] test. NOT related to WI-302 (value-in-type/denoted) or WI-307 (effect poly).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-25T09:06:45Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Last deferred item CLEARED: typing_pass_spec.anthill now parses to 0 errors and loads; typing_pass_spec_parses_and_loads is UN-IGNORED and genuinely green (full suite 1238 passed). The two blockers were resolved as: WI-306 (lambda->lambda_expr) + WI-308 (rewrite the 3 computed-Type-construction sites to explicit Type constructors — a spec syntax-mixing fix, NOT WI-302/denoted). WI-302 (value-in-type/denoted) was never actually a blocker for the spec parse; it stands as its own item.", at: "2026-05-25T09:06:21Z", workitem: "WI-303", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-309",
  description: "Load and surface operation-declaration metadata. Operation declarations already accept a [key: value] meta_block in the grammar (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js:319, operation_declaration) AND it is parsed into the IR (Operation.meta: Option<MetaBlock>, parse/ir.rs:336). But the loader (kb/load.rs) NEVER reads op.meta — operation metadata is silently dropped at load — and OperationInfo (stdlib/anthill/reflect/reflect.anthill:424) has no field to expose it (only name/params/return_type/effects/requires/ensures). Work: (1) loader consumes op.meta and stores it in the KB op record; (2) OperationInfo gains a meta field (or per-key surfacing) so operation metadata is queryable from reflection and the typer; (3) regression test: an operation declared with [key: value] has that metadata loaded and retrievable via OperationInfo. Motivation: proposal 046 (effect_derive / region tracking) needs [feeds: ...] metadata on operations to carry the feed-relationship for abstract/foreign higher-order operations that have no anthill body; more generally, ANY operation-level metadata (trust, source, project-defined keys) is currently parsed and thrown away. Prerequisite for 046's feeds annotation.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-310",
  description: "Add an 'unclaim' command to the anthill-todo CLI. Today there is no way to release a claimed work item back to Open: the command set is init/add/status/list/next/show/claim/deliver/verify/feedback/delete/update/add-dependency/remove-dependency/graph/skill — 'update' explicitly PRESERVES status, and there is no unclaim/release/reopen. Releasing a claim currently requires hand-editing workitems.anthill (status: Claimed(agent,since) -> status: Open), which is error-prone. Add 'anthill-todo unclaim WI-NNN' that transitions a Claimed item back to Open (clearing agent/since). Consider: only valid from Claimed (error otherwise); honor --agent for symmetry/auditing; possibly a paired status-transition audit. ACCEPTANCE: 'anthill-todo unclaim WI-NNN' on a Claimed item sets it to Open; on a non-Claimed item it errors clearly; help lists it. SCOPE: anthill-todo CLI crate.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-311",
  description: "commonTypeExpr grammar unification (STEP 1 toward FULL type/term conversion). FULL-CONVERSION GOAL: the grammar should NOT distinguish type-vs-term — merge the dual type/term productions into shared rules so 'types are terms' holds at the CFG level, and the LOADER classifies (sort_ref vs denoted/value vs application) via SymbolKind. This WI is the first, validated step: the application merge (parameterized_type == instantiation_term -> one 'application' rule) plus the dotted-path/field_access unification. VALIDATED (measured 2026-05-26, prototype reverted, baseline green): the application name MUST be the identifier-only dotted path $.name, NOT field_access — field_access's _atom_term receiver CASCADES type/term conflicts ([_atom_term,application] -> [_atom_term,_type] -> [_atom_term,_effect_type] -> ...). With $.name it generates CLEAN and Eq[T=Int] / a.b.Stack[T=Int] / Modify[c] / Vector[Int,3] all parse. REMAINING WORK: the contained name-vs-field_access overlap (a.b matches both) breaks p.x(?x) and g(a.b). Fix per 'do not distinguish in grammar, distinguish in loader': make a.b ONE path node everywhere — route fn_term names, bare references, and ident-chain projections through the dotted path — and RESTRICT field_access to non-name receivers (?x.y, foo().y); the loader classifies projection-vs-qualified-vs-application. SCOPE: grammar (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js: application rule, fn_term/_atom_term/field_access restructure; full conversion later also merges tuple_type==tuple_literal) + converter (anthill-core/src/parse/convert.rs) + corpus rebaseline (~27 trees, mostly node renames) + cargo green. PAYOFF: grammar cleanliness ('types are terms' at CFG level), NOT new capability — the loader already classifies. PREREQ/RELATED: builds on committed _common_type_expr = _type | literals + TypeExpr::Denoted (commit fcb75e6, branch wi302-denoted-value-in-type; WI-302 denoted value-in-type).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Claimed(agent: "claude", since: "2026-05-26T22:43:30Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-312",
  description: "WI-311 follow-up: field_access/path-node unification (the deferred 'one path node' part of WI-311). WI-311 (merged 7ada265) landed the APPLICATION merge (parameterized_type + instantiation_term -> one `application` node) and changed the bare-reference atom from $.identifier to $.name, but deliberately did NOT do the field_access restructure WI-311 listed as remaining work: 'make a.b ONE path node everywhere — route fn_term names, bare references, and ident-chain projections through the dotted path — and RESTRICT field_access to non-name receivers (?x.y, foo().y); the loader classifies projection-vs-qualified-vs-application'. Instead field_access was left unchanged (object is still $._atom_term; its prec(10) grabs the '.'), so p.x in TERM position parses as field_access(object: name, field: x) while a dotted name in TYPE position is a `name` node — i.e. a.b is NOT one node everywhere. This is FUNCTIONALLY COMPLETE (all WI-311 motivating cases p.x(?x)/g(a.b)/Foo.bar()/qualified-params parse and load; full workspace suite 1243 green) and the loader already classifies (field_access builtin defers + SymbolKind name resolution), so the restructure is NOT needed for correctness — it is purely the grammar-cleanliness payoff: make 'types are terms' uniform for projections/qualified-refs too, matching what the application merge already achieved for applications. TASK: restrict field_access object to non-name receivers (variable_term/paren_expr/fn_term/application/field_access); route bare and dotted ident paths through a single path node in _atom_term and fn_term-name; converter reconstructs projection-vs-qualified-vs-application from the path (the existing convert_term `name` arm already folds a multi-segment name into field_access builtins and convert_name handles application — extend so the field_access NODE is only ever a value-receiver). Corpus rebaseline. SCOPE: grammar (tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js) + converter (anthill-core/src/parse/convert.rs); cargo green. PAYOFF: grammar cleanliness only, NOT new capability. RELATED: builds on WI-311 (merge 7ada265); the broader 'full type/term conversion' (tuple_type == tuple_literal, etc.) is a further step beyond this one. Also note WI-302's Modify[kb] entity-case (Entity names stay sort_ref, not denoted) is a separate WI-302 follow-up, not this.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-311"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-313",
  description: "WI-302 follow-up: decide whether ENTITY (and other value-kind) names in type-argument position should lower to denoted instead of sort_ref. WI-302's name-case (merged 7ada265) flips ONLY SymbolKind::Param|Field -> denoted in type_expr_to_term's Simple arm (load.rs ~5052); an ENTITY name falls through to make_sort_ref. CONFIRMED EMPIRICALLY: for `sort KB { entity kb; operation mutate() -> Int effects Modify[kb] }`, the Modify[kb] binding value lowers to sort_ref(kb) (functor `sort_ref`), NOT denoted. This is the canonical effect-resource pattern (reflect.anthill: `sort KB { entity kb }` + `effects Modify[kb]` on assert/retract/add_guard). INCONSISTENCY: per value-in-type semantics (proposal 027.1 / 011 — a VALUE indexing a type denotes), a nullary entity `kb` IS a value, so Modify[kb] arguably should read denoted(kb) uniformly with Modify[c] (c a param, which DOES denote). Today Modify[c]=denoted but Modify[kb]=sort_ref — a split representation for the same 'resource value indexing the effect' concept. CURRENT mixed rep is TOLERATED (no bug): typing.rs extract_effect_resource_sym handles BOTH sort_ref and denoted, full suite green. TASK: decide whether Entity (and Variant/Operation?) value-kinds in a type-arg slot should flip to denoted; if yes, extend the is_value check in type_expr_to_term's Simple arm to include SymbolKind::Entity, and ASSESS BLAST RADIUS — entities appear in many MORE type-arg slots than params (effect resources, etc.), so this is broader/riskier than the Param/Field flip: re-check effect-matching (WI-219 transitivity), reflect queries, codegen, and the literal/parameterized paths. ACCEPTANCE: cargo-test green; a test pinning the chosen Modify[kb] representation (extend modify_name_arg_denotes_by_resolution_kind with an entity case). SCOPE: load.rs Simple arm + any effect-resource readers; converter shared, typer rust-only. RELATED: WI-302 name-case (Param/Field flip, merged 7ada265); SPLIT FROM WI-312 (which is the separate field_access/path-node grammar-cleanliness follow-up).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-302"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-27T11:37:13Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "The Modify[kb] entity-case mentioned in this WI's description is now split into its own WI-313 (decide whether entity/value-kind names in type-arg position lower to denoted).", at: "2026-05-27T05:18:14Z", workitem: "WI-312", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "REASONING / intended answer: Modify[kb] SHOULD lower to denoted(kb), NOT sort_ref(kb). kb is a VALUE (an entity instance of sort KB), so Modify[kb] means 'modifies the kb resource value' -- uniform with Modify[c] (param) and Modify[result]. sort_ref(kb) is wrong: it wraps a value in a sort-reference. THE DISCRIMINATOR IS min_sort: min_sort(x) = sort_functor_of(inferred_type(x)) (typing.rs:5911). min_sort(kb) = KB (Some) -- kb is a value of sort KB -- so it denotes. A name that IS a sort (e.g. C in Modify[C] where sort C = ?) has no value-level min_sort (it is type-level) -> sort_ref. So the correct rule is 'denote IFF the name is a value (min_sort is Some)', NOT 'iff Param|Field'; Entity and Variant are value-kinds too and were simply missed by the enumerated check. min_sort is the post-typing semantic truth; at LOAD time (type_expr_to_term Simple arm, before typing runs, so inferred_type/min_sort are unavailable) the proxy is SymbolKind -- value-kinds {Param, Field, Entity, Variant} -> denoted; type-kinds {Sort, Namespace} -> sort_ref. FIX: add Entity (and Variant) to the is_value check (load.rs ~5052) so the load-time SymbolKind decision agrees with what min_sort would say. CAUTION: entities appear in many more type-arg slots than params (effect resources especially) -> re-check effect-matching (WI-219 transitivity), reflect queries, and codegen; the full workspace suite is the guard.", at: "2026-05-27T05:23:12Z", workitem: "WI-313", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "Premise verified empirically + pinned: test wi313_min_sort_of_kb_entity_is_kb (anthill-core tests/include/wi284_min_sort_test.rs) asserts min_sort(kb) = KB, confirming kb is a value of sort KB — the basis for lowering Modify[kb] to denoted(kb).", at: "2026-05-27T05:27:59Z", workitem: "WI-313", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-314",
  description: "Modify region/escape analysis: make Modify[result] non-viral so constructors can declare it. SUCCESS CRITERION: stdlib cell.anthill operation `new(v: V) -> Cell` declares `effects Modify[result]` and the full suite is green — in particular wi205_cell_test passes with no \"undeclared effect Modify[T = result]\" failures.

BACKGROUND (045/046 review, 2026-05-27): Alloc was eliminated in favor of Modify[result] — a constructor's effect is { Modify[result] } (it initializes the region it returns; result flows out so the label is well-scoped). Proposals 045 §5.5 and 046's case table now document this. But adding `effects Modify[result]` to Cell.new TODAY breaks 6 wi205_cell_test: effect-checking is enforced and there is NO masking, so the effect goes VIRAL — every cell-allocating op (make/chain/make_and_read) must itself declare Modify[result].

MECHANISM NEEDED: at a call `c = f(...)` where f : Modify[result], rewrite Modify[result] -> Modify[c] (callee result -> caller binding), then (a) MASK it if c does not escape the caller (never reaches the caller's own result), or (b) re-key as the caller's Modify[result] and propagate if it does. The decision \"does this binding reach the operation's result?\" is escape / result-reachability analysis — the narrow slice of 046's region analysis (provenance: input / fresh-output / local; masking: Modify[input]->kept, Modify[fresh-output]->masked or handed off, Modify[local-non-escaping]->dropped). Full provenance+aliasing is the superset; the constructor case needs only result-reachability.

NOTE: the trivial alternative (unconditionally discharge Modify[result] at the call boundary) needs no analysis but makes Modify[result] semantically identical to {} — so a MEANINGFUL Modify[result] requires this analysis. (If the answer turns out to be \"{} is enough\", that is the alternative resolution and this item closes by documenting it.)

SCOPE: typer effect-checking (typing.rs) — a masking pass over derived effect rows keyed on result-reachability; possibly load.rs for result-keyed Modify handling. REFS: proposals 045 (§5.5; effect_derive default+dispatch §5.2.1), 046 (provenance/masking, the deferred body of effect_derive); builds on effect-checking (WI-307); WI-302 name-case (Modify[result] denotes, landed 7ada265); related but separate: WI-309 ([feeds:] metadata for the higher-order/foreach cases). ACCEPTANCE: cargo-test green WITH cell.anthill `new` declaring `effects Modify[result]`.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-307"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-27T15:43:21Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "CORRECTION (2026-05-27): the \"{} is enough\" alternative in this WI's NOTE is REJECTED. A no-effect Cell.new reads as PURE, which would let CSE / memoization merge distinct new() calls — but each must yield a distinct cell (new(); new() != reuse). So a non-empty effect on constructors is MANDATORY as the \"not pure / not CSE-able\" marker; the ONLY resolution is to build the analysis. CSE-safety AND non-virality both hold with Modify[result] + boundary masking: each new() stays effectful at its CALL SITE (CSE-safe), while masking happens only at the enclosing OPERATION BOUNDARY (so ops with non-escaping locals don't go viral).\n\nEXISTING SUBSTRATE (extend, don't build from scratch): the typer ALREADY masks Modify on let/match-bound local resources at the op boundary. external_effects() (typing.rs:486; called at 1712 and 6773) drops effects whose resource symbol is a local resource; TypingEnv.local_resources + declare_local_resource (449) are populated for let bindings (1579) and match-case patterns (4558); extract_effect_resource_sym (499) already sees through WI-302 denoted. GAP to close for WI-314: (a) at a call `c = f(...)` re-key the callee's Modify[result] -> Modify[c] (callee result -> caller binding); (b) make the local-resource drop ESCAPE-AWARE — today external_effects drops let/match-bound-local effects UNCONDITIONALLY, which becomes unsound once such a local ESCAPES via return: then it must be re-keyed as the op's own Modify[result] and propagated, not dropped.", at: "2026-05-27T08:32:17Z", workitem: "WI-314", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-315",
  description: "Promote the region/effect analysis to a typer PLUGIN-ENGINE (fused mini-phases in one walk). TRIGGER / DO-NOT-FORGET: build this ONLY when a SECOND fused mini-phase is needed beyond WI-314's region/escape analysis (candidates: linearity/borrow, purity, cost, ...). Do NOT build the engine for a single client.

CONTEXT: WI-314 implements the region/escape masking as a FACTORED MODULE the typer calls at its existing boundary frames — option 3' in docs/brainstorms/region-analysis-organization.md, i.e. an informal hardcoded-call-site \"plugin\" running inside the typer's one walk. THIS WI formalizes that into a generic engine: invert the typer's work-stack walk into engine + descend/ascend hooks; define shared vs per-plugin state; solve INTRA-NODE ORDERING (a plugin sees prior plugins' per-node results — region needs typing's per-node type/effects, so typing-up precedes region-up at each ascend); and POST-[simp]-REWRITE visibility (plugins run on the rewritten node, after typing's up-step). Then register typing + region + the new phase as plugins.

DESIGN: docs/brainstorms/region-analysis-organization.md (option 1 is this engine; 3' is its precursor; option 2 = the nanopass separate-pass alternative if the team prefers debuggable separate passes). ACCEPTANCE: the typer runs >=2 mini-phases as registered plugins in one walk (region + at least one more); WI-314's region module becomes a plugin with minimal change; cargo-test green. DEPENDS: WI-314.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-314"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "ORGANIZATION DECISION (2026-05-27; see docs/brainstorms/region-analysis-organization.md): implement WI-314 as OPTION 3' — a factored, separately-testable region/effect MODULE (grown from the existing external_effects / local_resources / extract_effect_resource_sym functions in typing.rs) that the typer calls at its existing boundary frames. NOT inline-scattered (option 3), NOT a post-typer pass (option 2), NOT a generic plugin-engine yet (option 1). Keep it PLUGIN-READY — a clear \"node + env + child results -> masked/re-keyed effect row\" interface — so it promotes cleanly to the Option-1 fused plugin-engine when a 2nd mini-phase arrives. That promotion is tracked as WI-315 (so it is not forgotten).", at: "2026-05-27T08:50:00Z", workitem: "WI-314", author: "user")
fact Feedback(content: "RESOLVED by REWRITE (the originally-intended 'entity->denoted' was WRONG and reverted). Per kernel-language 6.3 a standalone entity is a single-constructor SORT, so a bare entity name in a type slot (-> Pose, List[T=WorkItem]) is a TYPE -> sort_ref; adding Entity to is_value broke 15 cpp-gen tests + the anthill-todo typer. The motivating Modify[kb] was a mis-modeling: in real reflect code that kb is the PARAMETER (already denoted via WI-302), and the entity kb is only used as kb() in TERM position. FINAL RULE (load.rs): is_value = Param|Field|Operation. Value-in-type = value bindings (WI-302) + literals + a value-producing zero-arg OPERATION. Entities stay sort_ref. Also DONE: reflect.anthill 'entity kb' -> 'operation kb() -> KB' + new kb_ambient builtin (returns the Value::Unit sentinel kb_execute ignores). Tests: modify_name_arg_denotes_by_resolution_kind pins (1b) entity->sort_ref, (1c) operation->denoted. Full workspace 1243 green.", at: "2026-05-27T11:37:11Z", workitem: "WI-313", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-316",
  description: "Region escape analysis: structural reachability through returned named-sort fields (proposal 046 slice). WI-314's result_type_admits_region (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/region.rs) inspects only the return type's OWN structure — it catches a region in direct / tuple-field / list / parameterized-type-arg / bare-type-var position, but MISSES a fresh region reachable solely through a returned NAMED sort's field (e.g. `-> Pair` where `Pair` has a `Cell` field): that Modify[result] is masked (silent unsound drop, contradicting the intended over-approximation). Unreachable in the current stdlib (no op returns a fresh-cell-bearing named sort), so deferred from WI-314 and documented in the region.rs NARROW-SLICE LIMITATION note. FIX: extend result_type_admits_region to descend into a returned sort's entity field types — resolve the sort, recurse over each variant's field types, with a visited set (recursive sorts) and type-argument substitution (parametric sorts like Pair[A] whose field type A is bound to Cell at the use site). This is the structural-reachability part of 046's region analysis. ACCEPTANCE: an op make(n) -> Pair = mk(Cell.new(n), n) where Pair has a Cell field, WITHOUT effects Modify[result], is rejected with undeclared-Modify[result]; the parametric Box[A]-with-Cell-field case is handled via the binding; full cargo-test green. Sibling to WI-315 (plugin-engine promotion).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-314"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-317",
  description: "Inferred-effects model for operations: derive an op effect row from its body instead of requiring a declaration. WI-314 built the operation-boundary masking engine (kb/region.rs op_boundary_effects) and left the boundary as a CHECKED seam (actual subset-of declared). This WI extends that seam to INFERENCE: when an op opts in (an explicit effects-Inferred marker, or a WI-307 effects-? row-variable on a bodied op -- NOT bare-absent, which today means open/pure), the typer SETS the op effect row to the masked/re-keyed row that op_boundary_effects already computes, and writes it back to OperationInfo.effects so call sites (typing.rs call-effect accrual ~line 2006) propagate it. Effect: Cell.new-style allocation becomes non-viral WITHOUT per-op declarations -- make(n) -> Cell = Cell.new(n) carries an INFERRED Modify[result] (CSE-safe: present in the row callers/CSE see) without the author writing it, while allocate-and-discard ops infer the empty row. PIECES BEYOND WI-314 ENGINE: (a) write the computed row back into OperationInfo so callers read the inferred row (checked model needs no write-back -- the declaration IS the row); (b) a monotone fixpoint over the finite effect-label set for recursive ops (infer chain row from chain row), trivial/absent for non-recursive ops; (c) the effects-Inferred trigger kept DISTINCT from absent (=open/pure today), coordinated with WI-307 row-variable semantics. Inferring an op row from its body IS effect propagation = WI-307 phase 4/5; WI-314 masking makes the inferred row CORRECT (drops Modify on non-escaping locals). The checked->inferred transform is clean because both models consume the same masked row. ACCEPTANCE: an op with the inference trigger whose body allocates and returns a cell type-checks with no written effect AND its callers see the inferred Modify[result]; recursive allocating ops converge via the fixpoint; full cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-314", "WI-307"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-318",
  description: "Specify effect-variable binding on operations (045 prerequisite -- the operator effect-parameter question). Proposal 045 introduces effect-row variables (effects E) but does NOT pin HOW an operation binds one, and the grammar/loader have no mechanism for it: sort/op params are all SymbolKind::Sort, operation [..] lists admit TYPE params only (operation_type_param = name with optional = type), and there is no effects E = ? binder production. The reflect representation now exists (EffectExpression in prelude/effect-expression.anthill, with an open(type_var) row-variable tail), but its binding story is unspecified. Pin it BEFORE 045 implementation (WI-307) so the loader/grammar/typer build against a settled model.

CURRENT STATE (grounding): Function (function.anthill) declares sort E = ? at the SORT level and apply(f: Function[A,B,E], x) -> B effects E references it; Stream (stream.anthill) likewise has sort E = ? and six operations write effects E (comment: E is the abstract effect required to observe; concrete sorts bind E); collection.anthill and iteration.anthill write effects Effect -- using the Effect KIND-MARKER sort as a polymorphic-effect PLACEHOLDER because no row variable exists (a smell to remove). So today effect vars are mis-kinded as Sort, or hacked via the Effect marker.

THE QUESTION (decide): where and how is an effect-row variable bound on an operation? (a) IMPLICIT BY POSITION (045 section 3): an identifier in EFFECT position (an effects clause, an @ arrow annotation, or a Function-typed parameter effect slot) is a row variable, bound by the Function-typed parameter that introduces it (distinct per parameter -- option_fold gets E1, E2) or by a sort-level binder; never free-floating. (b) SORT-LEVEL BINDER: effects E = ? in a sort body (parallel to sort E = ?), referenced by member operations -- the Function/Stream pattern, but with E kinded as effect not type. (c) EXPLICIT PER-OPERATION BINDER: let an operation declare its own effect parameter (in the [..] list as [effects E] or a kinded [E: Effects], or an operation-level effects E = ?) -- needed for a FREE effect-polymorphic operation not inside a binding sort. ASYMMETRY TO SETTLE: type variables CAN be declared per-operation in [T], but 045 section 3 offers effect variables only (a)+(b), no explicit per-op form. Intended, or should operations bind effect vars explicitly too (symmetry)?

MUST SPECIFY: (1) kind-disambiguation -- how loader/typer knows E in effects E is a ROW variable not a type/sort (today sort E = ? kinds it Sort); (2) binder grammar -- effects E = ? as a sort-body declaration, and whether an explicit per-operation form is added; (3) scoping/binding-site rule for position-bound vars (which parameter binds E; E1/E2 distinctness across multiple function params; reuse of a named E across a signature); (4) migration -- Function and Stream sort E = ? -> effects E = ?, and collection/iteration effects Effect -> a proper row variable.

GATES WI-307 (045 row-unification implementation): WI-307 must build against this settled binding model. ACCEPTANCE: 045 (or a sub-spec) states the binding model + grammar; Function/Stream/collection/iteration migrated in spec/examples; WI-307 unblocked. REFS: 045 sections 2,3,5; EffectExpression (effect-expression.anthill); related WI-301 (effect-sets not type args), WI-013.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-28T14:47:30Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Variant analysis written into docs/brainstorms/effect-sets.md (section: Operation effect-parameters -- kinding E in op[..], 2026-05-27). Spells out 6 variants -- bare-list-kind-by-use; effect-set-as-marked-Type (is_effect_expression fact); explicit marker @E or effects E; kinded quantifier E: Effects; separate channel (op-level effects clause or second bracket); no list entry, by-position binding -- with trade-offs and a crux. First-principles check: effect-expressions do NOT classify runtime values (no x : {Modify[c]} value exists); they appear only as the effects sub-component of arrow types. Every other Type variant (sort_ref, parameterized, named_tuple, arrow) DOES classify a value population, so variant 2 (effect-set as a Type variant) creates a structurally unusual phantom Type with no inhabitants -- a smell. This vindicates 045 section 1 and the G1 EffectExpression-as-own-sort line and leans against variant 2. Recommended resolution: kinded quantifier (E: Effects) plus by-position binding as the no-ceremony default; variant 2 the serious counter only if we accept effect-expressions as a marked kind of Type.", at: "2026-05-28T06:42:04Z", workitem: "WI-318", author: "user")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-319",
  description: "Pattern reform: lift patterns to occurrence-native via a new NodeKind::Pattern(Pattern) sibling to NodeKind::Expr / NodeKind::RuleHead. PROBLEM: the original NodeOccurrence design (node_occurrence.rs:343-346) deferred 'pattern reform' — Expr's binding-position slots (Lambda.param, LambdaWithin.param, Let.pattern, MatchBranch.pattern) stayed as TermId even though every other child slot is Rc<NodeOccurrence>. The asymmetry forces the De Bruijn opener (open_debruijn_node) and closer (node_to_debruijn) to special-case those fields via term_from_debruijn / term_to_debruijn rather than uniform for_each_child + reassemble walking — the structural concern WI-298 was originally written to patch. The hash-consing of pattern TermIds is incidental (bodies are GOALS, not search keys; patterns aren't discrim-tree keys), so there's no search reason to keep TermId; the deferral was a 'separate concern' marker, not a load-bearing decision. DESIGN: patterns are not expressions (they have their own grammar — VarPattern / Wildcard / Literal / Constructor / Tuple — match-time matchers, not evaluable forms), so they get their own NodeKind variant rather than Expr sub-variants. (1) Add NodeKind::Pattern(Pattern) to NodeKind. (2) enum Pattern { Var { name: Symbol, type_ann: Option<Rc<NodeOccurrence>> }, Wildcard, Literal { value: Literal }, Constructor { name: Symbol, pos_args: Vec<Rc<NodeOccurrence>>, named_args: Vec<(Symbol, Rc<NodeOccurrence>)> }, Tuple { positional: Vec<Rc<NodeOccurrence>>, named: Vec<(Symbol, Rc<NodeOccurrence>)> } }. Each Pattern child is itself an Rc<NodeOccurrence> whose .kind is NodeKind::Pattern(...) (or NodeKind::Expr for the type_ann slot inside Var). (3) Change Expr::Let.pattern / Expr::Lambda.param / Expr::LambdaWithin.param / MatchBranch.pattern from TermId to Rc<NodeOccurrence>. TOUCH POINTS: (a) node_occurrence.rs: NodeKind + Pattern enum; extend for_each_child / reassemble / drain_expr_children to recurse into Pattern children; open_debruijn_node loses Lambda/LambdaWithin/Let/Match-pattern special-case arms (uniform fall-through via for_each_child); node_to_debruijn drops its Lambda/LambdaWithin arms and the pattern paths in Let/Match. (b) load.rs: build_frame now takes &KnowledgeBase and runs term_to_param_occurrence on the carried pattern TermId at BuildFrame::Lambda / Let / Match assembly. (c) eval/eval.rs::reduce_lambda / start_let / MatchDispatch bridge via pattern_to_term for the existing TermId-based match_pattern / extend_env_from_pattern paths; native Pattern dispatch is a follow-up. (d) typing.rs Lambda / Let / Match arms also bridge via pattern_to_term. (e) persistence/print.rs renders Pattern via write_pattern; Expr-kind sub-children delegate to write_occurrence. (f) cpp-gen pattern_var_name_occ / analyse_pattern_occ are Pattern-occurrence variants of the term-based helpers. OUT OF SCOPE: Let.type_annotation, Apply.type_args, ApplyWithin.type_args — type-position TermIds; their DeBruijn-remap stays in WI-298 scope. KNOWN DEFERRED (handled in a follow-up): collect_occurrence_global_vars_ordered / collect_occurrence_type_constraints / collect_unbound_vars_node / occurrence_to_term — three walkers don't yet descend into Pattern-kind occurrences (the asymmetry vs node_to_debruijn). Latent today because Pattern.Var.type_ann is always None at load_pattern_var; will become live the moment any pass populates that slot. ACCEPTANCE: NodeKind::Pattern(Pattern) exists; all 4 pattern slots are Rc<NodeOccurrence>; open_debruijn_node has no pattern arms; node_to_debruijn drops its pattern-position term_to_debruijn calls; full cargo-test green; multi-agent code review clean (with the documented deferrals).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-28T14:14:38Z"))
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-320",
  description: "Variant-7 substrate for proposal 045 — Phase 0: add Type::effects_rows variant + EffectsRuntime kind-anchor sort + loader bridge rule + auto-requires inference + 'effects' keyword sugar. Implements the variant-7 foundation 045 adopted 2026-05-28 (see docs/brainstorms/effect-sets.md §'Variant 7' marked ADOPTED 2026-05-28; docs/proposals/045-effect-sets-and-expressions.md §1/§2/§6/Next-steps phase 0). PIECES: (1) Type enum gets a new variant 'effects_rows(effects_expr: EffectExpression)' in stdlib/anthill/prelude/sort.anthill, parallel to existing 'denoted(value: NodeOccurrence)'; EffectExpression (prelude/effect-expression.anthill) stays its own reflect sort and becomes the wrapped payload — the variant is purely the bridge into Type position. (2) New carrier sort 'EffectsRuntime { sort Effects = ? }' in stdlib/anthill/prelude/ (pure kind anchor — no entities, no operations in scope A; the handler-bundle role is a captured follow-on, NOT in scope here). (3) Loader emits the bridge rule once: 'rule type_of(?occ, EffectsRuntime[Effects = effects_rows(?expr)]) :- is_entity_of(?occ, effects_rows(?expr))' — any Type binding to EffectsRuntime.Effects that is not effects_rows(...)-shape fails the requires at binding-site. (4) Loader auto-requires inference pass: walk each operation's 'effects <expr>' clause, collect free variables, emit 'requires EffectsRuntime[Effects = E_i]' per free variable into the operation's requires list. Examples: 'effects E' -> one requires; 'effects merge(E1, E2)' -> two requires; 'effects { E, -Modify[kb] }' -> one requires; 'effects { Modify[c] }' (closed, no free vars) -> none. (5) Grammar: add 'effects' keyword at sort-item position to tree-sitter-anthill/grammar.js, parsing 'effects E', 'effects E = ?', 'effects E = X' — desugars at load time to 'sort E = ? requires EffectsRuntime[Effects = E]'. Disambiguated by position from the existing post-signature 'effects (...)' clause. (6) Migrate existing declarations: Function.E (prelude/function.anthill) and Stream.E (prelude/stream.anthill) currently use 'sort E = ?' (mis-kinded); migrate to 'effects E'. The 'effects Effect' placeholders in prelude/collection.anthill and prelude/iteration.anthill (the Effect kind-marker standing in for a missing row variable) migrate to a real bound variable at the same time. NO ROW CHECKING YET — this is the substrate the row checking will build against. GATES WI-307 (which wires arrow.effects -> row and implements unify_arrow's effects_rows(...) <-> effects_rows(...) match arm — the actual row-rewrite algorithm). CLOSES WI-318 on adoption (the operation effect-var binding question dissolves under auto-requires). The handler-bundle direction (capability-passing dispatch via an EffectsRuntime 'perform' op, collapsing 027/027.1/037 into one witness) is captured in docs/brainstorms/effect-sets.md §'Addendum — EffectsRuntime as the handler-bundle witness' as a strictly-additive follow-on; explicitly OUT OF SCOPE for this WI. WI-301's prior design (add 'entity effect_set(effects: List[Type])' to Type enum) is superseded by variant 7's 'effects_rows(EffectExpression)' shape — WI-301 should be updated / closed once this substrate lands. SCOPE: shared grammar (tree-sitter) + Rust loader + stdlib .anthill files. ACCEPTANCE: (a) Type enum has effects_rows variant; (b) EffectsRuntime sort exists with the documented bridge rule; (c) 'effects E' / 'effects E = ?' / 'effects E = X' parse and convert to the right IR; (d) loader auto-requires inference fires on operation effects clauses (test: an op declared 'effects E' has 'requires EffectsRuntime[E]' in its OperationInfo.requires); (e) Function/Stream/Collection/Iteration migrated; (f) full cargo-test green; (g) typing/checking still works for existing (closed-row) effects without regression.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-28T18:07:12Z"))

fact Feedback(content: "Reflect-side substrate landed on branch wi320-variant-7-substrate (commits 2827071 + 4ecef86). Done: (1) Type::effects_rows(EffectExpression) variant in stdlib/anthill/prelude/sort.anthill, parallel to denoted(NodeOccurrence); (2) sort EffectsRuntime { sort Effects = ? } in stdlib/anthill/prelude/effects-runtime.anthill (pure kind anchor — no entities, no operations; the addendum's handler-bundle role stays out of scope); (3) Bridge fact emission from Rust — register_prelude (load.rs) pre-registers EffectsRuntime sort symbol + emits 'EffectsRuntime[Effects = effects_rows(effects_expr = ?expr)]' via assert_rule_debruijn. Bridge has to live in Rust, not stdlib, because surface _type admits only simple_type / parameterized_type / variable_term — an entity-construction term 'effects_rows(?)' in type-arg position does not parse (parse error tested). Full anthill-core test suite green at this checkpoint. Remaining (next session): (4) tree-sitter grammar — 'effects' keyword at sort-item position (effects E / effects E = ? / effects E = X); (5) convert.rs desugaring of the new sort-item rule to 'sort E = ? requires EffectsRuntime[Effects = E]'; (6) auto-requires inference loader pass — walk each operation's effects-clause free variables and auto-emit 'requires EffectsRuntime[Effects = E_i]' into OperationInfo.requires; (7) stdlib migrations (Function.E / Stream.E / collection.anthill / iteration.anthill) — must land WITH the auto-requires inference, not before, or existing 'sort E = ?' ops will fail the new kind constraint. Tasks 5–7 are tightly coupled (a fresh session).", at: "2026-05-28T15:19:23Z", workitem: "WI-320", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-321",
  description: "Cross-file mutually-recursive sort/enum declarations: loader robustness + policy. The loader's scan_definitions is a 4-sub-pass walk (rustland/anthill-core/src/kb/load.rs:225-258): pass1 defines all names across all files; pass2 resolves requires + imports; pass3 registers rule-head Goal functors; pass4 retries deferred predicate imports. This shape ACCIDENTALLY supports cross-file mutual structural dependencies (each file's pass1 ignores the other's content, so both names exist before either file's pass2 runs). Example uncovered during WI-320 (code-review finding #14): effect-expression.anthill imported Type from sort.anthill while sort.anthill (post-WI-320) imported EffectExpression — a mutual cycle whose soundness depended entirely on pass1 being unconditional. SHORT-TERM FIX (WI-320 last commit): colocated EffectExpression into sort.anthill, eliminating that specific cross-file cycle. But the GENERAL question remains: (1) is cross-file mutual structural recursion a SUPPORTED pattern (with documented robustness invariants the loader must preserve), or an INCIDENTAL one (works today, may regress)? (2) Should the loader DETECT cross-file structural cycles and warn / require they be in one file, mirroring how many module systems forbid cross-file mutual recursion (e.g., OCaml's module rec requirement, Rust's per-mod resolution boundary)? (3) Should there be a TEST that pins the invariant (a fixture with a benign cross-file cycle that must keep loading)? (4) Should anthill add a cross_file_recursive annotation or directory-as-module convention to ALLOW the pattern explicitly where intended? RISKS if left unaddressed: (a) a future refactor to a single-pass / streaming loader would re-expose the cycle silently; (b) imports may evolve to carry pass1-needed info (typed-symbol selective imports, qualified-name resolution touching parent files) which deadlocks the cycle; (c) load_incremental (skip-register_prelude path) has the same scan; user code mirroring this pattern across two user files would silently work today but is undocumented. TASK: (a) decide the policy — supported vs incidental, with docs in CLAUDE.md or a comment in scan_definitions; (b) if supported, add a fixture test asserting cross-file mutual structural deps load (e.g., two test files where each entity references the other's Type); (c) if forbidden, add a scan_definitions pass that detects the cycle (DFS over imports + entity field types) and reports a clear error; (d) update brainstorm/proposal docs that hand-wave the 2-pass scan handles cycles with a precise statement of which cycles are actually supported. Surfaced by WI-320 code-review finding #14 (Type vs EffectExpression cycle); the underlying mutual recursion remains (Type/EffectExpression are co-defined data) — colocation hides the cycle but doesnt remove the structural dependency, which any tooling that walks Type field types must still handle.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-322",
  description: "collect_unbound_vars_node (resolve.rs:2720) walks only for_each_child on the Expr arm — Globals living in Apply.type_args / ApplyWithin.type_args / Let.type_annotation (the TermId-typed Expr fields that WI-298 made the opener/closer/substitute walkers handle symmetrically) are NOT detected by the caller-var delay pre-check body_builtins_delay_on_caller_vars_nodes (resolve.rs:2656). PROBLEM: when a builtin delays on a goal whose first positional arg resolves to a var, the pre-check collects unbound vars from that arg and asks 'is any of them a caller var?'. If the arg's structure puts a caller var inside a type_args / type_annotation TermId, the precheck misses it and the rule does NOT propagate delay even though a caller var is genuinely unbound. SYMMETRY: mirror collect_occurrence_global_vars_ordered (node_occurrence.rs ~1188) which already handles this via collect_expr_termid_field_vars (node_occurrence.rs ~1215). SCOPE: extend the Expr arm to also walk Apply.type_args / ApplyWithin.type_args / Let.type_annotation, chasing each TermId via the existing collect_unbound_vars term walker (resolve.rs ~2620). LATENT today because builtin-delay first args are predicate applications without type args in the prelude; live once typer/simp populates type_args at a builtin's first-arg position. Code-review finding on WI-298 PR (98a9ea5). ACCEPTANCE: a delayed builtin whose first arg is f[T = ?caller_var](...) triggers rule delay (caller_var detected through the type_args TermId); cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-323",
  description: "typing.rs pattern-fragment walkers (occurrence_contains_functor ~7043 and check_ho_apply_pattern_occ ~7038) walk Expr children only via for_each_child — a ho_apply smuggled inside a Pattern's type_ann Expr child evades the WI-246 hereditary-Harrop pattern-fragment check (rules 1/2/3/3b). PROBLEM: WI-319 lifted Lambda.param / LambdaWithin.param / Let.pattern / MatchBranch.pattern to Pattern-kind Rc<NodeOccurrence>. WI-298 extended six listed walkers (occurrence_has_unbound_var, collect_occurrence_global_vars, collect_occurrence_global_vars_ordered, try_occurrence_to_term, collect_occurrence_type_constraints, collect_unbound_vars_node) with Pattern descent. These TWO parallel walkers in typing.rs were NOT on the WI-298 list and still early-return on Pattern-kind occurrences via `let Some(expr) = occ.as_expr() else { return }` (check_ho_apply_pattern_occ:7046) / `if let Some(expr) = o.as_expr()` (occurrence_contains_functor:7046). FAILURE: a rule body atom like Let { pattern: Pattern::Var { type_ann: Some(<expr containing ho_apply>) }, ... } bypasses check_ho_apply_pattern_occ — its rules-1/3/3b violation is silently missed; occurrence_contains_functor likewise misses a target functor nested in a Pattern.type_ann (used by the head-position check_pattern_fragment for the rules-1/3b body-vs-head co-occurrence test). LATENT today because Pattern.Var.type_ann is always None at load_pattern_var (load.rs:4963); live the moment proposal-035 binder annotations / reflection-synthesized patterns populate the slot. SCOPE: add Pattern arm to both walkers descending via for_each_pattern_child (mirror of resolve.rs collect_unbound_vars_node and node_occurrence.rs collect_occurrence_global_vars after WI-298). Code-review finding on WI-298 PR (98a9ea5). ACCEPTANCE: a rule body Let with Pattern.Var.type_ann containing ho_apply triggers the rule-fragment violation; cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "Substrate-half MERGED to main (2026-05-28, fast-forward c4fb24c..9ed183d). 6 commits landed: substrate ingredients (Type::effects_rows variant, EffectsRuntime kind anchor, bridge fact emitted from Rust), idempotency fix (code-review #1, guard against duplicate emission across the register_prelude-twice pattern in tests/load_all), five typing.rs arms recognizing effects_rows (#2/#3/#4/#5/#11), Type ↔ EffectExpression colocation (#14, eliminating cross-file cycle), fail-loud on missing bootstrap symbols (#9, replaced silent return with .expect()), doc/comment fixes (#6/#7/#10/#12/#13). Full anthill-core suite green throughout (972 tests, 0 failures). Filed WI-321 for the general cross-file mutual-recursion loader-policy question that #14 surfaced. WI-320 STILL CLAIMED — substrate is in, grammar + converter + auto-requires + stdlib migration (Function/Stream/Collection/Iteration to effects keyword) remain. Those four are tightly coupled (the migration breaks until the auto-requires inference fires correctly) and belong in a single follow-on session, ideally on a fresh branch wi320-grammar-and-migration or similar.", at: "2026-05-28T16:27:15Z", workitem: "WI-320", author: "user")

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-324",
  description: "Convert stdlib typeclass-satisfaction sites from rule-based to operation-with-body form. Today many sorts that satisfy a typeclass declare 'fact TypeclassName[...]' and then provide 'rule op_name(...) = ...' clauses to 'implement' the typeclass's operations. Per proposal 018 (expression bodies), the correct shape is 'operation op_name(...) -> RetType = match arg case ... -> ...' — operation declaration with a carrier-refined signature and a body that the evaluator executes, NOT a rule that the resolver matches. The rule-based form leaks behavior into the resolver/unification path instead of providing a real operation implementation that the evaluator can call. Audit and convert: list.anthill (length, member, append; nth via IndexedSeq; split via Iteration; insert, empty via Collection), map.anthill (operation laws across the file), bigint.anthill, and any other prelude sorts that follow the same anti-pattern. Once converted, library/map.md Phase 4 can write List→Stream / PersistentMap→MapReadable provisions in the correct form. Driver: discussed during library/map.md authoring (2026-05-28) when adding 'fact Stream[T]' to List surfaced the conflated rule-as-operation-implementation pattern. Reference proposal: docs/proposals/018-expressions-and-operation-implementation.md. Example of the correct shape: stdlib/anthill/cli/help.anthill:45 (render_args operation with match body).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude-opus-4-7", at: "2026-05-28T20:08:18Z"))
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-325",
  description: "Spec-op dispatch with abstract sort var and no covering requires-clause: report error instead of silently deferring. The typer's spec-op dispatch path at typing.rs:2109-2169 returns DispatchOutcome::NoCandidates silently when a body's spec-op call (e.g. eq(a, b) where a, b: T) hits an abstract sort variable in the substitution AND the enclosing operation's requires-chain doesn't cover the spec sort. The comment at 2130-2139 treats this as deliberate: 'Leaving the call as the spec op lets the runtime resolve it via its registered builtin or the spec's own derived rule.' This is correct for concrete sorts (Int.eq via host builtin, Eq.neq via derived rule) but UNSAFE for abstract sort vars without a requires-clause — the call site appears to type-check but will dispatch-fail at first runtime call. Example: List.member (added WI-324) calls eq(head, x) for abstract T but has no requires Eq[T]; typer accepts silently. Desired behavior: in req_insertion::run (or the typer's NoCandidates arm), distinguish concrete-sort NoCandidates (legitimate — leave the call alone) from abstract-sort-var NoCandidates with no covering requires (unsafe — report TypeError). The user then ADDS the explicit requires-clause to the operation signature; no auto-inference. This shifts the safety model from 'deferred to first call' to 'checked at body load'. Acceptance: 'operation foo(x: T) -> Bool = eq(x, x)' WITHOUT 'requires Eq[T]' fails to load with a diagnostic naming the missing requires (TypeError::MissingRequiresForSpecOp or equivalent). Adding 'requires Eq[T]' makes it load. cargo-test passes; existing stdlib that genuinely needs explicit requires (e.g. List.member after WI-324) is updated as part of the same patch. Driver: surfaced during WI-324 code-review (2026-05-28) — List.member's missing requires Eq[T] was a phantom finding because the NoCandidates path admits it silently; user feedback: 'we have insert_req pass, insert_req should insert or report' + 'we don't need inferred require clause'.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude-opus-4.7", at: "2026-05-29T05:58:58Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-326",
  description: "WI-307 v1a follow-on: row subtyping in arrow_compatible. The unify_arrow half of v1a row unification landed (commit 1d62e7a, Rémy/Lindley-Cheney on EffectExpression). The companion arrow_compatible half — open-row subtyping for the covariant-effects check — was NOT shipped and still uses the naive 'each actual ⊆ some(expected)' subset over effects_rows_to_flat_list (typing.rs:6303). PROBLEM: open-tail Var pushed into the flat list fails types_compatible (Var has no functor → false), so any arrow with an open row tail is wrongly rejected against any expected arrow whose tail TermId differs — even when row unification (now available) would absorb the extras. This actively rejects valid subtyping the typer would otherwise accept. SCOPE: replace arrow_compatible's effects-check with a directional row algorithm: actual labels must all be present in expected (or absorbed by expected's open tail); expected's extras may bind actual's open tail. Mirror the unify_effect_rows pattern (typing.rs ~5230) but covariant. Reuse decompose_effect_row + pair_present_labels + bind_row_tail; the only delta is directionality (actual extras MUST be absorbed by expected's tail, not symmetric). Update arrow_compatible signature to take &mut KnowledgeBase (the algorithm allocates fresh tail vars in the both-open case); ripple through types_compatible + is_subtype + entries_cover + ~30 callers + test sites — pure mechanical change like unify_types' signature change in commit 1d62e7a. ACCEPTANCE: open-row subtyping tests (pure ≤ effectful, open ≤ closed with absorbable extras, open ≤ open with shared tail); the closed/closed regression tests (subtype_arrow_fewer_effects, subtype_arrow_different_effects_incompatible) still green; full cargo-test green. Closes the v1a half of WI-307 proposal 045 §Phase 1. Code-review #2 from the WI-307 substrate review (commit 1f92799) resolves under this.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-307"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-28T22:35:04Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-327",
  description: "WI-307 phase 2: EffectExpression surface + grammar (proposal 045 §3, §Phase 2). Tree-sitter + converter for the user-facing effect-expression algebra: '{}' (empty/pure), 'e' (single effect, sugar for '+e'), '+e' (presence), '-e' (absence/lacks-constraint, v1b consumer), 'merge(E1, E2)' (union), 'E' (row variable). The set-literal '{e1, …, en}' is sugar for iterated merge — already lowered as a list today by the loader at make_arrow_type sites; this WI lifts merge/+/- to grammar-level constructors that elaborate to the EffectExpression entities (commits 7b39c4b + 1f92799 added the entity builders). PIECES: (a) grammar.js: extend effects_clause's _effect_set to admit prefix '+'/'-' on each effect-type element + a 'merge(' application form; document precedence with the existing '|' braces; (b) converter (convert.rs): emit Item-level EffectExpression terms via the existing make_effect_expression_{present,absent,merge,open,empty_row} builders into TypeExpr — currently emit_effects only handles List[Type], so a new path produces effects_rows(EffectExpression) directly from grammar without going through build_canonical_effects_rows' partition; (c) arrow.effects in TypeExpr — today still a Vec<TermId> the loader canonicalizes; either change TypeExpr to carry a single EffectExpression OR keep the Vec and treat '-' / 'merge' as flags resolved in canonicalization. The latter is less invasive. SCOPE: shared grammar + Rust convert. ACCEPTANCE: 'operation foo() -> Int effects +Modify[kb]' parses + lowers; 'operation foo() -> Int effects -Error' parses (lowers to absent(Error) — consumed in v1b, no-op for v1a); 'operation foo() -> Int effects merge(E1, E2)' parses + lowers to a merge chain; existing stdlib 'effects E' / 'effects {a, b}' continue to lower identically; full cargo-test green. Depends on WI-307 v1a (the row substrate must be in place — it is).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-307"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-29T06:38:10Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-328",
  description: "WI-307 v1b: lacks-constraints on row tails (proposal 045 §5.5, §7.1, §Phase 3). Adds '-e' (absent) semantics to row unification: a row containing 'absent(e)' (= 'lacks e') must NOT have 'e' in its extension. SUBSTRATE TODAY: v1a's decompose_effect_row (typing.rs ~5260, commit 1d62e7a) already collects 'absent(label)' nodes into the third tuple slot (_a_absent), but unify_effect_rows ignores them — v1a is presence-only. PIECES: (a) attach a 'lacks set' to each row-variable Var binding (a side-table keyed by VarId; cannot live in the EffectExpression term because the constraint is on the unbound tail, not on the row's labels); (b) at unify_effect_rows' tail-binding sites (bind_row_tail in typing.rs ~5310), check the new binding against each existing lacks constraint — if a present-label in the binding matches a lacked-label, the row unification fails; (c) on bind_row_tail's open(fresh) path, propagate the union of both sides' lacks constraints onto the fresh shared tail; (d) reject at parse time when a row has both 'present(e)' and 'absent(e)' for the same label (already a hard error per proposal §7.2); (e) tests covering: '-Modify' propagation through map/fold callbacks, '{Modify[c]} unifies with {-Error | ρ}' → ρ acquires '-Error' lacks, and proven impossibility ('{Error | ρ}' with ρ-lacks-Error fails). ACCEPTANCE: lacks-constraint tests pass; v1a row tests still green; decompose_effect_row's _a_absent slot is now consumed; full cargo-test green. Depends on WI-307 v1a having shipped unify_effect_rows (it has). Code-review #4 from WI-307 substrate (commit 1f92799) — present(Var)/open(Var) schema mismatch — overlaps here; if v1b lifts row vars to a dedicated schema-conformant shape (type_var-wrapped), this WI can close it too. Otherwise file separately.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-307"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-329",
  description: "WI-307 phase 4: handler discharge — handler drops a label by row unification (proposal 045 §5.6, §Phase 4). A 'handle_K(λ → e)' expression discharges effect K: the handler's body row equals the inner row MINUS the K label. Under v1a/v1b row unification this is mechanical — the handler's expected type carries a 'shared-tail' row pattern '{handled_labels | ρ_shared}' against the body's actual row, with the handled label REMOVED from the result row. PIECES: (a) typer: handle-expression's expected effects = body's actual effects ∖ {K} ∪ tail ρ_shared; the row-unification arm of unify_effect_rows drops the matching label and binds the result tail; (b) interaction with the ambient-handler runtime (proposal 027): the typer's check is purely static — it asserts the program is well-typed, not that the runtime handler exists. The runtime side is independent (027's perform/install machinery); (c) tests: 'handle_Error(λ → may_fail())' has result row without Error; nested handlers drop labels successively; un-handled labels propagate; handle of a non-present label is a type error. Available the moment v1a's row unification landed (it has). Depends on WI-307 v1a; the surface-syntax 'handle_K' grammar is part of (or precedes) this WI — coordinate with proposal 027 / WI on the handler-bundle direction. ACCEPTANCE: handle-expr tests pass; full cargo-test green; the runtime handler mechanism (027) is NOT in scope (separate WI).",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-307"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-330",
  description: "WI-307 phase 5: migrate typing_pass_spec onto row unification (proposal 045 §Phase 5). The reflect-side typing pass (stdlib/anthill/reflect/typing_pass_spec.anthill) declares effect handling that — until v1a — was a stub: effects were modeled as List[Type] with positional checks at the typer (typing.rs:6303). With v1a's unify_effect_rows live (commit 1d62e7a), the spec can honestly describe the algorithm. PIECES: (a) audit typing_pass_spec for effect-related operations and update their bodies to reflect row unification semantics (handler discharge, propagation of open tails, lacks-constraint accumulation once v1b lands); (b) replace positional 'actual ⊆ expected' rules with row-equivalence rules consulting effects_rows + EffectExpression algebra; (c) for the migrated stdlib Function/Stream/Collection/Iteration (post-WI-320 commit fae2516), thread the EffectsRuntime[Effects = E] requirement through the spec so the typer cross-checks against the auto-emitted requires that ship with each operation; (d) test that typing_pass_spec.anthill loads cleanly with the new shape and a sample operation type-checks via the spec — this is the proposal 013 deferred 'effect checking is honest now' acceptance criterion. SCOPE: spec stdlib file + integration tests that exercise the spec on the post-WI-307 typer. Depends on v1a (WI-307) shipped, ideally v1b (WI-328) and handler discharge (WI-329) too for full coverage. Completes proposal 013's deferred effect-checking.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-307", "WI-328", "WI-329"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-331",
  description: "WI-307 housekeeping: sync stdlib arrow.effects schema to the WI-307 v1a representation. Today stdlib/anthill/prelude/sort.anthill (line ~24) declares 'entity arrow(param: Type, result: Type, effects: List[Type])' but the loader's make_arrow_type (kb/mod.rs:2362 post commit 7b39c4b) stores effects as a singular 'effects_rows(EffectExpression)' Type, not a List. The schema is now out of sync with the implementation. PIECES: (a) update sort.anthill arrow's effects field type from 'List[Type]' to 'Type' with a doc-comment noting it's specifically an effects_rows-wrapped EffectExpression; (b) verify any reflect-side consumer that pattern-matches on arrow.effects (none today, per the WI-307 cross-file tracer code-review — but verify); (c) audit for any test or codegen path that would surface a schema validation pass and confirm green. Closes code-review #10 from the WI-307 substrate review (commit 1f92799). Trivial scope (one schema declaration line + doc comment) but pinned to WI-307 because the schema and the Rust shape must move together. ACCEPTANCE: stdlib schema matches Rust-built shape; full cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-307"],
  status: Open)

fact Feedback(content: "v1a unify_arrow half DELIVERED on main 2026-05-28 (three commits: 7b39c4b substrate / 1f92799 code-review fixes / 1d62e7a row-unification algorithm + 7 v1a tests). Remaining phases factored into separate WIs to keep tracking granular: WI-326 (v1a arrow_compatible row subtyping — the other half of v1a per the original design pivot; mechanical mirror of unify_effect_rows in directional form), WI-327 (phase 2: EffectExpression surface +/-/merge grammar), WI-328 (v1b lacks-constraints — substrate is in, decompose_effect_row already collects 'absent' labels), WI-329 (phase 4: handler discharge — straightforward once v1a row unification is live), WI-330 (phase 5: typing_pass_spec migration onto row unification — completes proposal 013's deferred effect-checking), WI-331 (housekeeping: stdlib sort.anthill arrow schema sync with the new Rust shape). WI-307 stays Claimed until v1a-compatible-half (WI-326) lands and the schema sync (WI-331) is done — at which point v1a is fully shipped and WI-307 can deliver, with the later phases tracked under their own WIs.", at: "2026-05-28T20:44:39Z", workitem: "WI-307", author: "user")
fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-332",
  description: "Code-review WI-326 F3: arrow_function_compatible discards effects while arrow_compatible (post-WI-326) checks them via row subtyping. PROBLEM: types_compatible(arrow(Int,Int,{ReadIO}), parameterized Function[A=Int,B=Int]) routes to arrow_function_compatible (typing.rs ~5664) which destructures (Some((a_param, a_result, _)), Some((b_param, b_result, _))) — discards effects via _, returns true. The semantically-identical types_compatible(arrow(Int,Int,{ReadIO}), arrow(Int,Int,{})) goes through arrow_compatible and is correctly rejected by subtype_effect_rows. Same denotational type written in two syntaxes (typer's arrow shorthand vs stdlib Function[A,B,E] alias) gives opposite subtype answers. Doc comment at ~5668-5671 ('Effects are not compared here, also as in arrow_compatible') is now stale. SCOPE: extend arrow_function_compatible to invoke subtype_effect_rows on the effects field of the Function[E] parameterized side (extract via arrow_parts which returns the flattened Vec — use effects_rows_to_flat_list canonicalization or reconstruct an effects_rows term first); update the docstring. Confirm both directions (arrow vs Function[E], Function[E] vs arrow) get consistent treatment. ACCEPTANCE: new test 'subtype_arrow_function_path_effects_consistent' demonstrates arrow(int,int,{Reads}) NOT <: Function[A=Int,B=Int,E=List[]] (was true pre-fix; should be false). Full cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-326"],
  status: Claimed(agent: "claude", since: "2026-05-29T04:50:32Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-333",
  description: "Code-review WI-326 F5: parameterized_compatible bypasses row subtyping for the Function[E] denotation. PROBLEM: types_compatible(Function[E={Reads}], Function[E={Reads, Writes}]) recurses via parameterized_compatible on each binding, hitting types_compatible(effects_rows({Reads}), effects_rows({Reads, Writes})). The (effects_rows, effects_rows) arm at typing.rs ~5633 does conservative recursive structural compatibility on effects_expr only — explicit doc-comment notes 'distinct logical-var positions inside differently-allocated EffectExpression terms compare incompatible. Sound (no false positives).' But arrow(Int,Int,{Reads}) <: arrow(Int,Int,{Reads,Writes}) is now correctly accepted via subtype_effect_rows post-WI-326. Same denotational type written as Function[E] gives a different answer than the arrow form. SCOPE: dispatch the (effects_rows, effects_rows) arm in types_compatible to subtype_effect_rows instead of recursive structural equality. Need a local Substitution (matches arrow_compatible's pattern); the result is the directional row sub. This makes Function[E={Reads}] <: Function[E={Reads, Writes}] hold consistently with the arrow form. ACCEPTANCE: new test 'subtype_function_E_binding_uses_row_sub' covers Function[E={A}] <: Function[E={A, B}] and the negative case. Full cargo-test green. Closely related to WI-326 F3 (WI-332) but distinct: F3 is the arrow-vs-Function alias path, F5 is the Function-vs-Function path.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-326"],
  status: Claimed(agent: "claude", since: "2026-05-29T05:13:47Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-334",
  description: "Code-review WI-326 F4: both-open subtype arm with shared row var + non-empty extras falsely rejects (completeness gap, inherited from unify_effect_rows). PROBLEM: when a_tail and e_tail walk to the same VarId (shared row var across two arrows) AND only one of only_a/only_e is non-empty, the fast-path early-return at typing.rs ~5660 requires both extras empty so it doesn't fire. Code then allocates a fresh shared tail and calls bind_row_tail(a_t, &only_e, Some(fresh)) followed by bind_row_tail(e_t, &only_a, Some(fresh)). For a_t == e_t this is two distinct binds on the same VarId with two structurally different terms → subst.is_contradiction() → returns false. EXAMPLE: A = arrow(Int,Int,{|rho}), B = arrow(Int,Int,{E2|rho}) (legal when arrows share rho via a generic context). decompose: a_present=[], a_tail=Some(rho), e_present=[E2], e_tail=Some(rho), only_a=[], only_e=[E2]. Semantically A's set = content_of_rho ⊆ {E2} ∪ content_of_rho = B's set, so A <: B should hold. But algorithm rejects. SCOPE: extend the both-open fast-path to handle a_walked == e_walked with non-empty extras: bind the shared tail once to merge(only_a, merge(only_e, open(fresh))) instead of two contradicting binds. Mirror fix into unify_effect_rows (where same pattern lurks). Add regression tests for both 'shared rho with only_a empty + only_e non-empty' and the symmetric case. ACCEPTANCE: shared-row-var subtype tests pass; unify_effect_rows fix has its own tests; full cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-326"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-29T05:32:47Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-335",
  description: "Code-review WI-326 F6: nested arrow_compatible uses a fresh local Substitution per level → soundness gap for arrows with shared row vars across param/result positions. PROBLEM: each arrow_compatible call (any nesting depth) allocates 'let mut local_subst = Substitution::new()' (typing.rs ~6785, ~6792, ~6798) and discards it on return. For an arrow with a row var shared across multiple positions, the substitution that binds it at one position does not propagate to checks at sibling positions. EXAMPLE: actual = arrow(arrow(Int,Int,{rho}), arrow(Int,Int,{rho}), {}) — nested arrows share rho. expected = arrow(arrow(Int,Int,{E1}), arrow(Int,Int,{E2}), {}). Outer arrow_compatible's param (contravariant): types_compatible(arrow(Int,Int,{E1}), arrow(Int,Int,{rho})) with local_subst1, binds rho := {E1}. Result (covariant): types_compatible(arrow(Int,Int,{rho}), arrow(Int,Int,{E2})) with local_subst2 (fresh, doesn't see prior binding), binds rho := empty_row. Both individually succeed; outer returns true. No consistent global binding of rho can satisfy both — unsound accept. SCOPE: thread a single shared Substitution through nested arrow_compatible calls within one types_compatible invocation. This may require expanding the entry-level types_compatible / arrow_compatible signatures to take an optional &mut Substitution (the caller could allocate it once and pass it down). Alternative: short-circuit the row binding to a fresh tail only when the variables are truly local to the row (not visible to outer scope). Carries design weight — may need an explicit free-vars analysis to detect 'this row var was passed in from outside'. ACCEPTANCE: 'nested_arrow_shared_row_var_inconsistent_rejects' test (current build accepts; should reject post-fix) plus 'nested_arrow_shared_row_var_consistent_accepts' positive control; full cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-326"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-29T06:02:32Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-336",
  description: "Code-review WI-326 F12: bind_row_tail's non-Global fallback returns true for Rigid/DeBruijn row tails — latent unsoundness for forall-quantified row vars. PROBLEM: bind_row_tail at typing.rs ~5440 matches the tail term against Term::Var(Var::Global(vid)); the fallback arm is '_ => return extra_labels.is_empty() && final_tail.is_none()'. For a Var::Rigid (forall-Skolem) or Var::DeBruijn tail, this returns TRUE whenever the binding would be a no-op (case 3 of subtype_effect_rows always calls bind_row_tail(a_t, &[], None) when only_a is empty). But a Rigid row var represents 'some universally-quantified row whose contents are unknown to this scope' — treating it as 'closes to empty' is unsound; ?rho_rigid could instantiate to {B} which is NOT subset of expected = {A}. SCOPE: in subtype_effect_rows case 3 (Some(a_t), None), explicitly check that a_t is Term::Var(Var::Global(_)) before treating the close-to-empty as a valid sub witness; reject otherwise. Symmetric check for the case 2 (None, Some(e_t)) where e_t being Rigid means 'we can't safely close it'. Currently latent (v1a has no forall-quantified effect-row vars in arrow.effects) but becomes a real hole when WI-307 v1b's lacks-constraint or polymorphic-effect-row signatures land. ACCEPTANCE: hardening check rejects Rigid/DeBruijn tails in case 2/3 of subtype_effect_rows; new test 'subtype_rejects_rigid_tail_close_to_empty' demonstrates the rejection; full cargo-test green; document in subtype_effect_rows docstring.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-326"],
  status: Delivered(agent: "claude", at: "2026-05-29T06:21:53Z"))

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-337",
  description: "Code-review WI-326 F2: arrow_compatible's (Some,None)/(None,Some) effects branches panic if prelude not registered. PROBLEM: pre-WI-326 arrow_compatible used get_named_arg(...).map(effects_rows_to_flat_list).unwrap_or_default() and produced an empty Vec without any bootstrap symbol lookup. Post-WI-326 the missing-side arms call kb.make_effect_expression_empty_row() and kb.make_effects_rows_type() at typing.rs ~6790, ~6796 — both call kb.resolve_symbol() on bootstrap names ('anthill.prelude.EffectExpression.empty_row', 'anthill.prelude.Type.effects_rows'). resolve_symbol panics with 'resolve_symbol: X is not a resolved symbol' if X hasn't been registered. SCOPE: either (a) guard the symbols with try_resolve_symbol and degrade gracefully (return false or true depending on semantics) for bootstrap-time fixtures, or (b) lift the empty_rows construction to a one-time pre-computed TermId stored on KB (cached on first registration), making it bootstrap-safe and faster. Option (b) is consistent with how the loader pre-registers stdlib scopes. ACCEPTANCE: a test invoking types_compatible on hand-built arrow terms BEFORE register_prelude (or after a partial-reset) does not panic; full cargo-test green. Low practical impact today (make_arrow_type always synthesizes effects_rows so the field is rarely missing), but a removed safety property that the bootstrap path used to provide.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-326"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-338",
  description: "Code-review WI-326 F8/F11/F9: pair_present_labels / cover_present_labels hardening. THREE small issues bundled because they touch the same family of helpers: (F8) functor-name pre-filter at typing.rs ~5395 (in pair_present_labels) and ~5705 (cover_present_labels) skips cross-arm pairings whose functors differ. Pre-WI-326 arrow_compatible called types_compatible(ae, ee) directly, which dispatches the (sort_ref, parameterized) and (parameterized, sort_ref) arms (typing.rs ~5615-5620) treating bare sort vs parameterized as compatible. pair/cover_present_labels never attempts unify_types in that case; drops the label into only_a. Fix: remove the strict functor-name pre-filter and let unify_types decide (small perf hit, less surprising semantics) OR add explicit (sort_ref, parameterized) bridge arms. (F11) pair_present_labels has no rollback (acknowledged in docstring) — partial-bind contamination when unify_types binds a Var then fails. Local-subst use in arrow_compatible isolates the impact but the helper is generally callable with a non-scratch subst. Fix: snapshot/restore subst around each unify_types attempt OR call a probe-only variant. (F9) Both-open arm in subtype_effect_rows (and unify_effect_rows) allocates kb.fresh_var(?rho) + kb.alloc(Term::Var) on every invocation — local_subst is discarded but kb.next_var grows monotonically and the term store accumulates orphan Var nodes. Fix: cache a thread-local Symbol for '?rho' OR memoize the result of subtype_effect_rows on (actual_effects, expected_effects) so repeat queries don't re-allocate. ACCEPTANCE: cross-arm sort_ref-vs-parameterized labels pair correctly; subst rollback semantics documented or implemented; kb.next_var growth bounded under stress. Full cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-326"],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-339",
  description: "Code-review WI-326 F10/F13: docs & malformed-input hardening. (F10) Stale doc on requires_chain_flat at typing.rs ~6204 says 'Keeps &KnowledgeBase so callers up the types_compatible chain don't need to convert to &mut' — but WI-326 made that chain &mut. The function legitimately remains & (no mutation), but the recorded rationale misleads. Fix: re-word the doc to say 'still & because the function does no mutation; types_compatible chain moved to &mut in WI-326, but this site doesn't need to'. (F13) decompose_effect_row at typing.rs ~5300-5307 silently drops second-and-later row tails on malformed inputs (debug_assert at ~5341 fires only in debug builds). External producers (loader bug, hand-built test term) could create EffectExpression like merge(open(?rho_1), open(?rho_2)) — two tail vars. The algorithm sees only ?rho_1; subtype/unify proceeds on incomplete info. Per CLAUDE.md 'avoid fallbacks, know about errors early', the algorithm should hard-reject (return None/false propagated as a row-shape error). Fix: turn the debug_assert into a hard error path (return Err(MalformedRow) or a sentinel that callers translate into false), and add a test that hand-builds a multi-tail row and confirms rejection. ACCEPTANCE: doc fixed; hard-rejection path tested with a malformed-row probe; full cargo-test green.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: ["WI-326"],
  status: Open)

